(function(){const grade5Unit3Selections={"selections":[{"selection_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":3,"week":1,"title":"from Love, Amalia","author":"Alma Flor Ada and Gabriel M. Zubizarreta","genre":"Realistic Fiction","essential_question":"How do relationships shape people\u0027s lives?","weekly_question":"How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["obvious","convincing","grandmother","friendship","comfort"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"from Love, Amalia. How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q001","read_aloud":"* What does the word \"obvious\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"* What does the word \"obvious\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q002","read_aloud":"When does Amalia usually visit her grandmother? A. Every day, B. On Monday, C. On Friday afternoon, D. Once a month.","excerpt":"\"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\"","stem":"When does Amalia usually visit her grandmother?","choices":{"A":"Every day,","B":"On Monday,","C":"On Friday afternoon,","D":"Once a month."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that Amalia has been visiting her grandmother on Friday afternoons for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q003","read_aloud":"Why is Amalia sad? A. Her grandmother is moving, B. She has to move to California, C. Her best friend Martha is moving away, D. She forgot her homework.","excerpt":"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California.\"","stem":"Why is Amalia sad?","choices":{"A":"Her grandmother is moving,","B":"She has to move to California,","C":"Her best friend Martha is moving away,","D":"She forgot her homework."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Amalia is upset because her friend Martha is moving far away to California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Who is the first person to guess that something is wrong with Amalia? A. Martha, B. Amalia\u0027s mother, C. Amalia\u0027s grandmother, D. Amalia\u0027s teacher.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\"","stem":"Who is the first person to guess that something is wrong with Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Martha,","B":"Amalia\u0027s mother,","C":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother,","D":"Amalia\u0027s teacher."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The grandmother notices Amalia is quiet and asks her what is bothering her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q005","read_aloud":"How does Amalia usually show she is upset? A. By crying loudly, B. By shaking her head, C. By running away, D. By yelling at her grandmother.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset, and her long black hair swept her shoulders.\"","stem":"How does Amalia usually show she is upset?","choices":{"A":"By crying loudly,","B":"By shaking her head,","C":"By running away,","D":"By yelling at her grandmother."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes Amalia shaking her head as something she \"frequently\" does when upset.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset, and her long black hair swept her shoulders.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"shattered\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. broken into many small pieces; deeply hurt B. cleaned and organized very carefully C. excited and full of happy energy D. confused and unable to understand","excerpt":"\"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\"","stem":"What does the word \"shattered\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"broken into many small pieces; deeply hurt","B":"cleaned and organized very carefully","C":"excited and full of happy energy","D":"confused and unable to understand"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Amalia is deeply hurt by Martha\u0027s news. \"Shattered\" means broken emotionally, which matches option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q007","read_aloud":"Why does Abuelita ask if Martha is all right? A. She knows Martha is sick at home. B. She wants Amalia to go home early. C. She notices Amalia is upset and guesses why. D. She forgot that Martha was moving away.","excerpt":"\"\"It\u0027s okay, Abuelita, de verdad. I\u0027m fine.\" Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \"Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\"\"","stem":"Why does Abuelita ask if Martha is all right?","choices":{"A":"She knows Martha is sick at home.","B":"She wants Amalia to go home early.","C":"She notices Amalia is upset and guesses why.","D":"She forgot that Martha was moving away."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Abuelita sees that Amalia is quiet and upset, so she correctly guesses that something involving Martha might be wrong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"It\u0027s okay, Abuelita, de verdad. I\u0027m fine.\" Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \"Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing? A. Baking a chocolate cake B. Making a sweet taffy candy C. Painting a picture of the kitchen D. Washing the dinner dishes","excerpt":"\"\"Shall we knead the melcocha, then?\" Amalia\u0027s grandmother asked as she lifted the old brass pot onto the kitchen table and poured the sticky melcocha into a bowl.\"","stem":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing?","choices":{"A":"Baking a chocolate cake","B":"Making a sweet taffy candy","C":"Painting a picture of the kitchen","D":"Washing the dinner dishes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions \"sticky melcocha\" and later describes it as sweet taffy that they pull and knead with their hands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Shall we knead the melcocha, then?\" Amalia\u0027s grandmother asked as she lifted the old brass pot onto the kitchen table and poured the sticky melcocha into a bowl.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Where is Martha moving? A. to a weird place in Chicago B. to the east coast C. to Mexico City D. to California","excerpt":"\"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago! Today she had to go straight home to start packing. It\u0027s not fair.\"\"","stem":"Where is Martha moving?","choices":{"A":"to a weird place in Chicago","B":"to the east coast","C":"to Mexico City","D":"to California"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Amalia explicitly states that Martha\u0027s family is moving to California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago! Today she had to go straight home to start packing. It\u0027s not fair.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the bowl no longer look like a small sun to Amalia? A. Her sadness is making her focus only on her heavy feelings. B. The kitchen is too dark to see it clearly. C. Her grandmother broke the bowl yesterday. D. She is angry at her grandmother for making her work.","excerpt":"\"Once, the bowl had made Amalia think that it looked like a small sun on the kitchen table. Today she was too upset to see anything but the heavy bowl.\"","stem":"Why does the bowl no longer look like a small sun to Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Her sadness is making her focus only on her heavy feelings.","B":"The kitchen is too dark to see it clearly.","C":"Her grandmother broke the bowl yesterday.","D":"She is angry at her grandmother for making her work."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Amalia\u0027s emotional pain is clouding her usual happy perspective, making the bowl feel \"heavy\" instead of bright like the sun.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, the bowl had made Amalia think that it looked like a small sun on the kitchen table. Today she was too upset to see anything but the heavy bowl.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"grandmother\" mean in this sentence? A. A mother\u0027s or father\u0027s mother B. A teacher C. A friend D. A sister","excerpt":"\"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\"","stem":"What does \"grandmother\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A mother\u0027s or father\u0027s mother","B":"A teacher","C":"A friend","D":"A sister"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Grandmother is the mother of one\u0027s parent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q012","read_aloud":"Why does Abuelita think Amalia might be upset? A. Amalia failed a test. B. Martha did not come with her. C. Amalia lost her book. D. The weather is bad.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Abuelita think Amalia might be upset?","choices":{"A":"Amalia failed a test.","B":"Martha did not come with her.","C":"Amalia lost her book.","D":"The weather is bad."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita asks if Martha is all right and did not come.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is Amalia trying to control? A. Her laughter B. Her feelings (sadness) C. Her hunger D. Her homework","excerpt":"\"Amalia paused before answering, \u0027She is not coming back anymore, Abuelita. ¡Nunca mas!\u0027 Despite Amalia\u0027s efforts to control her feelings, her voice cracked and her brown eyes watered.\"","stem":"What is Amalia trying to control?","choices":{"A":"Her laughter","B":"Her feelings (sadness)","C":"Her hunger","D":"Her homework"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her voice cracks and eyes water, showing she is trying not to cry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia paused before answering, \u0027She is not coming back anymore, Abuelita. ¡Nunca mas!\u0027 Despite Amalia\u0027s efforts to control her feelings, her voice cracked and her brown eyes watered.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q014","read_aloud":"Why is Amalia upset? A. She lost her toy. B. Her best friend Martha is moving far away. C. She has too much homework. D. It is raining.","excerpt":"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago!\"","stem":"Why is Amalia upset?","choices":{"A":"She lost her toy.","B":"Her best friend Martha is moving far away.","C":"She has too much homework.","D":"It is raining."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Martha is moving far away to California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q015","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"convincing\"? A. Believable, B. Quiet, C. Confusing, D. Loud.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"convincing\"?","choices":{"A":"Believable,","B":"Quiet,","C":"Confusing,","D":"Loud."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"If something is convincing, it makes people believe it is true.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this story excerpt? A. Amalia likes to cook honey with her grandma, B. Amalia is sad about her friend moving and seeks comfort from her grandmother, C. Martha does not want to be friends with Amalia anymore, D. Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a very good cook.","excerpt":"\"Twelve-year-old Amalia is heartbroken when she learns that her best friend is moving away. She turns to her grandmother for comfort.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this story excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Amalia likes to cook honey with her grandma,","B":"Amalia is sad about her friend moving and seeks comfort from her grandmother,","C":"Martha does not want to be friends with Amalia anymore,","D":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a very good cook."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage focuses on Amalia\u0027s sadness about Martha moving and the support she gets from her grandmother.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Twelve-year-old Amalia is heartbroken when she learns that her best friend is moving away. She turns to her grandmother for comfort.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What did they do immediately after drying their hands? A. Scoop the taffy, B. Wash their hands again, C. Slather their hands with butter, D. Sit on the sofa.","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter... Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy...\"","stem":"What did they do immediately after drying their hands?","choices":{"A":"Scoop the taffy,","B":"Wash their hands again,","C":"Slather their hands with butter,","D":"Sit on the sofa."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists the steps in order: first they dry their hands, then they put butter on them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter... Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when saying the bowl had \"chips that spoke of its long use\"? A. The bowl could talk, B. The bowl was very new, C. The bowl was very old and used often, D. The bowl was made of plastic.","excerpt":"\"The thick white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when saying the bowl had \"chips that spoke of its long use\"?","choices":{"A":"The bowl could talk,","B":"The bowl was very new,","C":"The bowl was very old and used often,","D":"The bowl was made of plastic."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Chips\" in a bowl are small cracks from wear, showing it has been used for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The thick white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Why does the author describe the sofa as bringing a \"piece of the garden\" inside? A. It has flowers on it, B. It is made of grass, C. It smells like dirt, D. It is kept outside in the garden.","excerpt":"\"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside the house.\"","stem":"Why does the author describe the sofa as bringing a \"piece of the garden\" inside?","choices":{"A":"It has flowers on it,","B":"It is made of grass,","C":"It smells like dirt,","D":"It is kept outside in the garden."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sofa is \"floral,\" meaning it has a pattern of flowers, which reminds the author of a garden.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside the house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q020","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean? A. Only once, B. Almost never, C. Very often, D. Only on Fridays.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Only once,","B":"Almost never,","C":"Very often,","D":"Only on Fridays."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Frequently\" means happening many times or very often.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness? A. She lost her hair ribbon, B. Her friend Martha is moving away, C. Her grandmother is busy, D. She does not like taffy.","excerpt":"\"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\"","stem":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness?","choices":{"A":"She lost her hair ribbon,","B":"Her friend Martha is moving away,","C":"Her grandmother is busy,","D":"She does not like taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that Martha\u0027s moving is the reason for Amalia\u0027s sadness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What does the floral sofa look like? A. Plain and brown, B. Covered in flowers, C. Made of wood, D. Very new.","excerpt":"\"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\"","stem":"What does the floral sofa look like?","choices":{"A":"Plain and brown,","B":"Covered in flowers,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Very new."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A \"floral\" pattern means it is covered in flowers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together? A. Cleaning the kitchen, B. Making taffy, C. Reading a book, D. Playing a game.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\"","stem":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together?","choices":{"A":"Cleaning the kitchen,","B":"Making taffy,","C":"Reading a book,","D":"Playing a game."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The actions of scooping and buttering clearly show they are making taffy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit? A. Amalia forgot her homework, B. Something is bothering Amalia, C. Martha is hiding, D. They ran out of taffy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\"","stem":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit?","choices":{"A":"Amalia forgot her homework,","B":"Something is bothering Amalia,","C":"Martha is hiding,","D":"They ran out of taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The grandmother asks questions because she sees that something is wrong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What does \"brightened\" mean in this context? A. Made the room darker, B. Made the room look more cheerful or light, C. Cleaned the floor, D. Made the room colder.","excerpt":"\"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room...\"","stem":"What does \"brightened\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"Made the room darker,","B":"Made the room look more cheerful or light,","C":"Cleaned the floor,","D":"Made the room colder."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When something brightens a room, it adds color or light to make it feel more cheerful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room...\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"convincing\"? A. Believable, B. Quiet, C. Confusing, D. Loud.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"convincing\"?","choices":{"A":"Believable,","B":"Quiet,","C":"Confusing,","D":"Loud."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"If something is convincing, it makes people believe it is true.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this story excerpt? A. Amalia likes to cook honey with her grandma, B. Amalia is sad about her friend moving and seeks comfort from her grandmother, C. Martha does not want to be friends with Amalia anymore, D. Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a very good cook.","excerpt":"\"Twelve-year-old Amalia is heartbroken when she learns that her best friend is moving away. She turns to her grandmother for comfort.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this story excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Amalia likes to cook honey with her grandma,","B":"Amalia is sad about her friend moving and seeks comfort from her grandmother,","C":"Martha does not want to be friends with Amalia anymore,","D":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a very good cook."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage focuses on Amalia\u0027s sadness about Martha moving and the support she gets from her grandmother.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Twelve-year-old Amalia is heartbroken when she learns that her best friend is moving away. She turns to her grandmother for comfort.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What did they do immediately after drying their hands? A. Scoop the taffy, B. Wash their hands again, C. Slather their hands with butter, D. Sit on the sofa.","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter... Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy...\"","stem":"What did they do immediately after drying their hands?","choices":{"A":"Scoop the taffy,","B":"Wash their hands again,","C":"Slather their hands with butter,","D":"Sit on the sofa."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists the steps in order: first they dry their hands, then they put butter on them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter... Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when saying the bowl had \"chips that spoke of its long use\"? A. The bowl could talk, B. The bowl was very new, C. The bowl was very old and used often, D. The bowl was made of plastic.","excerpt":"\"The thick white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when saying the bowl had \"chips that spoke of its long use\"?","choices":{"A":"The bowl could talk,","B":"The bowl was very new,","C":"The bowl was very old and used often,","D":"The bowl was made of plastic."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Chips\" in a bowl are small cracks from wear, showing it has been used for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The thick white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the author describe the sofa as bringing a \"piece of the garden\" inside? A. It has flowers on it, B. It is made of grass, C. It smells like dirt, D. It is kept outside in the garden.","excerpt":"\"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside the house.\"","stem":"Why does the author describe the sofa as bringing a \"piece of the garden\" inside?","choices":{"A":"It has flowers on it,","B":"It is made of grass,","C":"It smells like dirt,","D":"It is kept outside in the garden."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sofa is \"floral,\" meaning it has a pattern of flowers, which reminds the author of a garden.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside the house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"inseparable\" mean in this context? A. always arguing and fighting B. living in different countries C. never apart; unable to be split up D. growing older and wiser","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"What does \"inseparable\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"always arguing and fighting","B":"living in different countries","C":"never apart; unable to be split up","D":"growing older and wiser"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says they \"spent all their time together,\" which means they were always together and inseparable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happens right after they dry their hands? A. They cover their hands in soft butter. B. They eat the raw cookie dough. C. They wash the brass pot in the sink. D. They go to the dining room to read cards.","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers or burning their skin. Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy from the bowl and poured it onto their hands.\"","stem":"What happens right after they dry their hands?","choices":{"A":"They cover their hands in soft butter.","B":"They eat the raw cookie dough.","C":"They wash the brass pot in the sink.","D":"They go to the dining room to read cards."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sequence of events shows that right after drying their hands, they slather them with soft butter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers or burning their skin. Then, with a large wooden spoon, Abuelita scooped some taffy from the bowl and poured it onto their hands.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What does Abuelita say happens when someone you love goes away? A. You forget about them very quickly. B. You immediately start packing to follow them. C. You stop talking to your family members. D. You feel a mix of anger and sadness.","excerpt":"\"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away. One moment you are angry, then you become sad, and then it seems so unbelievable you almost erase it. Then, when you realize it is true, the anger and the sadness come back all over again...\"\"","stem":"What does Abuelita say happens when someone you love goes away?","choices":{"A":"You forget about them very quickly.","B":"You immediately start packing to follow them.","C":"You stop talking to your family members.","D":"You feel a mix of anger and sadness."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Abuelita describes the emotional stages of loss, specifically mentioning feeling angry and then sad.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away. One moment you are angry, then you become sad, and then it seems so unbelievable you almost erase it. Then, when you realize it is true, the anger and the sadness come back all over again...\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What holiday is coming up soon? A. Halloween B. Thanksgiving C. Easter D. Valentine\u0027s Day","excerpt":"\"\"Are you writing your Christmas cards already, Abuelita? It\u0027s not even Thanksgiving!\" Amalia was relieved to change the subject. \"What are the dry leaves for?\"\"","stem":"What holiday is coming up soon?","choices":{"A":"Halloween","B":"Thanksgiving","C":"Easter","D":"Valentine\u0027s Day"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia mentions that it is not even Thanksgiving yet, indicating that Thanksgiving is the upcoming holiday.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Are you writing your Christmas cards already, Abuelita? It\u0027s not even Thanksgiving!\" Amalia was relieved to change the subject. \"What are the dry leaves for?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why does Abuelita like to write her cards slowly? A. She wants to take her time to express her thoughts. B. She does not have enough ink to write quickly. C. She is waiting for the glue to dry on the envelopes. D. She wants Amalia to help her write the addresses.","excerpt":"\"\"I like writing my cards slowly,\" her grandmother replied as she picked up an unfinished card. \"That way I can really think about what I will write on each one. There are so many things I want to say.\"\"","stem":"Why does Abuelita like to write her cards slowly?","choices":{"A":"She wants to take her time to express her thoughts.","B":"She does not have enough ink to write quickly.","C":"She is waiting for the glue to dry on the envelopes.","D":"She wants Amalia to help her write the addresses."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Abuelita explains that writing slowly allows her to think carefully about her message and everything she wants to say.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I like writing my cards slowly,\" her grandmother replied as she picked up an unfinished card. \"That way I can really think about what I will write on each one. There are so many things I want to say.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"subtle\" mean in this sentence? A. Very bright and obvious B. Faint, delicate, and not too strong C. Dark and scary D. Loud and noisy","excerpt":"\"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\"","stem":"What does \"subtle\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Very bright and obvious","B":"Faint, delicate, and not too strong","C":"Dark and scary","D":"Loud and noisy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A subtle hint is light and not overpowering.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q012","read_aloud":"Her grandmother\u0027s voice was filled with understanding, and Amalia let out a great sigh. For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air. What happened after Amalia sighed? A. She laughed. B. There was silence, and the sunlight faded. C. She ran outside. D. Her grandmother left the room.","excerpt":"That must be difficult.","stem":"Her grandmother\u0027s voice was filled with understanding, and Amalia let out a great sigh. For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air. What happened after Amalia sighed?","choices":{"A":"She laughed.","B":"There was silence, and the sunlight faded.","C":"She ran outside.","D":"Her grandmother left the room."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says there was silence and the sunlight faded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: That must be difficult."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q013","read_aloud":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother asked as she lifted the old brass pot onto the kitchen table and poured the sticky melcocha into a bowl. What are Amalia and Abuelita about to do? a) A. Read a book B. Knead taffy (melcoch C. Go for a walk D. Watch television","excerpt":"Shall we knead the melcocha, then?","stem":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother asked as she lifted the old brass pot onto the kitchen table and poured the sticky melcocha into a bowl. What are Amalia and Abuelita about to do? a)","choices":{"A":"Read a book","B":"Knead taffy (melcoch","C":"Go for a walk","D":"Watch television"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita asks if they shall knead the melcocha.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Shall we knead the melcocha, then?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What day is it? A. Monday B. Friday C. Sunday D. Wednesday","excerpt":"\"They washed their hands thoroughly in the sink and dried them. Her grandmother\u0027s kitchen towels each had a day of the week embroidered in a different color. Since today was Friday, the cross‑stiched embroidery spelled VIERNES in azul marino, deep blue.\"","stem":"What day is it?","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Friday","C":"Sunday","D":"Wednesday"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The towel says VIERNES, which is Friday in Spanish.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They washed their hands thoroughly in the sink and dried them. Her grandmother\u0027s kitchen towels each had a day of the week embroidered in a different color. Since today was Friday, the cross‑stiched embroidery spelled VIERNES in azul marino, deep blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q015","read_aloud":"How does Abuelita teach Amalia? A. With strict lessons and tests B. Naturally, through everyday activities C. By sending her to school D. By yelling instructions","excerpt":"\"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week and the names of the colors in Spanish using these towels. Although her grandmother never seemed to be teaching, Amalia was frequently surprised when she realized how many things she had learned from Abuelita.\"","stem":"How does Abuelita teach Amalia?","choices":{"A":"With strict lessons and tests","B":"Naturally, through everyday activities","C":"By sending her to school","D":"By yelling instructions"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita teaches in a gentle, everyday way without seeming to teach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week and the names of the colors in Spanish using these towels. Although her grandmother never seemed to be teaching, Amalia was frequently surprised when she realized how many things she had learned from Abuelita.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q016","read_aloud":"* What does the word \"obvious\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"* What does the word \"obvious\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q017","read_aloud":"When does Amalia usually visit her grandmother? A. Every day, B. On Monday, C. On Friday afternoon, D. Once a month.","excerpt":"\"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\"","stem":"When does Amalia usually visit her grandmother?","choices":{"A":"Every day,","B":"On Monday,","C":"On Friday afternoon,","D":"Once a month."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that Amalia has been visiting her grandmother on Friday afternoons for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Why is Amalia sad? A. Her grandmother is moving, B. She has to move to California, C. Her best friend Martha is moving away, D. She forgot her homework.","excerpt":"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California.\"","stem":"Why is Amalia sad?","choices":{"A":"Her grandmother is moving,","B":"She has to move to California,","C":"Her best friend Martha is moving away,","D":"She forgot her homework."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Amalia is upset because her friend Martha is moving far away to California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Who is the first person to guess that something is wrong with Amalia? A. Martha, B. Amalia\u0027s mother, C. Amalia\u0027s grandmother, D. Amalia\u0027s teacher.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\"","stem":"Who is the first person to guess that something is wrong with Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Martha,","B":"Amalia\u0027s mother,","C":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother,","D":"Amalia\u0027s teacher."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The grandmother notices Amalia is quiet and asks her what is bothering her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today? Is she all right?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q020","read_aloud":"How does Amalia usually show she is upset? A. By crying loudly, B. By shaking her head, C. By running away, D. By yelling at her grandmother.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset, and her long black hair swept her shoulders.\"","stem":"How does Amalia usually show she is upset?","choices":{"A":"By crying loudly,","B":"By shaking her head,","C":"By running away,","D":"By yelling at her grandmother."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes Amalia shaking her head as something she \"frequently\" does when upset.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset, and her long black hair swept her shoulders.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q021","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean? A. Only once, B. Almost never, C. Very often, D. Only on Fridays.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Only once,","B":"Almost never,","C":"Very often,","D":"Only on Fridays."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Frequently\" means happening many times or very often.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness? A. She lost her hair ribbon, B. Her friend Martha is moving away, C. Her grandmother is busy, D. She does not like taffy.","excerpt":"\"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\"","stem":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness?","choices":{"A":"She lost her hair ribbon,","B":"Her friend Martha is moving away,","C":"Her grandmother is busy,","D":"She does not like taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that Martha\u0027s moving is the reason for Amalia\u0027s sadness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q023","read_aloud":"What does the floral sofa look like? A. Plain and brown, B. Covered in flowers, C. Made of wood, D. Very new.","excerpt":"\"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\"","stem":"What does the floral sofa look like?","choices":{"A":"Plain and brown,","B":"Covered in flowers,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Very new."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A \"floral\" pattern means it is covered in flowers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together? A. Cleaning the kitchen, B. Making taffy, C. Reading a book, D. Playing a game.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\"","stem":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together?","choices":{"A":"Cleaning the kitchen,","B":"Making taffy,","C":"Reading a book,","D":"Playing a game."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The actions of scooping and buttering clearly show they are making taffy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit? A. Amalia forgot her homework, B. Something is bothering Amalia, C. Martha is hiding, D. They ran out of taffy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\"","stem":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit?","choices":{"A":"Amalia forgot her homework,","B":"Something is bothering Amalia,","C":"Martha is hiding,","D":"They ran out of taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The grandmother asks questions because she sees that something is wrong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q001","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean? A. Only once, B. Almost never, C. Very often, D. Only on Fridays.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"frequently\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Only once,","B":"Almost never,","C":"Very often,","D":"Only on Fridays."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Frequently\" means happening many times or very often.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness? A. She lost her hair ribbon, B. Her friend Martha is moving away, C. Her grandmother is busy, D. She does not like taffy.","excerpt":"\"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\"","stem":"What is the cause of Amalia\u0027s sadness?","choices":{"A":"She lost her hair ribbon,","B":"Her friend Martha is moving away,","C":"Her grandmother is busy,","D":"She does not like taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that Martha\u0027s moving is the reason for Amalia\u0027s sadness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because Martha is moving away, Amalia is very sad.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What does the floral sofa look like? A. Plain and brown, B. Covered in flowers, C. Made of wood, D. Very new.","excerpt":"\"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\"","stem":"What does the floral sofa look like?","choices":{"A":"Plain and brown,","B":"Covered in flowers,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Very new."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A \"floral\" pattern means it is covered in flowers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The floral sofa brightened the room as if a piece of the garden had been brought inside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together? A. Cleaning the kitchen, B. Making taffy, C. Reading a book, D. Playing a game.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\"","stem":"What are Amalia and her grandmother doing together?","choices":{"A":"Cleaning the kitchen,","B":"Making taffy,","C":"Reading a book,","D":"Playing a game."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The actions of scooping and buttering clearly show they are making taffy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita scooped some taffy onto the buttered surface. Then she handed a portion to Amalia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit? A. Amalia forgot her homework, B. Something is bothering Amalia, C. Martha is hiding, D. They ran out of taffy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\"","stem":"What does Amalia\u0027s grandmother realize about the visit?","choices":{"A":"Amalia forgot her homework,","B":"Something is bothering Amalia,","C":"Martha is hiding,","D":"They ran out of taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The grandmother asks questions because she sees that something is wrong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued, \u0027Is it because Martha did not come with you today?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"reassuring\" mean? A. making someone feel scared and alone B. giving comfort; reminding someone not to worry C. asking a lot of difficult questions D. giving a gift to show love","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"What does \"reassuring\" mean?","choices":{"A":"making someone feel scared and alone","B":"giving comfort; reminding someone not to worry","C":"asking a lot of difficult questions","D":"giving a gift to show love"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s hugs and words are meant to comfort Amalia and make her feel safe, which is the definition of reassuring.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How does Amalia feel about talking about Martha\u0027s move? A. She wants to share her feelings with her grandmother. B. She is excited to plan a visit to California. C. She thinks her grandmother does not understand. D. She feels it makes her sadness even worse.","excerpt":"\"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation. It was bad enough that Martha had told her that she had a surprise and it had turned out to be that Martha was moving to California very soon... Talking about it only made Amalia feel worse.\"","stem":"How does Amalia feel about talking about Martha\u0027s move?","choices":{"A":"She wants to share her feelings with her grandmother.","B":"She is excited to plan a visit to California.","C":"She thinks her grandmother does not understand.","D":"She feels it makes her sadness even worse."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text explicitly states that talking about the move \"only made Amalia feel worse.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation. It was bad enough that Martha had told her that she had a surprise and it had turned out to be that Martha was moving to California very soon... Talking about it only made Amalia feel worse.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q008","read_aloud":"Why did Tío Manuel move to Mexico? A. To work on a movie set B. To help his uncle on the rancho C. To go to a university D. To visit his childhood friends","excerpt":"\"\"Your tío Manuel is quite a person, Amalia. When my brother, your great-uncle Felipe, said it was becoming hard for him to manage the old rancho alone, Manuel went back to Mexico, to help his uncle.\"","stem":"Why did Tío Manuel move to Mexico?","choices":{"A":"To work on a movie set","B":"To help his uncle on the rancho","C":"To go to a university","D":"To visit his childhood friends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita explains that Tío Manuel moved to Mexico to help his uncle manage the old rancho.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Your tío Manuel is quite a person, Amalia. When my brother, your great-uncle Felipe, said it was becoming hard for him to manage the old rancho alone, Manuel went back to Mexico, to help his uncle.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What does Amalia wish would happen? A. That Martha\u0027s move was just a bad dream B. That she could move to Mexico instead C. That her grandmother would bake more taffy D. That her father would pick her up early","excerpt":"\"Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake and they were not moving after all. And it would all disappear like bad dreams do in the morning.\"","stem":"What does Amalia wish would happen?","choices":{"A":"That Martha\u0027s move was just a bad dream","B":"That she could move to Mexico instead","C":"That her grandmother would bake more taffy","D":"That her father would pick her up early"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Amalia wishes the news was a mistake and compares the situation to a bad dream that disappears in the morning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake and they were not moving after all. And it would all disappear like bad dreams do in the morning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q010","read_aloud":"How does Abuelita\u0027s voice affect Amalia? A. It makes her feel angry and frustrated. B. It makes her feel sleepy and tired. C. It makes her feel sad and lonely. D. It makes her feel warm and comforted.","excerpt":"\"But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller, so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\"","stem":"How does Abuelita\u0027s voice affect Amalia?","choices":{"A":"It makes her feel angry and frustrated.","B":"It makes her feel sleepy and tired.","C":"It makes her feel sad and lonely.","D":"It makes her feel warm and comforted."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Even though she cannot be held, Amalia feels \"surrounded by the warmth\" of her grandmother\u0027s voice, showing she is comforted by it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller, so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"slathered\" mean in this sentence? A. Washed carefully B. Spread thickly C. Dried off D. Hid","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers or burning their skin.\"","stem":"What does \"slathered\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Washed carefully","B":"Spread thickly","C":"Dried off","D":"Hid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Slathered means spread thickly all over.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers or burning their skin.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What caused Amalia to frown? A. The taffy was too hot. B. Thinking about Martha moving away. C. The kitchen was messy. D. She lost her homework.","excerpt":"\"Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\"","stem":"What caused Amalia to frown?","choices":{"A":"The taffy was too hot.","B":"Thinking about Martha moving away.","C":"The kitchen was messy.","D":"She lost her homework."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Thinking about Martha made her frown.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What emotions does Abuelita describe feeling when someone goes away? A. Only happiness B. Anger, sadness, disbelief C. Fear and hunger D. Excitement and joy","excerpt":"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away. One moment you are angry, then you become sad, and then it seems so unbelievable you almost erase it.\"","stem":"What emotions does Abuelita describe feeling when someone goes away?","choices":{"A":"Only happiness","B":"Anger, sadness, disbelief","C":"Fear and hunger","D":"Excitement and joy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita lists anger, sadness, and disbelief.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away. One moment you are angry, then you become sad, and then it seems so unbelievable you almost erase it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q014","read_aloud":"her grandmother added. What does Abuelita mean by \"keep them close\"? A. Tie them with a rope B. Stay connected emotionally even when apart C. Never let them leave the house D. Take a photo only","excerpt":"But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,","stem":"her grandmother added. What does Abuelita mean by \"keep them close\"?","choices":{"A":"Tie them with a rope","B":"Stay connected emotionally even when apart","C":"Never let them leave the house","D":"Take a photo only"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Keeping close means staying connected in your heart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q017","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l03-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"brightened\" mean in this context? A. Made the room darker, B. Made the room look more cheerful or light, C. Cleaned the floor, D. Made the room colder.","excerpt":"\"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room...\"","stem":"What does \"brightened\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"Made the room darker,","B":"Made the room look more cheerful or light,","C":"Cleaned the floor,","D":"Made the room colder."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When something brightens a room, it adds color or light to make it feel more cheerful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They both sat on the floral sofa, which brightened the room...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why does Abuelita share this with Amalia? A. To show she is also sad, B. To make Amalia feel better by letting her know she is not alone, C. To brag about her past, D. To tell Amalia to stop crying.","excerpt":"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... I have gone through that many times.\"","stem":"Why does Abuelita share this with Amalia?","choices":{"A":"To show she is also sad,","B":"To make Amalia feel better by letting her know she is not alone,","C":"To brag about her past,","D":"To tell Amalia to stop crying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By sharing her own experiences, Abuelita shows Amalia that it is okay to be sad and that she understands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... I have gone through that many times.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q003","read_aloud":"What can we infer about their relationship? A. They do not know each other well, B. They are very close and the grandmother knows Amalia well, C. Amalia is afraid of her grandmother, D. They do not talk to each other.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\"","stem":"What can we infer about their relationship?","choices":{"A":"They do not know each other well,","B":"They are very close and the grandmother knows Amalia well,","C":"Amalia is afraid of her grandmother,","D":"They do not talk to each other."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that the grandmother can tell Amalia is hiding her feelings shows how well they know each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing, but her grandmother continued...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q004","read_aloud":"What can we learn about the bowl based on this description? A. It is a very expensive, new bowl, B. It is a sentimental object that has been part of their family for a long time, C. It is a bowl they bought at the store today, D. It is a bowl Amalia made in school.","excerpt":"\"The thick white porcelain bowl... had a few chips that spoke of its long use.\"","stem":"What can we learn about the bowl based on this description?","choices":{"A":"It is a very expensive, new bowl,","B":"It is a sentimental object that has been part of their family for a long time,","C":"It is a bowl they bought at the store today,","D":"It is a bowl Amalia made in school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The chips show that the bowl has been used over many years, implying it has deep meaning to the family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The thick white porcelain bowl... had a few chips that spoke of its long use.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q005","read_aloud":"If you had a friend moving away, how could you use the lesson Amalia learned to handle it? A. Talk to someone you trust about your feelings, B. Ignore your friend, C. Stay inside and never go out, D. Get angry at your friend.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"If you had a friend moving away, how could you use the lesson Amalia learned to handle it?","choices":{"A":"Talk to someone you trust about your feelings,","B":"Ignore your friend,","C":"Stay inside and never go out,","D":"Get angry at your friend."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Amalia found comfort by opening up to her grandmother, which is a good way to handle sadness.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"encompass\" mean? A. break into tiny pieces B. hide from plain sight C. surround or completely cover D. draw with a pencil","excerpt":"\"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\"","stem":"What does \"encompass\" mean?","choices":{"A":"break into tiny pieces","B":"hide from plain sight","C":"surround or completely cover","D":"draw with a pencil"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Abuelita moves her hands around the table as if to surround or encompass it, showing the size of the area she is describing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Amalia and her grandmother\u0027s relationship? A. They rarely spend time together. B. They have a close and comforting bond. C. They often argue about the past. D. They prefer to sit in silence.","excerpt":"\"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\"","stem":"What can you infer about Amalia and her grandmother\u0027s relationship?","choices":{"A":"They rarely spend time together.","B":"They have a close and comforting bond.","C":"They often argue about the past.","D":"They prefer to sit in silence."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia finds her grandmother\u0027s familiar stories \"comforting\" during a hard time, which shows they share a close, supportive bond.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q008","read_aloud":"How is Tío Patricio\u0027s situation similar to Martha\u0027s? A. They both moved far away from the people they love. B. They both moved to Mexico to work on a farm. C. They both moved because they were angry. D. They both moved to live with their grandparents.","excerpt":"\"\"He was very concerned about leaving me and moving away. However, I reminded him that we, too, had moved away, and sometimes that is necessary,\" Abuelita said. \"It\u0027s true that I gained a beautiful daughter-in-law and grandchildren, but it has been hard having my eldest child live so far from me.\"","stem":"How is Tío Patricio\u0027s situation similar to Martha\u0027s?","choices":{"A":"They both moved far away from the people they love.","B":"They both moved to Mexico to work on a farm.","C":"They both moved because they were angry.","D":"They both moved to live with their grandparents."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tío Patricio moved to Costa Rica and Martha is moving to California; both involve moving far away from loved ones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"He was very concerned about leaving me and moving away. However, I reminded him that we, too, had moved away, and sometimes that is necessary,\" Abuelita said. \"It\u0027s true that I gained a beautiful daughter-in-law and grandchildren, but it has been hard having my eldest child live so far from me.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If your best friend moved away, how could you use Abuelita\u0027s advice? A. By refusing to make any new friends B. By being angry at your friend for leaving C. By pretending the friendship never happened D. By remembering the good times and being open to new friendships","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"If your best friend moved away, how could you use Abuelita\u0027s advice?","choices":{"A":"By refusing to make any new friends","B":"By being angry at your friend for leaving","C":"By pretending the friendship never happened","D":"By remembering the good times and being open to new friendships"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s advice suggests that while things fade, new things can take their place, meaning one should cherish memories while remaining open to new experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the story of Amalia\u0027s aunt? A. To show that moving away can lead to achieving your dreams B. To prove that Mexico City is better than Hollywood C. To explain why Amalia\u0027s mother is sad D. To show that Amalia wants to be a costume designer","excerpt":"\"\"Here is another one who went back. My daughter is just so in love with Mexico City. She\u0027s been fascinated by dresses ever since she was a little girl... And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\"","stem":"Why does the author include the story of Amalia\u0027s aunt?","choices":{"A":"To show that moving away can lead to achieving your dreams","B":"To prove that Mexico City is better than Hollywood","C":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s mother is sad","D":"To show that Amalia wants to be a costume designer"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The aunt moved to follow her passion and found great success, illustrating that moving away can lead to fulfilling one\u0027s dreams.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Here is another one who went back. My daughter is just so in love with Mexico City. She\u0027s been fascinated by dresses ever since she was a little girl... And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Amalia feels about talking about Martha moving? A. She wants to talk about it all day. B. She is so upset she wants to stop talking about it. C. She thinks it is funny. D. She does not care.","excerpt":"\"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation. It was bad enough that Martha had told her that she had a surprise and it had turned out to be that Martha was moving to California very soon. Martha\u0027s leaving sounded so definite and permanent that she hated even the thought of it.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Amalia feels about talking about Martha moving?","choices":{"A":"She wants to talk about it all day.","B":"She is so upset she wants to stop talking about it.","C":"She thinks it is funny.","D":"She does not care."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She wants to end the conversation and hates thinking about it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation. It was bad enough that Martha had told her that she had a surprise and it had turned out to be that Martha was moving to California very soon. Martha\u0027s leaving sounded so definite and permanent that she hated even the thought of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How is Abuelita different from what Amalia imagines? A. Abuelita is mean. B. Abuelita seems calm, but she admits she has made mistakes. C. Abuelita never talks. D. Abuelita is a child.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita always looked so calm and sure. It was almost impossible to imagine her acting foolishly.\"","stem":"How is Abuelita different from what Amalia imagines?","choices":{"A":"Abuelita is mean.","B":"Abuelita seems calm, but she admits she has made mistakes.","C":"Abuelita never talks.","D":"Abuelita is a child."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia sees her as calm, but Abuelita says she has made mistakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita always looked so calm and sure. It was almost impossible to imagine her acting foolishly.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What is Abuelita saying about treasured things and people? A. They last forever unchanged. B. They change and may fade, but new things or memories may come. C. They always disappear and never come back. D. They are not important.","excerpt":"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"","stem":"What is Abuelita saying about treasured things and people?","choices":{"A":"They last forever unchanged.","B":"They change and may fade, but new things or memories may come.","C":"They always disappear and never come back.","D":"They are not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Life and relationships change, but new joys can appear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q014","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l04-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"slathered\" mean? A. Touched lightly, B. Spread thickly, C. Wiped off, D. Measured exactly.","excerpt":"\"...slathered them with soft butter...\"","stem":"What does \"slathered\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Touched lightly,","B":"Spread thickly,","C":"Wiped off,","D":"Measured exactly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Slathered\" means to spread something in a thick, generous layer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...slathered them with soft butter...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q002","read_aloud":"How does the visit differ from usual? A. There is no taffy, B. They are sitting on the floor instead of the sofa, C. Martha is not there, so the room feels different, D. The grandmother is not there.","excerpt":"\"Amalia was quiet... the room felt different without Martha\u0027s laughter.\"","stem":"How does the visit differ from usual?","choices":{"A":"There is no taffy,","B":"They are sitting on the floor instead of the sofa,","C":"Martha is not there, so the room feels different,","D":"The grandmother is not there."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text notes the absence of Martha and how that changes the atmosphere of the room.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia was quiet... the room felt different without Martha\u0027s laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What does this tell us about the grandmother\u0027s way of teaching? A. She uses objects from their daily life to teach, B. She is a school teacher, C. She only teaches when Amalia is very young, D. She does not like to teach.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week... using these towels.\"","stem":"What does this tell us about the grandmother\u0027s way of teaching?","choices":{"A":"She uses objects from their daily life to teach,","B":"She is a school teacher,","C":"She only teaches when Amalia is very young,","D":"She does not like to teach."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The grandmother uses household items like towels to teach Amalia things, showing her hands-on approach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week... using these towels.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author take time to describe the bowl? A. To make the story longer, B. To show that the setting is a cozy, lived-in home, C. To describe a bowl for sale, D. Because the bowl is a character.","excerpt":"\"The bowl... had a wide yellow rim.\"","stem":"Why does the author take time to describe the bowl?","choices":{"A":"To make the story longer,","B":"To show that the setting is a cozy, lived-in home,","C":"To describe a bowl for sale,","D":"Because the bowl is a character."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Small, specific details like this help the reader visualize the home and feel the warmth of the scene.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The bowl... had a wide yellow rim.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q005","read_aloud":"How does the setting of the kitchen contribute to the story? A. It is a place where they can work together and talk, B. It is where they store the homework, C. It is where they sleep, D. It is where the grandmother hides secrets.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How does the setting of the kitchen contribute to the story?","choices":{"A":"It is a place where they can work together and talk,","B":"It is where they store the homework,","C":"It is where they sleep,","D":"It is where the grandmother hides secrets."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Working on the taffy in the kitchen provides the perfect environment for their conversation.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q006","read_aloud":"You can tell me all about the people who sent them. What does \"enthusiasm\" mean? A. deep sadness; grief B. loud anger; frustration C. quiet boredom; sleepiness D. high interest; excitement","excerpt":"Today she did not feel much like listening, but making an effort to show some enthusiasm for her grandmother\u0027s offer, she added,","stem":"You can tell me all about the people who sent them. What does \"enthusiasm\" mean?","choices":{"A":"deep sadness; grief","B":"loud anger; frustration","C":"quiet boredom; sleepiness","D":"high interest; excitement"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Amalia is trying to show interest and excitement about her grandmother\u0027s stories, which is the definition of enthusiasm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Today she did not feel much like listening, but making an effort to show some enthusiasm for her grandmother\u0027s offer, she added,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What does Amalia\u0027s reaction to the taffy\u0027s color show about her? A. She is easily distracted by her surroundings. B. She is deeply connected to her friend Martha. C. She dislikes helping her grandmother cook. D. She is angry at the taffy for changing color.","excerpt":"\"Amalia had helped her grandmother pull the melcocha many times, but she never ceased to marvel at how the sweet taffy changed color just from being pulled, kneaded, and pulled again. It transformed from a deep dark brown into a light blond color, just like Martha\u0027s hair. Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\"","stem":"What does Amalia\u0027s reaction to the taffy\u0027s color show about her?","choices":{"A":"She is easily distracted by her surroundings.","B":"She is deeply connected to her friend Martha.","C":"She dislikes helping her grandmother cook.","D":"She is angry at the taffy for changing color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The taffy\u0027s color reminds Amalia of Martha\u0027s hair, showing how deeply her friend is on her mind and in her heart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia had helped her grandmother pull the melcocha many times, but she never ceased to marvel at how the sweet taffy changed color just from being pulled, kneaded, and pulled again. It transformed from a deep dark brown into a light blond color, just like Martha\u0027s hair. Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q008","read_aloud":"There is a poem I like very much. The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring. Why does Abuelita quote this poem? A. To teach Amalia about biology and trees B. To prove that autumn is the best season C. To show that endings can lead to new beginnings D. To explain why she saves dry leaves","excerpt":"Holding the leaves up one by one, she added,","stem":"There is a poem I like very much. The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring. Why does Abuelita quote this poem?","choices":{"A":"To teach Amalia about biology and trees","B":"To prove that autumn is the best season","C":"To show that endings can lead to new beginnings","D":"To explain why she saves dry leaves"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem describes a dry leaf as a \"promise of a distant spring,\" symbolizing that an ending is just the start of something new.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Holding the leaves up one by one, she added,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q009","read_aloud":"How does this description of the kitchen help the reader understand the story? A. It creates a warm, loving atmosphere for their conversation. B. It shows that the kitchen is cold and unwelcoming. C. It proves that Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a professional gardener. D. It shows that it is early morning and time for breakfast.","excerpt":"\"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\"","stem":"How does this description of the kitchen help the reader understand the story?","choices":{"A":"It creates a warm, loving atmosphere for their conversation.","B":"It shows that the kitchen is cold and unwelcoming.","C":"It proves that Amalia\u0027s grandmother is a professional gardener.","D":"It shows that it is early morning and time for breakfast."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The \"soft glow\" and \"hint of pink\" create a gentle, cozy, and loving setting for the emotional talk between Amalia and her grandmother.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What does the olive wood box symbolize in the story? A. Amalia\u0027s grandmother\u0027s wealth and expensive taste B. The delicious foods they cook together in the kitchen C. The family\u0027s history and their connections across distances D. Amalia\u0027s desire to move to a different state","excerpt":"\"On the lace tablecloth there was a stack of Christmas cards, several red and gold leaves, and a box made of beautiful olive wood that Amalia immediately recognized. Her grandmother used that box to save the special cards and letters sent by relatives and close friends.\"","stem":"What does the olive wood box symbolize in the story?","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s grandmother\u0027s wealth and expensive taste","B":"The delicious foods they cook together in the kitchen","C":"The family\u0027s history and their connections across distances","D":"Amalia\u0027s desire to move to a different state"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The box holds letters from faraway relatives, symbolizing the family\u0027s history and the love that connects them despite the distance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"On the lace tablecloth there was a stack of Christmas cards, several red and gold leaves, and a box made of beautiful olive wood that Amalia immediately recognized. Her grandmother used that box to save the special cards and letters sent by relatives and close friends.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q011","read_aloud":"Where does Abuelita suggest Amalia visit? A. Chicago B. Costa Rica C. California D. Mexico City","excerpt":"\"Someday you must go to Costa Rica, Amalia, and visit them. It is an amazing place.\"","stem":"Where does Abuelita suggest Amalia visit?","choices":{"A":"Chicago","B":"Costa Rica","C":"California","D":"Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita says she must go to Costa Rica.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Someday you must go to Costa Rica, Amalia, and visit them. It is an amazing place.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What does Abuelita\u0027s response teach about change? A. Change is always bad. B. Moving away is sometimes necessary, and families can adapt. C. You should never move. D. Only young people should move.","excerpt":"\"He was very concerned about leaving me and moving away. However, I reminded him that we, too, had moved away, and sometimes that is necessary.\"","stem":"What does Abuelita\u0027s response teach about change?","choices":{"A":"Change is always bad.","B":"Moving away is sometimes necessary, and families can adapt.","C":"You should never move.","D":"Only young people should move."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita accepts that moving is sometimes needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He was very concerned about leaving me and moving away. However, I reminded him that we, too, had moved away, and sometimes that is necessary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q013","read_aloud":"Why is hearing familiar stories comforting to Amalia? A. She hates stories. B. It reminds her of Abuelita\u0027s grandparents. C. Familiar stories are a source of stability when she feels shattered. D. She wants to become a storyteller.","excerpt":"\"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say.\"","stem":"Why is hearing familiar stories comforting to Amalia?","choices":{"A":"She hates stories.","B":"It reminds her of Abuelita\u0027s grandparents.","C":"Familiar stories are a source of stability when she feels shattered.","D":"She wants to become a storyteller."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Familiar stories bring comfort during painful change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia continued listening with interest. It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories. Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q014","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q016","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l05-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for \"convincing\"? A. True, B. Believable, C. Unlikely, D. Real.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing...\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for \"convincing\"?","choices":{"A":"True,","B":"Believable,","C":"Unlikely,","D":"Real."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Unlikely\" is an antonym for convincing because if something is unlikely, it is hard to believe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Why does the author tell us Amalia shakes her head? A. To describe a habit so we know she is upset without her saying it, B. To show she has a headache, C. To show she is trying to dance, D. To show she is dizzy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\"","stem":"Why does the author tell us Amalia shakes her head?","choices":{"A":"To describe a habit so we know she is upset without her saying it,","B":"To show she has a headache,","C":"To show she is trying to dance,","D":"To show she is dizzy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Writers use physical actions to show how characters feel without having to state it directly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head, as she frequently did when she was upset...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why is it important that Abuelita is the one to comfort Amalia? A. Because she is the only person who knows Martha, B. Because they have a bond of trust and long tradition, C. Because Amalia is afraid of her mother, D. Because Abuelita is a doctor.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Why is it important that Abuelita is the one to comfort Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Because she is the only person who knows Martha,","B":"Because they have a bond of trust and long tradition,","C":"Because Amalia is afraid of her mother,","D":"Because Abuelita is a doctor."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Their long history of visiting together creates a safe space for Amalia to share her feelings.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How does the word \"shattered\" emphasize Amalia\u0027s feelings? A. It shows she is feeling completely broken and devastated. B. It shows she is feeling excited and ready for a change. C. It shows she is feeling confused by her grandmother\u0027s words. D. It shows she is feeling hungry after making the taffy.","excerpt":"\"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say, as she had on other occasions...\"","stem":"How does the word \"shattered\" emphasize Amalia\u0027s feelings?","choices":{"A":"It shows she is feeling completely broken and devastated.","B":"It shows she is feeling excited and ready for a change.","C":"It shows she is feeling confused by her grandmother\u0027s words.","D":"It shows she is feeling hungry after making the taffy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Shattered\" is a strong word that emphasizes how deeply devastated and emotionally broken Amalia feels by the news.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say, as she had on other occasions...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why doesn\u0027t Abuelita pick Amalia up and hold her? A. Amalia is too old and heavy, and Abuelita is getting older. B. Abuelita is angry with Amalia for being sad. C. Amalia refuses to let her grandmother touch her. D. Abuelita\u0027s hands are covered in sticky taffy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller... But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller, so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\"","stem":"Why doesn\u0027t Abuelita pick Amalia up and hold her?","choices":{"A":"Amalia is too old and heavy, and Abuelita is getting older.","B":"Abuelita is angry with Amalia for being sad.","C":"Amalia refuses to let her grandmother touch her.","D":"Abuelita\u0027s hands are covered in sticky taffy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text notes that Amalia is \"bigger now\" and Abuelita is \"getting smaller,\" implying physical limitations due to age and growth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller... But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller, so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q006","read_aloud":"How does Amalia\u0027s current feeling contrast with Abuelita\u0027s memories? A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"How does Amalia\u0027s current feeling contrast with Abuelita\u0027s memories?","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q007","read_aloud":"How could you apply Abuelita\u0027s habit to your own life when a friend moves? A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"How could you apply Abuelita\u0027s habit to your own life when a friend moves?","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the detail about Abuelita being born on a kitchen table? A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Why does the author include the detail about Abuelita being born on a kitchen table?","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q009","read_aloud":"What does \"shattered\" mean in this sentence? A. Made her laugh B. Emotionally devastated or broken C. Fixed her problem D. Made her fall asleep","excerpt":"\"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say.\"","stem":"What does \"shattered\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Made her laugh","B":"Emotionally devastated or broken","C":"Fixed her problem","D":"Made her fall asleep"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Shattered emotionally means deeply hurt or broken.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q010","read_aloud":"What does the sparkle in Abuelita\u0027s eyes reveal about her feelings? A. She is bored. B. She is angry. C. She is happy and full of life when remembering. D. She is about to cry.","excerpt":"\"It seemed to Amalia that as her grandmother spoke of those distant memories, her eyes sparkled like the lake when the sun\u0027s rays hit it at midday.\"","stem":"What does the sparkle in Abuelita\u0027s eyes reveal about her feelings?","choices":{"A":"She is bored.","B":"She is angry.","C":"She is happy and full of life when remembering.","D":"She is about to cry."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Sparkling eyes show joy and fond memories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It seemed to Amalia that as her grandmother spoke of those distant memories, her eyes sparkled like the lake when the sun\u0027s rays hit it at midday.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What does this reveal about how Amalia sees herself and Abuelita changing? A. They are both growing larger. B. Amalia is growing up and Abuelita is aging. C. Nothing has changed. D. They have switched roles completely.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change. But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller.\"","stem":"What does this reveal about how Amalia sees herself and Abuelita changing?","choices":{"A":"They are both growing larger.","B":"Amalia is growing up and Abuelita is aging.","C":"Nothing has changed.","D":"They have switched roles completely."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is getting bigger; Abuelita seems smaller with age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change. But Amalia was bigger now, and Abuelita seemed to keep getting smaller.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What does Amalia feel she needs most right now? A. A new toy B. A sense of belonging and stability C. More homework D. A vacation","excerpt":"\"Reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"What does Amalia feel she needs most right now?","choices":{"A":"A new toy","B":"A sense of belonging and stability","C":"More homework","D":"A vacation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She needs to feel part of something lasting and secure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q013","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q014","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q015","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l06-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect. B. It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems. C. It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food. D. It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"Which choice gives the strongest evidence-based answer about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect.","B":"It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems.","C":"It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food.","D":"It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Reassuring\" means providing comfort and stability, showing that Abuelita is a safe emotional anchor for Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"floral\" mean? A. Made of wood, B. Having a flower pattern, C. Very old, D. Bright yellow.","excerpt":"\"The floral sofa brightened the room...\"","stem":"What does \"floral\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Made of wood,","B":"Having a flower pattern,","C":"Very old,","D":"Bright yellow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Floral\" means having a pattern of flowers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The floral sofa brightened the room...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What is Abuelita\u0027s role in this scene? A. She is a listener and a comforter, B. She is a teacher giving a test, C. She is a chef teaching a class, D. She is a stranger.","excerpt":"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away...\"","stem":"What is Abuelita\u0027s role in this scene?","choices":{"A":"She is a listener and a comforter,","B":"She is a teacher giving a test,","C":"She is a chef teaching a class,","D":"She is a stranger."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Abuelita is there to listen to Amalia and provide emotional support.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What can you tell about Amalia based on this sentence? A. She is young and has long hair, B. She is old, C. She is wearing a hat, D. She is a short-haired girl.","excerpt":"\"Amalia shook her head... her long black hair swept her shoulders.\"","stem":"What can you tell about Amalia based on this sentence?","choices":{"A":"She is young and has long hair,","B":"She is old,","C":"She is wearing a hat,","D":"She is a short-haired girl."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author describes her specific physical traits through her actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia shook her head... her long black hair swept her shoulders.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does the author show the passage of time? A. By mentioning the time of day and the progress of the taffy, B. By using a calendar, C. By having the characters leave the room, D. By not showing time passing at all.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How does the author show the passage of time?","choices":{"A":"By mentioning the time of day and the progress of the taffy,","B":"By using a calendar,","C":"By having the characters leave the room,","D":"By not showing time passing at all."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author mentions the sun setting and the step-by-step cooking process, which helps the reader follow the timeline.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q005","read_aloud":"What is the underlying theme of the story? A. Cooking is hard work, B. Friends should never move, C. Support from loved ones helps us deal with change, D. Grandmothers are always right.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"What is the underlying theme of the story?","choices":{"A":"Cooking is hard work,","B":"Friends should never move,","C":"Support from loved ones helps us deal with change,","D":"Grandmothers are always right."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The story centers on how Amalia receives help from her grandmother to cope with a big life change.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the word \"inseparable\" to describe Amalia\u0027s mother and aunt? A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the word \"inseparable\" to describe Amalia\u0027s mother and aunt?","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q007","read_aloud":"What theme is developed through Abuelita\u0027s actions? A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"What theme is developed through Abuelita\u0027s actions?","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What event interrupts the storytelling? A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"What event interrupts the storytelling?","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q009","read_aloud":"How does the aroma of the honey contribute to the mood of the scene? A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"How does the aroma of the honey contribute to the mood of the scene?","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q010","read_aloud":"If you were writing a story about losing a pet, what object could you use to represent this theme? A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"If you were writing a story about losing a pet, what object could you use to represent this theme?","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What motivates Amalia\u0027s aunt to live in Mexico City? A. She hates her family. B. She loves the city and has a passion for designing dresses. C. She was forced to move. D. She wants to be a farmer.","excerpt":"\"My daughter is just so in love with Mexico City. She\u0027s been fascinated by dresses ever since she was a little girl.\"","stem":"What motivates Amalia\u0027s aunt to live in Mexico City?","choices":{"A":"She hates her family.","B":"She loves the city and has a passion for designing dresses.","C":"She was forced to move.","D":"She wants to be a farmer."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her love for Mexico City and dress design keeps her there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My daughter is just so in love with Mexico City. She\u0027s been fascinated by dresses ever since she was a little girl.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q012","read_aloud":"Why did the sorrow come back? A. She remembered the taffy. B. The car ride was bumpy. C. She stopped listening to stories and thought about Martha again. D. She saw Martha\u0027s house.","excerpt":"\"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\"","stem":"Why did the sorrow come back?","choices":{"A":"She remembered the taffy.","B":"The car ride was bumpy.","C":"She stopped listening to stories and thought about Martha again.","D":"She saw Martha\u0027s house."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Without the distraction of stories, she returned to sad thoughts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q014","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q015","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q016","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q017","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l07-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect. B. It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems. C. It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food. D. It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect.","B":"It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems.","C":"It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food.","D":"It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Reassuring\" means providing comfort and stability, showing that Abuelita is a safe emotional anchor for Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"prevented\" mean? A. Allowed, B. Stopped from happening, C. Encouraged, D. Caused.","excerpt":"\"...which prevented the taffy from sticking...\"","stem":"What does \"prevented\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Allowed,","B":"Stopped from happening,","C":"Encouraged,","D":"Caused."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Prevented\" means to stop something from occurring.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...which prevented the taffy from sticking...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Is Amalia\u0027s reaction to her friend moving typical for her age? A. No, she should be happy, B. Yes, it is common to feel sad when a best friend moves away, C. No, she is acting like a baby, D. Yes, but only if she is angry.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Is Amalia\u0027s reaction to her friend moving typical for her age?","choices":{"A":"No, she should be happy,","B":"Yes, it is common to feel sad when a best friend moves away,","C":"No, she is acting like a baby,","D":"Yes, but only if she is angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is a normal human reaction to feel heartbroken when someone close to you leaves.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s choice of words, like \"heartbroken,\" help the reader? A. It shows us exactly how deeply Amalia is feeling, B. It makes the story sound funny, C. It tells us the story is about a medical problem, D. It shows that Amalia is sick.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How does the author\u0027s choice of words, like \"heartbroken,\" help the reader?","choices":{"A":"It shows us exactly how deeply Amalia is feeling,","B":"It makes the story sound funny,","C":"It tells us the story is about a medical problem,","D":"It shows that Amalia is sick."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Strong words like \"heartbroken\" help the reader understand the intensity of the character\u0027s emotions.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think making taffy is the best way to spend time with a sad grandchild? A. Yes, because it gives them something to do with their hands and a reason to talk, B. No, it\u0027s a waste of time, C. No, they should just watch TV, D. Yes, because taffy is healthy.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Do you think making taffy is the best way to spend time with a sad grandchild?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it gives them something to do with their hands and a reason to talk,","B":"No, it\u0027s a waste of time,","C":"No, they should just watch TV,","D":"Yes, because taffy is healthy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Shared activities can take the pressure off a person to talk, making it easier for them to share their feelings when they are ready.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q005","read_aloud":"How might the story be different if Martha had stayed? A. Amalia would not have felt the need to talk to her grandmother, B. The grandmother would be sad, C. They would be moving to California, D. The story would be about taffy only.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How might the story be different if Martha had stayed?","choices":{"A":"Amalia would not have felt the need to talk to her grandmother,","B":"The grandmother would be sad,","C":"They would be moving to California,","D":"The story would be about taffy only."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The main conflict is caused by the move, so if the friend stayed, the conversation about sadness would not have happened.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"reassuring\" help describe Abuelita\u0027s role in Amalia\u0027s life? A. It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect. B. It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems. C. It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food. D. It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"How does the word \"reassuring\" help describe Abuelita\u0027s role in Amalia\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect.","B":"It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems.","C":"It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food.","D":"It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Reassuring\" means providing comfort and stability, showing that Abuelita is a safe emotional anchor for Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author include these descriptive details at the beginning of the story? A. To show that it is time for Amalia to go to sleep B. To establish a gentle, loving setting for the emotional talk C. To prove that Abuelita has a lot of free time for gardening D. To distract the reader from the main conflict of the story","excerpt":"\"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\"","stem":"Why does the author include these descriptive details at the beginning of the story?","choices":{"A":"To show that it is time for Amalia to go to sleep","B":"To establish a gentle, loving setting for the emotional talk","C":"To prove that Abuelita has a lot of free time for gardening","D":"To distract the reader from the main conflict of the story"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The soft, pink lighting sets a gentle and loving tone, preparing the reader for the intimate and emotional conversation that follows.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s approach to helping Amalia is effective? A. No, because Amalia still feels sad when she gets in the car. B. No, because she avoids talking about Martha directly. C. Yes, because she gives Amalia tools and perspectives to cope with loss. D. Yes, because she forces Amalia to stop crying immediately.","excerpt":"\"\"But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added. And then, smiling as if having just gotten a new idea, she said, \"Ven. Come with me.\"\"","stem":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s approach to helping Amalia is effective?","choices":{"A":"No, because Amalia still feels sad when she gets in the car.","B":"No, because she avoids talking about Martha directly.","C":"Yes, because she gives Amalia tools and perspectives to cope with loss.","D":"Yes, because she forces Amalia to stop crying immediately."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Abuelita shares wisdom, stories, and tangible ways to remember loved ones, giving Amalia healthy tools to process her grief.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added. And then, smiling as if having just gotten a new idea, she said, \"Ven. Come with me.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Abuelita\u0027s view that things \"fade away\" but \"something else will take their place\"? A. No, because once a friendship ends, it is gone forever. B. Yes, because life brings new experiences and relationships to cherish. C. No, because it is better to hold onto the past than look forward. D. Yes, because people should never feel sad about losing things.","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Do you agree with Abuelita\u0027s view that things \"fade away\" but \"something else will take their place\"?","choices":{"A":"No, because once a friendship ends, it is gone forever.","B":"Yes, because life brings new experiences and relationships to cherish.","C":"No, because it is better to hold onto the past than look forward.","D":"Yes, because people should never feel sad about losing things."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s view is a healthy perspective on life; while we miss what is lost, new experiences and relationships eventually bring joy again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q010","read_aloud":"If you were to write the next scene, what action might Amalia take to \"stay close\" to Martha? A. She might throw away all of Martha\u0027s old letters. B. She might refuse to talk to her father for the rest of the ride. C. She might ask her father to drive them to California immediately. D. She might start a journal to write down her favorite memories with Martha.","excerpt":"\"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\"","stem":"If you were to write the next scene, what action might Amalia take to \"stay close\" to Martha?","choices":{"A":"She might throw away all of Martha\u0027s old letters.","B":"She might refuse to talk to her father for the rest of the ride.","C":"She might ask her father to drive them to California immediately.","D":"She might start a journal to write down her favorite memories with Martha."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Writing in a journal is a creative and healthy way for Amalia to preserve her memories and feel connected to Martha, honoring her grandmother\u0027s advice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q011","read_aloud":"If two friends are inseparable, they are ______. A. Always fighting B. Always together C. Never speaking D. Living in different cities","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two.\"","stem":"If two friends are inseparable, they are ______.","choices":{"A":"Always fighting","B":"Always together","C":"Never speaking","D":"Living in different cities"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Inseparable means always together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q012","read_aloud":"What change does the author suggest might happen? A. Amalia will never speak to Martha again. B. Amalia may learn to stay connected despite distance. C. Amalia will move away too. D. Amalia will forget Martha.","excerpt":"At the beginning, Amalia says, \"I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" At the end, Abuelita whispers, \"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\"","stem":"What change does the author suggest might happen?","choices":{"A":"Amalia will never speak to Martha again.","B":"Amalia may learn to stay connected despite distance.","C":"Amalia will move away too.","D":"Amalia will forget Martha."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s encouragement suggests Amalia will find a way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: At the beginning, Amalia says, \"I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" At the end, Abuelita whispers, \"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why do the authors include these family stories? A. To make the book longer B. To show that separation is common and people find ways to cope C. To confuse the reader D. To prove that moving is always bad","excerpt":"The authors include many stories about Abuelita\u0027s children and relatives.","stem":"Why do the authors include these family stories?","choices":{"A":"To make the book longer","B":"To show that separation is common and people find ways to cope","C":"To confuse the reader","D":"To prove that moving is always bad"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stories show that many family members live apart but stay connected.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The authors include many stories about Abuelita\u0027s children and relatives."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice is realistic and helpful? Why? A. No, because Martha is moving too far. B. Yes, because technology (phone, letters, visits) can keep friendships alive. C. No, because friends never stay friends after moving. D. Yes, but only for adults.","excerpt":"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\"","stem":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice is realistic and helpful? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because Martha is moving too far.","B":"Yes, because technology (phone, letters, visits) can keep friendships alive.","C":"No, because friends never stay friends after moving.","D":"Yes, but only for adults."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Modern communication makes staying close possible.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q016","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q017","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l08-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What is the best definition for \"chips\" in this context? A. Fried potatoes, B. Small broken pieces, C. Sounds made by birds, D. Something bought at a store.","excerpt":"\"The bowl... had a few chips that spoke of its long use.\"","stem":"What is the best definition for \"chips\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"Fried potatoes,","B":"Small broken pieces,","C":"Sounds made by birds,","D":"Something bought at a store."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Chips\" here refers to small pieces broken off the edge of the bowl.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The bowl... had a few chips that spoke of its long use.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q002","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author chose to have the grandmother share her own experiences with loss? A. To show that she is older than Amalia, B. To make her seem wise and relatable, C. To make the story about the grandmother, D. To show that everyone moves away.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Why do you think the author chose to have the grandmother share her own experiences with loss?","choices":{"A":"To show that she is older than Amalia,","B":"To make her seem wise and relatable,","C":"To make the story about the grandmother,","D":"To show that everyone moves away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It builds the grandmother\u0027s character as someone who has wisdom to share.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author connect the setting to the characters\u0027 emotions? A. By describing the room as warm and bright, which matches the comfort Amalia gets, B. By making the kitchen messy to show Amalia\u0027s mood, C. By having it rain during the whole story, D. By ignoring the setting entirely.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How does the author connect the setting to the characters\u0027 emotions?","choices":{"A":"By describing the room as warm and bright, which matches the comfort Amalia gets,","B":"By making the kitchen messy to show Amalia\u0027s mood,","C":"By having it rain during the whole story,","D":"By ignoring the setting entirely."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The \"soft glow\" and \"floral\" warmth mirror the comfort Amalia finds in her grandmother\u0027s care.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Does the author successfully build an emotional bond between the two characters? A. No, they never speak, B. Yes, by showing their shared tradition and the grandmother\u0027s empathy, C. No, Amalia leaves early, D. Yes, by having them fight.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Does the author successfully build an emotional bond between the two characters?","choices":{"A":"No, they never speak,","B":"Yes, by showing their shared tradition and the grandmother\u0027s empathy,","C":"No, Amalia leaves early,","D":"Yes, by having them fight."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The actions and dialogue create a clear sense of a loving, supportive relationship.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q005","read_aloud":"If you were writing this story, what other detail could you add to show Amalia\u0027s sadness? A. Describe her throwing the taffy, B. Describe her looking at a photo of Martha, C. Describe her going to sleep, D. Describe her playing with a dog.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"If you were writing this story, what other detail could you add to show Amalia\u0027s sadness?","choices":{"A":"Describe her throwing the taffy,","B":"Describe her looking at a photo of Martha,","C":"Describe her going to sleep,","D":"Describe her playing with a dog."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Looking at a photo would be a clear, visual way to show she misses her friend.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"encompass\" enhance the imagery of this scene? A. It paints a picture of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the memory. B. It shows that Abuelita is trying to hide the table. C. It proves that the table is too small for their activities. D. It shows that Amalia is confused by her grandmother\u0027s gestures.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\"","stem":"How does the word \"encompass\" enhance the imagery of this scene?","choices":{"A":"It paints a picture of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the memory.","B":"It shows that Abuelita is trying to hide the table.","C":"It proves that the table is too small for their activities.","D":"It shows that Amalia is confused by her grandmother\u0027s gestures."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Encompass\" means to surround, creating a vivid image of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the table and the memories it holds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How does the author show Amalia\u0027s emotional maturity in this moment? A. By showing her ability to accept the situation immediately B. By showing her realistic, albeit painful, defensive reaction to loss C. By showing her excitement about making new friends D. By showing her deep understanding of Abuelita\u0027s wisdom","excerpt":"\"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation... Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake... Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\"","stem":"How does the author show Amalia\u0027s emotional maturity in this moment?","choices":{"A":"By showing her ability to accept the situation immediately","B":"By showing her realistic, albeit painful, defensive reaction to loss","C":"By showing her excitement about making new friends","D":"By showing her deep understanding of Abuelita\u0027s wisdom"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia\u0027s thought process shows a realistic defense mechanism; she is trying to protect herself from the pain of loss by acting like she doesn\u0027t care.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation... Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake... Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q008","read_aloud":"How does the aunt\u0027s story in Mexico City connect to the story\u0027s main theme? A. It shows that moving far away can lead to personal and professional fulfillment. B. It proves that Hollywood is not a good place for artists. C. It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother is jealous of her sister. D. It explains why Amalia wants to move to Mexico.","excerpt":"\"\"And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\"","stem":"How does the aunt\u0027s story in Mexico City connect to the story\u0027s main theme?","choices":{"A":"It shows that moving far away can lead to personal and professional fulfillment.","B":"It proves that Hollywood is not a good place for artists.","C":"It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother is jealous of her sister.","D":"It explains why Amalia wants to move to Mexico."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The aunt moved far away to follow her passion and found great success, reinforcing the theme that distance can lead to positive growth and fulfillment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q009","read_aloud":"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow... Is Amalia\u0027s reaction to her grandmother\u0027s whisper realistic? A. No, because she should be completely happy and comforted. B. No, because she does not love her grandmother enough to listen. C. Yes, because she is angry that her grandmother hugged her. D. Yes, because grief comes in waves and comfort doesn\u0027t erase sadness instantly.","excerpt":"As Amalia was leaving, her grandmother hugged her and whispered in her ear,","stem":"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow... Is Amalia\u0027s reaction to her grandmother\u0027s whisper realistic?","choices":{"A":"No, because she should be completely happy and comforted.","B":"No, because she does not love her grandmother enough to listen.","C":"Yes, because she is angry that her grandmother hugged her.","D":"Yes, because grief comes in waves and comfort doesn\u0027t erase sadness instantly."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"It is highly realistic that Amalia feels sorrow again; grief is a process, and a comforting conversation does not instantly erase the pain of a friend moving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Amalia was leaving, her grandmother hugged her and whispered in her ear,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If you were to design a care package for a friend who moved away, inspired by Abuelita, what would you include and why? A. A new video game so they can play it every day B. A pressed flower from your garden to remind them of your shared walks C. A map of their new city so they can stop feeling lost D. A dictionary so they can learn a new language","excerpt":"\"\"I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card... I have gathered some of this autumn\u0027s leaves to remind them of those times.\"\"","stem":"If you were to design a care package for a friend who moved away, inspired by Abuelita, what would you include and why?","choices":{"A":"A new video game so they can play it every day","B":"A pressed flower from your garden to remind them of your shared walks","C":"A map of their new city so they can stop feeling lost","D":"A dictionary so they can learn a new language"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A pressed flower mirrors Abuelita\u0027s leaves, serving as a tangible, natural reminder of shared memories and home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card... I have gathered some of this autumn\u0027s leaves to remind them of those times.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"rancho\" mean? A. A city skyscraper B. A ranch or farm C. A school D. A car","excerpt":"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho.\"","stem":"What does \"rancho\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A city skyscraper","B":"A ranch or farm","C":"A school","D":"A car"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rancho means ranch or farm in Spanish.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think admitting mistakes makes Abuelita more or less believable as a character? Why? A. Less believable, because grandmothers are perfect. B. More believable, because all real people make mistakes. C. Less believable, because she never actually makes mistakes in the story. D. More believable, because she is bragging.","excerpt":"Abuelita says, \"I have made terrible mistakes in my life when I didn\u0027t think before speaking.\"","stem":"Do you think admitting mistakes makes Abuelita more or less believable as a character? Why?","choices":{"A":"Less believable, because grandmothers are perfect.","B":"More believable, because all real people make mistakes.","C":"Less believable, because she never actually makes mistakes in the story.","D":"More believable, because she is bragging."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Flaws make characters realistic and relatable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Abuelita says, \"I have made terrible mistakes in my life when I didn\u0027t think before speaking.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q013","read_aloud":"What theme does this quote support? A. Things ending are only sad. B. Endings can also be beginnings or promises of new life. C. Leaves are not important. D. Winter is forever.","excerpt":"Abuelita says, \"The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring.\"","stem":"What theme does this quote support?","choices":{"A":"Things ending are only sad.","B":"Endings can also be beginnings or promises of new life.","C":"Leaves are not important.","D":"Winter is forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dry leaf (ending) promises spring (new beginning).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Abuelita says, \"The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Is this an effective use of imagery? Why? A. No, because lakes are not related to eyes. B. Yes, because it creates a vivid, happy picture of Abuelita\u0027s joy. C. No, because it is too long. D. Yes, because it uses difficult words.","excerpt":"\"It seemed to Amalia that as her grandmother spoke of those distant memories, her eyes sparkled like the lake when the sun\u0027s rays hit it at midday.\"","stem":"Is this an effective use of imagery? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because lakes are not related to eyes.","B":"Yes, because it creates a vivid, happy picture of Abuelita\u0027s joy.","C":"No, because it is too long.","D":"Yes, because it uses difficult words."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The simile helps readers see and feel Abuelita\u0027s happiness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It seemed to Amalia that as her grandmother spoke of those distant memories, her eyes sparkled like the lake when the sun\u0027s rays hit it at midday.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q015","read_aloud":"What could the authors add to this excerpt to help readers better understand Amalia\u0027s sadness about Martha? A. A flashback of a fun day Amalia and Martha shared B. A recipe for taffy C. A map of Chicago D. A list of chores","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"What could the authors add to this excerpt to help readers better understand Amalia\u0027s sadness about Martha?","choices":{"A":"A flashback of a fun day Amalia and Martha shared","B":"A recipe for taffy","C":"A map of Chicago","D":"A list of chores"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Showing a happy memory would make her loss feel more real.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q018","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l09-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"sticking\"? A. Falling, B. Adhering or clinging, C. Cleaning, D. Drying.","excerpt":"\"...which prevented the taffy from sticking...\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"sticking\"?","choices":{"A":"Falling,","B":"Adhering or clinging,","C":"Cleaning,","D":"Drying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To \"stick\" means to cling or adhere to a surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...which prevented the taffy from sticking...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q002","read_aloud":"Why is the fact that Amalia has been visiting since she was little so important? A. It shows this is a permanent and reliable part of her life, B. It shows she lives with her grandmother, C. It shows she does not have other friends, D. It shows she is bored.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Why is the fact that Amalia has been visiting since she was little so important?","choices":{"A":"It shows this is a permanent and reliable part of her life,","B":"It shows she lives with her grandmother,","C":"It shows she does not have other friends,","D":"It shows she is bored."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"It emphasizes the stability and trust in their relationship, which contrasts with the instability caused by her friend moving away.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q003","read_aloud":"How could this story change if it were told from the grandmother\u0027s point of view? A. We would understand how she worries about Amalia, B. We would know more about Martha, C. It would be shorter, D. It would have no dialogue.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"How could this story change if it were told from the grandmother\u0027s point of view?","choices":{"A":"We would understand how she worries about Amalia,","B":"We would know more about Martha,","C":"It would be shorter,","D":"It would have no dialogue."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Seeing the story through the grandmother\u0027s eyes would reveal her empathy and concern for Amalia\u0027s feelings.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q004","read_aloud":"You can tell me all about the people who sent them. How does Amalia\u0027s lack of \"enthusiasm\" reveal her character development? A. It shows she is naturally a grumpy and rude child. B. It shows she dislikes her family\u0027s history and stories. C. It shows she is genuinely hurting but still trying to be respectful. D. It shows she is too tired from making the taffy.","excerpt":"Today she did not feel much like listening, but making an effort to show some enthusiasm for her grandmother\u0027s offer, she added,","stem":"You can tell me all about the people who sent them. How does Amalia\u0027s lack of \"enthusiasm\" reveal her character development?","choices":{"A":"It shows she is naturally a grumpy and rude child.","B":"It shows she dislikes her family\u0027s history and stories.","C":"It shows she is genuinely hurting but still trying to be respectful.","D":"It shows she is too tired from making the taffy."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Amalia is deeply sad, but she still makes an \"effort\" to show interest, revealing that she is empathetic and respectful despite her own pain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Today she did not feel much like listening, but making an effort to show some enthusiasm for her grandmother\u0027s offer, she added,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q005","read_aloud":"How does the theme of connection across distance develop throughout the text? A. It shifts from Amalia\u0027s fear of losing Martha to understanding that love persists through memories. B. It shifts from Amalia wanting to move away to wanting to stay in Chicago forever. C. It shifts from Abuelita being sad to Amalia being happy about the move. D. It shifts from focusing on family members to focusing on school friends.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away... Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received... This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"How does the theme of connection across distance develop throughout the text?","choices":{"A":"It shifts from Amalia\u0027s fear of losing Martha to understanding that love persists through memories.","B":"It shifts from Amalia wanting to move away to wanting to stay in Chicago forever.","C":"It shifts from Abuelita being sad to Amalia being happy about the move.","D":"It shifts from focusing on family members to focusing on school friends."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The theme evolves as Amalia listens to her grandmother and begins to understand that physical distance does not erase emotional connections.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away... Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received... This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Why is the story of the mother and aunt important to the overall message? A. It proves that sisters always fight when they grow up. B. It provides a historical parallel to Amalia\u0027s current friendship with Martha. C. It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother never moved away from Chicago. D. It explains why Amalia\u0027s grandmother lives alone.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\"","stem":"Why is the story of the mother and aunt important to the overall message?","choices":{"A":"It proves that sisters always fight when they grow up.","B":"It provides a historical parallel to Amalia\u0027s current friendship with Martha.","C":"It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother never moved away from Chicago.","D":"It explains why Amalia\u0027s grandmother lives alone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story of the mother and aunt being inseparable mirrors Amalia and Martha\u0027s friendship, showing that close bonds are a family tradition that transcends time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Considering the entire selection, has Amalia\u0027s visit to her grandmother been a success? A. No, because she is still sad and angry in the car. B. Yes, because Abuelita has planted seeds of wisdom that Amalia will eventually understand. C. No, because Amalia refused to eat the taffy or look at the cards. D. Yes, because Amalia immediately called Martha to say goodbye.","excerpt":"\"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories. Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\"","stem":"Considering the entire selection, has Amalia\u0027s visit to her grandmother been a success?","choices":{"A":"No, because she is still sad and angry in the car.","B":"Yes, because Abuelita has planted seeds of wisdom that Amalia will eventually understand.","C":"No, because Amalia refused to eat the taffy or look at the cards.","D":"Yes, because Amalia immediately called Martha to say goodbye."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Though Amalia is still sad, the visit was a success because Abuelita provided her with the wisdom, comfort, and tools she will need to eventually cope with the move.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories. Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q008","read_aloud":"If you were to write a letter from Amalia to Martha a month later, what two elements from Abuelita\u0027s advice would Amalia likely include? A. A complaint about how boring Chicago is without her B. A pressed leaf from her neighborhood and a memory of a time they played together C. A list of all the new friends she has made and why they are better D. A request for Martha to send her a new doll from California","excerpt":"\"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\"\"","stem":"If you were to write a letter from Amalia to Martha a month later, what two elements from Abuelita\u0027s advice would Amalia likely include?","choices":{"A":"A complaint about how boring Chicago is without her","B":"A pressed leaf from her neighborhood and a memory of a time they played together","C":"A list of all the new friends she has made and why they are better","D":"A request for Martha to send her a new doll from California"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Inspired by Abuelita, Amalia would likely include a natural memento (like a leaf) and a shared memory to maintain their emotional connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q009","read_aloud":"What does \"tio\" mean in Spanish? A. Uncle B. Aunt C. Grandmother D. Friend","excerpt":"\"Your tio Manuel is quite a person, Amalia.\"","stem":"What does \"tio\" mean in Spanish?","choices":{"A":"Uncle","B":"Aunt","C":"Grandmother","D":"Friend"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tío means uncle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Your tio Manuel is quite a person, Amalia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q010","read_aloud":"What common idea do these stories share? A. , her son Manuel (Mexico), and her daughter (Mexico City). B. All her children moved away for love or purpose, and she found ways to stay connected. C. All her children failed in life. D. Abuelita forced them to leave.","excerpt":"Review Abuelita\u0027s stories about her son Patricio (Costa Ric","stem":"What common idea do these stories share?","choices":{"A":", her son Manuel (Mexico), and her daughter (Mexico City).","B":"All her children moved away for love or purpose, and she found ways to stay connected.","C":"All her children failed in life.","D":"Abuelita forced them to leave."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each child moved, but Abuelita keeps them close through memory and cards.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Review Abuelita\u0027s stories about her son Patricio (Costa Ric"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q011","read_aloud":"How does this point of view affect the reader? A. We know everyone\u0027s thoughts. B. We know only Amalia\u0027s thoughts and feelings. C. We know only Abuelita\u0027s thoughts. D. We know no one\u0027s thoughts.","excerpt":"The story is told from Amalia\u0027s third-person limited point of view.","stem":"How does this point of view affect the reader?","choices":{"A":"We know everyone\u0027s thoughts.","B":"We know only Amalia\u0027s thoughts and feelings.","C":"We know only Abuelita\u0027s thoughts.","D":"We know no one\u0027s thoughts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Third‑person limited follows one character\u0027s perspective.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The story is told from Amalia\u0027s third-person limited point of view."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q012","read_aloud":"If you were to write a sequel set one month after Martha moves, what would be a good title? A. \"Taffy Recipes for Beginners\" B. \"Finding a Way to Stay Close\" C. \"The Worst Day Ever\" D. \"How to Build a Cardboard Box\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you were to write a sequel set one month after Martha moves, what would be a good title?","choices":{"A":"\"Taffy Recipes for Beginners\"","B":"\"Finding a Way to Stay Close\"","C":"\"The Worst Day Ever\"","D":"\"How to Build a Cardboard Box\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story is about finding connection despite distance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think Abuelita is a wise character? Why? A. No, because she makes mistakes. B. Yes, because she learns from mistakes and teaches Amalia how to cope with loss. C. No, because she talks too much. D. Yes, because she knows how to cook taffy.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"Do you think Abuelita is a wise character? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because she makes mistakes.","B":"Yes, because she learns from mistakes and teaches Amalia how to cope with loss.","C":"No, because she talks too much.","D":"Yes, because she knows how to cook taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wisdom comes from learning and sharing helpful lessons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q015","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q016","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q019","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q021","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q022","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q023","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q024","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-l10-q025","read_aloud":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"Which choice most clearly connects the evidence to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q001","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"glow\"? A. Darkness, B. Radiance/Light, C. Heat, D. Noise.","excerpt":"\"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"glow\"?","choices":{"A":"Darkness,","B":"Radiance/Light,","C":"Heat,","D":"Noise."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A glow is a soft, steady light.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q002","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for \"convincing\"? A. Trustworthy, B. Doubtful, C. Realistic, D. Clear.","excerpt":"\"Amalia tried to sound convincing...\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for \"convincing\"?","choices":{"A":"Trustworthy,","B":"Doubtful,","C":"Realistic,","D":"Clear."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If something is not convincing, it is doubtful or hard to believe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia tried to sound convincing...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q003","read_aloud":"In this story, what is \"Abuelita\"? A. A type of kitchen tool, B. A Spanish word for grandmother, C. A brand of butter, D. A day of the week.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week... using these towels.\"","stem":"In this story, what is \"Abuelita\"?","choices":{"A":"A type of kitchen tool,","B":"A Spanish word for grandmother,","C":"A brand of butter,","D":"A day of the week."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Throughout the story, Amalia calls her grandmother \"Abuelita.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita had taught Amalia the days of the week... using these towels.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q004","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Abuelita? A. She has never moved, B. She understands how Amalia feels because she has also lost people, C. She does not care about Amalia\u0027s problems, D. She is happy that Martha is moving.","excerpt":"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... I have gone through that many times.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Abuelita?","choices":{"A":"She has never moved,","B":"She understands how Amalia feels because she has also lost people,","C":"She does not care about Amalia\u0027s problems,","D":"She is happy that Martha is moving."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita shares that she has also felt the sadness of losing loved ones, which helps her comfort Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... I have gone through that many times.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q005","read_aloud":"What does this tell us about Amalia and her grandmother? A. They do not like each other, B. They have a long-standing, close tradition, C. They only meet when it\u0027s necessary, D. They are strangers.","excerpt":"\"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\"","stem":"What does this tell us about Amalia and her grandmother?","choices":{"A":"They do not like each other,","B":"They have a long-standing, close tradition,","C":"They only meet when it\u0027s necessary,","D":"They are strangers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Having a routine visit since she was little shows a strong, established connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Going to her grandmother\u0027s home on Friday afternoon was something Amalia had been doing since she was little.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q006","read_aloud":"Why did they put butter on their hands? A. To make the taffy taste better, B. To keep the taffy from sticking to their skin, C. To clean their hands, D. To cool down the taffy.","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers...\"","stem":"Why did they put butter on their hands?","choices":{"A":"To make the taffy taste better,","B":"To keep the taffy from sticking to their skin,","C":"To clean their hands,","D":"To cool down the taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that the butter \"prevented the taffy from sticking.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter, which prevented the taffy from sticking to their fingers...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q007","read_aloud":"Why does Amalia frown when thinking of Martha? A. Because she is mad at Martha, B. Because Martha told a bad joke, C. Because thinking of Martha reminds her that she is moving away, D. Because Amalia wants to be alone.","excerpt":"\"Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\"","stem":"Why does Amalia frown when thinking of Martha?","choices":{"A":"Because she is mad at Martha,","B":"Because Martha told a bad joke,","C":"Because thinking of Martha reminds her that she is moving away,","D":"Because Amalia wants to be alone."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The story established that Martha\u0027s move is making Amalia sad, and thinking about it causes her to feel that sadness again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Thinking about Martha made Amalia frown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q008","read_aloud":"If you were Amalia\u0027s friend moving away, what is one thing you could do to keep your friendship strong, based on the themes in the story? A. Stop talking to her, B. Write letters or share pictures like Abuelita does, C. Move back without telling anyone, D. Pretend nothing happened.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"If you were Amalia\u0027s friend moving away, what is one thing you could do to keep your friendship strong, based on the themes in the story?","choices":{"A":"Stop talking to her,","B":"Write letters or share pictures like Abuelita does,","C":"Move back without telling anyone,","D":"Pretend nothing happened."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita teaches Amalia that stories, cards, and pictures help people feel close even when they are far apart.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the scene of making the taffy? A. To show a recipe for taffy, B. To provide a calm setting for the characters to talk about their feelings, C. To show that Amalia is a professional cook, D. To show that cooking is dangerous.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Why does the author include the scene of making the taffy?","choices":{"A":"To show a recipe for taffy,","B":"To provide a calm setting for the characters to talk about their feelings,","C":"To show that Amalia is a professional cook,","D":"To show that cooking is dangerous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The cooking activity serves as a background setting that allows Abuelita to comfort Amalia and share her wisdom.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice to Amalia was helpful? Why? A. No, because she just made taffy, B. Yes, because she listened to Amalia and shared her own experience, C. No, because she told Amalia to stop crying, D. Yes, because she gave Amalia money.","excerpt":"from Love, Amalia includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How does Amalia\u0027s grandmother help her face change?","stem":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice to Amalia was helpful? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because she just made taffy,","B":"Yes, because she listened to Amalia and shared her own experience,","C":"No, because she told Amalia to stop crying,","D":"Yes, because she gave Amalia money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita validates Amalia\u0027s feelings and shares her own experiences to show she understands, which is a supportive way to help someone grieving. Section A - Text Information Title: \"from Love, Amalia\" Author: Alma Flor Ada and Gabriel M. Zubizarreta","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"shattered\" mean in this context? A. deeply hurt and broken emotionally B. excited and full of energy C. confused and distracted D. hungry and tired","excerpt":"\"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\"","stem":"What does \"shattered\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"deeply hurt and broken emotionally","B":"excited and full of energy","C":"confused and distracted","D":"hungry and tired"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Amalia is devastated by the news of Martha moving, so \"shattered\" means emotionally broken.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Especially today, after Martha\u0027s announcement had shattered her, it was good to hear once again the words she had anticipated Abuelita would say...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"inseparable\"? A. distant B. close C. angry D. forgetful","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"inseparable\"?","choices":{"A":"distant","B":"close","C":"angry","D":"forgetful"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" means always together, which is a synonym for being very close.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q013","read_aloud":"How is \"encompass\" used in this sentence? A. To describe breaking the table into pieces B. To describe cleaning the table quickly C. To describe hiding objects under the table D. To describe surrounding or covering an area","excerpt":"\"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\"","stem":"How is \"encompass\" used in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To describe breaking the table into pieces","B":"To describe cleaning the table quickly","C":"To describe hiding objects under the table","D":"To describe surrounding or covering an area"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Abuelita uses her hands to gesture around the table, meaning to surround or encompass the space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of Abuelita\u0027s message to Amalia? A. Moving away is the hardest thing a person can do. B. You can maintain emotional connections even when people move. C. You should never let your loved ones move far away. D. The best way to cope is to stop thinking about the person.","excerpt":"\"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of Abuelita\u0027s message to Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Moving away is the hardest thing a person can do.","B":"You can maintain emotional connections even when people move.","C":"You should never let your loved ones move far away.","D":"The best way to cope is to stop thinking about the person."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s main message is that physical distance does not mean you have to lose your emotional connection to someone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I know how hard it is when someone you love goes away... But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q015","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt reveal about Amalia and Abuelita\u0027s relationship? A. They are distant and rarely show affection. B. They share a deep, comforting bond despite Amalia growing up. C. They are frustrated with each other\u0027s generations. D. They only interact when they are making taffy.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller... But Amalia was bigger now... so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt reveal about Amalia and Abuelita\u0027s relationship?","choices":{"A":"They are distant and rarely show affection.","B":"They share a deep, comforting bond despite Amalia growing up.","C":"They are frustrated with each other\u0027s generations.","D":"They only interact when they are making taffy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even though they cannot hug like they used to, Amalia still finds deep comfort in her grandmother\u0027s presence and voice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller... But Amalia was bigger now... so Amalia just let herself feel surrounded by the warmth of her grandmother\u0027s voice.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q016","read_aloud":"What do the dry leaves symbolize in the story? A. The end of life and the inevitability of death B. The changing of seasons and the beauty of nature C. That endings can lead to new beginnings and hope D. That Amalia\u0027s grandmother needs to clean her yard","excerpt":"\"\"There is a poem I like very much. The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring.\"\"","stem":"What do the dry leaves symbolize in the story?","choices":{"A":"The end of life and the inevitability of death","B":"The changing of seasons and the beauty of nature","C":"That endings can lead to new beginnings and hope","D":"That Amalia\u0027s grandmother needs to clean her yard"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The dry leaf is a \"prelude\" to spring, symbolizing that an ending is just the beginning of something new and hopeful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"There is a poem I like very much. The poet says that a dry leaf is not an elegy, a song of death, but rather a prelude, a promise of a distant spring.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q017","read_aloud":"Where do Amalia and Martha live? A. California B. Mexico City C. Costa Rica D. Chicago","excerpt":"\"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago!\"","stem":"Where do Amalia and Martha live?","choices":{"A":"California","B":"Mexico City","C":"Costa Rica","D":"Chicago"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Amalia notes that California is far away from their current home of Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Martha is going away. Her family is moving west, to some weird place in California. So far away from Chicago!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q018","read_aloud":"Why does Amalia feel upset in the kitchen? A. She burned the taffy on the stove. B. She is heartbroken about her best friend moving. C. She is angry at her grandmother for asking questions. D. She is worried about her school grades.","excerpt":"\"Today she was too upset to see anything but the heavy bowl.\"","stem":"Why does Amalia feel upset in the kitchen?","choices":{"A":"She burned the taffy on the stove.","B":"She is heartbroken about her best friend moving.","C":"She is angry at her grandmother for asking questions.","D":"She is worried about her school grades."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia\u0027s heaviness and upset feelings stem from the news that her best friend Martha is moving away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today she was too upset to see anything but the heavy bowl.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q019","read_aloud":"How does Abuelita\u0027s habit of reading old cards help her cope with distance? A. It reminds her that her loved ones still care about her. B. It helps her memorize the addresses for the post office. C. It allows her to critique their handwriting and spelling. D. It proves that she has more friends than Amalia does.","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"How does Abuelita\u0027s habit of reading old cards help her cope with distance?","choices":{"A":"It reminds her that her loved ones still care about her.","B":"It helps her memorize the addresses for the post office.","C":"It allows her to critique their handwriting and spelling.","D":"It proves that she has more friends than Amalia does."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Reading old cards reassures Abuelita that the desire to stay connected is mutual, easing the pain of distance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q020","read_aloud":"Based on the entire text, what is the most likely outcome for Amalia\u0027s feelings about Martha\u0027s move? A. She will immediately forget about Martha and make new friends. B. She will remain angry forever and refuse to write letters. C. She will eventually use her grandmother\u0027s wisdom to find a way to stay connected. D. She will convince her parents to move to California right away.","excerpt":"\"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories. Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\"","stem":"Based on the entire text, what is the most likely outcome for Amalia\u0027s feelings about Martha\u0027s move?","choices":{"A":"She will immediately forget about Martha and make new friends.","B":"She will remain angry forever and refuse to write letters.","C":"She will eventually use her grandmother\u0027s wisdom to find a way to stay connected.","D":"She will convince her parents to move to California right away."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"While Amalia is currently defensive and sad, her grandmother has planted seeds of wisdom that will likely help Amalia process her grief and find ways to maintain the friendship. Section A - Text Information Title: from Love, Amalia Authors: Alma Flor Ada and Gabriel M. Zubizarreta","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories. Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q021","read_aloud":"Slathered means ______. A. Spread thickly B. Washed gently C. Dried quickly D. Hid secretly","excerpt":"\"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter.\"","stem":"Slathered means ______.","choices":{"A":"Spread thickly","B":"Washed gently","C":"Dried quickly","D":"Hid secretly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Slathered means spread thickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After drying their hands, they slathered them with soft butter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is another word for \"massive\"? A. Tiny B. Enormous C. Light D. Fragile","excerpt":"\"Abuelita signaled Amalia to come sit at the massive dining room table.\"","stem":"What is another word for \"massive\"?","choices":{"A":"Tiny","B":"Enormous","C":"Light","D":"Fragile"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Massive means very large.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita signaled Amalia to come sit at the massive dining room table.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt from Love, Amalia? A. Amalia learns to make taffy. B. Abuelita helps Amalia cope with her best friend moving away by sharing family stories and wisdom. C. Amalia decides to move to California. D. Abuelita is angry at Amalia.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt from Love, Amalia?","choices":{"A":"Amalia learns to make taffy.","B":"Abuelita helps Amalia cope with her best friend moving away by sharing family stories and wisdom.","C":"Amalia decides to move to California.","D":"Abuelita is angry at Amalia."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses stories and advice to help Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q024","read_aloud":"What do the chips in the bowl indicate? A. The bowl is new. B. The bowl has been used for a very long time. C. The bowl is made of plastic. D. The bowl is from a store.","excerpt":"\"The white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\"","stem":"What do the chips in the bowl indicate?","choices":{"A":"The bowl is new.","B":"The bowl has been used for a very long time.","C":"The bowl is made of plastic.","D":"The bowl is from a store."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chips show age and long use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The white porcelain bowl, with a few chips that spoke of its long use, had a wide yellow rim.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q025","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Abuelita\u0027s storytelling? A. She tells stories to avoid work. B. She tells stories to connect, teach, and comfort. C. She only tells stories on holidays. D. She dislikes telling stories.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Abuelita\u0027s storytelling?","choices":{"A":"She tells stories to avoid work.","B":"She tells stories to connect, teach, and comfort.","C":"She only tells stories on holidays.","D":"She dislikes telling stories."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stories are her way of teaching and comforting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q026","read_aloud":"What does this story about Uncle Manuel teach? A. People never change. B. People can grow and succeed despite past mistakes. C. Dropping out of school is always good. D. Only farmers can be successful.","excerpt":"\"He did many dumb things when he was in high school, and ended up dropping out. … Yet he has managed to save our rancho.\"","stem":"What does this story about Uncle Manuel teach?","choices":{"A":"People never change.","B":"People can grow and succeed despite past mistakes.","C":"Dropping out of school is always good.","D":"Only farmers can be successful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Uncle Manuel turned his life around.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He did many dumb things when he was in high school, and ended up dropping out. … Yet he has managed to save our rancho.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q027","read_aloud":"How has Amalia\u0027s mood changed? A. From sad/upset to comforted B. From happy to angry C. From confused to scared D. No change","excerpt":"Compare Amalia\u0027s mood in paragraph 5 (\"her voice cracked and her brown eyes watered\") with paragraph 39 (\"It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories\").","stem":"How has Amalia\u0027s mood changed?","choices":{"A":"From sad/upset to comforted","B":"From happy to angry","C":"From confused to scared","D":"No change"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The stories comfort her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Amalia\u0027s mood in paragraph 5 (\"her voice cracked and her brown eyes watered\") with paragraph 39 (\"It was comforting to hear Abuelita retelling the familiar stories\")."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q028","read_aloud":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice will help Amalia? Why? A. No, because nothing can help. B. Yes, because Abuelita speaks from experience with her own separated family. C. No, because Amalia is too young. D. Yes, because moving is easy.","excerpt":"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\"","stem":"Do you think Abuelita\u0027s advice will help Amalia? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because nothing can help.","B":"Yes, because Abuelita speaks from experience with her own separated family.","C":"No, because Amalia is too young.","D":"Yes, because moving is easy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s own experience makes her advice trustworthy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q029","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q030","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q031","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q032","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? A. Hard to see, B. Easy to notice, C. A secret, D. A lie.","excerpt":"\"It is obvious that something is wrong.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ?","choices":{"A":"Hard to see,","B":"Easy to notice,","C":"A secret,","D":"A lie."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Obvious\" means something is clear or easy for everyone to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is obvious that something is wrong.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q033","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past. B. Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds. C. Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago. D. Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them.","excerpt":"\"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Amalia wants to make new friends, while Abuelita only cares about the past.","B":"Amalia wants to push Martha away to avoid pain, while Abuelita cherishes close bonds.","C":"Amalia is excited to move, while Abuelita wants to stay in Chicago.","D":"Amalia loves reading letters, while Abuelita hates writing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia is defensively trying to avoid the pain of loss by not caring, while Abuelita\u0027s stories celebrate the beauty of inseparable bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You can\u0027t imagine, mi amor, how your mother and her sister would play together when they were little girls... They were inseparable, those two.\" (Abuelita\u0027s memory) vs \"Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\" (Amalia\u0027s current thought)"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q034","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. By throwing away old cards to forget the past B. By writing a new card every single day C. By asking your friend to send you a gift D. By reading old messages to remember your shared bond","excerpt":"\"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"By throwing away old cards to forget the past","B":"By writing a new card every single day","C":"By asking your friend to send you a gift","D":"By reading old messages to remember your shared bond"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Reading old messages helps reinforce the connection and reminds you that the friendship and desire to stay close are mutual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Before writing each card, I like to read ones I received from the person to whom I am about to write. This reminds me that I am not the only one who wants to stay close.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q035","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that hospitals were not invented yet B. To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s C. To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago D. To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer","excerpt":"\"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that hospitals were not invented yet","B":"To highlight how different Abuelita\u0027s past life was from Amalia\u0027s","C":"To prove that Abuelita does not like living in Chicago","D":"To explain why Amalia\u0027s uncle Manuel is a farmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stark contrast of being born on a kitchen table without a doctor highlights the vast differences between Abuelita\u0027s past in Mexico and Amalia\u0027s modern life in Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Ay, hijita, how we loved that rancho. It was there where my brother Felipe and I were born-on the kitchen table! There was no doctor, of course... we were born with the help of our aunts. Who would ever have thought I would end up living so far away?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q036","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show that they were forced to live in the same house B. To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were C. To prove that they never argued with each other D. To explain why they both moved to Mexico City","excerpt":"\"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show that they were forced to live in the same house","B":"To emphasize how incredibly close and connected they were","C":"To prove that they never argued with each other","D":"To explain why they both moved to Mexico City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Inseparable\" emphasizes that the sisters were always together and shared a deeply connected childhood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were inseparable, those two. Whether they were jumping rope or playing jacks, they spent all their time together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q037","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Moving away is always a terrible experience. B. Family traditions and memories can keep people connected. C. Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems. D. Nature is more important than human relationships.","excerpt":"\"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Moving away is always a terrible experience.","B":"Family traditions and memories can keep people connected.","C":"Cooking is the best way to solve emotional problems.","D":"Nature is more important than human relationships."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita uses cards, leaves, and memories to maintain a connection with her family, highlighting the theme of staying connected through traditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"As I was telling you, one must find ways to keep loved ones close, even if they move away. This year I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card. Every year at this time, my children and I had many good moments getting ready for the holidays.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q038","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home. B. The taffy burns on the kitchen stove. C. Martha calls on the telephone. D. It starts raining heavily outside.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Amalia\u0027s father arrives to take her home.","B":"The taffy burns on the kitchen stove.","C":"Martha calls on the telephone.","D":"It starts raining heavily outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that a knock on the door interrupted them because Amalia\u0027s father had arrived to pick her up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita probably would have continued telling more stories, but she was interrupted by a light knock on the door. It was already dark, and Amalia\u0027s father had come to get her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q039","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It creates a tense and scary atmosphere. B. It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth. C. It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry. D. It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated.","excerpt":"\"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It creates a tense and scary atmosphere.","B":"It adds a sense of comfort and domestic warmth.","C":"It shows that Amalia is angry and hungry.","D":"It proves that the kitchen is poorly ventilated."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"sweet aroma\" of the honey adds to the cozy, comforting, and warm mood of the kitchen as they spend time together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For a while there was silence. The sunlight faded in the kitchen, and as the boiled honey cooled into a dark, thick mass, its sweet aroma filled the air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q040","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A broken toy that cannot be fixed B. A seed that grows into a new flower C. A heavy rock that sinks in water D. A dark cloud that blocks the sun","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A broken toy that cannot be fixed","B":"A seed that grows into a new flower","C":"A heavy rock that sinks in water","D":"A dark cloud that blocks the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A seed growing into a new flower represents the idea that while one thing fades away, something new and beautiful can take its place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q041","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect. B. It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems. C. It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food. D. It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability.","excerpt":"\"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"It shows Abuelita is strict and demands respect.","B":"It shows Abuelita is confused by Amalia\u0027s problems.","C":"It shows Abuelita is trying to distract Amalia with food.","D":"It shows Abuelita provides safety and emotional stability."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Reassuring\" means providing comfort and stability, showing that Abuelita is a safe emotional anchor for Amalia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia wished Abuelita could just pick her up and hold her tightly as she used to do when Amalia was smaller, reassuring her grandchild that she belonged to something that would never change.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q042","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. To show that it is time for Amalia to go to sleep B. To establish a gentle, loving setting for the emotional talk C. To prove that Abuelita has a lot of free time for gardening D. To distract the reader from the main conflict of the story","excerpt":"\"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"To show that it is time for Amalia to go to sleep","B":"To establish a gentle, loving setting for the emotional talk","C":"To prove that Abuelita has a lot of free time for gardening","D":"To distract the reader from the main conflict of the story"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The soft, pink lighting sets a gentle and loving tone, preparing the reader for the intimate and emotional conversation that follows.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The light from the setting sun entered the small window over the sink with a soft glow. The geraniums on the windowsill added a subtle hint of pink.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q043","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. No, because Amalia still feels sad when she gets in the car. B. No, because she avoids talking about Martha directly. C. Yes, because she gives Amalia tools and perspectives to cope with loss. D. Yes, because she forces Amalia to stop crying immediately.","excerpt":"\"\"But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added. And then, smiling as if having just gotten a new idea, she said, \"Ven. Come with me.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"No, because Amalia still feels sad when she gets in the car.","B":"No, because she avoids talking about Martha directly.","C":"Yes, because she gives Amalia tools and perspectives to cope with loss.","D":"Yes, because she forces Amalia to stop crying immediately."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Abuelita shares wisdom, stories, and tangible ways to remember loved ones, giving Amalia healthy tools to process her grief.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"But one finds ways, Amalia, to keep them close,\" her grandmother added. And then, smiling as if having just gotten a new idea, she said, \"Ven. Come with me.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q044","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. No, because once a friendship ends, it is gone forever. B. Yes, because life brings new experiences and relationships to cherish. C. No, because it is better to hold onto the past than look forward. D. Yes, because people should never feel sad about losing things.","excerpt":"\"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"No, because once a friendship ends, it is gone forever.","B":"Yes, because life brings new experiences and relationships to cherish.","C":"No, because it is better to hold onto the past than look forward.","D":"Yes, because people should never feel sad about losing things."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelita\u0027s view is a healthy perspective on life; while we miss what is lost, new experiences and relationships eventually bring joy again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The same is true with the things we treasure: They happen, bloom for a time, and then fade away. Then sometimes they may reappear again, or something else will take their place.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q045","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. She might throw away all of Martha\u0027s old letters. B. She might refuse to talk to her father for the rest of the ride. C. She might ask her father to drive them to California immediately. D. She might start a journal to write down her favorite memories with Martha.","excerpt":"\"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"She might throw away all of Martha\u0027s old letters.","B":"She might refuse to talk to her father for the rest of the ride.","C":"She might ask her father to drive them to California immediately.","D":"She might start a journal to write down her favorite memories with Martha."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Writing in a journal is a creative and healthy way for Amalia to preserve her memories and feel connected to Martha, honoring her grandmother\u0027s advice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"You will find a way to stay close to Martha.\" Riding in the car, Amalia pondered her grandmother\u0027s words. They had brought back the sorrow she had been able to forget while listening to the family stories.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q046","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. It paints a picture of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the memory. B. It shows that Abuelita is trying to hide the table. C. It proves that the table is too small for their activities. D. It shows that Amalia is confused by her grandmother\u0027s gestures.","excerpt":"\"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"It paints a picture of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the memory.","B":"It shows that Abuelita is trying to hide the table.","C":"It proves that the table is too small for their activities.","D":"It shows that Amalia is confused by her grandmother\u0027s gestures."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Encompass\" means to surround, creating a vivid image of Abuelita\u0027s arms wrapping around the table and the memories it holds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelita gestured with her hands as if to encompass the huge table, and Amalia could just see it covered with colorful paper doll clothes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q047","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 515. A. By showing her ability to accept the situation immediately B. By showing her realistic, albeit painful, defensive reaction to loss C. By showing her excitement about making new friends D. By showing her deep understanding of Abuelita\u0027s wisdom","excerpt":"\"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation... Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake... Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 515.","choices":{"A":"By showing her ability to accept the situation immediately","B":"By showing her realistic, albeit painful, defensive reaction to loss","C":"By showing her excitement about making new friends","D":"By showing her deep understanding of Abuelita\u0027s wisdom"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Amalia\u0027s thought process shows a realistic defense mechanism; she is trying to protect herself from the pain of loss by acting like she doesn\u0027t care.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Amalia just wanted to end the conversation... Maybe then she could call Martha and hear her say that it all had been a great mistake... Who cares about staying close? she thought. I don\u0027t want to care about someone who won\u0027t be here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q048","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 516. A. It shows that moving far away can lead to personal and professional fulfillment. B. It proves that Hollywood is not a good place for artists. C. It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother is jealous of her sister. D. It explains why Amalia wants to move to Mexico.","excerpt":"\"\"And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 516.","choices":{"A":"It shows that moving far away can lead to personal and professional fulfillment.","B":"It proves that Hollywood is not a good place for artists.","C":"It shows that Amalia\u0027s mother is jealous of her sister.","D":"It explains why Amalia wants to move to Mexico."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The aunt moved far away to follow her passion and found great success, reinforcing the theme that distance can lead to positive growth and fulfillment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"And that is why she lives in Mexico City, in the capital, en el D.F. She says she could never have the same opportunity in Hollywood, but in Mexico she dresses all the most famous stars.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q049","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 517. A. No, because she should be completely happy and comforted. B. No, because she does not love her grandmother enough to listen. C. Yes, because she is angry that her grandmother hugged her. D. Yes, because grief comes in waves and comfort doesn\u0027t erase sadness instantly.","excerpt":"As Amalia was leaving, her grandmother hugged her and whispered in her ear,","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 517.","choices":{"A":"No, because she should be completely happy and comforted.","B":"No, because she does not love her grandmother enough to listen.","C":"Yes, because she is angry that her grandmother hugged her.","D":"Yes, because grief comes in waves and comfort doesn\u0027t erase sadness instantly."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"It is highly realistic that Amalia feels sorrow again; grief is a process, and a comforting conversation does not instantly erase the pain of a friend moving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Amalia was leaving, her grandmother hugged her and whispered in her ear,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w1-from-love-amalia-std-q050","read_aloud":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 518. A. A new video game so they can play it every day B. A pressed flower from your garden to remind them of your shared walks C. A map of their new city so they can stop feeling lost D. A dictionary so they can learn a new language","excerpt":"\"\"I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card... I have gathered some of this autumn\u0027s leaves to remind them of those times.\"\"","stem":"What should a careful reader infer from the detail connected to ? Choose the answer for practice item 518.","choices":{"A":"A new video game so they can play it every day","B":"A pressed flower from your garden to remind them of your shared walks","C":"A map of their new city so they can stop feeling lost","D":"A dictionary so they can learn a new language"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A pressed flower mirrors Abuelita\u0027s leaves, serving as a tangible, natural reminder of shared memories and home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I have decided to send a little bit of my backyard with each card... I have gathered some of this autumn\u0027s leaves to remind them of those times.\"\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":3,"week":2,"title":"A Borrowed Bunny","author":"Fran Hodgkins","genre":"Realistic Fiction","essential_question":"How do people show care and responsibility?","weekly_question":"What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["wriggled","fostering","pen","responsibility","animal"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"A Borrowed Bunny. What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"wriggled\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What does \"wriggled\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q002","read_aloud":"How long have the kittens been with the Ryan family? A. One week, B. Two months, C. One year, D. Two days.","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\"","stem":"How long have the kittens been with the Ryan family?","choices":{"A":"One week,","B":"Two months,","C":"One year,","D":"Two days."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states the kittens had been with the family for two months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What kind of animal is Pip? A. A kitten, B. A macaw, C. A snake, D. A rabbit.","excerpt":"\"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit.\"","stem":"What kind of animal is Pip?","choices":{"A":"A kitten,","B":"A macaw,","C":"A snake,","D":"A rabbit."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text identifies Pip as a beautiful brown rabbit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q004","read_aloud":"According to the story, what animal was once in the bathtub? A. A kitten, B. A rabbit, C. A boa constrictor, D. A macaw.","excerpt":"\"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub...\"","stem":"According to the story, what animal was once in the bathtub?","choices":{"A":"A kitten,","B":"A rabbit,","C":"A boa constrictor,","D":"A macaw."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text recalls that Mavis the boa constrictor was once in the bathtub.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What does it mean for an animal to be a \"foster\" pet? A. The animal will live with the family forever, B. The family is taking care of the animal temporarily, C. The animal belongs to the grandmother, D. The animal is a wild pet.","excerpt":"\"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\"","stem":"What does it mean for an animal to be a \"foster\" pet?","choices":{"A":"The animal will live with the family forever,","B":"The family is taking care of the animal temporarily,","C":"The animal belongs to the grandmother,","D":"The animal is a wild pet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Foster animals stay with a family for a short time until they find their \"forever home.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q006","read_aloud":"The cooing continued. Remembering the feel of Pip\u0027s wriggling body in her hands, Katya had to admit, \"Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\" but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business. What does the word \"snuggly\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. very loud and noisy B. fast and energetic C. cuddly and liking to be held D. hungry and ready to eat","excerpt":"Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?","stem":"The cooing continued. Remembering the feel of Pip\u0027s wriggling body in her hands, Katya had to admit, \"Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\" but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business. What does the word \"snuggly\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"very loud and noisy","B":"fast and energetic","C":"cuddly and liking to be held","D":"hungry and ready to eat"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The classmates are asking if the rabbit is soft and cuddly. \"Snuggly\" means liking to be held in an affectionate way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Katya\u0027s family fosters animals waiting for forever homes. B. Katya\u0027s family only likes to keep snakes as pets. C. Katya\u0027s family works at a local veterinary clinic. D. Katya\u0027s family refuses to take care of kittens.","excerpt":"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Katya\u0027s family fosters animals waiting for forever homes.","B":"Katya\u0027s family only likes to keep snakes as pets.","C":"Katya\u0027s family works at a local veterinary clinic.","D":"Katya\u0027s family refuses to take care of kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that animals from a rescue agency wait for new homes while Katya\u0027s parents take care of them, which describes fostering.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What did the family foster right before the rabbit? A. a boa constrictor B. a litter of kittens C. a group of puppies D. a pair of parrots","excerpt":"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper, and now they were old enough to run around the house.","stem":"What did the family foster right before the rabbit?","choices":{"A":"a boa constrictor","B":"a litter of kittens","C":"a group of puppies","D":"a pair of parrots"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states that the family was fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper, and now they were old enough to run around the house."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Where did Katya find the boa constrictor? A. in the living room B. in the laundry room C. in the kitchen D. in the bathtub","excerpt":"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub, but Mavis the snake had been with them only for an overnight. Katya wasn\u0027t a big fan of snakes.","stem":"Where did Katya find the boa constrictor?","choices":{"A":"in the living room","B":"in the laundry room","C":"in the kitchen","D":"in the bathtub"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text directly states that there had been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub, but Mavis the snake had been with them only for an overnight. Katya wasn\u0027t a big fan of snakes."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q010","read_aloud":"she exclaimed. \"Dad, you know how snakes freak me out. Why is Katya upset when she sees the look on her father\u0027s face? A. She thinks he brought home another snake. B. She thinks he forgot to feed the kittens. C. She thinks he is bringing home a loud bird. D. She thinks he is taking away her favorite pet.","excerpt":"Oh, please, not another Mavis!","stem":"she exclaimed. \"Dad, you know how snakes freak me out. Why is Katya upset when she sees the look on her father\u0027s face?","choices":{"A":"She thinks he brought home another snake.","B":"She thinks he forgot to feed the kittens.","C":"She thinks he is bringing home a loud bird.","D":"She thinks he is taking away her favorite pet."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Katya mentions Mavis the snake and says snakes freak her out, showing she fears her dad brought another snake.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oh, please, not another Mavis!"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"snuggled\" most likely mean? A. Jumped up quickly B. Settled in cozily and comfortably C. Ran away fast D. Shouted loudly","excerpt":"\"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"What does \"snuggled\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"Jumped up quickly","B":"Settled in cozily and comfortably","C":"Ran away fast","D":"Shouted loudly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Snuggled means to settle into a warm, comfortable position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q012","read_aloud":"Why do animals come and go at Katya\u0027s house? A. Her family runs a pet store. B. Her parents foster animals from a rescue agency. C. They buy a new pet every week. D. Animals wander in from the street.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\"","stem":"Why do animals come and go at Katya\u0027s house?","choices":{"A":"Her family runs a pet store.","B":"Her parents foster animals from a rescue agency.","C":"They buy a new pet every week.","D":"Animals wander in from the street."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her parents take care of foster animals from a rescue agency.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. Katya\u0027s house has had many different foster animals. B. Katya hates all animals. C. The family only fosters kittens. D. Animals are not allowed in the house.","excerpt":"\"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Katya\u0027s house has had many different foster animals.","B":"Katya hates all animals.","C":"The family only fosters kittens.","D":"Animals are not allowed in the house."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The examples show a variety of foster animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q014","read_aloud":"How did Katya and her parents feed the kittens when they first arrived? A. With a bowl of milk B. With an eyedropper C. With a spoon D. With a bottle","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper.\"","stem":"How did Katya and her parents feed the kittens when they first arrived?","choices":{"A":"With a bowl of milk","B":"With an eyedropper","C":"With a spoon","D":"With a bottle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they fed them with an eyedropper.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"forever home\" mean? A. A temporary shelter B. A permanent, loving home where the animal will stay C. A cage at the rescue agency D. A vacation house","excerpt":"\"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets. Eventually, each animal would leave the Ryans and go with someone else to its real forever home.\"","stem":"What does \"forever home\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A temporary shelter","B":"A permanent, loving home where the animal will stay","C":"A cage at the rescue agency","D":"A vacation house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A forever home is a permanent home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets. Eventually, each animal would leave the Ryans and go with someone else to its real forever home.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word \"snuggled\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. ran quickly B. moved closer for warmth and comfort C. jumped up and down D. stayed very still","excerpt":"\"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"What does the word \"snuggled\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"ran quickly","B":"moved closer for warmth and comfort","C":"jumped up and down","D":"stayed very still"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Snuggled\" means to get comfortable and cozy, usually by curling up. Katya was getting comfy under her blankets.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Katya owns many pets permanently. B. Katya\u0027s family helps take care of animals until they find homes. C. Katya likes to play with animals after school. D. The rescue agency brings dangerous animals to Katya\u0027s house.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Katya owns many pets permanently.","B":"Katya\u0027s family helps take care of animals until they find homes.","C":"Katya likes to play with animals after school.","D":"The rescue agency brings dangerous animals to Katya\u0027s house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph tells us that Katya\u0027s family fosters animals from a rescue agency, meaning they care for them until the animals get adopted.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q018","read_aloud":"Which animal was NOT in Katya\u0027s house? A. a macaw B. kittens C. a boa constrictor D. a hamster","excerpt":"\"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\"","stem":"Which animal was NOT in Katya\u0027s house?","choices":{"A":"a macaw","B":"kittens","C":"a boa constrictor","D":"a hamster"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The excerpt mentions a macaw, kittens, and a boa constrictor, but it does not mention a hamster.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q019","read_aloud":"How long had the kittens been with the Ryan family? A. one week B. two months C. one year D. three days","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\"","stem":"How long had the kittens been with the Ryan family?","choices":{"A":"one week","B":"two months","C":"one year","D":"three days"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states the kittens had been with them for two months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q020","read_aloud":"What does \"foster animals, not forever pets\" mean? A. The animals are mean and cannot stay. B. The animals will stay for a short time and then go to new homes. C. The animals are sick and need medicine. D. The animals do not like Katya.","excerpt":"\"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\"","stem":"What does \"foster animals, not forever pets\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The animals are mean and cannot stay.","B":"The animals will stay for a short time and then go to new homes.","C":"The animals are sick and need medicine.","D":"The animals do not like Katya."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Foster\" means temporary. The animals stay with the Ryans for a while until they get adopted by other families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q021","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"quarters\" mean? A. A type of money, B. A specific living area or space, C. Four parts of a whole, D. A place to cook food.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"quarters\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A type of money,","B":"A specific living area or space,","C":"Four parts of a whole,","D":"A place to cook food."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, quarters refers to the area where the rabbit is kept.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What caused Katya to jump out of bed? A. Her alarm clock went off, B. Her mom called her, C. She heard a crash, D. It was time for school.","excerpt":"\"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs...\"","stem":"What caused Katya to jump out of bed?","choices":{"A":"Her alarm clock went off,","B":"Her mom called her,","C":"She heard a crash,","D":"It was time for school."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says Katya jumped out of bed immediately after hearing a crash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the first paragraph? A. Katya loves snakes, B. Katya\u0027s family frequently takes care of different foster animals, C. Katya wants to adopt a kitten, D. Katya is moving to a new house.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the first paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Katya loves snakes,","B":"Katya\u0027s family frequently takes care of different foster animals,","C":"Katya wants to adopt a kitten,","D":"Katya is moving to a new house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The opening paragraph describes Katya\u0027s experience with the many different animals that temporarily live in her home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning... What is the new foster animal\u0027s name? A. Mavis, B. Fizzle, C. Fink, D. Pip.","excerpt":"Her name is Pip,","stem":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning... What is the new foster animal\u0027s name?","choices":{"A":"Mavis,","B":"Fizzle,","C":"Fink,","D":"Pip."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Mom introduces the new rabbit as Pip.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her name is Pip,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What is Pip doing in this scene? A. Trying to escape, B. Sleeping in her pen, C. Eating a pinecone, D. Playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"\"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\"","stem":"What is Pip doing in this scene?","choices":{"A":"Trying to escape,","B":"Sleeping in her pen,","C":"Eating a pinecone,","D":"Playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip is running quickly around the kitchen, and Katya is chasing her, which shows the rabbit is trying to get away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q001","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"quarters\" mean? A. A type of money, B. A specific living area or space, C. Four parts of a whole, D. A place to cook food.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"quarters\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A type of money,","B":"A specific living area or space,","C":"Four parts of a whole,","D":"A place to cook food."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, quarters refers to the area where the rabbit is kept.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What caused Katya to jump out of bed? A. Her alarm clock went off, B. Her mom called her, C. She heard a crash, D. It was time for school.","excerpt":"\"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs...\"","stem":"What caused Katya to jump out of bed?","choices":{"A":"Her alarm clock went off,","B":"Her mom called her,","C":"She heard a crash,","D":"It was time for school."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says Katya jumped out of bed immediately after hearing a crash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the first paragraph? A. Katya loves snakes, B. Katya\u0027s family frequently takes care of different foster animals, C. Katya wants to adopt a kitten, D. Katya is moving to a new house.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the first paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Katya loves snakes,","B":"Katya\u0027s family frequently takes care of different foster animals,","C":"Katya wants to adopt a kitten,","D":"Katya is moving to a new house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The opening paragraph describes Katya\u0027s experience with the many different animals that temporarily live in her home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q004","read_aloud":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning... What is the new foster animal\u0027s name? A. Mavis, B. Fizzle, C. Fink, D. Pip.","excerpt":"Her name is Pip,","stem":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning... What is the new foster animal\u0027s name?","choices":{"A":"Mavis,","B":"Fizzle,","C":"Fink,","D":"Pip."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Mom introduces the new rabbit as Pip.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her name is Pip,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What is Pip doing in this scene? A. Trying to escape, B. Sleeping in her pen, C. Eating a pinecone, D. Playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"\"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\"","stem":"What is Pip doing in this scene?","choices":{"A":"Trying to escape,","B":"Sleeping in her pen,","C":"Eating a pinecone,","D":"Playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip is running quickly around the kitchen, and Katya is chasing her, which shows the rabbit is trying to get away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q006","read_aloud":"her Mom said with a laugh. \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets. What does the word \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence? A. to run away from quickly B. to allow or accept without fighting C. to play with happily all day D. to hide from in a dark box","excerpt":"Yes, you did an amazing job with those two,","stem":"her Mom said with a laugh. \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets. What does the word \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to run away from quickly","B":"to allow or accept without fighting","C":"to play with happily all day","D":"to hide from in a dark box"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The kittens would only accept Katya and no one else. \"Tolerate\" means to allow or accept someone or something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Yes, you did an amazing job with those two,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q007","read_aloud":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning while your dad was delivering the kittens. The usual rabbit foster person is out of town, so he volunteered us. What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Mom is angry that Dad brought home a new animal. B. Dad brought home a rabbit named Pip because her foster person is away. C. Pip is a wild rabbit that Dad caught in the backyard. D. Mom wants to take Pip back to the rescue center immediately.","excerpt":"Her name is Pip,","stem":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning while your dad was delivering the kittens. The usual rabbit foster person is out of town, so he volunteered us. What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Mom is angry that Dad brought home a new animal.","B":"Dad brought home a rabbit named Pip because her foster person is away.","C":"Pip is a wild rabbit that Dad caught in the backyard.","D":"Mom wants to take Pip back to the rescue center immediately."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom explains that Pip is a rabbit whose usual foster person is out of town, so Dad volunteered their family to take care of her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her name is Pip,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q008","read_aloud":"Katya thought. \"A rabbit will be different, but not completely different.\" The rabbit had her own ideas. What happens right after Katya thinks the rabbit will be easy to handle? A. Pip jumps into Katya\u0027s arms for a hug. B. Pip falls asleep in the cardboard box. C. Pip breaks a bowl and runs around the house. D. Pip eats all the vegetables in the kitchen.","excerpt":"Okay,","stem":"Katya thought. \"A rabbit will be different, but not completely different.\" The rabbit had her own ideas. What happens right after Katya thinks the rabbit will be easy to handle?","choices":{"A":"Pip jumps into Katya\u0027s arms for a hug.","B":"Pip falls asleep in the cardboard box.","C":"Pip breaks a bowl and runs around the house.","D":"Pip eats all the vegetables in the kitchen."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The phrase \"The rabbit had her own ideas\" signals that Pip is about to cause trouble, which leads to her breaking a bowl and running away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Okay,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What day of the week did Pip escape from her pen? A. Friday B. Sunday C. Saturday D. Monday","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"What day of the week did Pip escape from her pen?","choices":{"A":"Friday","B":"Sunday","C":"Saturday","D":"Monday"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The excerpt explicitly states that the next morning, when Pip escaped, was Saturday.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why did Pip leap off the coffee table? A. She was scared of Katya\u0027s loud voice. B. She wanted to run away and eat a pinecone. C. She was trying to catch a fly in the air. D. She wanted Katya to chase her around the room.","excerpt":"Pip was on the nearby coffee table, looking over the edge at the broken bowl that once held decorative pinecones. As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones.","stem":"Why did Pip leap off the coffee table?","choices":{"A":"She was scared of Katya\u0027s loud voice.","B":"She wanted to run away and eat a pinecone.","C":"She was trying to catch a fly in the air.","D":"She wanted Katya to chase her around the room."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Pip looking at the broken bowl and then leaping off to start nibbling on a pinecone, showing she was moving on to her next activity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip was on the nearby coffee table, looking over the edge at the broken bowl that once held decorative pinecones. As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this context? A. To love immediately B. To allow or put up with something C. To run away from D. To eat","excerpt":"\"A rabbit-well, we\u0027ll all just have to get to know her a little better.\"","stem":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"To love immediately","B":"To allow or put up with something","C":"To run away from","D":"To eat"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tolerate means to accept or allow something even if you don\u0027t love it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A rabbit-well, we\u0027ll all just have to get to know her a little better.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What did the rabbit try to do? A. Eat a banana B. Get away from Katya C. Go to sleep D. Build a nest","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What did the rabbit try to do?","choices":{"A":"Eat a banana","B":"Get away from Katya","C":"Go to sleep","D":"Build a nest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The rabbit wriggled to try to escape.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What caused Pip to dash back into the dining room? A. She saw food. B. The front door slammed shut near her face. C. Katya called her name. D. She was tired.","excerpt":"\"As the front door slammed shut just inches from her face, Pip whirled around and dashed back into the dining room.\"","stem":"What caused Pip to dash back into the dining room?","choices":{"A":"She saw food.","B":"The front door slammed shut near her face.","C":"Katya called her name.","D":"She was tired."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The slamming door startled her and made her turn back.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the front door slammed shut just inches from her face, Pip whirled around and dashed back into the dining room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q014","read_aloud":"How did Katya hold Pip? A. Firmly but gently B. Very tightly and roughly C. By one ear D. She didn\u0027t catch her.","excerpt":"\"Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands.\"","stem":"How did Katya hold Pip?","choices":{"A":"Firmly but gently","B":"Very tightly and roughly","C":"By one ear","D":"She didn\u0027t catch her."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says firmly but gently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Katya declared. Why does Katya say this? A. She is comparing Pip\u0027s behavior to the cats she knows. B. She thinks Pip is a cat. C. She is angry at her cat. D. She wants a different pet.","excerpt":"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,","stem":"Katya declared. Why does Katya say this?","choices":{"A":"She is comparing Pip\u0027s behavior to the cats she knows.","B":"She thinks Pip is a cat.","C":"She is angry at her cat.","D":"She wants a different pet."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Katya is used to cats, and Pip behaves differently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You\u0027re nothing like a cat,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"quarters\" mean in this sentence? A. four equal parts of something B. a living space or place to stay C. money used to buy things D. a group of soldiers","excerpt":"\"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\u0027 Mom said.\"","stem":"What does \"quarters\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"four equal parts of something","B":"a living space or place to stay","C":"money used to buy things","D":"a group of soldiers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Quarters\" here means a place where someone lives or stays. Mom is talking about keeping Pip in her pen, which is her living space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\u0027 Mom said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. The kittens ran around the house. B. The kittens were adopted. C. Katya and her parents fed the kittens with an eyedropper. D. The kittens went to the rescue center.","excerpt":"\"When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper, and now they were old enough to run around the house.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"The kittens ran around the house.","B":"The kittens were adopted.","C":"Katya and her parents fed the kittens with an eyedropper.","D":"The kittens went to the rescue center."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"when the kittens first arrived\" they were fed with an eyedropper. This happened before they could run around.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper, and now they were old enough to run around the house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Why did Katya say \"Aw\"? A. She was happy the kittens were gone. B. She was sad because she would miss the kittens. C. She was afraid of the new animal. D. She wanted to go to the rescue center.","excerpt":"\"Dad said as he stirred his coffee. \u0027I took them back to the rescue center this morning.\u0027 \u0027Aw,\u0027 Katya said. She would miss them.\"","stem":"Why did Katya say \"Aw\"?","choices":{"A":"She was happy the kittens were gone.","B":"She was sad because she would miss the kittens.","C":"She was afraid of the new animal.","D":"She wanted to go to the rescue center."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"She would miss them,\" which means she felt sad the kittens were leaving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad said as he stirred his coffee. \u0027I took them back to the rescue center this morning.\u0027 \u0027Aw,\u0027 Katya said. She would miss them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning while your dad was delivering the kittens. How did Pip come to the Ryan family? A. They bought her at a pet store. B. Dad brought her from the rescue center. C. She ran away from a neighbor. D. Mom found her in the backyard.","excerpt":"Her name is Pip,","stem":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning while your dad was delivering the kittens. How did Pip come to the Ryan family?","choices":{"A":"They bought her at a pet store.","B":"Dad brought her from the rescue center.","C":"She ran away from a neighbor.","D":"Mom found her in the backyard."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Dad was delivering kittens to the rescue center and brought Pip back because the usual rabbit foster person was away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her name is Pip,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What can you tell about Pip from this excerpt? A. She is a white rabbit with spots. B. She is a beautiful brown rabbit. C. She is a small baby rabbit. D. She is a mean rabbit.","excerpt":"\"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit. \u0027Her name is Pip,\u0027 Mom said.\"","stem":"What can you tell about Pip from this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"She is a white rabbit with spots.","B":"She is a beautiful brown rabbit.","C":"She is a small baby rabbit.","D":"She is a mean rabbit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly describes Pip as \"a beautiful brown rabbit.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit. \u0027Her name is Pip,\u0027 Mom said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What does \"wriggled\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What does \"wriggled\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q022","read_aloud":"How long have the kittens been with the Ryan family? A. One week, B. Two months, C. One year, D. Two days.","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\"","stem":"How long have the kittens been with the Ryan family?","choices":{"A":"One week,","B":"Two months,","C":"One year,","D":"Two days."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states the kittens had been with the family for two months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q023","read_aloud":"What kind of animal is Pip? A. A kitten, B. A macaw, C. A snake, D. A rabbit.","excerpt":"\"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit.\"","stem":"What kind of animal is Pip?","choices":{"A":"A kitten,","B":"A macaw,","C":"A snake,","D":"A rabbit."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text identifies Pip as a beautiful brown rabbit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q024","read_aloud":"According to the story, what animal was once in the bathtub? A. A kitten, B. A rabbit, C. A boa constrictor, D. A macaw.","excerpt":"\"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub...\"","stem":"According to the story, what animal was once in the bathtub?","choices":{"A":"A kitten,","B":"A rabbit,","C":"A boa constrictor,","D":"A macaw."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text recalls that Mavis the boa constrictor was once in the bathtub.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What does it mean for an animal to be a \"foster\" pet? A. The animal will live with the family forever, B. The family is taking care of the animal temporarily, C. The animal belongs to the grandmother, D. The animal is a wild pet.","excerpt":"\"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\"","stem":"What does it mean for an animal to be a \"foster\" pet?","choices":{"A":"The animal will live with the family forever,","B":"The family is taking care of the animal temporarily,","C":"The animal belongs to the grandmother,","D":"The animal is a wild pet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Foster animals stay with a family for a short time until they find their \"forever home.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence? A. To love deeply, B. To allow or accept, C. To run away from, D. To play with.","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\"","stem":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To love deeply,","B":"To allow or accept,","C":"To run away from,","D":"To play with."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To tolerate means to accept or put up with someone or something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What happened right after the blanket was put over the pen? A. Katya gave Pip a carrot, B. Pip hopped around the room, C. Pip stayed inside the cardboard box, D. The kittens arrived.","excerpt":"\"After the blanket was in place, Pip stayed inside the cardboard box...\"","stem":"What happened right after the blanket was put over the pen?","choices":{"A":"Katya gave Pip a carrot,","B":"Pip hopped around the room,","C":"Pip stayed inside the cardboard box,","D":"The kittens arrived."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The story describes Pip staying in her box immediately after the blanket was secured.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After the blanket was in place, Pip stayed inside the cardboard box...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the relationship between Katya and Pip at this moment? A. They are best friends, B. Pip is starting to see this as a game or a challenge, C. Katya is scared of Pip, D. Pip is very happy to be caught.","excerpt":"\"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you infer about the relationship between Katya and Pip at this moment?","choices":{"A":"They are best friends,","B":"Pip is starting to see this as a game or a challenge,","C":"Katya is scared of Pip,","D":"Pip is very happy to be caught."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"look\" suggests a playful, challenging interaction, as if the rabbit knows she was caught in a game of chase.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What did Pip do when Katya walked toward her? A. Stayed still, B. Bit Katya, C. Stomped her foot and raced away, D. Fell asleep.","excerpt":"\"As Katya stepped toward her, Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\"","stem":"What did Pip do when Katya walked toward her?","choices":{"A":"Stayed still,","B":"Bit Katya,","C":"Stomped her foot and raced away,","D":"Fell asleep."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly lists these actions as Pip\u0027s reaction to Katya.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Katya stepped toward her, Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Mom said. Why did Mom put a blanket over the pen? A. To keep the rabbit warm, B. To keep the rabbit inside her pen, C. To hide the rabbit from Katya, D. To clean the pen.","excerpt":"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,","stem":"Mom said. Why did Mom put a blanket over the pen?","choices":{"A":"To keep the rabbit warm,","B":"To keep the rabbit inside her pen,","C":"To hide the rabbit from Katya,","D":"To clean the pen."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom says the blanket should keep Pip in her \"quarters,\" which refers to her pen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"wriggled\" mean in this excerpt? A. moved by twisting and turning B. stayed completely still and quiet C. jumped up very high in the air D. bit down very hard on a finger","excerpt":"Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands. The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.","stem":"What does the word \"wriggled\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"moved by twisting and turning","B":"stayed completely still and quiet","C":"jumped up very high in the air","D":"bit down very hard on a finger"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip is trying to get away from Katya\u0027s hold. \"Wriggled\" means moved by twisting her body to escape.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands. The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How did Katya finally catch Pip? A. She trapped Pip in a corner with a broom. B. She lured Pip into the pen with a carrot. C. She asked Dad to help her corner the rabbit. D. She threw herself toward Pip and grabbed her.","excerpt":"Stepping carefully around pieces of the broken bowl, Katya went after the running rabbit. Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.","stem":"How did Katya finally catch Pip?","choices":{"A":"She trapped Pip in a corner with a broom.","B":"She lured Pip into the pen with a carrot.","C":"She asked Dad to help her corner the rabbit.","D":"She threw herself toward Pip and grabbed her."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text describes a wild chase that ends with Katya throwing herself toward the \"brown blur\" and catching Pip firmly in her hands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Stepping carefully around pieces of the broken bowl, Katya went after the running rabbit. Pip skidded a little bit on the tile of the kitchen floor, but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q008","read_aloud":"she said gently; she\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm. Pip\u0027s ears perked up. Her nose twitched. What can you infer about Pip from this excerpt? A. Pip is deaf and cannot hear Katya at all. B. Pip responds to calm and gentle voices. C. Pip is angry and wants to bite Katya. D. Pip is asleep and ignoring Katya\u0027s words.","excerpt":"Come on, bunny-bunny,","stem":"she said gently; she\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm. Pip\u0027s ears perked up. Her nose twitched. What can you infer about Pip from this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Pip is deaf and cannot hear Katya at all.","B":"Pip responds to calm and gentle voices.","C":"Pip is angry and wants to bite Katya.","D":"Pip is asleep and ignoring Katya\u0027s words."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya uses a soft voice based on her experience with kittens, and Pip\u0027s ears perk up and nose twitches, showing she is listening and reacting to the calm tone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Come on, bunny-bunny,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q009","read_aloud":"Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one. What did Katya declare to Pip after catching her? A. That Pip was exactly like a cat B. That Pip was nothing like a cat C. That Pip was the best rabbit ever D. That Pip needed to go back to the shelter","excerpt":"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,","stem":"Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one. What did Katya declare to Pip after catching her?","choices":{"A":"That Pip was exactly like a cat","B":"That Pip was nothing like a cat","C":"That Pip was the best rabbit ever","D":"That Pip needed to go back to the shelter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly quotes Katya declaring, \"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,\" because Pip was acting stubborn and uncooperative.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You\u0027re nothing like a cat,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Katya said. While Dad fed the other animals, she swept the pieces of broken bowl and crumbling pinecones from the hardwood floor. How does Katya feel about Pip at the end of the morning? A. She feels excited to play with Pip. B. She feels like Pip is her new best friend. C. She feels like Pip does not like her. D. She feels angry and wants to give Pip away.","excerpt":"I don\u0027t think that rabbit likes me so much,","stem":"Katya said. While Dad fed the other animals, she swept the pieces of broken bowl and crumbling pinecones from the hardwood floor. How does Katya feel about Pip at the end of the morning?","choices":{"A":"She feels excited to play with Pip.","B":"She feels like Pip is her new best friend.","C":"She feels like Pip does not like her.","D":"She feels angry and wants to give Pip away."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Katya explicitly tells her dad that she doesn\u0027t think the rabbit likes her, showing she feels rejected by Pip\u0027s stubborn behavior.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I don\u0027t think that rabbit likes me so much,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What color is Pip? A. White B. Brown C. Black D. Gray","excerpt":"\"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit. \u0027Her name is Pip,\u0027 Mom said.\"","stem":"What color is Pip?","choices":{"A":"White","B":"Brown","C":"Black","D":"Gray"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says a beautiful brown rabbit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya peered into the pen at a beautiful brown rabbit. \u0027Her name is Pip,\u0027 Mom said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer from this sentence? A. Pip will be easy to handle. B. Pip will do things her own way, not just follow along. C. Pip cannot think. D. Pip is sick.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit had her own ideas.\"","stem":"What can you infer from this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Pip will be easy to handle.","B":"Pip will do things her own way, not just follow along.","C":"Pip cannot think.","D":"Pip is sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Had her own ideas\" means she is independent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit had her own ideas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What woke Katya up? A. Her alarm clock B. A crash C. Her mother calling D. The phone ringing","excerpt":"\"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs to find that the wire pen where Pip had been stood empty.\"","stem":"What woke Katya up?","choices":{"A":"Her alarm clock","B":"A crash","C":"Her mother calling","D":"The phone ringing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She heard a crash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then she heard a crash. Without thinking twice, she jumped out of bed and raced down the stairs to find that the wire pen where Pip had been stood empty.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q014","read_aloud":"How does Katya feel toward Pip at this moment? A. Happy and excited B. Annoyed or frustrated C. Scared D. Sleepy","excerpt":"\"As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones.\"","stem":"How does Katya feel toward Pip at this moment?","choices":{"A":"Happy and excited","B":"Annoyed or frustrated","C":"Scared","D":"Sleepy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Glaring shows annoyance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"wriggled\" mean? A. moved by twisting and turning B. jumped very high C. sat completely still D. made a loud sound","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What does \"wriggled\" mean?","choices":{"A":"moved by twisting and turning","B":"jumped very high","C":"sat completely still","D":"made a loud sound"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Wriggled\" means to twist and squirm your body to get free. Pip was trying to escape from Katya\u0027s hands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Katya? A. She likes all animals equally. B. She is afraid of snakes. C. She wants another snake. D. She does not like her dad.","excerpt":"\"Katya noticed the look on her father\u0027s face-and she knew what that look meant. \u0027Oh, please, not another Mavis!\u0027 she exclaimed. \u0027Dad, you know how snakes freak me out.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you infer about Katya?","choices":{"A":"She likes all animals equally.","B":"She is afraid of snakes.","C":"She wants another snake.","D":"She does not like her dad."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya says \"snakes freak me out,\" which means snakes scare her. She was worried Dad had brought home another snake.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya noticed the look on her father\u0027s face-and she knew what that look meant. \u0027Oh, please, not another Mavis!\u0027 she exclaimed. \u0027Dad, you know how snakes freak me out.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Katya? A. She is careless and rough. B. She is fast and careful with animals. C. She is slow and lazy. D. She is afraid of rabbits.","excerpt":"\"Katya threw herself toward the brown blur. Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Katya?","choices":{"A":"She is careless and rough.","B":"She is fast and careful with animals.","C":"She is slow and lazy.","D":"She is afraid of rabbits."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya moved quickly (\"threw herself\") but held Pip \"firmly but gently,\" showing she is careful and kind with animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya threw herself toward the brown blur. Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q018","read_aloud":"What did Pip break? A. a window B. a bowl C. a chair D. a lamp","excerpt":"\"Pip was on the nearby coffee table, looking over the edge at the broken bowl that once held decorative pinecones. As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones.\"","stem":"What did Pip break?","choices":{"A":"a window","B":"a bowl","C":"a chair","D":"a lamp"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"the broken bowl that once held decorative pinecones,\" so Pip broke a bowl.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip was on the nearby coffee table, looking over the edge at the broken bowl that once held decorative pinecones. As Katya glared at Pip, the rabbit leaped off the table and started nibbling on one of the cones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q019","read_aloud":"Why did Katya use a soft, calm voice? A. She was tired and sleepy. B. She knew loud noises scare animals. C. She was angry at the rabbit. D. She wanted to surprise her mom.","excerpt":"\"Katya dropped to her hands and knees. \u0027Come on, bunny-bunny,\u0027 she said gently; she\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm.\"","stem":"Why did Katya use a soft, calm voice?","choices":{"A":"She was tired and sleepy.","B":"She knew loud noises scare animals.","C":"She was angry at the rabbit.","D":"She wanted to surprise her mom."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya had experience with kittens and knew that a soft, calm voice helps catch animals. Loud noises would scare Pip away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya dropped to her hands and knees. \u0027Come on, bunny-bunny,\u0027 she said gently; she\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for \"success\" in this context? A. Victory, B. Failure, C. Happiness, D. Speed.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for \"success\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"Victory,","B":"Failure,","C":"Happiness,","D":"Speed."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Without success\" means the rabbit failed to escape, making \"failure\" the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author help the reader understand that this is a temporary situation? A. By calling them \"foster animals,\" B. By saying they are bad pets, C. By ignoring the kittens, D. By saying they live there forever.","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\"","stem":"How does the author help the reader understand that this is a temporary situation?","choices":{"A":"By calling them \"foster animals,\"","B":"By saying they are bad pets,","C":"By ignoring the kittens,","D":"By saying they live there forever."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Calling them \"foster\" animals clearly labels them as temporary residents.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q003","read_aloud":"What was the result of Pip\u0027s sharp turn? A. She stopped running, B. She raced around the kitchen island, C. She fell asleep, D. She hid under the rug.","excerpt":"\"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile... but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\"","stem":"What was the result of Pip\u0027s sharp turn?","choices":{"A":"She stopped running,","B":"She raced around the kitchen island,","C":"She fell asleep,","D":"She hid under the rug."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly connects the sharp turn to her racing around the island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip skidded a little bit on the tile... but managed to execute a sharp right turn that sent her racing around the kitchen island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q004","read_aloud":"How does the author build suspense in the kitchen scene? A. By describing the rabbit\u0027s speed and Katya\u0027s efforts to catch her, B. By ending the story, C. By talking about the kittens, D. By describing the weather.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"How does the author build suspense in the kitchen scene?","choices":{"A":"By describing the rabbit\u0027s speed and Katya\u0027s efforts to catch her,","B":"By ending the story,","C":"By talking about the kittens,","D":"By describing the weather."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The fast-paced description of the chase creates tension and keeps the reader wondering if she will be caught.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q005","read_aloud":"What does the word \"quarters\" mean in this sentence? A. a type of healthy rabbit food B. a special toy for rabbits to chew C. a coin used to buy rabbit supplies D. a living space or place to stay","excerpt":"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\" Mom said.","stem":"What does the word \"quarters\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a type of healthy rabbit food","B":"a special toy for rabbits to chew","C":"a coin used to buy rabbit supplies","D":"a living space or place to stay"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Mom is talking about the wire pen where Pip lives. \"Quarters\" refers to an animal\u0027s living space or home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\" Mom said."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: Katya gave Pip a banana; Effect: Pip came out of the box. B. Cause: Mom put a blanket over the pen; Effect: Pip hid in the box. C. Cause: Pip broke a bowl; Effect: Mom swept the floor. D. Cause: Dad fed the animals; Effect: Pip ate the lettuce.","excerpt":"After the blanket was in place, Pip stayed inside the cardboard box, stubbornly refusing to come out- especially while Katya was in the room. It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought.","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Katya gave Pip a banana; Effect: Pip came out of the box.","B":"Cause: Mom put a blanket over the pen; Effect: Pip hid in the box.","C":"Cause: Pip broke a bowl; Effect: Mom swept the floor.","D":"Cause: Dad fed the animals; Effect: Pip ate the lettuce."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that after the blanket was secured over the pen, Pip stayed hidden inside her cardboard box, refusing to come out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After the blanket was in place, Pip stayed inside the cardboard box, stubbornly refusing to come out- especially while Katya was in the room. It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt reveal about Pip\u0027s personality? A. She is very brave and loves loud noises. B. She is cautious and prefers to feel safe. C. She is hungry and will eat anything quickly. D. She is friendly and wants to play with Dad.","excerpt":"Dad lifted the corner of Pip\u0027s roof-blanket and set a bowl of greens on the floor of her pen. The rabbit waited until he had reattached the blanket before she hopped over to the mixed lettuce.","stem":"What does this excerpt reveal about Pip\u0027s personality?","choices":{"A":"She is very brave and loves loud noises.","B":"She is cautious and prefers to feel safe.","C":"She is hungry and will eat anything quickly.","D":"She is friendly and wants to play with Dad."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip waits for the blanket to be put back before eating, showing she is cautious and needs to feel covered and safe before she relaxes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Dad lifted the corner of Pip\u0027s roof-blanket and set a bowl of greens on the floor of her pen. The rabbit waited until he had reattached the blanket before she hopped over to the mixed lettuce."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q008","read_aloud":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. \"You\u0027ve seen it yourself. Remember the kittens? If you were Katya\u0027s friend, what advice would you give her based on Mom\u0027s words? A. Stop trying to be friends with Pip and ignore her. B. Give Pip time and space to get used to you. C. Bring home more kittens so Pip gets jealous. D. Take Pip back to the rescue center today.","excerpt":"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.","stem":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. \"You\u0027ve seen it yourself. Remember the kittens? If you were Katya\u0027s friend, what advice would you give her based on Mom\u0027s words?","choices":{"A":"Stop trying to be friends with Pip and ignore her.","B":"Give Pip time and space to get used to you.","C":"Bring home more kittens so Pip gets jealous.","D":"Take Pip back to the rescue center today."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom explains that not all animals will like you right away, so the best advice is to be patient and give Pip time to adjust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Katya said. \"You caught her, though,\" Mom said. \"Do you think I hurt her pride?\" Katya said. \"Could be,\" Mom replied. How does Katya\u0027s conversation with her mom help her understand Pip\u0027s behavior? A. It helps her realize Pip might feel embarrassed from being caught. B. It helps her realize Pip is actually a wild animal from the forest. C. It helps her realize Pip is angry about the broken wooden bowl. D. It helps her realize Pip is sick and needs to see a veterinarian.","excerpt":"It\u0027s not like I\u0027m the one who put up the blanket,","stem":"Katya said. \"You caught her, though,\" Mom said. \"Do you think I hurt her pride?\" Katya said. \"Could be,\" Mom replied. How does Katya\u0027s conversation with her mom help her understand Pip\u0027s behavior?","choices":{"A":"It helps her realize Pip might feel embarrassed from being caught.","B":"It helps her realize Pip is actually a wild animal from the forest.","C":"It helps her realize Pip is angry about the broken wooden bowl.","D":"It helps her realize Pip is sick and needs to see a veterinarian."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Katya wonders if she hurt Pip\u0027s \"pride\" by catching her, showing she is starting to think about Pip\u0027s feelings and perspective.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It\u0027s not like I\u0027m the one who put up the blanket,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q010","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Katya? A. She has experience with foster animals. B. She is afraid of animals. C. She has never owned a pet. D. She only likes snakes.","excerpt":"\"She\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Katya?","choices":{"A":"She has experience with foster animals.","B":"She is afraid of animals.","C":"She has never owned a pet.","D":"She only likes snakes."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"She has chased many kittens before.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She\u0027d pursued enough rambunctious kittens to know that she had to keep her voice soft, soothing, and calm.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q011","read_aloud":"How is Pip different from a kitten or snake? A. She is larger than both. B. She behaves differently from the animals Katya knows well. C. She is green. D. She can fly.","excerpt":"\"Pip wasn\u0027t a boa constrictor, true enough, she thought, but she was no kitten, either.\"","stem":"How is Pip different from a kitten or snake?","choices":{"A":"She is larger than both.","B":"She behaves differently from the animals Katya knows well.","C":"She is green.","D":"She can fly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows cats and snakes; rabbits are new to her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip wasn\u0027t a boa constrictor, true enough, she thought, but she was no kitten, either.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q012","read_aloud":"If you were Katya, what might you try next to befriend Pip? A. Yell at her B. Give her space and offer treats like banana C. Chase her around the room D. Ignore her completely","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought.\"","stem":"If you were Katya, what might you try next to befriend Pip?","choices":{"A":"Yell at her","B":"Give her space and offer treats like banana","C":"Chase her around the room","D":"Ignore her completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Later in the story, Katya uses banana and patience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What does Mom mean by this? A. Every animal will love Katya. B. Just like people, each animal has its own personality. C. Animals are better than people. D. Katya should stop trying.","excerpt":"\"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.\"","stem":"What does Mom mean by this?","choices":{"A":"Every animal will love Katya.","B":"Just like people, each animal has its own personality.","C":"Animals are better than people.","D":"Katya should stop trying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Animals have individual preferences and personalities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q014","read_aloud":"What does \"snuggly\" mean? A. angry and mean B. cuddly and liking to be held C. fast and energetic D. quiet and shy","excerpt":"\"Katya had to admit, \u0027Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\u0027 but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business.\"","stem":"What does \"snuggly\" mean?","choices":{"A":"angry and mean","B":"cuddly and liking to be held","C":"fast and energetic","D":"quiet and shy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Snuggly\" means cuddly and affectionate. Katya admitted Pip was soft but did not say she liked to be cuddled.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya had to admit, \u0027Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\u0027 but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q015","read_aloud":"Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one. How is Pip different from a cat, based on the story? A. Cats are slower than rabbits. B. Rabbits do not like to be held and are harder to catch. C. Cats are brown and rabbits are white. D. Cats break bowls and rabbits do not.","excerpt":"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,","stem":"Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one. How is Pip different from a cat, based on the story?","choices":{"A":"Cats are slower than rabbits.","B":"Rabbits do not like to be held and are harder to catch.","C":"Cats are brown and rabbits are white.","D":"Cats break bowls and rabbits do not."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya had experience with kittens, but Pip wriggled, ran fast, and was hard to catch. Rabbits behave differently than cats.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You\u0027re nothing like a cat,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What problem did Mom solve? A. Pip was cold. B. Pip kept escaping from her pen. C. Pip was hungry. D. Pip was too noisy.","excerpt":"\"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\u0027\"","stem":"What problem did Mom solve?","choices":{"A":"Pip was cold.","B":"Pip kept escaping from her pen.","C":"Pip was hungry.","D":"Pip was too noisy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip had escaped and caused trouble. Mom covered the pen with a blanket so Pip could not get out again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why do you think Pip waited for Dad to leave? A. She was not hungry. B. She was shy and did not trust people yet. C. She wanted to sleep first. D. She did not like lettuce.","excerpt":"\"Dad lifted the corner of Pip\u0027s roof-blanket and set a bowl of greens on the floor of her pen. The rabbit waited until he had reattached the blanket before she hopped over to the mixed lettuce.\"","stem":"Why do you think Pip waited for Dad to leave?","choices":{"A":"She was not hungry.","B":"She was shy and did not trust people yet.","C":"She wanted to sleep first.","D":"She did not like lettuce."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip was new and scared. She waited until Dad stepped away because she was not comfortable around people yet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad lifted the corner of Pip\u0027s roof-blanket and set a bowl of greens on the floor of her pen. The rabbit waited until he had reattached the blanket before she hopped over to the mixed lettuce.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q018","read_aloud":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. Why does Mom say this to Katya? A. Mom wants Katya to stop helping animals. B. Mom is teaching Katya that relationships take time. C. Mom thinks Katya is mean to animals. D. Mom does not like rabbits.","excerpt":"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.","stem":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. Why does Mom say this to Katya?","choices":{"A":"Mom wants Katya to stop helping animals.","B":"Mom is teaching Katya that relationships take time.","C":"Mom thinks Katya is mean to animals.","D":"Mom does not like rabbits."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom is helping Katya understand that you cannot force an animal to like you. Trust takes time, just like with people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"accustomed\" mean? A. Surprised by, B. Used to, C. Afraid of, D. Tired of.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\"","stem":"What does \"accustomed\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Surprised by,","B":"Used to,","C":"Afraid of,","D":"Tired of."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To be accustomed to something means it is familiar and you are used to it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q002","read_aloud":"Why does the author use personification by giving the rabbit human-like thoughts? A. To make the rabbit seem like a real person, B. To show the close and playful connection forming between Katya and the rabbit, C. To make the story sad, D. To show the rabbit can talk.","excerpt":"\"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author use personification by giving the rabbit human-like thoughts?","choices":{"A":"To make the rabbit seem like a real person,","B":"To show the close and playful connection forming between Katya and the rabbit,","C":"To make the story sad,","D":"To show the rabbit can talk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Giving the animal thoughts helps the reader see the playful \"game\" being played between the two.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What do these actions tell us about Pip? A. She is happy, B. She is feeling annoyed or threatened, C. She is hungry, D. She is hurt.","excerpt":"\"Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\"","stem":"What do these actions tell us about Pip?","choices":{"A":"She is happy,","B":"She is feeling annoyed or threatened,","C":"She is hungry,","D":"She is hurt."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In rabbit behavior, stomping a foot and twitching the nose are signs of stress, annoyance, or feeling threatened.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Why does Katya\u0027s mom have rules about \"foster\" versus \"forever\" pets? A. To teach Katya not to get too attached, B. Because they don\u0027t have enough food, C. Because the animals don\u0027t like children, D. Because the house is too small.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why does Katya\u0027s mom have rules about \"foster\" versus \"forever\" pets?","choices":{"A":"To teach Katya not to get too attached,","B":"Because they don\u0027t have enough food,","C":"Because the animals don\u0027t like children,","D":"Because the house is too small."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Keeping animals temporarily prevents the pain of permanent loss and keeps the focus on helping animals get ready for their permanent homes.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q005","read_aloud":"What does the word \"tingled\" mean in this excerpt? A. felt a sharp pain in her legs B. felt a prickling sensation of excitement C. felt very cold and shivery D. felt tired and ready for sleep","excerpt":"When Pip hopped over to the banana and started eating, Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"What does the word \"tingled\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"felt a sharp pain in her legs","B":"felt a prickling sensation of excitement","C":"felt very cold and shivery","D":"felt tired and ready for sleep"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya is very happy that Pip is eating the banana. \"Tingled\" describes a physical feeling of excitement and joy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When Pip hopped over to the banana and started eating, Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Max\u0027s aunt loves to eat fruit for lunch. B. Max teaches Katya that rabbits like bananas. C. Max thinks Katya\u0027s rabbit is a goofball. D. Max wants Katya to bring Pip to school.","excerpt":"At lunchtime, Katya\u0027s friend Max plopped down across the table. \"My aunt has a rabbit,\" he said, \"and she likes bananas.\" \"Your aunt likes bananas?\" \"No, goofball, her rabbit likes bananas.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Max\u0027s aunt loves to eat fruit for lunch.","B":"Max teaches Katya that rabbits like bananas.","C":"Max thinks Katya\u0027s rabbit is a goofball.","D":"Max wants Katya to bring Pip to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Max shares a tip from his aunt that rabbits enjoy eating bananas, which gives Katya a new idea to try with Pip.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: At lunchtime, Katya\u0027s friend Max plopped down across the table. \"My aunt has a rabbit,\" he said, \"and she likes bananas.\" \"Your aunt likes bananas?\" \"No, goofball, her rabbit likes bananas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What sequence of events happens in this excerpt? A. Katya eats a banana, then gives the peel to Pip. B. Katya offers Pip a banana, and Pip investigates it. C. Pip eats the banana, then hides in the box. D. Pip pokes her head out, then Katya peels a banana.","excerpt":"Katya peeled a banana and broke off a small piece. She had her doubts, but she went to the pen and held the bit of banana though the wire grate anyway. After a moment, Pip poked her head out of the cardboard box.","stem":"What sequence of events happens in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Katya eats a banana, then gives the peel to Pip.","B":"Katya offers Pip a banana, and Pip investigates it.","C":"Pip eats the banana, then hides in the box.","D":"Pip pokes her head out, then Katya peels a banana."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya first breaks off a piece of banana and offers it, which causes Pip to poke her head out to smell it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya peeled a banana and broke off a small piece. She had her doubts, but she went to the pen and held the bit of banana though the wire grate anyway. After a moment, Pip poked her head out of the cardboard box."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q008","read_aloud":"How could Katya use this new information to help her bond with Pip? A. By using banana time as a quiet, daily routine to talk to Pip. B. By feeding Pip ten bananas at once to make her very happy. C. By hiding the bananas so Pip has to search for them. D. By eating the bananas in front of Pip to show they are safe.","excerpt":"Nobody in the family saw her do it, but Pip eventually ate the banana. Every afternoon from then on, Katya put another bit of banana in the pen. And just like clockwork, every morning, it was gone.","stem":"How could Katya use this new information to help her bond with Pip?","choices":{"A":"By using banana time as a quiet, daily routine to talk to Pip.","B":"By feeding Pip ten bananas at once to make her very happy.","C":"By hiding the bananas so Pip has to search for them.","D":"By eating the bananas in front of Pip to show they are safe."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since Pip reliably eats the banana, Katya can use this daily treat as a peaceful time to sit nearby and talk to her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Nobody in the family saw her do it, but Pip eventually ate the banana. Every afternoon from then on, Katya put another bit of banana in the pen. And just like clockwork, every morning, it was gone."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q009","read_aloud":"Why does Katya force herself to act casually? A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables instead. B. She knows sudden movements or loud noises will scare Pip. C. She is actually bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story, then starting talking about a new book.","stem":"Why does Katya force herself to act casually?","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables instead.","B":"She knows sudden movements or loud noises will scare Pip.","C":"She is actually bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm and casual to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story, then starting talking about a new book."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"tingled\" mean in this sentence? A. Felt cold B. Felt a prickling sensation of excitement C. Felt nothing D. Felt tired","excerpt":"\"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\"","stem":"What does \"tingled\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Felt cold","B":"Felt a prickling sensation of excitement","C":"Felt nothing","D":"Felt tired"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tingled with joy means excitement made her feel a prickly sensation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q011","read_aloud":"How is Katya\u0027s attitude changing? A. She is giving up. B. She is being patient and continuing to try. C. She is getting angry. D. She is ignoring Pip.","excerpt":"\"Katya started thinking of it as game they played, she and this rabbit that didn\u0027t like her. Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning.\"","stem":"How is Katya\u0027s attitude changing?","choices":{"A":"She is giving up.","B":"She is being patient and continuing to try.","C":"She is getting angry.","D":"She is ignoring Pip."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She keeps trying every morning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya started thinking of it as game they played, she and this rabbit that didn\u0027t like her. Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q012","read_aloud":"Why does Katya stay calm when Pip eats the banana? A. She is not interested. B. She knows sudden moves or excitement might scare Pip away. C. She is pretending not to care. D. She is afraid of bananas.","excerpt":"\"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\"","stem":"Why does Katya stay calm when Pip eats the banana?","choices":{"A":"She is not interested.","B":"She knows sudden moves or excitement might scare Pip away.","C":"She is pretending not to care.","D":"She is afraid of bananas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Excitement could frighten Pip.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What does this moment show about the trust between Katya and Pip? A. They still do not trust each other at all. B. Pip is beginning to trust Katya enough to let her near the box. C. Katya is afraid of Pip. D. Pip wants to attack Katya.","excerpt":"\"Katya dropped the blanket and reached into the pen; for an instant, she worried that Pip was going to nip her, but the rabbit ducked back inside.\"","stem":"What does this moment show about the trust between Katya and Pip?","choices":{"A":"They still do not trust each other at all.","B":"Pip is beginning to trust Katya enough to let her near the box.","C":"Katya is afraid of Pip.","D":"Pip wants to attack Katya."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip allows Katya close without biting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya dropped the blanket and reached into the pen; for an instant, she worried that Pip was going to nip her, but the rabbit ducked back inside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q014","read_aloud":"How does discovering the babies change the situation? A. It makes Katya want to return Pip. B. It explains why Pip was protective and gives Katya a new reason to care. C. It makes Katya afraid. D. It has no effect.","excerpt":"\"Each bunny was a tiny version of Pip, with miniature ears and eyelids squeezed tightly shut.\"","stem":"How does discovering the babies change the situation?","choices":{"A":"It makes Katya want to return Pip.","B":"It explains why Pip was protective and gives Katya a new reason to care.","C":"It makes Katya afraid.","D":"It has no effect."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip was being a protective mother.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Each bunny was a tiny version of Pip, with miniature ears and eyelids squeezed tightly shut.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence? A. play with happily B. allow or put up with C. run away from D. bite and scratch","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\"","stem":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"play with happily","B":"allow or put up with","C":"run away from","D":"bite and scratch"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Tolerate\" means to accept or put up with someone. The kittens would not accept anyone except Katya at first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q016","read_aloud":"Mom said. \"Do you think I hurt her pride?\" Katya asked. \"Could be,\" Mom replied. What theme is developing in this story? A. Animals are dangerous. B. Winning trust takes patience and understanding. C. Rabbits are better pets than cats. D. It is easy to make friends with animals.","excerpt":"You caught her, though,","stem":"Mom said. \"Do you think I hurt her pride?\" Katya asked. \"Could be,\" Mom replied. What theme is developing in this story?","choices":{"A":"Animals are dangerous.","B":"Winning trust takes patience and understanding.","C":"Rabbits are better pets than cats.","D":"It is easy to make friends with animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya is learning that catching Pip may have hurt the rabbit\u0027s feelings. She needs to be patient to win Pip\u0027s trust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You caught her, though,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q017","read_aloud":"How does Katya feel about Pip\u0027s behavior? A. She thinks Pip is funny. B. She feels hurt and confused. C. She wants to return Pip to the rescue center. D. She thinks Pip is sick.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought.\"","stem":"How does Katya feel about Pip\u0027s behavior?","choices":{"A":"She thinks Pip is funny.","B":"She feels hurt and confused.","C":"She wants to return Pip to the rescue center.","D":"She thinks Pip is sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya takes Pip\u0027s behavior personally. She feels confused because animals usually love her, but Pip seems annoyed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s as if she\u0027s annoyed with me personally, Katya thought.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q018","read_aloud":"he said, \"and she likes bananas. Fresh bananas, but you\u0027ve gotta peel them, and those dried-up banana chips. Why does Max share this information? A. He wants to tease Katya. B. He is trying to help Katya make friends with Pip. C. He wants to trade his aunt\u0027s rabbit for Pip. D. He is writing a report about rabbits.","excerpt":"My aunt has a rabbit,","stem":"he said, \"and she likes bananas. Fresh bananas, but you\u0027ve gotta peel them, and those dried-up banana chips. Why does Max share this information?","choices":{"A":"He wants to tease Katya.","B":"He is trying to help Katya make friends with Pip.","C":"He wants to trade his aunt\u0027s rabbit for Pip.","D":"He is writing a report about rabbits."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Max is being a good friend. He knows Katya is having trouble with Pip, so he shares a tip that might help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: My aunt has a rabbit,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q019","read_aloud":"What does this show about Katya? A. She is lazy and does not try new things. B. She is willing to try new ideas even if she is unsure. C. She does not trust her friends. D. She is afraid of bananas.","excerpt":"\"Katya peeled a banana and broke off a small piece. She had her doubts, but she went to the pen and held the bit of banana through the wire grate anyway.\"","stem":"What does this show about Katya?","choices":{"A":"She is lazy and does not try new things.","B":"She is willing to try new ideas even if she is unsure.","C":"She does not trust her friends.","D":"She is afraid of bananas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya had \"doubts\" but tried anyway. This shows she is open to new ideas and willing to make an effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya peeled a banana and broke off a small piece. She had her doubts, but she went to the pen and held the bit of banana through the wire grate anyway.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"tolerate\"? A. Ignore, B. Bear or endure, C. Hunt, D. Escape.","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you...\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"tolerate\"?","choices":{"A":"Ignore,","B":"Bear or endure,","C":"Hunt,","D":"Escape."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To tolerate is to endure or accept something that might be difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q002","read_aloud":"How does Katya\u0027s attitude change from the beginning to the middle of the story? A. She goes from wanting to help to being mean, B. She goes from being used to kittens to being challenged by a rabbit, C. She changes from happy to sad, D. She decides she doesn\u0027t want pets anymore.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"How does Katya\u0027s attitude change from the beginning to the middle of the story?","choices":{"A":"She goes from wanting to help to being mean,","B":"She goes from being used to kittens to being challenged by a rabbit,","C":"She changes from happy to sad,","D":"She decides she doesn\u0027t want pets anymore."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya expects the rabbit to act like the kittens she is used to, but Pip\u0027s different behavior challenges her.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why might the author mention the boa constrictor in the bathtub? A. To show that Katya\u0027s family takes in very unusual pets, B. To scare the reader, C. To make the story about snakes, D. To show that they don\u0027t like rabbits.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why might the author mention the boa constrictor in the bathtub?","choices":{"A":"To show that Katya\u0027s family takes in very unusual pets,","B":"To scare the reader,","C":"To make the story about snakes,","D":"To show that they don\u0027t like rabbits."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This detail establishes how varied and interesting the family\u0027s fostering experiences have been.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q004","read_aloud":"What does the phrase \"not exactly a force field\" tell us about the mother? A. She is a scientist, B. She has a sense of humor, C. She is very strict, D. She doesn\u0027t like blankets.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"What does the phrase \"not exactly a force field\" tell us about the mother?","choices":{"A":"She is a scientist,","B":"She has a sense of humor,","C":"She is very strict,","D":"She doesn\u0027t like blankets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using a pop-culture reference like \"force field\" shows she is trying to make a stressful situation a bit lighter and more humorous.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Mom said. She turned to Katya and asked, \"Why do you think she doesn\u0027t like you? How does the word \"quarters\" help the reader understand Pip\u0027s situation? A. It shows that Pip is a prisoner who cannot leave. B. It shows that the pen is Pip\u0027s temporary living space. C. It shows that Pip is being paid to live in the pen. D. It shows that the pen is a military base for animals.","excerpt":"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,","stem":"Mom said. She turned to Katya and asked, \"Why do you think she doesn\u0027t like you? How does the word \"quarters\" help the reader understand Pip\u0027s situation?","choices":{"A":"It shows that Pip is a prisoner who cannot leave.","B":"It shows that the pen is Pip\u0027s temporary living space.","C":"It shows that Pip is being paid to live in the pen.","D":"It shows that the pen is a military base for animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Quarters\" refers to living spaces. In this context, it highlights that the pen is where Pip is staying while she is fostered.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q006","read_aloud":"What detail shows that Pip is a mother? A. She is eating a large banana. B. She is hiding from Katya in the dark. C. She has three babies in a nest of fur. D. She is chewing on a decorative pinecone.","excerpt":"Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \"Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\" Katya exclaimed.","stem":"What detail shows that Pip is a mother?","choices":{"A":"She is eating a large banana.","B":"She is hiding from Katya in the dark.","C":"She has three babies in a nest of fur.","D":"She is chewing on a decorative pinecone."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Katya sees three small shapes in a nest made of hay and fur, which reveals that Pip has given birth to babies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \"Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\" Katya exclaimed."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the baby bunnies from this excerpt? A. They are ready to run around the house. B. They are very young and cannot see yet. C. They are hungry and looking for bananas. D. They are angry at Katya for waking them.","excerpt":"Each bunny was a tiny version of Pip, with miniature ears and eyelids squeezed tightly shut. Pip stood on her hind legs. \"You must be very proud of your new family!\" Katya said.","stem":"What can you infer about the baby bunnies from this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"They are ready to run around the house.","B":"They are very young and cannot see yet.","C":"They are hungry and looking for bananas.","D":"They are angry at Katya for waking them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The babies have \"eyelids squeezed tightly shut,\" which indicates they are newborns and not yet able to open their eyes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Each bunny was a tiny version of Pip, with miniature ears and eyelids squeezed tightly shut. Pip stood on her hind legs. \"You must be very proud of your new family!\" Katya said."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q008","read_aloud":"How does Pip\u0027s reaction show that she trusts Katya? A. Pip bites Katya\u0027s hand to get the baby back. B. Pip ignores Katya and stays in the cardboard box. C. Pip allows Katya to hold her baby without attacking. D. Pip jumps out of the pen and runs away.","excerpt":"Pip twitched her nose at Katya\u0027s fingers and, after deciding her baby was safe, hopped over to the other two. The baby bunny in Katya\u0027s hand was warm and soft, even though it didn\u0027t yet have fur.","stem":"How does Pip\u0027s reaction show that she trusts Katya?","choices":{"A":"Pip bites Katya\u0027s hand to get the baby back.","B":"Pip ignores Katya and stays in the cardboard box.","C":"Pip allows Katya to hold her baby without attacking.","D":"Pip jumps out of the pen and runs away."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Pip decides her baby is safe and moves to the other babies, showing she trusts Katya enough to let her hold her newborn.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip twitched her nose at Katya\u0027s fingers and, after deciding her baby was safe, hopped over to the other two. The baby bunny in Katya\u0027s hand was warm and soft, even though it didn\u0027t yet have fur."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q009","read_aloud":"What does Pip\u0027s action of licking the baby reveal about her? A. She is cleaning her baby and showing maternal care. B. She is tasting the baby to see if it is a banana. C. She is angry and trying to hurt the baby. D. She is asking Katya to take the baby home.","excerpt":"Katya put the baby back in the nest and stroked the other two. Pip licked the baby Katya had held and tucked it back in between its siblings. \"Thank you for showing me,\" Katya whispered.","stem":"What does Pip\u0027s action of licking the baby reveal about her?","choices":{"A":"She is cleaning her baby and showing maternal care.","B":"She is tasting the baby to see if it is a banana.","C":"She is angry and trying to hurt the baby.","D":"She is asking Katya to take the baby home."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip licks the baby and tucks it in, which are natural maternal behaviors showing she is caring for her newborn.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya put the baby back in the nest and stroked the other two. Pip licked the baby Katya had held and tucked it back in between its siblings. \"Thank you for showing me,\" Katya whispered."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q010","read_aloud":"Why is this moment the climax (turning point) of the story? A. Because Katya catches Pip. B. Because Pip shows Katya her babies, proving she trusts her. C. Because the babies are born. D. Because Katya decides to keep the babies.","excerpt":"\"Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom! … Congratulations! They\u0027re beautiful!\"","stem":"Why is this moment the climax (turning point) of the story?","choices":{"A":"Because Katya catches Pip.","B":"Because Pip shows Katya her babies, proving she trusts her.","C":"Because the babies are born.","D":"Because Katya decides to keep the babies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Trust is the main conflict, and this shows Pip finally trusts Katya.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom! … Congratulations! They\u0027re beautiful!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Pip from this sentence? A. She does not care about her babies. B. She is checking to make sure her baby is safe with Katya. C. She wants Katya to take the babies away. D. She is afraid of Katya\u0027s fingers.","excerpt":"\"Pip twitched her nose at Katya\u0027s fingers and, after deciding her baby was safe, hopped over to the other two.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Pip from this sentence?","choices":{"A":"She does not care about her babies.","B":"She is checking to make sure her baby is safe with Katya.","C":"She wants Katya to take the babies away.","D":"She is afraid of Katya\u0027s fingers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She checks before hopping away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip twitched her nose at Katya\u0027s fingers and, after deciding her baby was safe, hopped over to the other two.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What does Katya\u0027s careful movement show? A. She is clumsy. B. She respects Pip\u0027s space and is trying not to scare her. C. She is afraid of the babies. D. She wants to run away.","excerpt":"\"Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip, and slowly moved the box so she could see the baby rabbits inside.\"","stem":"What does Katya\u0027s careful movement show?","choices":{"A":"She is clumsy.","B":"She respects Pip\u0027s space and is trying not to scare her.","C":"She is afraid of the babies.","D":"She wants to run away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gingerly means with great care.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip, and slowly moved the box so she could see the baby rabbits inside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What lesson about trust can be learned from this story? A. Trust happens instantly. B. Trust can be built slowly with patience, kindness, and respect. C. Animals never trust humans. D. Only treats create trust.","excerpt":"\"I think she\u0027s finally decided to trust me.\"","stem":"What lesson about trust can be learned from this story?","choices":{"A":"Trust happens instantly.","B":"Trust can be built slowly with patience, kindness, and respect.","C":"Animals never trust humans.","D":"Only treats create trust."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust over time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I think she\u0027s finally decided to trust me.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q014","read_aloud":"What does \"tingled\" mean in this sentence? A. felt sharp pain B. felt excitement or a prickling sensation C. felt very cold D. felt sleepy","excerpt":"\"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\"","stem":"What does \"tingled\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"felt sharp pain","B":"felt excitement or a prickling sensation","C":"felt very cold","D":"felt sleepy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Tingled\" means to feel excitement or a prickling feeling. Katya was very happy but tried to stay calm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q015","read_aloud":"Why did Katya stay calm? A. She was not really happy. B. She knew excitement would scare Pip away. C. Her mom told her to be quiet. D. She was too tired to move.","excerpt":"\"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\"","stem":"Why did Katya stay calm?","choices":{"A":"She was not really happy.","B":"She knew excitement would scare Pip away.","C":"Her mom told her to be quiet.","D":"She was too tired to move."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya understood that sudden excitement might scare Pip. She stayed calm to keep Pip comfortable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q016","read_aloud":"What is Pip trying to tell Katya? A. Pip wants Katya to follow her. B. Pip wants more banana. C. Pip is scared of the box. D. Pip wants to go outside.","excerpt":"\"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box-and then back to Katya.\"","stem":"What is Pip trying to tell Katya?","choices":{"A":"Pip wants Katya to follow her.","B":"Pip wants more banana.","C":"Pip is scared of the box.","D":"Pip wants to go outside."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip keeps looking back and forth between Katya and the box. This suggests she wants Katya to notice something inside the box.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box-and then back to Katya.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Pip stomp her foot? A. She is happy to see Katya. B. She is annoyed or irritated. C. She wants to play a game. D. She is hungry for lettuce.","excerpt":"\"With an irritated stomp, Pip ducked back into her cardboard box.\"","stem":"Why does Pip stomp her foot?","choices":{"A":"She is happy to see Katya.","B":"She is annoyed or irritated.","C":"She wants to play a game.","D":"She is hungry for lettuce."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"irritated stomp.\" Rabbits stomp when they are annoyed or unhappy. Pip was not ready to trust Katya yet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With an irritated stomp, Pip ducked back into her cardboard box.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q018","read_aloud":"How has Katya\u0027s attitude changed? A. She now hates Pip and wants her gone. B. She has become more patient and creative. C. She has decided to stop trying. D. She wants to get a different rabbit.","excerpt":"\"Katya started thinking of it as a game they played, she and this rabbit that didn\u0027t like her. Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning.\"","stem":"How has Katya\u0027s attitude changed?","choices":{"A":"She now hates Pip and wants her gone.","B":"She has become more patient and creative.","C":"She has decided to stop trying.","D":"She wants to get a different rabbit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Instead of giving up, Katya made a game of it and kept talking to Pip. She found a creative, patient way to build trust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya started thinking of it as a game they played, she and this rabbit that didn\u0027t like her. Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Why does the author start with the story of the kittens before introducing Pip? A. To establish that the family is experienced with fostering, B. To show she hates rabbits, C. To fill up space, D. To make us feel sorry for the kittens.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why does the author start with the story of the kittens before introducing Pip?","choices":{"A":"To establish that the family is experienced with fostering,","B":"To show she hates rabbits,","C":"To fill up space,","D":"To make us feel sorry for the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"It creates context that the Ryans are experts at fostering, which highlights why Pip is a \"different\" kind of challenge.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What does it mean when the author says Katya is \"accustomed\" to foster animals? A. She has to be taught how to behave, B. She is comfortable and experienced with this lifestyle, C. She is always surprised, D. She is usually afraid of new pets.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"What does it mean when the author says Katya is \"accustomed\" to foster animals?","choices":{"A":"She has to be taught how to behave,","B":"She is comfortable and experienced with this lifestyle,","C":"She is always surprised,","D":"She is usually afraid of new pets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being accustomed means it is part of her normal life; she is not surprised by it anymore.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q003","read_aloud":"How does Katya show maturity during the story? A. By giving up on the rabbit, B. By listening to her mother\u0027s advice and trying to understand the rabbit\u0027s needs, C. By letting the rabbit out, D. By crying for the kittens.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"How does Katya show maturity during the story?","choices":{"A":"By giving up on the rabbit,","B":"By listening to her mother\u0027s advice and trying to understand the rabbit\u0027s needs,","C":"By letting the rabbit out,","D":"By crying for the kittens."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She moves from being frustrated by the rabbit\u0027s behavior to following her mom\u0027s advice, showing she can learn and adapt.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does the word \"wriggled\" emphasize the conflict between Katya and Pip? A. It shows that Pip is trying to escape Katya\u0027s hold. B. It shows that Pip is happily playing a game with Katya. C. It shows that Pip is asleep and cannot move. D. It shows that Pip is eating a banana peacefully.","excerpt":"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success. \"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,\" Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one.\"","stem":"How does the word \"wriggled\" emphasize the conflict between Katya and Pip?","choices":{"A":"It shows that Pip is trying to escape Katya\u0027s hold.","B":"It shows that Pip is happily playing a game with Katya.","C":"It shows that Pip is asleep and cannot move.","D":"It shows that Pip is eating a banana peacefully."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Wriggled\" means twisting to get free. This physical struggle highlights the early tension and lack of trust between them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success. \"You\u0027re nothing like a cat,\" Katya declared. Pip gave her a look that said, \"You\u0027ve won round one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q005","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Katya is cleaning the pen and throwing away the box. B. Katya is carefully securing the pen after seeing the babies. C. Katya is taking the baby bunnies out to play. D. Katya is removing the blanket to feed Pip.","excerpt":"She gently replaced the cardboard box over the little family. Then she climbed out of Pip\u0027s pen, reattached the roof blanket, and stepped carefully out of the room.","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Katya is cleaning the pen and throwing away the box.","B":"Katya is carefully securing the pen after seeing the babies.","C":"Katya is taking the baby bunnies out to play.","D":"Katya is removing the blanket to feed Pip."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya carefully puts the box back, climbs out, and reattaches the blanket, showing she is respectfully securing the space after her special visit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She gently replaced the cardboard box over the little family. Then she climbed out of Pip\u0027s pen, reattached the roof blanket, and stepped carefully out of the room."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q006","read_aloud":"How does Katya\u0027s mood change from the beginning of the story to this moment? A. She goes from feeling scared to feeling angry. B. She goes from feeling frustrated to feeling joyful. C. She goes from feeling bored to feeling sleepy. D. She goes from feeling sad to feeling hungry.","excerpt":"Smiling, Katya walked outside, where her parents were drinking tea at the patio table. Mom said, \"Why the big grin, Sunshine? Did something just happen?\"","stem":"How does Katya\u0027s mood change from the beginning of the story to this moment?","choices":{"A":"She goes from feeling scared to feeling angry.","B":"She goes from feeling frustrated to feeling joyful.","C":"She goes from feeling bored to feeling sleepy.","D":"She goes from feeling sad to feeling hungry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya starts the story frustrated that Pip doesn\u0027t like her, but she is now smiling and grinning because Pip showed her the babies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Smiling, Katya walked outside, where her parents were drinking tea at the patio table. Mom said, \"Why the big grin, Sunshine? Did something just happen?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Why do the parents exchange \"concerned glances\"? A. They think Katya is in trouble for breaking the pen. B. They think Katya might be sick or hurt. C. They think something bad might have happened to Pip. D. They think Katya is lying about the baby bunnies.","excerpt":"Her parents exchanged quick, concerned glances, the way parents often do. \"Is something...wrong with Pip?\" Dad asked cautiously.","stem":"Why do the parents exchange \"concerned glances\"?","choices":{"A":"They think Katya is in trouble for breaking the pen.","B":"They think Katya might be sick or hurt.","C":"They think something bad might have happened to Pip.","D":"They think Katya is lying about the baby bunnies."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Parents often look concerned when a child has a huge, unexpected grin, fearing that the child might have done something wrong or that a pet might be sick.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her parents exchanged quick, concerned glances, the way parents often do. \"Is something...wrong with Pip?\" Dad asked cautiously."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. What does Dad\u0027s statement reveal about his character? A. He is strict and never changes the family rules. B. He is observant and values Katya\u0027s hard work and empathy. C. He is lazy and doesn\u0027t want to take care of more animals. D. He is angry that Katya didn\u0027t ask for permission first.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. What does Dad\u0027s statement reveal about his character?","choices":{"A":"He is strict and never changes the family rules.","B":"He is observant and values Katya\u0027s hard work and empathy.","C":"He is lazy and doesn\u0027t want to take care of more animals.","D":"He is angry that Katya didn\u0027t ask for permission first."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dad recognizes how hard Katya worked to earn Pip\u0027s trust and wants to reward her effort, showing he is supportive and observant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"wriggled\"? A. Squirmed B. Stood still C. Slept D. Ate","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"wriggled\"?","choices":{"A":"Squirmed","B":"Stood still","C":"Slept","D":"Ate"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wriggled means twisted and squirmed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Katya asked Mom one morning, after Pip had once again ignored her best all-out efforts to make friends. What is the problem Katya is trying to solve? A. How to catch Pip B. How to make friends with Pip C. How to feed the kittens D. How to clean the pen","excerpt":"Why do you think she\u0027s acting that way?","stem":"Katya asked Mom one morning, after Pip had once again ignored her best all-out efforts to make friends. What is the problem Katya is trying to solve?","choices":{"A":"How to catch Pip","B":"How to make friends with Pip","C":"How to feed the kittens","D":"How to clean the pen"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She wants Pip to like her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Why do you think she\u0027s acting that way?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What is Mom\u0027s advice to Katya? A. Give up on Pip. B. Accept that not every animal will like her immediately. C. Force Pip to like her. D. Get a different pet.","excerpt":"\"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.\"","stem":"What is Mom\u0027s advice to Katya?","choices":{"A":"Give up on Pip.","B":"Accept that not every animal will like her immediately.","C":"Force Pip to like her.","D":"Get a different pet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom explains that animals have individual preferences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q012","read_aloud":"How does Katya\u0027s mental image of Pip show her feelings have changed? A. She now sees Pip as mean and scary. B. She now sees Pip as a good mother deserving care and respect. C. She thinks Pip is boring. D. She is angry at Pip.","excerpt":"\"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet. She pictured Pip in the box, the good mama keeping her baby bunnies warm.\"","stem":"How does Katya\u0027s mental image of Pip show her feelings have changed?","choices":{"A":"She now sees Pip as mean and scary.","B":"She now sees Pip as a good mother deserving care and respect.","C":"She thinks Pip is boring.","D":"She is angry at Pip."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her image is warm and positive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet. She pictured Pip in the box, the good mama keeping her baby bunnies warm.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Why does Katya feel sorry about this? A. She doesn\u0027t like the babies. B. She has bonded with Pip and the babies and wants them to stay. C. The babies are sick. D. She wants to return them immediately.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\"","stem":"Why does Katya feel sorry about this?","choices":{"A":"She doesn\u0027t like the babies.","B":"She has bonded with Pip and the babies and wants them to stay.","C":"The babies are sick.","D":"She wants to return them immediately."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She has grown attached.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Using context clues from the paragraph, what does \"gingerly\" mean? A. quickly and loudly B. slowly and carefully C. angrily and roughly D. happily and excitedly","excerpt":"\"Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip.\"","stem":"Using context clues from the paragraph, what does \"gingerly\" mean?","choices":{"A":"quickly and loudly","B":"slowly and carefully","C":"angrily and roughly","D":"happily and excitedly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The words \"tiptoed,\" \"ever so,\" and \"gently\" are clues. \"Gingerly\" means to move slowly and carefully so you do not scare someone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Why is this the climax of the story? A. It is the most exciting turning point. B. It happens at the very end. C. It is the saddest part of the story. D. It is the first time we meet Pip.","excerpt":"\"Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \u0027Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\u0027 Katya exclaimed.\"","stem":"Why is this the climax of the story?","choices":{"A":"It is the most exciting turning point.","B":"It happens at the very end.","C":"It is the saddest part of the story.","D":"It is the first time we meet Pip."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This is the climax because it is the turning point where everything changes. Katya finally understands why Pip was acting strangely.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \u0027Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\u0027 Katya exclaimed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Pip\u0027s feelings? A. Pip is scared of her babies. B. Pip is proud and trusts Katya enough to show her babies. C. Pip wants to leave her babies. D. Pip is angry at Katya.","excerpt":"\"Pip stood on her hind legs. \u0027You must be very proud of your new family!\u0027 Katya said.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Pip\u0027s feelings?","choices":{"A":"Pip is scared of her babies.","B":"Pip is proud and trusts Katya enough to show her babies.","C":"Pip wants to leave her babies.","D":"Pip is angry at Katya."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip stood up tall and showed Katya her babies. This means Pip trusts Katya and is proud of her new family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip stood on her hind legs. \u0027You must be very proud of your new family!\u0027 Katya said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Pip lick the baby and tuck it back in? A. Pip is cleaning her baby and keeping it safe. B. Pip does not like Katya touching the baby. C. Pip wants to play with the baby. D. Pip is hungry and wants to eat.","excerpt":"\"Katya put the baby back in the nest and stroked the other two. Pip licked the baby Katya had held and tucked it back in between its siblings.\"","stem":"Why does Pip lick the baby and tuck it back in?","choices":{"A":"Pip is cleaning her baby and keeping it safe.","B":"Pip does not like Katya touching the baby.","C":"Pip wants to play with the baby.","D":"Pip is hungry and wants to eat."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mother animals lick their babies to clean them. Tucking the baby back in the nest keeps it warm and safe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya put the baby back in the nest and stroked the other two. Pip licked the baby Katya had held and tucked it back in between its siblings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Why does Katya \"shake herself\"? A. She is cold. B. She is trying to wake up from a dream. C. She is so surprised she needs to calm down. D. She is angry at her parents.","excerpt":"\"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet.\"","stem":"Why does Katya \"shake herself\"?","choices":{"A":"She is cold.","B":"She is trying to wake up from a dream.","C":"She is so surprised she needs to calm down.","D":"She is angry at her parents."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Katya can hardly believe what happened. Shaking herself helps her realize it is real and calm her excitement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What is the best antonym for \"success\" in this context? A. Achievement, B. Failure, C. Gain, D. Luck.","excerpt":"\"...trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What is the best antonym for \"success\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"Achievement,","B":"Failure,","C":"Gain,","D":"Luck."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Success\" is reaching a goal; \"failure\" is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Do you think the author made a good decision to have Pip act skittish rather than friendly at first? A. No, because it\u0027s boring, B. Yes, because it makes the growth of their relationship more realistic and rewarding, C. No, because all rabbits are friendly, D. Yes, because it makes the rabbit seem mean.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Do you think the author made a good decision to have Pip act skittish rather than friendly at first?","choices":{"A":"No, because it\u0027s boring,","B":"Yes, because it makes the growth of their relationship more realistic and rewarding,","C":"No, because all rabbits are friendly,","D":"Yes, because it makes the rabbit seem mean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It creates a narrative arc-it\u0027s more interesting to watch the character \"earn\" the rabbit\u0027s trust.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q003","read_aloud":"What is the underlying theme of the story? A. Rabbits are better than kittens, B. Taking care of animals requires patience and understanding their unique behaviors, C. Fostering is too hard for kids, D. Snakes make the best pets.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"What is the underlying theme of the story?","choices":{"A":"Rabbits are better than kittens,","B":"Taking care of animals requires patience and understanding their unique behaviors,","C":"Fostering is too hard for kids,","D":"Snakes make the best pets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The central lesson is that every animal is different, and being a good foster parent means adjusting to those differences.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Is Katya a successful foster owner? Why? A. No, she can\u0027t catch the rabbit, B. Yes, because she is willing to learn, observe, and respect the rabbit\u0027s needs, C. No, she misses the kittens, D. Yes, because she is rich.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Is Katya a successful foster owner? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, she can\u0027t catch the rabbit,","B":"Yes, because she is willing to learn, observe, and respect the rabbit\u0027s needs,","C":"No, she misses the kittens,","D":"Yes, because she is rich."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her willingness to try, fail, and listen to her mother shows she is a responsible and caring foster owner.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q005","read_aloud":"How would the story change if Katya had been the one to choose Pip at the center? A. She might have been more prepared for Pip\u0027s personality, B. She would have chosen a snake, C. The rabbit would be friendlier, D. Her mom would be angry.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"How would the story change if Katya had been the one to choose Pip at the center?","choices":{"A":"She might have been more prepared for Pip\u0027s personality,","B":"She would have chosen a snake,","C":"The rabbit would be friendlier,","D":"Her mom would be angry."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"If Katya chose the animal, she might have had more \"buy-in\" or understanding of why she picked that specific rabbit, changing her emotional reaction.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q006","read_aloud":"her Mom said with a laugh. \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets. How does the concept of \"tolerate\" explain the difference between the kittens and Pip? A. The kittens tolerated Katya\u0027s love, while Pip refuses to tolerate Katya at all. B. The kittens tolerated everyone, while Pip only tolerates Dad. C. The kittens tolerated Katya\u0027s presence, while Pip currently does not tolerate Katya near her. D. The kittens did not tolerate food, while Pip tolerates only bananas.","excerpt":"Yes, you did an amazing job with those two,","stem":"her Mom said with a laugh. \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets. How does the concept of \"tolerate\" explain the difference between the kittens and Pip?","choices":{"A":"The kittens tolerated Katya\u0027s love, while Pip refuses to tolerate Katya at all.","B":"The kittens tolerated everyone, while Pip only tolerates Dad.","C":"The kittens tolerated Katya\u0027s presence, while Pip currently does not tolerate Katya near her.","D":"The kittens did not tolerate food, while Pip tolerates only bananas."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The kittens eventually accepted and tolerated Katya, leading to a bond. Pip currently hides and does not tolerate Katya\u0027s presence in the room.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Yes, you did an amazing job with those two,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What detail shows that Pip is easily frightened by loud noises? A. Pip eats a banana very quickly. B. Pip bolts for the open door when Dad enters. C. Pip hides in the cardboard box all day. D. Pip licks her baby bunnies gently.","excerpt":"Bang! The front door crashed open; Dad was back from his morning run. At the sound, Pip jumped to her feet and bolted past Katya, heading for the front hall and the open door.","stem":"What detail shows that Pip is easily frightened by loud noises?","choices":{"A":"Pip eats a banana very quickly.","B":"Pip bolts for the open door when Dad enters.","C":"Pip hides in the cardboard box all day.","D":"Pip licks her baby bunnies gently."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When the door crashes open, Pip immediately jumps up and runs away, showing she is startled by the loud noise.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bang! The front door crashed open; Dad was back from his morning run. At the sound, Pip jumped to her feet and bolted past Katya, heading for the front hall and the open door."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q008","read_aloud":"What sequence of events leads to Pip trusting Katya? A. Katya chases Pip, then feeds her lettuce, then puts up a blanket. B. Katya offers a banana, then talks daily to the box, then Pip comes out. C. Katya yells at Pip, then gives her a toy, then Pip shows her babies. D. Katya ignores Pip, then cleans the pen, then Pip eats a pinecone.","excerpt":"Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning, telling Pip about things she did with her friends, about the books she was reading, and about what happened at school.","stem":"What sequence of events leads to Pip trusting Katya?","choices":{"A":"Katya chases Pip, then feeds her lettuce, then puts up a blanket.","B":"Katya offers a banana, then talks daily to the box, then Pip comes out.","C":"Katya yells at Pip, then gives her a toy, then Pip shows her babies.","D":"Katya ignores Pip, then cleans the pen, then Pip eats a pinecone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya consistently offers bananas and talks calmly to the box, which eventually leads to Pip feeling safe enough to come out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Still, she would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning, telling Pip about things she did with her friends, about the books she was reading, and about what happened at school."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think Katya made the right choice by removing the clothespins? Use clues from the text. A. No, because Pip bit Katya\u0027s hand when she removed the pins. B. Yes, because her slow and careful actions showed Pip she was safe. C. No, because Pip ran away and hid under the sofa. D. Yes, because Katya wanted to take the blanket home to wash it.","excerpt":"Not wanting to frighten Pip, Katya rose slowly and reached for the first clothespin. Cautious but not scared, Pip watched carefully. As she removed the rest of the pins Katya was so excited that her hands were shaking.","stem":"Do you think Katya made the right choice by removing the clothespins? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because Pip bit Katya\u0027s hand when she removed the pins.","B":"Yes, because her slow and careful actions showed Pip she was safe.","C":"No, because Pip ran away and hid under the sofa.","D":"Yes, because Katya wanted to take the blanket home to wash it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya moves slowly and Pip watches \"cautious but not scared,\" proving that Katya\u0027s respectful choice allowed Pip to feel safe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Not wanting to frighten Pip, Katya rose slowly and reached for the first clothespin. Cautious but not scared, Pip watched carefully. As she removed the rest of the pins Katya was so excited that her hands were shaking."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Based on the entire story, was the family\u0027s decision to keep Pip a good one? A. No, because foster animals are never allowed to stay forever. B. Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust and they formed a family bond. C. No, because Pip will miss the other animals at the rescue center. D. Yes, because Katya needed a pet that was exactly like a cat.","excerpt":"Katya beamed, thinking, \"Forever, not fosters!\"","stem":"Based on the entire story, was the family\u0027s decision to keep Pip a good one?","choices":{"A":"No, because foster animals are never allowed to stay forever.","B":"Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust and they formed a family bond.","C":"No, because Pip will miss the other animals at the rescue center.","D":"Yes, because Katya needed a pet that was exactly like a cat."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya worked hard to win Pip\u0027s trust, and Pip showed her the babies, proving they had formed a strong, loving bond worthy of a forever home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya beamed, thinking, \"Forever, not fosters!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q011","read_aloud":"How has Katya\u0027s attitude toward Pip changed? A. From angry/frustrated to caring and respectful B. From loving to hating C. No change D. From scared to brave","excerpt":"Compare Katya\u0027s attitude in paragraph 13 (\"As Katya glared at Pip\") with paragraph 64 (\"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet.\")","stem":"How has Katya\u0027s attitude toward Pip changed?","choices":{"A":"From angry/frustrated to caring and respectful","B":"From loving to hating","C":"No change","D":"From scared to brave"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"At first she glared; later she is gentle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Katya\u0027s attitude in paragraph 13 (\"As Katya glared at Pip\") with paragraph 64 (\"Katya shook herself, hardly believing what had just happened. Then, she peered back into the living room, where all was quiet.\")"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail? A. To show that Katya is lonely B. To show that Katya is persistent and patient in building a relationship C. To make the story longer D. To show that Katya hates talking","excerpt":"The author includes the detail that Katya talked to Pip\u0027s box every morning.","stem":"Why does the author include this detail?","choices":{"A":"To show that Katya is lonely","B":"To show that Katya is persistent and patient in building a relationship","C":"To make the story longer","D":"To show that Katya hates talking"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It shows her dedication.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author includes the detail that Katya talked to Pip\u0027s box every morning."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. Do you think the rule should be changed? Why? A. No, because rules are rules. B. Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust, and keeping them together could be best. C. No, because rabbits do not need homes. D. Yes, because all fosters should stay.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. Do you think the rule should be changed? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because rules are rules.","B":"Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust, and keeping them together could be best.","C":"No, because rabbits do not need homes.","D":"Yes, because all fosters should stay."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Trust and care are good reasons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q014","read_aloud":"If Katya wrote a guide for \"How to Befriend a Shy Foster Rabbit,\" what would be the first tip? A. Chase the rabbit around the house. B. Be patient, speak softly, and offer small treats like banana. C. Ignore the rabbit completely. D. Yell to get its attention.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If Katya wrote a guide for \"How to Befriend a Shy Foster Rabbit,\" what would be the first tip?","choices":{"A":"Chase the rabbit around the house.","B":"Be patient, speak softly, and offer small treats like banana.","C":"Ignore the rabbit completely.","D":"Yell to get its attention."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"These are the methods Katya used successfully.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"tolerate\"? A. accept B. allow C. refuse D. permit","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"tolerate\"?","choices":{"A":"accept","B":"allow","C":"refuse","D":"permit"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Tolerate\" means to accept or put up with. The opposite is \"refuse,\" which means to not accept or reject.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use this sentence? A. To show that Pip is really talking. B. To add humor and show Pip\u0027s personality. C. To make Katya seem mean. D. To show that rabbits can talk.","excerpt":"\"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author use this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To show that Pip is really talking.","B":"To add humor and show Pip\u0027s personality.","C":"To make Katya seem mean.","D":"To show that rabbits can talk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses humor by making it seem like Pip has human thoughts. This makes Pip seem like a character with attitude.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pip gave her a look that said, \u0027You\u0027ve won round one.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q017","read_aloud":"How has the meaning of \"borrowed bunny\" changed from the beginning to the end? A. It changed from temporary to possibly permanent. B. It changed from a rabbit to a cat. C. It changed from a pet to a wild animal. D. It changed from happy to sad.","excerpt":"\"Katya pulled up a chair. \u0027Well, it looks like we don\u0027t have a borrowed bunny anymore,\u0027 she said.\"","stem":"How has the meaning of \"borrowed bunny\" changed from the beginning to the end?","choices":{"A":"It changed from temporary to possibly permanent.","B":"It changed from a rabbit to a cat.","C":"It changed from a pet to a wild animal.","D":"It changed from happy to sad."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"At first, Pip was a temporary foster. At the end, Dad suggests keeping her forever because of the babies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya pulled up a chair. \u0027Well, it looks like we don\u0027t have a borrowed bunny anymore,\u0027 she said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think Dad makes a good decision? Why or why not? A. No, because rabbits are too much work. B. Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust and Pip has babies now. C. No, because they should only foster cats. D. Yes, because Pip is expensive.","excerpt":"\"Dad said. \u0027Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think Dad makes a good decision? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because rabbits are too much work.","B":"Yes, because Katya earned Pip\u0027s trust and Pip has babies now.","C":"No, because they should only foster cats.","D":"Yes, because Pip is expensive."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya worked hard to build trust. Separating Pip from her babies and home would break that trust. It is kind to let them stay.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad said. \u0027Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Why is this a good ending for the story? A. It shows Katya learned that hard work and patience pay off. B. It shows that fostering is always bad. C. It shows that rabbits are better than kittens. D. It shows that Katya never liked Pip.","excerpt":"\"Katya beamed, thinking, \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\"","stem":"Why is this a good ending for the story?","choices":{"A":"It shows Katya learned that hard work and patience pay off.","B":"It shows that fostering is always bad.","C":"It shows that rabbits are better than kittens.","D":"It shows that Katya never liked Pip."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The ending shows Katya\u0027s growth. She learned that patience and kindness earned Pip\u0027s trust, and now they have a forever home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya beamed, thinking, \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"execute\" mean here? A. To kill, B. To perform or carry out, C. To stop, D. To break.","excerpt":"\"...but managed to execute a sharp right turn...\"","stem":"What does \"execute\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"To kill,","B":"To perform or carry out,","C":"To stop,","D":"To break."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To execute a move means to successfully perform or carry it out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...but managed to execute a sharp right turn...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q002","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the detail that Pip stomped her foot? A. To show the rabbit is excited, B. To demonstrate the rabbit\u0027s frustration and need for space, C. To show the rabbit is dancing, D. To explain how rabbits walk.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why does the author include the detail that Pip stomped her foot?","choices":{"A":"To show the rabbit is excited,","B":"To demonstrate the rabbit\u0027s frustration and need for space,","C":"To show the rabbit is dancing,","D":"To explain how rabbits walk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stomping is a very specific rabbit action that communicates \"I am annoyed\" or \"I feel threatened.\"","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q003","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Ryans\u0027 house environment? A. It is a place of constant change and animal activity, B. It is very quiet and boring, C. It is a place where only kittens are allowed, D. It is a place that hates animals.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"What can you infer about the Ryans\u0027 house environment?","choices":{"A":"It is a place of constant change and animal activity,","B":"It is very quiet and boring,","C":"It is a place where only kittens are allowed,","D":"It is a place that hates animals."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The mention of kittens, rabbits, and boa constrictors shows an environment defined by diverse animal foster care.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q004","read_aloud":"How well does the title \"A Borrowed Bunny\" fit the story? A. It fits perfectly because the rabbit is a temporary \"borrowed\" pet, B. It doesn\u0027t make sense, C. It\u0027s confusing because the rabbit isn\u0027t a toy, D. It\u0027s only about a toy bunny.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"How well does the title \"A Borrowed Bunny\" fit the story?","choices":{"A":"It fits perfectly because the rabbit is a temporary \"borrowed\" pet,","B":"It doesn\u0027t make sense,","C":"It\u0027s confusing because the rabbit isn\u0027t a toy,","D":"It\u0027s only about a toy bunny."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Borrowed\" reflects the temporary nature of fostering-you have them for a while, but they aren\u0027t yours forever.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Write a one-sentence ending for this story. A. Katya and Pip sat quietly together, finally starting to trust each other, B. Katya decided to keep the snake instead, C. The rabbit ran away to California, D. Katya went to school.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Write a one-sentence ending for this story.","choices":{"A":"Katya and Pip sat quietly together, finally starting to trust each other,","B":"Katya decided to keep the snake instead,","C":"The rabbit ran away to California,","D":"Katya went to school."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This ending provides a satisfying resolution to the conflict of the rabbit\u0027s fear and Katya\u0027s initial impatience.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"tingled\" help the reader understand Katya\u0027s internal conflict? A. It shows she is physically sick from eating too many bananas. B. It shows she is feeling intense joy but must hide it to keep Pip calm. C. It shows she is angry at Pip for ignoring her. D. It shows she is cold because the blanket is not working.","excerpt":"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story, then starting talking about a new book she had gotten from the library.","stem":"How does the word \"tingled\" help the reader understand Katya\u0027s internal conflict?","choices":{"A":"It shows she is physically sick from eating too many bananas.","B":"It shows she is feeling intense joy but must hide it to keep Pip calm.","C":"It shows she is angry at Pip for ignoring her.","D":"It shows she is cold because the blanket is not working."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Tingled with joy\" shows her inner excitement, which contrasts with her need to act \"casually\" on the outside so she doesn\u0027t scare Pip.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story, then starting talking about a new book she had gotten from the library."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q007","read_aloud":"What detail shows that Pip is interested in the banana? A. Her nose is twitching madly at the scent. B. Her ears are flattened against her head. C. Her eyes are closed tightly in sleep. D. Her feet are stomping loudly on the floor.","excerpt":"After a moment, Pip poked her head out of the cardboard box, her nose twitching madly at the scent of the fruit. \"Come on, it\u0027s all right,\" Katya whispered.","stem":"What detail shows that Pip is interested in the banana?","choices":{"A":"Her nose is twitching madly at the scent.","B":"Her ears are flattened against her head.","C":"Her eyes are closed tightly in sleep.","D":"Her feet are stomping loudly on the floor."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip\u0027s nose twitches \"madly at the scent,\" which is a clear physical sign that she is curious and interested in the smell of the fruit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a moment, Pip poked her head out of the cardboard box, her nose twitching madly at the scent of the fruit. \"Come on, it\u0027s all right,\" Katya whispered."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q008","read_aloud":"What can you infer from Pip looking back and forth? A. Pip is trying to decide if she should run away. B. Pip is inviting Katya to come see something in the box. C. Pip is angry that Katya didn\u0027t bring more bananas. D. Pip is checking to see if the front door is open.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"What can you infer from Pip looking back and forth?","choices":{"A":"Pip is trying to decide if she should run away.","B":"Pip is inviting Katya to come see something in the box.","C":"Pip is angry that Katya didn\u0027t bring more bananas.","D":"Pip is checking to see if the front door is open."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip\u0027s repeated glances between Katya and the box act as an invitation, showing she wants Katya to follow her to see the babies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Katya asked. \"Is there something wrong with your box?\" Not wanting to frighten Pip, Katya rose slowly and reached for the first clothespin. If you were to write a short story from Pip\u0027s perspective at this moment, what would she be thinking? A. \"I hope Katya doesn\u0027t take my babies away from me.\" B. \"I am going to bite Katya if she opens this blanket.\" C. \"I want to show Katya my new family because she is kind.\" D. \"I wish Katya would bring me more pinecones to eat.\"","excerpt":"What is it, Pip?","stem":"Katya asked. \"Is there something wrong with your box?\" Not wanting to frighten Pip, Katya rose slowly and reached for the first clothespin. If you were to write a short story from Pip\u0027s perspective at this moment, what would she be thinking?","choices":{"A":"\"I hope Katya doesn\u0027t take my babies away from me.\"","B":"\"I am going to bite Katya if she opens this blanket.\"","C":"\"I want to show Katya my new family because she is kind.\"","D":"\"I wish Katya would bring me more pinecones to eat.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Pip has accepted the bananas and Katya\u0027s calm voice, so she is likely thinking about sharing her secret because she trusts Katya.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What is it, Pip?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q010","read_aloud":"he said. \"I think we\u0027ve got a couple of bananas in the kitchen. Why don\u0027t you give it a try? How would the story change if Max had never told Katya about the bananas? A. Katya would have taken Pip back to the rescue center the next day. B. Katya would have never found a way to bond with Pip and see the babies. C. Katya would have fed Pip only carrots until Pip finally came out. D. Katya would have asked her dad to build a larger pen for Pip.","excerpt":"I thought rabbits only liked vegetables, you know, carrots and lettuce and celery,","stem":"he said. \"I think we\u0027ve got a couple of bananas in the kitchen. Why don\u0027t you give it a try? How would the story change if Max had never told Katya about the bananas?","choices":{"A":"Katya would have taken Pip back to the rescue center the next day.","B":"Katya would have never found a way to bond with Pip and see the babies.","C":"Katya would have fed Pip only carrots until Pip finally came out.","D":"Katya would have asked her dad to build a larger pen for Pip."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The banana was the breakthrough that allowed Katya to sit quietly with Pip daily, which ultimately led to Pip trusting her enough to show her the babies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I thought rabbits only liked vegetables, you know, carrots and lettuce and celery,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What is an antonym of \"tingled\" in this context? A. Felt numb or no feeling B. Felt excited C. Felt pricked D. Felt warm","excerpt":"\"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\"","stem":"What is an antonym of \"tingled\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"Felt numb or no feeling","B":"Felt excited","C":"Felt pricked","D":"Felt warm"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tingled is a feeling; numb is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Is this a fair observation? Why? A. No, because all pets are the same. B. Yes, because Pip behaves differently from the cats Katya knows. C. No, because she should compare her to a snake. D. Yes, because cats are better.","excerpt":"Katya says, \"You\u0027re nothing like a cat.\"","stem":"Is this a fair observation? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because all pets are the same.","B":"Yes, because Pip behaves differently from the cats Katya knows.","C":"No, because she should compare her to a snake.","D":"Yes, because cats are better."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pip\u0027s behavior is different from cats.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya says, \"You\u0027re nothing like a cat.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q013","read_aloud":"What is one theme of \"A Borrowed Bunny\"? A. Animals are boring. B. Patience and kindness can build trust. C. Give up if something is hard. D. Only adults can care for animals.","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"What is one theme of \"A Borrowed Bunny\"?","choices":{"A":"Animals are boring.","B":"Patience and kindness can build trust.","C":"Give up if something is hard.","D":"Only adults can care for animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya\u0027s patience pays off.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Was staying calm a good choice? Why? A. No, because she should show her excitement. B. Yes, because sudden movements would scare Pip away. C. No, because Pip doesn\u0027t care. D. Yes, because Katya is shy.","excerpt":"\"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm.\"","stem":"Was staying calm a good choice? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because she should show her excitement.","B":"Yes, because sudden movements would scare Pip away.","C":"No, because Pip doesn\u0027t care.","D":"Yes, because Katya is shy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Staying calm kept Pip eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q015","read_aloud":"If the author wrote a sequel about the baby bunnies, what would be a good title? A. \"The Bunnies Who Never Grew\" B. \"Growing Up with Pip\u0027s Family\" C. \"How to Catch a Rabbit Again\" D. \"The Day the Bunnies Left\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If the author wrote a sequel about the baby bunnies, what would be a good title?","choices":{"A":"\"The Bunnies Who Never Grew\"","B":"\"Growing Up with Pip\u0027s Family\"","C":"\"How to Catch a Rabbit Again\"","D":"\"The Day the Bunnies Left\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It follows the theme of growth and family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"snuggled\"? A. hid B. cuddled C. jumped D. ran","excerpt":"\"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"snuggled\"?","choices":{"A":"hid","B":"cuddled","C":"jumped","D":"ran"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Snuggled\" and \"cuddled\" both mean to get comfortable and cozy by curling up close.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What is the main theme of this story? A. All animals are dangerous. B. Patience and kindness can build trust and change relationships. C. Rabbits do not make good pets. D. It is easy to make animals like you.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\"","stem":"What is the main theme of this story?","choices":{"A":"All animals are dangerous.","B":"Patience and kindness can build trust and change relationships.","C":"Rabbits do not make good pets.","D":"It is easy to make animals like you."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya was patient and kind even when Pip ignored her. Over time, Pip learned to trust her, showing how patience changes relationships.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail? A. To show that Katya\u0027s family has unusual experiences. B. To make readers afraid of snakes. C. To show that snakes are good pets. D. To explain why Katya hates all animals.","excerpt":"\"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub, but Mavis the snake had been with them only for an overnight.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this detail?","choices":{"A":"To show that Katya\u0027s family has unusual experiences.","B":"To make readers afraid of snakes.","C":"To show that snakes are good pets.","D":"To explain why Katya hates all animals."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses humor to show that fostering animals leads to funny, surprising situations. It makes the story more interesting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub, but Mavis the snake had been with them only for an overnight.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Is Katya right to feel that Pip is annoyed with her? Use evidence. A. No, because Pip was just scared of a new place. B. Yes, because rabbits are always mean. C. No, because Katya was too loud. D. Yes, because Pip hated all girls.","excerpt":"\"Katya sighed. \u0027I\u0027m not sure, really. There\u0027s just something about the way she looks at me.\u0027\"","stem":"Is Katya right to feel that Pip is annoyed with her? Use evidence.","choices":{"A":"No, because Pip was just scared of a new place.","B":"Yes, because rabbits are always mean.","C":"No, because Katya was too loud.","D":"Yes, because Pip hated all girls."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Later we learn Pip was pregnant and protective. She was not annoyed with Katya personally-she was being a protective mother.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya sighed. \u0027I\u0027m not sure, really. There\u0027s just something about the way she looks at me.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q020","read_aloud":"What might have happened if Katya had stopped trying to befriend Pip? A. Pip would have trusted her faster. B. Pip might never have shown her babies to Katya. C. Pip would have run away forever. D. Katya would have won a prize.","excerpt":"\"Katya would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning, telling Pip about things she did with her friends, about the books she was reading, and about what happened at school.\"","stem":"What might have happened if Katya had stopped trying to befriend Pip?","choices":{"A":"Pip would have trusted her faster.","B":"Pip might never have shown her babies to Katya.","C":"Pip would have run away forever.","D":"Katya would have won a prize."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If Katya had given up, Pip would not have learned to trust her. Katya might never have seen the babies or earned Pip\u0027s friendship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya would sit and talk to Pip\u0027s cardboard box every morning, telling Pip about things she did with her friends, about the books she was reading, and about what happened at school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q022","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"accustomed\"? A. Unfamiliar, B. Used to, C. Excited, D. Afraid.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals...\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"accustomed\"?","choices":{"A":"Unfamiliar,","B":"Used to,","C":"Excited,","D":"Afraid."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Accustomed to\" means you are habituated or used to something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q002","read_aloud":"If you were to explain this story to a friend, what would be the most important lesson? A. Rabbits are faster than kittens, B. Patience and respecting an animal\u0027s personality are key to building trust, C. You should never foster animals, D. Kitchens are good places to run.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"If you were to explain this story to a friend, what would be the most important lesson?","choices":{"A":"Rabbits are faster than kittens,","B":"Patience and respecting an animal\u0027s personality are key to building trust,","C":"You should never foster animals,","D":"Kitchens are good places to run."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The heart of the story is about the bond built through patience and observing the animal\u0027s needs rather than forcing your own desires on it.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q003","read_aloud":"The cooing continued. Remembering the feel of Pip\u0027s wriggling body in her hands, Katya had to admit, \"Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\" but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business. Why does Katya refuse to comment on whether Pip is \"snuggly\"? A. Because she knows Pip is stubborn and does not like to be held. B. Because she thinks her classmates are allergic to rabbits. C. Because she wants to keep Pip a secret from her friends. D. Because she forgot what Pip feels like in her hands.","excerpt":"Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?","stem":"The cooing continued. Remembering the feel of Pip\u0027s wriggling body in her hands, Katya had to admit, \"Yes, she\u0027s soft, all right,\" but she didn\u0027t comment on the snuggly business. Why does Katya refuse to comment on whether Pip is \"snuggly\"?","choices":{"A":"Because she knows Pip is stubborn and does not like to be held.","B":"Because she thinks her classmates are allergic to rabbits.","C":"Because she wants to keep Pip a secret from her friends.","D":"Because she forgot what Pip feels like in her hands."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Katya remembers Pip wriggling to get away, so she knows Pip is not \"snuggly\" or cuddly, even if she is soft.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q004","read_aloud":"How does this excerpt establish the setting and background for the story? A. It shows that Katya lives on a large farm with many wild animals. B. It shows that Katya\u0027s home is a temporary safe place for rescue animals. C. It shows that Katya\u0027s parents work at a zoo as animal trainers. D. It shows that Katya\u0027s family only adopts animals that are sick.","excerpt":"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.","stem":"How does this excerpt establish the setting and background for the story?","choices":{"A":"It shows that Katya lives on a large farm with many wild animals.","B":"It shows that Katya\u0027s home is a temporary safe place for rescue animals.","C":"It shows that Katya\u0027s parents work at a zoo as animal trainers.","D":"It shows that Katya\u0027s family only adopts animals that are sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that rescue animals \"waited for new homes\" while staying with Katya\u0027s family, establishing their home as a foster environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q005","read_aloud":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. What theme is developed through Dad\u0027s decision at the end of the story? A. Animals are too much work for a family to handle. B. Patience and kindness can build trust between humans and animals. C. Foster animals should never be allowed to stay in one place. D. Parents should always make the rules without asking their children.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. What theme is developed through Dad\u0027s decision at the end of the story?","choices":{"A":"Animals are too much work for a family to handle.","B":"Patience and kindness can build trust between humans and animals.","C":"Foster animals should never be allowed to stay in one place.","D":"Parents should always make the rules without asking their children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dad specifically mentions that Katya \"worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust,\" highlighting the theme that patience and effort lead to strong bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q006","read_aloud":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. Do you think Mom\u0027s advice was helpful for Katya? Use evidence from the text. A. No, because Katya stopped trying to be friends with Pip. B. Yes, because it helped Katya understand that Pip needed time and space. C. No, because Katya decided to only foster kittens from now on. D. Yes, because it made Pip immediately come out of the cardboard box.","excerpt":"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.","stem":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. Do you think Mom\u0027s advice was helpful for Katya? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because Katya stopped trying to be friends with Pip.","B":"Yes, because it helped Katya understand that Pip needed time and space.","C":"No, because Katya decided to only foster kittens from now on.","D":"Yes, because it made Pip immediately come out of the cardboard box."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mom\u0027s advice helps Katya realize that she can\u0027t force a friendship, which leads her to try a new approach (bananas and talking calmly) that eventually works.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q007","read_aloud":"If you were to design a \"Foster Animal Guide\" based on Katya\u0027s experience, what rule would you include as the most important? A. Always give foster animals as many treats as they want. B. Never put a blanket over a wire pen because it is too dark. C. Respect an animal\u0027s space and let them come to you at their own pace. D. Chase the animal if it escapes so it learns not to run away.","excerpt":"Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip, and slowly moved the box so she could see the baby rabbits inside.","stem":"If you were to design a \"Foster Animal Guide\" based on Katya\u0027s experience, what rule would you include as the most important?","choices":{"A":"Always give foster animals as many treats as they want.","B":"Never put a blanket over a wire pen because it is too dark.","C":"Respect an animal\u0027s space and let them come to you at their own pace.","D":"Chase the animal if it escapes so it learns not to run away."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Katya learns that she cannot force Pip to like her; she has to be patient, offer treats, and let Pip feel safe, proving that respecting an animal\u0027s pace is key.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya tiptoed ever so gingerly over the pen wall, gently sat down next to Pip, and slowly moved the box so she could see the baby rabbits inside."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Which word means the opposite of \"excitement\"? A. Joy B. Boredom or calmness C. Thrill D. Tingling","excerpt":"\"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm.\"","stem":"Which word means the opposite of \"excitement\"?","choices":{"A":"Joy","B":"Boredom or calmness","C":"Thrill","D":"Tingling"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Excitement is high energy; boredom is low energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q009","read_aloud":"What is the most important change in Katya? A. She learns to be more patient and empathetic. B. She learns to run faster. C. She stops liking animals. D. to the end (calmly earning trust).","excerpt":"Review Katya\u0027s actions from the beginning (chasing Pip, feeling frustrate","stem":"What is the most important change in Katya?","choices":{"A":"She learns to be more patient and empathetic.","B":"She learns to run faster.","C":"She stops liking animals.","D":"to the end (calmly earning trust)."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Her approach changes from force to patience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Review Katya\u0027s actions from the beginning (chasing Pip, feeling frustrate"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q010","read_aloud":"How does this point of view help the reader understand the conflict? A. We know everyone\u0027s thoughts. B. We know only Katya\u0027s thoughts and feelings, so we understand her struggle. C. We know only Pip\u0027s thoughts. D. We know no one\u0027s thoughts.","excerpt":"The story is told from Katya\u0027s third-person limited point of view.","stem":"How does this point of view help the reader understand the conflict?","choices":{"A":"We know everyone\u0027s thoughts.","B":"We know only Katya\u0027s thoughts and feelings, so we understand her struggle.","C":"We know only Pip\u0027s thoughts.","D":"We know no one\u0027s thoughts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Third-person limited follows Katya.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The story is told from Katya\u0027s third-person limited point of view."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q011","read_aloud":"If you could add a chapter where Katya teaches a friend how to befriend a shy pet, what would be her most important advice? A. \"Yell its name until it comes.\" B. \"Be patient, move slowly, and offer favorite treats.\" C. \"Catch it quickly and hold it tight.\" D. \"Ignore it forever.\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you could add a chapter where Katya teaches a friend how to befriend a shy pet, what would be her most important advice?","choices":{"A":"\"Yell its name until it comes.\"","B":"\"Be patient, move slowly, and offer favorite treats.\"","C":"\"Catch it quickly and hold it tight.\"","D":"\"Ignore it forever.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"These are the successful strategies Katya used.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think Fran Hodgkins successfully showed how determination helps someone reach a goal? Why? A. No, because Katya gave up. B. Yes, because Katya kept trying different methods (bananas, talking calmly) and eventually earned Pip\u0027s trust. C. No, because the goal was too easy. D. Yes, but only because of the babies.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"Do you think Fran Hodgkins successfully showed how determination helps someone reach a goal? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because Katya gave up.","B":"Yes, because Katya kept trying different methods (bananas, talking calmly) and eventually earned Pip\u0027s trust.","C":"No, because the goal was too easy.","D":"Yes, but only because of the babies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her persistent, kind efforts succeeded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"tingled\" in this context? A. excited B. bored C. thrilled D. happy","excerpt":"\"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"tingled\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"excited","B":"bored","C":"thrilled","D":"happy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Tingled\" means excited and joyful. \"Bored\" means not interested or excited, which is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q014","read_aloud":"How does this ending resolve the story\u0027s conflict? A. It solves the problem by keeping Pip and her babies forever. B. It makes the conflict worse. C. It introduces a new character. D. It changes the setting to a new house.","excerpt":"\"Katya pulled up a chair. \u0027Well, it looks like we don\u0027t have a borrowed bunny anymore,\u0027 she said. \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\"","stem":"How does this ending resolve the story\u0027s conflict?","choices":{"A":"It solves the problem by keeping Pip and her babies forever.","B":"It makes the conflict worse.","C":"It introduces a new character.","D":"It changes the setting to a new house."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The main conflict was that Pip was temporary. The resolution changes the rule so Pip and her babies can stay forever.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya pulled up a chair. \u0027Well, it looks like we don\u0027t have a borrowed bunny anymore,\u0027 she said. \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q015","read_aloud":"AND \"Moving slowly and carefully, Katya lifted the closest bunny and cradled it in her hand. How has Katya changed? A. She became rougher with animals. B. She learned to be more patient and gentle. C. She decided to stop helping animals. D. She became faster at running.","excerpt":"Katya threw herself toward the brown blur. Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands.","stem":"AND \"Moving slowly and carefully, Katya lifted the closest bunny and cradled it in her hand. How has Katya changed?","choices":{"A":"She became rougher with animals.","B":"She learned to be more patient and gentle.","C":"She decided to stop helping animals.","D":"She became faster at running."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"At first, Katya chased Pip roughly. Later, she moves \"slowly and carefully\" with the babies. She learned patience and gentleness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Katya threw herself toward the brown blur. Her hands closed around the rabbit as Katya rolled onto her back, with Pip held firmly but gently in her hands."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Should families be allowed to adopt foster animals they grow attached to? Why? A. No, because it is always too expensive. B. Yes, because it is good for both the animal and the family if they have bonded. C. No, because foster families are not good owners. D. Yes, because all animals should be free.","excerpt":"\"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\"","stem":"Should families be allowed to adopt foster animals they grow attached to? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because it is always too expensive.","B":"Yes, because it is good for both the animal and the family if they have bonded.","C":"No, because foster families are not good owners.","D":"Yes, because all animals should be free."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If an animal and family have bonded, separating them can hurt both. The animal has a loving home, and the family has worked hard to build trust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q017","read_aloud":"If the story continued, what might happen next? A. Pip and her babies leave for a new home. B. The Ryans keep Pip and her babies, and Katya helps raise the baby bunnies. C. Pip runs away and never returns. D. Katya decides she does not like rabbits after all.","excerpt":"\"Katya beamed, thinking, \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\"","stem":"If the story continued, what might happen next?","choices":{"A":"Pip and her babies leave for a new home.","B":"The Ryans keep Pip and her babies, and Katya helps raise the baby bunnies.","C":"Pip runs away and never returns.","D":"Katya decides she does not like rabbits after all."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ending suggests they will keep Pip. The most logical continuation is Katya helping care for the new baby bunnies as part of her family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya beamed, thinking, \u0027Forever, not fosters!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Jumped up quickly B. Settled in cozily and comfortably C. Ran away fast D. Shouted loudly","excerpt":"\"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Jumped up quickly","B":"Settled in cozily and comfortably","C":"Ran away fast","D":"Shouted loudly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Snuggled means to settle into a warm, comfortable position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"snuggled\"? A. Jumped, B. Cuddled, C. Ran, D. Stomped.","excerpt":"\"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"snuggled\"?","choices":{"A":"Jumped,","B":"Cuddled,","C":"Ran,","D":"Stomped."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To snuggle means to settle into a warm, comfortable, and cozy position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q002","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for \"tolerate\"? A. Accept, B. Endure, C. Reject, D. Allow.","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you...\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for \"tolerate\"?","choices":{"A":"Accept,","B":"Endure,","C":"Reject,","D":"Allow."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"To tolerate means to accept; therefore, to reject is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does the word \"wriggled\" mean in this sentence? A. Moved by twisting and turning, B. Sat very still, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What does the word \"wriggled\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Moved by twisting and turning,","B":"Sat very still,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wriggling is the action of twisting and turning the body to move or escape.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this story? A. Katya prefers rabbits over kittens, B. Being a foster parent to animals is a challenging but rewarding responsibility, C. Snakes are difficult pets to keep in the bathtub, D. Katya is bad at catching animals.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house... but these were foster animals, not forever pets.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this story?","choices":{"A":"Katya prefers rabbits over kittens,","B":"Being a foster parent to animals is a challenging but rewarding responsibility,","C":"Snakes are difficult pets to keep in the bathtub,","D":"Katya is bad at catching animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story explores the Ryan family\u0027s life of fostering and how they handle the different needs and personalities of various animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house... but these were foster animals, not forever pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q005","read_aloud":"What was the sequence of foster animals mentioned in the story? A. A rabbit then a kitten, B. A boa constrictor then a rabbit, C. Kittens, then a rabbit, D. A snake, then kittens.","excerpt":"\"First came the litter of kittens... Then, Mom brought home a brown rabbit.\"","stem":"What was the sequence of foster animals mentioned in the story?","choices":{"A":"A rabbit then a kitten,","B":"A boa constrictor then a rabbit,","C":"Kittens, then a rabbit,","D":"A snake, then kittens."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text introduces the kittens first as the current foster animals, followed by the arrival of Pip the rabbit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"First came the litter of kittens... Then, Mom brought home a brown rabbit.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q006","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Pip feels in this moment? A. She is excited to play tag, B. She is hungry for a snack, C. She feels threatened or annoyed by Katya\u0027s approach, D. She wants to sleep in the kitchen.","excerpt":"\"Katya stepped toward her, Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Pip feels in this moment?","choices":{"A":"She is excited to play tag,","B":"She is hungry for a snack,","C":"She feels threatened or annoyed by Katya\u0027s approach,","D":"She wants to sleep in the kitchen."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Stomping the foot and racing away are common behaviors rabbits use to show stress or annoyance when they feel crowded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya stepped toward her, Pip twitched her nose, stomped her foot, and raced away.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q007","read_aloud":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning. According to Mom, where did Pip come from? A. A pet store, B. A neighbor\u0027s house, C. The center, D. The forest.","excerpt":"Her name is Pip,","stem":"Mom said, \"and she came to the center this morning. According to Mom, where did Pip come from?","choices":{"A":"A pet store,","B":"A neighbor\u0027s house,","C":"The center,","D":"The forest."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mom clearly states that the rabbit came from \"the center\" that morning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Her name is Pip,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the image of a \"force field\" when describing the blanket over the pen? A. To show that the mother is a scientist, B. To humorously highlight the struggle to keep a clever rabbit inside its pen, C. Because the blanket is actually magic, D. To show that the rabbit is dangerous.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why does the author use the image of a \"force field\" when describing the blanket over the pen?","choices":{"A":"To show that the mother is a scientist,","B":"To humorously highlight the struggle to keep a clever rabbit inside its pen,","C":"Because the blanket is actually magic,","D":"To show that the rabbit is dangerous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is a playful way for the mother to say that even with the blanket, the rabbit might still find a way out, emphasizing the rabbit\u0027s determined nature.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why is it important for Katya to learn that not all animals behave the same way? A. Because she should only foster kittens, B. Because it makes her a more patient and observant caretaker, C. Because she is going to be a veterinarian, D. Because it makes the house quieter.","excerpt":"A Borrowed Bunny includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about What does Katya learn from caring for Pip?","stem":"Why is it important for Katya to learn that not all animals behave the same way?","choices":{"A":"Because she should only foster kittens,","B":"Because it makes her a more patient and observant caretaker,","C":"Because she is going to be a veterinarian,","D":"Because it makes the house quieter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Learning that each animal has a unique personality and needs is a key part of growing into a responsible and empathetic caretaker. Section A - Text Information Title: \"A Borrowed Bunny\" Author: Fran Hodgkins Source: Student Interactive U3 Week 2, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q010","read_aloud":"The cooing continued. What does \"snuggly\" mean in this context? A. liking to be held in an affectionate way B. running away very quickly from danger C. eating food very loudly and quickly D. hiding in a dark place to sleep","excerpt":"Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?","stem":"The cooing continued. What does \"snuggly\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"liking to be held in an affectionate way","B":"running away very quickly from danger","C":"eating food very loudly and quickly","D":"hiding in a dark place to sleep"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The classmates are asking if the rabbit is soft and cuddly, which matches the definition of snuggly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence? A. to run away from B. to allow or accept C. to play with D. to hide from","excerpt":"\"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\"","stem":"What does \"tolerate\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to run away from","B":"to allow or accept","C":"to play with","D":"to hide from"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The kittens would only accept Katya and no one else, meaning they would \"tolerate\" or allow her presence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They wouldn\u0027t tolerate anyone but you, but after a month, you transformed them into perfectly loving little pets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"wriggled\" mean in this excerpt? A. moved by twisting and turning B. stayed completely still C. jumped very high D. bit down hard","excerpt":"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.","stem":"What does \"wriggled\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"moved by twisting and turning","B":"stayed completely still","C":"jumped very high","D":"bit down hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pip is trying to escape Katya\u0027s hold by twisting her body, which is the definition of wriggled.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q013","read_aloud":"What is the correct sequence of events in the kittens\u0027 time with the family? A. They ran around the house, then arrived, then were fed with an eyedropper. B. They arrived, were fed with an eyedropper, then ran around the house. C. They were fed with an eyedropper, ran around, then arrived. D. They arrived, ran around, then were fed with an eyedropper.","excerpt":"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens... When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper...","stem":"What is the correct sequence of events in the kittens\u0027 time with the family?","choices":{"A":"They ran around the house, then arrived, then were fed with an eyedropper.","B":"They arrived, were fed with an eyedropper, then ran around the house.","C":"They were fed with an eyedropper, ran around, then arrived.","D":"They arrived, ran around, then were fed with an eyedropper."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states they arrived first, were fed with an eyedropper when they first came, and are now old enough to run around.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens... When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper..."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q014","read_aloud":"What was the effect of Mom putting the blanket over the pen? A. Pip felt safe and came out to play with Katya. B. Pip felt trapped and hid inside her cardboard box. C. Pip ate all the lettuce inside the pen. D. Pip broke the wire pen and escaped.","excerpt":"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\" Mom said.","stem":"What was the effect of Mom putting the blanket over the pen?","choices":{"A":"Pip felt safe and came out to play with Katya.","B":"Pip felt trapped and hid inside her cardboard box.","C":"Pip ate all the lettuce inside the pen.","D":"Pip broke the wire pen and escaped."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"After the blanket was put up, the text notes that Pip stayed inside the cardboard box, stubbornly refusing to come out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \"It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\" Mom said."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q015","read_aloud":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. What does this conversation reveal about Katya\u0027s character? A. She is experienced with animals and knows they are all different. B. She is surprised that an animal does not instantly love her. C. She is angry and wants to return the rabbit to the shelter. D. She is scared of rabbits and wants her mom to take over.","excerpt":"Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you.","stem":"But animals love me, Mom!\" Katya said. What does this conversation reveal about Katya\u0027s character?","choices":{"A":"She is experienced with animals and knows they are all different.","B":"She is surprised that an animal does not instantly love her.","C":"She is angry and wants to return the rabbit to the shelter.","D":"She is scared of rabbits and wants her mom to take over."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya is used to animals loving her, so she is shocked and confused that Pip does not like her right away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Animals are like people, Katya; not all of them are going to like you."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q016","read_aloud":"What woke Katya up on Saturday morning? A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"What woke Katya up on Saturday morning?","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Katya act casually while Pip is eating the banana? A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"Why does Katya act casually while Pip is eating the banana?","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q018","read_aloud":"How does Pip\u0027s behavior change from the beginning of the story to this moment? A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"How does Pip\u0027s behavior change from the beginning of the story to this moment?","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q019","read_aloud":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. If you were writing a sequel to this story, what would be the main focus of Katya\u0027s new journey? A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"Dad said. \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down. If you were writing a sequel to this story, what would be the main focus of Katya\u0027s new journey?","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q020","read_aloud":"What does \"snuggly\" describe? A. An animal that bites B. An animal that likes to be held closely and cuddled C. An animal that runs away D. An animal that is loud","excerpt":"\"Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?\"","stem":"What does \"snuggly\" describe?","choices":{"A":"An animal that bites","B":"An animal that likes to be held closely and cuddled","C":"An animal that runs away","D":"An animal that is loud"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Snuggly means cuddly and affectionate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oooh, is she snuggly? Is she soft?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q021","read_aloud":"What did the rabbit do? A. Sat perfectly still B. Twisted and turned to escape C. Ate a banana D. Went to sleep","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What did the rabbit do?","choices":{"A":"Sat perfectly still","B":"Twisted and turned to escape","C":"Ate a banana","D":"Went to sleep"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wriggled means twisted and squirmed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of \"A Borrowed Bunny\"? A. Katya learns to make banana treats. B. Katya patiently earns the trust of a shy foster rabbit named Pip. C. Rabbits are better than cats. D. Katya does not like animals.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"What is the main idea of \"A Borrowed Bunny\"?","choices":{"A":"Katya learns to make banana treats.","B":"Katya patiently earns the trust of a shy foster rabbit named Pip.","C":"Rabbits are better than cats.","D":"Katya does not like animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story focuses on building trust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q023","read_aloud":"What suggestion does Max give Katya? A. To give Pip carrots B. To try feeding Pip bananas C. To chase Pip D. To ignore Pip","excerpt":"\"Max plopped down across the table. \u0027My aunt has a rabbit,\u0027 he said, \u0027and she likes bananas.\u0027\"","stem":"What suggestion does Max give Katya?","choices":{"A":"To give Pip carrots","B":"To try feeding Pip bananas","C":"To chase Pip","D":"To ignore Pip"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Max suggests bananas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Max plopped down across the table. \u0027My aunt has a rabbit,\u0027 he said, \u0027and she likes bananas.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q024","read_aloud":"Mom asked. Katya nodded. \"I think she\u0027s finally decided to trust me. What can you infer about Pip\u0027s behavior before this moment? A. She was always friendly. B. She was hiding and avoiding Katya. C. She was eating out of Katya\u0027s hand. D. She never came out of her box.","excerpt":"Pip let you see them?","stem":"Mom asked. Katya nodded. \"I think she\u0027s finally decided to trust me. What can you infer about Pip\u0027s behavior before this moment?","choices":{"A":"She was always friendly.","B":"She was hiding and avoiding Katya.","C":"She was eating out of Katya\u0027s hand.","D":"She never came out of her box."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Trust had to be earned, so she was avoiding Katya.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip let you see them?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q025","read_aloud":"What does Katya wish for at the end? A. To return the rabbits immediately B. To keep Pip and her babies forever C. To get a snake instead D. To move to a new house","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\"","stem":"What does Katya wish for at the end?","choices":{"A":"To return the rabbits immediately","B":"To keep Pip and her babies forever","C":"To get a snake instead","D":"To move to a new house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She wants them to be \"forevers.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m only sorry that they\u0027re just borrowed. Fosters, not forevers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Dad\u0027s suggestion to change the rule? Why? A. No, because rules should never change. B. Yes, because Katya earned the rabbits through her effort and care. C. No, because Pip is not special. D. Yes, because Katya is the parent.","excerpt":"\"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust.\"","stem":"Do you agree with Dad\u0027s suggestion to change the rule? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because rules should never change.","B":"Yes, because Katya earned the rabbits through her effort and care.","C":"No, because Pip is not special.","D":"Yes, because Katya is the parent."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Effort and care are good reasons to make an exception.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q027","read_aloud":"If you could write a new final line for the story, what would it be? A. \"And then Katya decided she never wanted another pet again.\" B. \"Forever, not fosters.\" C. \"The rabbits were returned the next day.\" D. \"Pip never trusted Katya.\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you could write a new final line for the story, what would it be?","choices":{"A":"\"And then Katya decided she never wanted another pet again.\"","B":"\"Forever, not fosters.\"","C":"\"The rabbits were returned the next day.\"","D":"\"Pip never trusted Katya.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This matches the happy, hopeful ending. Section A - Text information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does \"quarters\" mean? A. four parts of a circle B. a place where someone lives or stays C. money used to buy candy D. a group of four friends","excerpt":"\"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\u0027 Mom said.\"","stem":"What does \"quarters\" mean?","choices":{"A":"four parts of a circle","B":"a place where someone lives or stays","C":"money used to buy candy","D":"a group of four friends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Quarters\" here means a living space. Mom is talking about keeping Pip in her pen, which is her home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mom came in with one of Katya\u0027s old baby blankets and secured it with a fistful of clothespins over the top of Pip\u0027s wire pen. \u0027It\u0027s not exactly a force field, but it should at least keep her in her quarters,\u0027 Mom said.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q029","read_aloud":"What does \"wriggled\" mean? A. sang loudly B. moved by twisting and turning C. slept peacefully D. jumped over fences","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"What does \"wriggled\" mean?","choices":{"A":"sang loudly","B":"moved by twisting and turning","C":"slept peacefully","D":"jumped over fences"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Wriggled\" means to twist and squirm to get free. Pip was trying to escape from Katya\u0027s hands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q030","read_aloud":"What does \"tingled\" mean? A. felt sharp pain in her foot B. felt excitement and happiness C. felt very cold and shivery D. felt tired and sleepy","excerpt":"\"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\"","stem":"What does \"tingled\" mean?","choices":{"A":"felt sharp pain in her foot","B":"felt excitement and happiness","C":"felt very cold and shivery","D":"felt tired and sleepy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Tingled\" means to feel excitement or a prickling sensation of joy. Katya was very happy but stayed calm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q031","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the beginning of the story? A. Katya\u0027s family permanently owns many pets. B. Katya\u0027s family helps care for animals until they find forever homes. C. Katya does not like animals at all. D. The rescue agency brings only cats to Katya\u0027s house.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the beginning of the story?","choices":{"A":"Katya\u0027s family permanently owns many pets.","B":"Katya\u0027s family helps care for animals until they find forever homes.","C":"Katya does not like animals at all.","D":"The rescue agency brings only cats to Katya\u0027s house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Ryan family fosters animals. They care for them temporarily until the animals are adopted by other families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q032","read_aloud":"Which event happens first in the story? A. Pip shows Katya her babies. B. Katya chases Pip around the house. C. The kittens are adopted and Pip arrives. D. Katya feeds Pip banana.","excerpt":"From the whole story.","stem":"Which event happens first in the story?","choices":{"A":"Pip shows Katya her babies.","B":"Katya chases Pip around the house.","C":"The kittens are adopted and Pip arrives.","D":"Katya feeds Pip banana."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The story begins with the kittens being adopted. Then Pip arrives as the new foster animal. The chase, banana, and babies happen later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From the whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q033","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Katya\u0027s family? A. They never help animals. B. They often bring home new foster animals. C. They only foster rabbits. D. They do not like Katya.","excerpt":"\"Katya noticed the look on her father\u0027s face-and she knew what that look meant. \u0027Oh, please, not another Mavis!\u0027 she exclaimed.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Katya\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"They never help animals.","B":"They often bring home new foster animals.","C":"They only foster rabbits.","D":"They do not like Katya."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya recognizes \"the look\" on Dad\u0027s face. This means they have a pattern of bringing home new foster animals regularly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya noticed the look on her father\u0027s face-and she knew what that look meant. \u0027Oh, please, not another Mavis!\u0027 she exclaimed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why was Pip acting unfriendly at first? A. She was sick and needed medicine. B. She was pregnant and protecting her babies. C. She did not like the color of Katya\u0027s clothes. D. She was allergic to bananas.","excerpt":"\"Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \u0027Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\u0027\"","stem":"Why was Pip acting unfriendly at first?","choices":{"A":"She was sick and needed medicine.","B":"She was pregnant and protecting her babies.","C":"She did not like the color of Katya\u0027s clothes.","D":"She was allergic to bananas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"At the end, we learn Pip was going to have babies. She was being protective, not mean. This explains her strange behavior.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya lifted the flaps and peered inside, where she noticed three small shapes huddled together in a nest made of hay and fur. \u0027Oh, Pip! You\u0027re a mom!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q035","read_aloud":"Why is this moment important in the story? A. It shows Katya has learned to think about Pip\u0027s feelings. B. It shows Katya is boring and never has fun. C. It shows Pip is a mean rabbit. D. It shows bananas are bad for rabbits.","excerpt":"\"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\"","stem":"Why is this moment important in the story?","choices":{"A":"It shows Katya has learned to think about Pip\u0027s feelings.","B":"It shows Katya is boring and never has fun.","C":"It shows Pip is a mean rabbit.","D":"It shows bananas are bad for rabbits."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Katya has grown. She thinks about what Pip needs instead of just doing what she wants. This patience helps her earn Pip\u0027s trust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya wanted to jump up and down with excitement, but she made herself stay calm. She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q036","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Dad\u0027s character? A. He is mean and does not care about Katya. B. He notices Katya\u0027s hard work and values kindness. C. He wants to get rid of all the animals. D. He does not like rabbits.","excerpt":"\"Dad said. \u0027Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Dad\u0027s character?","choices":{"A":"He is mean and does not care about Katya.","B":"He notices Katya\u0027s hard work and values kindness.","C":"He wants to get rid of all the animals.","D":"He does not like rabbits."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dad sees how hard Katya worked. He wants to reward her kindness and keep Pip\u0027s trust. This shows he is caring and fair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad said. \u0027Maybe we can change that rule this time. After all, you\u0027ve worked awfully hard to win Pip\u0027s trust. It would be a shame to let her down.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q037","read_aloud":"What is the most important lesson Katya learns in \"A Borrowed Bunny\"? A. All animals are easy to befriend. B. Patience, kindness, and understanding can build trust. C. Rabbits are better pets than cats. D. It is best to give up when things are hard.","excerpt":"From the whole story.","stem":"What is the most important lesson Katya learns in \"A Borrowed Bunny\"?","choices":{"A":"All animals are easy to befriend.","B":"Patience, kindness, and understanding can build trust.","C":"Rabbits are better pets than cats.","D":"It is best to give up when things are hard."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya learned that you cannot force trust. She was patient, kind, and understanding. Over time, Pip learned to trust her, and they became a family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From the whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q038","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. Sat very still, B. Moved by twisting and turning, C. Jumped very high, D. Slept quietly.","excerpt":"\"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"Sat very still,","B":"Moved by twisting and turning,","C":"Jumped very high,","D":"Slept quietly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To wriggle means to move with quick, twisting, or turning motions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The rabbit wriggled, trying to get away, but without success.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. a loud crash B. a hungry kitten C. her dad\u0027s alarm D. a barking dog","excerpt":"The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"a loud crash","B":"a hungry kitten","C":"her dad\u0027s alarm","D":"a barking dog"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Katya heard a crash, which woke her up from her sleep.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next morning was Saturday, so when a ray of light streaked in though the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers. Then she heard a crash."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables. B. She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away. C. She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana. D. She is trying to hide the banana from her parents.","excerpt":"She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"She wants to trick Pip into eating vegetables.","B":"She knows sudden reactions will scare Pip away.","C":"She is bored and doesn\u0027t care about the banana.","D":"She is trying to hide the banana from her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Katya knows that rabbits are easily frightened, so she stays calm to ensure Pip doesn\u0027t get scared and stop eating.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She knew that if she reacted as if something unusual was happening-in any way, really-Pip would stop eating for sure. Although she tingled with joy, Katya casually finished the gym class story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies. B. She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya. C. She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn. D. She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens.","excerpt":"Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"She goes from hiding from Katya to inviting Katya to see her babies.","B":"She goes from eating bananas to running away from Katya.","C":"She goes from being friendly to being angry and stubborn.","D":"She goes from sleeping in the box to playing with the kittens."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Early in the story, Pip hides in her box and avoids Katya. Now, she is actively looking back and forth to invite Katya to see her secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pip finished the banana and gazed at Katya. Slowly, she turned and hopped back toward the box. Katya\u0027s heart sank. But then, Pip turned and looked at her steadily-then back at the box- and then back to Katya."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat. B. Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies. C. Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor. D. Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school.","excerpt":"Well,","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Katya trying to teach Pip how to catch mice like a cat.","B":"Katya learning how to take care of Pip and her four newborn babies.","C":"Katya going back to the rescue center to foster a boa constrictor.","D":"Katya selling the baby bunnies to her friends at school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the family decided to keep Pip (\"Forever, not fosters!\"), the next logical step in the story would be Katya caring for the new family of rabbits. Section A - Text Information Title: A Borrowed Bunny Author: Fran Hodgkins","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Well,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Jumped up quickly B. Settled in cozily and comfortably C. Ran away fast D. Shouted loudly","excerpt":"\"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Jumped up quickly","B":"Settled in cozily and comfortably","C":"Ran away fast","D":"Shouted loudly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Snuggled means to settle into a warm, comfortable position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a ray of light streaked in through the blinds, Katya snuggled down, deep under the covers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Her family runs a pet store. B. Her parents foster animals from a rescue agency. C. They buy a new pet every week. D. Animals wander in from the street.","excerpt":"\"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Her family runs a pet store.","B":"Her parents foster animals from a rescue agency.","C":"They buy a new pet every week.","D":"Animals wander in from the street."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her parents take care of foster animals from a rescue agency.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya was accustomed to the animals that came and went at her house. While different animals from the local rescue agency waited for new homes, Katya\u0027s mom and dad took care of them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Katya\u0027s house has had many different foster animals. B. Katya hates all animals. C. The family only fosters kittens. D. Animals are not allowed in the house.","excerpt":"\"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Katya\u0027s house has had many different foster animals.","B":"Katya hates all animals.","C":"The family only fosters kittens.","D":"Animals are not allowed in the house."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The examples show a variety of foster animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once, there had been a gigantic macaw in the laundry room. Oftentimes she would find a cardboard box full of kittens in the living room. Once, there had even been a boa constrictor in the bathtub.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. With a bowl of milk B. With an eyedropper C. With a spoon D. With a bottle","excerpt":"\"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"With a bowl of milk","B":"With an eyedropper","C":"With a spoon","D":"With a bottle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they fed them with an eyedropper.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Right now, the Ryans were fostering a litter of kittens that had been with them for two months. When the kittens first arrived, Katya and her parents had fed them with an eyedropper.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. A temporary shelter B. A permanent, loving home where the animal will stay C. A cage at the rescue agency D. A vacation house","excerpt":"\"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets. Eventually, each animal would leave the Ryans and go with someone else to its real forever home.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"A temporary shelter","B":"A permanent, loving home where the animal will stay","C":"A cage at the rescue agency","D":"A vacation house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A forever home is a permanent home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Katya liked having the animals around, but she knew the rules-these were foster animals, not forever pets. Eventually, each animal would leave the Ryans and go with someone else to its real forever home.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w2-a-borrowed-bunny-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. To love immediately B. To allow or put up with something C. To run away from D. To eat","excerpt":"\"A rabbit-well, we\u0027ll all just have to get to know her a little better.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"To love immediately","B":"To allow or put up with something","C":"To run away from","D":"To eat"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tolerate means to accept or allow something even if you don\u0027t love it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A rabbit-well, we\u0027ll all just have to get to know her a little better.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":3,"week":3,"title":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush","author":"Marie Yuen and Dana Crum","genre":"Paired Literary Text","essential_question":"How can art and music reveal a person\u0027s feelings?","weekly_question":"How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["quell","doubts","concert","talent","practice"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush. How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why did Rosetsu\u0027s parents save their money? A. To buy him a new brush B. To take him on a vacation to Kyoto C. To help him attend art school D. To help him buy food","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why did Rosetsu\u0027s parents save their money?","choices":{"A":"To buy him a new brush","B":"To take him on a vacation to Kyoto","C":"To help him attend art school","D":"To help him buy food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that his parents saved every penny specifically so Rosetsu could go to art school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Based on this excerpt, how often does the family hold a concert? A. Every day B. Once a month C. Once a week D. Once a year","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert... hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Based on this excerpt, how often does the family hold a concert?","choices":{"A":"Every day","B":"Once a month","C":"Once a week","D":"Once a year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly identifies the day as the family\u0027s \"weekly concert\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert... hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What happens when Hayate tries to play his saxophone? A. He plays the song perfectly. B. He plays very loudly and scares his family. C. He struggles, makes harsh sounds, and stops playing early. D. He forgets the notes to the song.","excerpt":"\"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What happens when Hayate tries to play his saxophone?","choices":{"A":"He plays the song perfectly.","B":"He plays very loudly and scares his family.","C":"He struggles, makes harsh sounds, and stops playing early.","D":"He forgets the notes to the song."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The excerpt describes the sounds as \"harsh\" and notes that Hayate stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana make this comment to Hayate? A. She is trying to help him learn. B. She thinks he is playing very well. C. She is making a mean joke about his playing. D. She is asking him to play a different song.","excerpt":"\"Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana make this comment to Hayate?","choices":{"A":"She is trying to help him learn.","B":"She thinks he is playing very well.","C":"She is making a mean joke about his playing.","D":"She is asking him to play a different song."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"By comparing his playing to a \"sick moose,\" Wakana is teasing Hayate, which upsets him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. to make a feeling much stronger B. to hide a secret from other people C. to put an end to a feeling or doubt D. to share a feeling with a good friend","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to make a feeling much stronger","B":"to hide a secret from other people","C":"to put an end to a feeling or doubt","D":"to share a feeling with a good friend"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stranger wants Rosetsu to prove he is a painter to stop or \"quell\" his doubts. This means to put an end to a feeling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q007","read_aloud":"Where is Rosetsu traveling to at the beginning of the story? A. a quiet village in the mountains B. the city of Kyoto to study painting C. a busy port to sail on a ship D. a large castle to meet the emperor","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu kissed his parents goodbye and headed down the road to Kyoto, home of the famous Maruyama School, where Rosetsu hoped to study with the master painter Maruyama Okyo.\"","stem":"Where is Rosetsu traveling to at the beginning of the story?","choices":{"A":"a quiet village in the mountains","B":"the city of Kyoto to study painting","C":"a busy port to sail on a ship","D":"a large castle to meet the emperor"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that Rosetsu headed down the road to Kyoto to study at the Maruyama School.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu kissed his parents goodbye and headed down the road to Kyoto, home of the famous Maruyama School, where Rosetsu hoped to study with the master painter Maruyama Okyo.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What does Rosetsu do right after he finishes his painting? A. He throws the twig into the river. B. He hands the painting to the stranger. C. He asks the stranger for some ink. D. He runs away into the forest.","excerpt":"\"With a few strokes of the twig, Rosetsu painted a picture of a sparrow and two turtles, and then he handed it to the stranger.\"","stem":"What does Rosetsu do right after he finishes his painting?","choices":{"A":"He throws the twig into the river.","B":"He hands the painting to the stranger.","C":"He asks the stranger for some ink.","D":"He runs away into the forest."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states that after painting the picture, Rosetsu handed it to the stranger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With a few strokes of the twig, Rosetsu painted a picture of a sparrow and two turtles, and then he handed it to the stranger.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What is Rosetsu\u0027s biggest dream? A. to become the greatest painter in Japan B. to travel the world and see new places C. to build a large school for young artists D. to paint pictures of the emperor\u0027s castle","excerpt":"\"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\"","stem":"What is Rosetsu\u0027s biggest dream?","choices":{"A":"to become the greatest painter in Japan","B":"to travel the world and see new places","C":"to build a large school for young artists","D":"to paint pictures of the emperor\u0027s castle"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly states that Rosetsu dreamed of becoming the greatest painter in all of Japan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the stranger ask Rosetsu to paint without any tools? A. to see if Rosetsu can make his own ink B. to test if Rosetsu truly has the heart of a painter C. to show Rosetsu that painting is too hard D. to trick Rosetsu into giving up his dream","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s see how you do without one. Paint a picture for me.\" \"Without a brush, or ink, or paper, or silk?\"\"","stem":"Why does the stranger ask Rosetsu to paint without any tools?","choices":{"A":"to see if Rosetsu can make his own ink","B":"to test if Rosetsu truly has the heart of a painter","C":"to show Rosetsu that painting is too hard","D":"to trick Rosetsu into giving up his dream"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stranger wants to see if Rosetsu can create art using only his natural talent and imagination, testing if he is truly meant to be a painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s see how you do without one. Paint a picture for me.\" \"Without a brush, or ink, or paper, or silk?\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"quell\" most likely mean? A. To start or increase B. To put an end to or calm C. To ignore D. To celebrate","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What does \"quell\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"To start or increase","B":"To put an end to or calm","C":"To ignore","D":"To celebrate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Quell means to stop or calm something, like doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What did Rosetsu dream of becoming? A. A musician B. The greatest painter in Japan C. A gatekeeper D. A fisherman","excerpt":"\"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\"","stem":"What did Rosetsu dream of becoming?","choices":{"A":"A musician","B":"The greatest painter in Japan","C":"A gatekeeper","D":"A fisherman"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu wanted to be the greatest painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sentence? A. Rosetsu\u0027s parents were rich. B. Rosetsu\u0027s parents worked hard and saved money to help him go to art school. C. Rosetsu did not want to go to school. D. Art school was free.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu\u0027s parents were rich.","B":"Rosetsu\u0027s parents worked hard and saved money to help him go to art school.","C":"Rosetsu did not want to go to school.","D":"Art school was free."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His parents sacrificed and saved to support his dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What did Rosetsu do when he saw the sparrow? A. He threw a rock at it. B. He whistled softly to it. C. He ran away. D. He ignored it.","excerpt":"\"He paused to watch a sparrow flying overhead and whistled softly to the bird as it soared over the treetops and out of sight.\"","stem":"What did Rosetsu do when he saw the sparrow?","choices":{"A":"He threw a rock at it.","B":"He whistled softly to it.","C":"He ran away.","D":"He ignored it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he whistled softly to the bird.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He paused to watch a sparrow flying overhead and whistled softly to the bird as it soared over the treetops and out of sight.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"bliss\" suggest about how Rosetsu feels about learning to paint? A. He thinks it will be boring. B. He thinks it will bring him great happiness. C. He is afraid of it. D. He does not want to do it.","excerpt":"\"Making ink, preparing paper and silk, and learning the proper way to hold a brush will be bliss.\"","stem":"What does \"bliss\" suggest about how Rosetsu feels about learning to paint?","choices":{"A":"He thinks it will be boring.","B":"He thinks it will bring him great happiness.","C":"He is afraid of it.","D":"He does not want to do it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Bliss means perfect happiness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Making ink, preparing paper and silk, and learning the proper way to hold a brush will be bliss.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Rosetsu lives in a small village. B. Rosetsu wants to become a great painter. C. Rosetsu is already a famous painter. D. Rosetsu does not like school.","excerpt":"\"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu lives in a small village.","B":"Rosetsu wants to become a great painter.","C":"Rosetsu is already a famous painter.","D":"Rosetsu does not like school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph tells us that Rosetsu dreams of becoming the greatest painter in Japan. This is his main goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What did Rosetsu\u0027s parents do to help him? A. They bought him a new house. B. They saved money for his art school. C. They found him a job. D. They taught him to paint.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"What did Rosetsu\u0027s parents do to help him?","choices":{"A":"They bought him a new house.","B":"They saved money for his art school.","C":"They found him a job.","D":"They taught him to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says his parents \"scraped and saved every penny\" so he could go to art school. They worked hard to save money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q018","read_aloud":"Where was Rosetsu going? A. To his grandmother\u0027s house B. To the Maruyama School in Kyoto C. To a fishing village D. To a music school","excerpt":"\"When the time came, Rosetsu kissed his parents goodbye and headed down the road to Kyoto, home of the famous Maruyama School.\"","stem":"Where was Rosetsu going?","choices":{"A":"To his grandmother\u0027s house","B":"To the Maruyama School in Kyoto","C":"To a fishing village","D":"To a music school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states Rosetsu was going to the Maruyama School in Kyoto to study painting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When the time came, Rosetsu kissed his parents goodbye and headed down the road to Kyoto, home of the famous Maruyama School.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Rosetsu? A. He is mean to animals. B. He notices and enjoys nature. C. He is afraid of birds. D. He wants to be a bird watcher.","excerpt":"\"He paused to watch a sparrow flying overhead and whistled softly to the bird as it soared over the treetops and out of sight.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"He is mean to animals.","B":"He notices and enjoys nature.","C":"He is afraid of birds.","D":"He wants to be a bird watcher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu stops to watch the sparrow and whistles to it. This shows he pays attention to nature and enjoys it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He paused to watch a sparrow flying overhead and whistled softly to the bird as it soared over the treetops and out of sight.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q020","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this sentence? A. Different types of food B. Planned actions or methods C. A group of fast fish D. Loud splashing sounds","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Different types of food","B":"Planned actions or methods","C":"A group of fast fish","D":"Loud splashing sounds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp used different planned actions to try to get the cracker.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q021","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What was the result of Rosetsu\u0027s parents saving money? A. Rosetsu could buy a new house. B. Rosetsu could attend art school. C. Rosetsu became a famous musician. D. Rosetsu decided to stop painting.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What was the result of Rosetsu\u0027s parents saving money?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu could buy a new house.","B":"Rosetsu could attend art school.","C":"Rosetsu became a famous musician.","D":"Rosetsu decided to stop painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states they saved money specifically so he could attend art school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q022","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What can you infer about how Hayate feels while he plays? A. He feels calm and happy. B. He feels frustrated and anxious. C. He feels bored and sleepy. D. He feels excited to show his family.","excerpt":"\"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What can you infer about how Hayate feels while he plays?","choices":{"A":"He feels calm and happy.","B":"He feels frustrated and anxious.","C":"He feels bored and sleepy.","D":"He feels excited to show his family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Harsh sounds, sweating, and stopping early suggest he is struggling and feeling stressed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q023","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Where does Hayate sit when he arrives at the concert? A. In the center of the room B. Next to his father C. In the corner D. By the front door","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Where does Hayate sit when he arrives at the concert?","choices":{"A":"In the center of the room","B":"Next to his father","C":"In the corner","D":"By the front door"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly states that he sits in the corner.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why is Rosetsu acting nervously in this scene? A. He is afraid of the trees. B. He is worried about what the stranger thinks of his painting. C. He wants to go home to his parents. D. He is cold and wants to find a fire.","excerpt":"\"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why is Rosetsu acting nervously in this scene?","choices":{"A":"He is afraid of the trees.","B":"He is worried about what the stranger thinks of his painting.","C":"He wants to go home to his parents.","D":"He is cold and wants to find a fire."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He is waiting for the stranger\u0027s reaction to the picture he just painted, which makes him nervous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l01-q025","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing? A. Giving up quickly when things get hard B. Continuing to try even when it is difficult C. Asking someone else to do the work for you D. Moving to a new place to start over","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing?","choices":{"A":"Giving up quickly when things get hard","B":"Continuing to try even when it is difficult","C":"Asking someone else to do the work for you","D":"Moving to a new place to start over"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Perseverance means to keep working towards a goal despite obstacles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this sentence? A. Different types of food B. Planned actions or methods C. A group of fast fish D. Loud splashing sounds","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Different types of food","B":"Planned actions or methods","C":"A group of fast fish","D":"Loud splashing sounds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp used different planned actions to try to get the cracker.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What was the result of Rosetsu\u0027s parents saving money? A. Rosetsu could buy a new house. B. Rosetsu could attend art school. C. Rosetsu became a famous musician. D. Rosetsu decided to stop painting.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What was the result of Rosetsu\u0027s parents saving money?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu could buy a new house.","B":"Rosetsu could attend art school.","C":"Rosetsu became a famous musician.","D":"Rosetsu decided to stop painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states they saved money specifically so he could attend art school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What can you infer about how Hayate feels while he plays? A. He feels calm and happy. B. He feels frustrated and anxious. C. He feels bored and sleepy. D. He feels excited to show his family.","excerpt":"\"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What can you infer about how Hayate feels while he plays?","choices":{"A":"He feels calm and happy.","B":"He feels frustrated and anxious.","C":"He feels bored and sleepy.","D":"He feels excited to show his family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Harsh sounds, sweating, and stopping early suggest he is struggling and feeling stressed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Where does Hayate sit when he arrives at the concert? A. In the center of the room B. Next to his father C. In the corner D. By the front door","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Where does Hayate sit when he arrives at the concert?","choices":{"A":"In the center of the room","B":"Next to his father","C":"In the corner","D":"By the front door"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly states that he sits in the corner.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why is Rosetsu acting nervously in this scene? A. He is afraid of the trees. B. He is worried about what the stranger thinks of his painting. C. He wants to go home to his parents. D. He is cold and wants to find a fire.","excerpt":"\"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why is Rosetsu acting nervously in this scene?","choices":{"A":"He is afraid of the trees.","B":"He is worried about what the stranger thinks of his painting.","C":"He wants to go home to his parents.","D":"He is cold and wants to find a fire."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He is waiting for the stranger\u0027s reaction to the picture he just painted, which makes him nervous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"demanded\" mean in this context? A. asked in a loud and angry way B. whispered quietly to a friend C. sang a happy and cheerful song D. wrote down in a letter","excerpt":"\"\"Where did you get this brush?\" he demanded. \"Did you steal it?\" \"No!\" cried Rosetsu. \"I met a stranger on my way to Kyoto. He told me to paint a picture, and then he gave me the brush!\"\"","stem":"What does the word \"demanded\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"asked in a loud and angry way","B":"whispered quietly to a friend","C":"sang a happy and cheerful song","D":"wrote down in a letter"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The gatekeeper is shocked and suspicious about the brush, so he \"demanded\" or asked in a loud, angry way to know where Rosetsu got it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Where did you get this brush?\" he demanded. \"Did you steal it?\" \"No!\" cried Rosetsu. \"I met a stranger on my way to Kyoto. He told me to paint a picture, and then he gave me the brush!\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q007","read_aloud":"Who does the gatekeeper reveal that he really is? A. a famous painter named Sensei Yutei B. a stranger who walks the roads to Kyoto C. the master painter Sensei Maruyama Okyo D. a guard who protects the school\u0027s brushes","excerpt":"\"\"Yes, I am Sensei Maruyama Okyo, and the stranger you met on your way here was Sensei Yutei. If my sensei gave you his brush, he must think highly of you indeed.\"","stem":"Who does the gatekeeper reveal that he really is?","choices":{"A":"a famous painter named Sensei Yutei","B":"a stranger who walks the roads to Kyoto","C":"the master painter Sensei Maruyama Okyo","D":"a guard who protects the school\u0027s brushes"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The gatekeeper reveals that he is actually Sensei Maruyama Okyo, the master painter Rosetsu came to study with.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Yes, I am Sensei Maruyama Okyo, and the stranger you met on your way here was Sensei Yutei. If my sensei gave you his brush, he must think highly of you indeed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the gatekeeper laugh after Rosetsu explains where he got the brush? A. He realizes Rosetsu is telling the truth and is not a thief. B. He thinks Rosetsu\u0027s story about a stranger is very funny. C. He is happy that Rosetsu brought the brush back to him. D. He knows that Rosetsu bought the brush with his own money.","excerpt":"\"\"I now know you didn\u0027t steal this painting brush because you don\u0027t know its owner or its true worth. The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\"\"","stem":"Why does the gatekeeper laugh after Rosetsu explains where he got the brush?","choices":{"A":"He realizes Rosetsu is telling the truth and is not a thief.","B":"He thinks Rosetsu\u0027s story about a stranger is very funny.","C":"He is happy that Rosetsu brought the brush back to him.","D":"He knows that Rosetsu bought the brush with his own money."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The gatekeeper laughs because he realizes Rosetsu has no idea how valuable the brush is, proving he didn\u0027t steal it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I now know you didn\u0027t steal this painting brush because you don\u0027t know its owner or its true worth. The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How long has Rosetsu been painting when he meets the gatekeeper? A. for many years B. for a very short time C. since he was a tiny baby D. for exactly three years","excerpt":"\"\"How long have you been painting?\" Rosetsu\u0027s heart beat faster as he responded, \"Not long, sir, but I am eager to learn.\"","stem":"How long has Rosetsu been painting when he meets the gatekeeper?","choices":{"A":"for many years","B":"for a very short time","C":"since he was a tiny baby","D":"for exactly three years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu answers \"Not long, sir,\" which means he has only been painting for a very short time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"How long have you been painting?\" Rosetsu\u0027s heart beat faster as he responded, \"Not long, sir, but I am eager to learn.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why does Sensei Okyo tell Rosetsu to keep the brush safe? A. because the brush is made of solid gold B. because Rosetsu must prove himself worthy before using it C. because the brush is broken and needs to be fixed D. because Rosetsu needs to sell it to pay for his school","excerpt":"\"\"Of course you will be admitted to Maruyama School. Here is your brush. Keep it safe so that one day-after proving yourself worthy-you will be ready to paint with it.\"\"","stem":"Why does Sensei Okyo tell Rosetsu to keep the brush safe?","choices":{"A":"because the brush is made of solid gold","B":"because Rosetsu must prove himself worthy before using it","C":"because the brush is broken and needs to be fixed","D":"because Rosetsu needs to sell it to pay for his school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sensei Okyo tells Rosetsu to keep it safe until he has proven himself worthy, meaning he must earn the right to use such a special tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Of course you will be admitted to Maruyama School. Here is your brush. Keep it safe so that one day-after proving yourself worthy-you will be ready to paint with it.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What happened right after Rosetsu finished his lunch? A. He went swimming. B. An elderly man appeared. C. He fell asleep. D. He painted a picture.","excerpt":"\"Just as Rosetsu finished his lunch, an elderly man, gray-bearded and bent from years of toil, appeared before him.\"","stem":"What happened right after Rosetsu finished his lunch?","choices":{"A":"He went swimming.","B":"An elderly man appeared.","C":"He fell asleep.","D":"He painted a picture."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The man appeared just as he finished lunch.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Just as Rosetsu finished his lunch, an elderly man, gray-bearded and bent from years of toil, appeared before him.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q012","read_aloud":"asked the man. \"When I dream at night, that is what I am. What does Rosetsu\u0027s answer reveal about him? A. He is not serious about painting. B. He dreams of being a painter and believes in himself. C. He only paints in his dreams. D. He has no talent.","excerpt":"What makes you think you can be a great painter?","stem":"asked the man. \"When I dream at night, that is what I am. What does Rosetsu\u0027s answer reveal about him?","choices":{"A":"He is not serious about painting.","B":"He dreams of being a painter and believes in himself.","C":"He only paints in his dreams.","D":"He has no talent."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He believes in his dream deeply.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What makes you think you can be a great painter?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q013","read_aloud":"How does Rosetsu feel while waiting for the man\u0027s reaction? A. Confident B. Nervous C. Angry D. Sleepy","excerpt":"\"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\"","stem":"How does Rosetsu feel while waiting for the man\u0027s reaction?","choices":{"A":"Confident","B":"Nervous","C":"Angry","D":"Sleepy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Drawing circles nervously shows he is anxious.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The man stared at the painting in silence, as Rosetsu nervously drew circles in the dirt with his foot.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What does \"tactics\" mean in this sentence? A. planned actions to reach a goal B. mistakes and errors C. songs and music D. colors and paints","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"What does \"tactics\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"planned actions to reach a goal","B":"mistakes and errors","C":"songs and music","D":"colors and paints"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Tactics\" are planned actions or strategies. The carp tried different ways to reach the cracker.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What did Rosetsu do first? A. He peeled off bark. B. He mashed berries to make ink. C. He painted the picture. D. He handed it to the stranger.","excerpt":"\"He broke off a twig and picked off a few berries, mashing and mixing them to form a kind of ink, and then he peeled off a piece of pale bark to paint on.\"","stem":"What did Rosetsu do first?","choices":{"A":"He peeled off bark.","B":"He mashed berries to make ink.","C":"He painted the picture.","D":"He handed it to the stranger."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he first broke off a twig and mashed berries to make ink. Then he peeled bark to paint on.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He broke off a twig and picked off a few berries, mashing and mixing them to form a kind of ink, and then he peeled off a piece of pale bark to paint on.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q016","read_aloud":"How would you describe the stranger at first? A. friendly and kind B. rude and demanding C. shy and quiet D. young and strong","excerpt":"\"Without so much as a hello, the man shook his crooked walking stick at Rosetsu and demanded, \u0027Who are you, and what do you want?\u0027\"","stem":"How would you describe the stranger at first?","choices":{"A":"friendly and kind","B":"rude and demanding","C":"shy and quiet","D":"young and strong"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stranger did not say hello. He shook his stick and demanded answers. This shows he was rude and demanding at first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Without so much as a hello, the man shook his crooked walking stick at Rosetsu and demanded, \u0027Who are you, and what do you want?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Who did the brush belong to? A. Rosetsu\u0027s father B. Sensei Maruyama Okyo C. Ishida Yutei D. The gatekeeper","excerpt":"\"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\"","stem":"Who did the brush belong to?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu\u0027s father","B":"Sensei Maruyama Okyo","C":"Ishida Yutei","D":"The gatekeeper"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The gatekeeper says the brush belonged to his sensei, Ishida Yutei, who taught Sensei Okyo.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the gatekeeper let Rosetsu into the school? A. Rosetsu paid him money. B. The stranger\u0027s brush proves Rosetsu is worthy. C. Rosetsu threatened him. D. The school needed more students.","excerpt":"\"If my sensei gave you his brush, he must think highly of you indeed. Of course you will be admitted to Maruyama School.\"","stem":"Why does the gatekeeper let Rosetsu into the school?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu paid him money.","B":"The stranger\u0027s brush proves Rosetsu is worthy.","C":"Rosetsu threatened him.","D":"The school needed more students."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The gatekeeper recognizes the brush. He knows that if Sensei Yutei gave it to Rosetsu, Rosetsu must be special and worthy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If my sensei gave you his brush, he must think highly of you indeed. Of course you will be admitted to Maruyama School.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does the word \"quell\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q020","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why did Rosetsu\u0027s parents save their money? A. To buy him a new brush B. To take him on a vacation to Kyoto C. To help him attend art school D. To help him buy food","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why did Rosetsu\u0027s parents save their money?","choices":{"A":"To buy him a new brush","B":"To take him on a vacation to Kyoto","C":"To help him attend art school","D":"To help him buy food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that his parents saved every penny specifically so Rosetsu could go to art school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu\u0027s mother and father scraped and saved every penny so Rosetsu could attend art school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Based on this excerpt, how often does the family hold a concert? A. Every day B. Once a month C. Once a week D. Once a year","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert... hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Based on this excerpt, how often does the family hold a concert?","choices":{"A":"Every day","B":"Once a month","C":"Once a week","D":"Once a year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly identifies the day as the family\u0027s \"weekly concert\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert... hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What happens when Hayate tries to play his saxophone? A. He plays the song perfectly. B. He plays very loudly and scares his family. C. He struggles, makes harsh sounds, and stops playing early. D. He forgets the notes to the song.","excerpt":"\"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What happens when Hayate tries to play his saxophone?","choices":{"A":"He plays the song perfectly.","B":"He plays very loudly and scares his family.","C":"He struggles, makes harsh sounds, and stops playing early.","D":"He forgets the notes to the song."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The excerpt describes the sounds as \"harsh\" and notes that Hayate stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana make this comment to Hayate? A. She is trying to help him learn. B. She thinks he is playing very well. C. She is making a mean joke about his playing. D. She is asking him to play a different song.","excerpt":"\"Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana make this comment to Hayate?","choices":{"A":"She is trying to help him learn.","B":"She thinks he is playing very well.","C":"She is making a mean joke about his playing.","D":"She is asking him to play a different song."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"By comparing his playing to a \"sick moose,\" Wakana is teasing Hayate, which upsets him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing? A. Giving up quickly when things get hard B. Continuing to try even when it is difficult C. Asking someone else to do the work for you D. Moving to a new place to start over","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing?","choices":{"A":"Giving up quickly when things get hard","B":"Continuing to try even when it is difficult","C":"Asking someone else to do the work for you","D":"Moving to a new place to start over"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Perseverance means to keep working towards a goal despite obstacles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l02-q025","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What did Hayate do before he went to the backyard? A. He finished his song perfectly. B. He practiced his saxophone. C. He went to the concert. D. He talked to his friend Ben.","excerpt":"\"Scene 3 It\u0027s Thursday. After practicing his sax, hayate has gone outside to the backyard to get some fresh air.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What did Hayate do before he went to the backyard?","choices":{"A":"He finished his song perfectly.","B":"He practiced his saxophone.","C":"He went to the concert.","D":"He talked to his friend Ben."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states he went to the backyard \"after practicing his sax.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scene 3 It\u0027s Thursday. After practicing his sax, hayate has gone outside to the backyard to get some fresh air.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing? A. Giving up quickly when things get hard B. Continuing to try even when it is difficult C. Asking someone else to do the work for you D. Moving to a new place to start over","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp If you \"persevere,\" what are you doing?","choices":{"A":"Giving up quickly when things get hard","B":"Continuing to try even when it is difficult","C":"Asking someone else to do the work for you","D":"Moving to a new place to start over"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Perseverance means to keep working towards a goal despite obstacles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What did Hayate do before he went to the backyard? A. He finished his song perfectly. B. He practiced his saxophone. C. He went to the concert. D. He talked to his friend Ben.","excerpt":"\"Scene 3 It\u0027s Thursday. After practicing his sax, hayate has gone outside to the backyard to get some fresh air.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What did Hayate do before he went to the backyard?","choices":{"A":"He finished his song perfectly.","B":"He practiced his saxophone.","C":"He went to the concert.","D":"He talked to his friend Ben."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states he went to the backyard \"after practicing his sax.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scene 3 It\u0027s Thursday. After practicing his sax, hayate has gone outside to the backyard to get some fresh air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does this tell you about Rosetsu\u0027s work ethic? A. He stopped working as hard as before. B. He is a dedicated and hardworking student. C. He only works when his teacher is watching. D. He is naturally talented and does not need to study.","excerpt":"\"After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does this tell you about Rosetsu\u0027s work ethic?","choices":{"A":"He stopped working as hard as before.","B":"He is a dedicated and hardworking student.","C":"He only works when his teacher is watching.","D":"He is naturally talented and does not need to study."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Improving his skills over a year of study shows he is diligent and dedicated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Who gives this advice to Hayate? A. His friend Ben B. His sister, Wakana C. His father D. His music teacher","excerpt":"\"If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit?\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Who gives this advice to Hayate?","choices":{"A":"His friend Ben","B":"His sister, Wakana","C":"His father","D":"His music teacher"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In the dialogue, Wakana is the one who suggests he could quit if he does not enjoy it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Whose brush did the stranger give to Rosetsu? A. Sensei Okyo\u0027s B. Rosetsu\u0027s father\u0027s C. Ishida Yutei\u0027s D. The gatekeeper\u0027s","excerpt":"\"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Whose brush did the stranger give to Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"Sensei Okyo\u0027s","B":"Rosetsu\u0027s father\u0027s","C":"Ishida Yutei\u0027s","D":"The gatekeeper\u0027s"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The gatekeeper explains that the brush belonged to his teacher, Ishida Yutei.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"discouraged\" mean in this sentence? A. feeling very happy and proud B. feeling angry and ready to fight C. feeling sad and losing hope D. feeling tired and ready to sleep","excerpt":"\"As his classmates finished school and went on to become great painters, Rosetsu was left behind. He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt.\"","stem":"What does the word \"discouraged\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"feeling very happy and proud","B":"feeling angry and ready to fight","C":"feeling sad and losing hope","D":"feeling tired and ready to sleep"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Rosetsu feels \"discouraged\" because his classmates are becoming great painters while he feels left behind, meaning he is sad and losing hope.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As his classmates finished school and went on to become great painters, Rosetsu was left behind. He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What does Rosetsu do after hearing the other students talking about him? A. He argues with them and tells them they are wrong. B. He packs his belongings and runs away into the night. C. He goes to Sensei Okyo to ask for more help. D. He hides in his room and paints a picture of them.","excerpt":"\"As the sound of their footsteps died away down the hall, Rosetsu was flooded with embarrassment and shame. He packed up his belongings and ran out of the school, relieved to escape into the cold winter night.\"","stem":"What does Rosetsu do after hearing the other students talking about him?","choices":{"A":"He argues with them and tells them they are wrong.","B":"He packs his belongings and runs away into the night.","C":"He goes to Sensei Okyo to ask for more help.","D":"He hides in his room and paints a picture of them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that Rosetsu packed up his belongings and ran out of the school into the cold winter night.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the sound of their footsteps died away down the hall, Rosetsu was flooded with embarrassment and shame. He packed up his belongings and ran out of the school, relieved to escape into the cold winter night.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q008","read_aloud":"Why do the other students think Rosetsu is missing something? A. because he never finishes his paintings B. because he does not have a good brush C. because he spends too much time making ink D. because he does not like to paint landscapes","excerpt":"\"\"Rosetsu has never completed a painting, not even once!\" one student said, adding, \"It must be because he is missing something-like talent, or taste.\"\"","stem":"Why do the other students think Rosetsu is missing something?","choices":{"A":"because he never finishes his paintings","B":"because he does not have a good brush","C":"because he spends too much time making ink","D":"because he does not like to paint landscapes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The student explicitly says Rosetsu has \"never completed a painting, not even once,\" which is why they think he lacks talent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Rosetsu has never completed a painting, not even once!\" one student said, adding, \"It must be because he is missing something-like talent, or taste.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q009","read_aloud":"How long does Rosetsu study at the Maruyama School before he feels discouraged? A. one year B. three years C. five years D. ten years","excerpt":"\"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like.\"","stem":"How long does Rosetsu study at the Maruyama School before he feels discouraged?","choices":{"A":"one year","B":"three years","C":"five years","D":"ten years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states that \"Three years passed quickly\" before Rosetsu started feeling discouraged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Why does Rosetsu collapse into a snow bank? A. He is exhausted from walking and feeling completely hopeless. B. He is trying to hide from the other students at the school. C. He wants to catch a wild animal in the cold winter night. D. He is playing a game with the pine trees in the forest.","excerpt":"\"Finally, when he could walk no more, he collapsed into a snow bank beneath some pine trees, where he burrowed under the snow and fell asleep.\"","stem":"Why does Rosetsu collapse into a snow bank?","choices":{"A":"He is exhausted from walking and feeling completely hopeless.","B":"He is trying to hide from the other students at the school.","C":"He wants to catch a wild animal in the cold winter night.","D":"He is playing a game with the pine trees in the forest."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Rosetsu has been walking for hours in the snow while feeling flooded with shame and embarrassment, so he collapses from exhaustion and hopelessness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Finally, when he could walk no more, he collapsed into a snow bank beneath some pine trees, where he burrowed under the snow and fell asleep.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q011","read_aloud":"Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. … I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize. What does \"persevere\" mean? A. To give up easily B. To continue trying despite difficulty C. To run away D. To forget a goal","excerpt":"If I am to succeed,","stem":"Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. … I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize. What does \"persevere\" mean?","choices":{"A":"To give up easily","B":"To continue trying despite difficulty","C":"To run away","D":"To forget a goal"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Persevere means to keep trying even when it is hard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If I am to succeed,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the stranger? A. He is a thief. B. He is a wise judge of talent, possibly magical. C. He is lying. D. He is Rosetsu\u0027s father.","excerpt":"\"The stranger clapped Rosetsu on the back and announced, \u0027You young man, are a painter-one destined to paint pictures more wondrous than the world has ever seen.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you infer about the stranger?","choices":{"A":"He is a thief.","B":"He is a wise judge of talent, possibly magical.","C":"He is lying.","D":"He is Rosetsu\u0027s father."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stranger\u0027s pronouncement and later identity as Yutei show wisdom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stranger clapped Rosetsu on the back and announced, \u0027You young man, are a painter-one destined to paint pictures more wondrous than the world has ever seen.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q013","read_aloud":"Excerpt from The Carp: Rosetsu must paint without a brush. How is this different from a typical art student today? A. Today\u0027s students always paint with their fingers. B. Today\u0027s students usually have brushes and supplies. C. Today\u0027s students never paint. D. It is exactly the same.","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Excerpt from The Carp: Rosetsu must paint without a brush. How is this different from a typical art student today?","choices":{"A":"Today\u0027s students always paint with their fingers.","B":"Today\u0027s students usually have brushes and supplies.","C":"Today\u0027s students never paint.","D":"It is exactly the same."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu had to improvise; today supplies are common.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q014","read_aloud":"replied the man, and suddenly, as if from thin air, he produced a painting brush-old and worn and nothing to look at-and placed it in Rosetsu\u0027s hand. What did the stranger give Rosetsu? A. A book B. An old painting brush C. A bag of gold D. A new set of paints","excerpt":"Not before I give you this,","stem":"replied the man, and suddenly, as if from thin air, he produced a painting brush-old and worn and nothing to look at-and placed it in Rosetsu\u0027s hand. What did the stranger give Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"A book","B":"An old painting brush","C":"A bag of gold","D":"A new set of paints"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stranger gave him an old, worn brush.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Not before I give you this,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What problem is Rosetsu facing after three years? A. He has no teacher. B. He is discouraged and doubts himself because he isn\u0027t progressing fast enough. C. He lost his brush. D. He wants to quit school.","excerpt":"\"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like. He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt.\"","stem":"What problem is Rosetsu facing after three years?","choices":{"A":"He has no teacher.","B":"He is discouraged and doubts himself because he isn\u0027t progressing fast enough.","C":"He lost his brush.","D":"He wants to quit school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He feels discouraged and full of self-doubt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like. He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"persevere\" mean? A. give up quickly B. do something even when it is hard C. ask for help D. take a long break","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"What does \"persevere\" mean?","choices":{"A":"give up quickly","B":"do something even when it is hard","C":"ask for help","D":"take a long break"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Persevere\" means to keep trying even when things are difficult. Rosetsu will not give up until he succeeds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Rosetsu? A. He thought the brush was ugly and useless. B. He was polite and did not want to be rude. C. He was angry at the stranger. D. He wanted to sell the brush.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu didn\u0027t want to hurt the stranger\u0027s feelings, so he smiled and thanked him, and he put the brush in his pack.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"He thought the brush was ugly and useless.","B":"He was polite and did not want to be rude.","C":"He was angry at the stranger.","D":"He wanted to sell the brush."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu smiled and thanked the stranger even though the brush looked old. He was being polite and kind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu didn\u0027t want to hurt the stranger\u0027s feelings, so he smiled and thanked him, and he put the brush in his pack.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Why did Rosetsu leave the school? A. He was hungry. B. He heard other students make fun of him. C. He wanted to visit his parents. D. The school was closed.","excerpt":"\"As the sound of their footsteps died away down the hall, Rosetsu was flooded with embarrassment and shame. He packed up his belongings and ran out of the school.\"","stem":"Why did Rosetsu leave the school?","choices":{"A":"He was hungry.","B":"He heard other students make fun of him.","C":"He wanted to visit his parents.","D":"The school was closed."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu heard two students say he had no talent. He felt embarrassed and ashamed, so he ran away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the sound of their footsteps died away down the hall, Rosetsu was flooded with embarrassment and shame. He packed up his belongings and ran out of the school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What was the carp trying to get? A. a fish B. a sembei C. a painting brush D. a piece of ice","excerpt":"\"A giant carp was jumping wildly in the middle of a half-frozen pond. Just out of reach, on the ice, lay a sembei-a sweet-salty Japanese cracker.\"","stem":"What was the carp trying to get?","choices":{"A":"a fish","B":"a sembei","C":"a painting brush","D":"a piece of ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says a sembei was on the ice, just out of the carp\u0027s reach. The carp was trying to get the cracker.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A giant carp was jumping wildly in the middle of a half-frozen pond. Just out of reach, on the ice, lay a sembei-a sweet-salty Japanese cracker.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Why is the treat called \"hard-won\"? A. It was expensive. B. The carp worked very hard to get it. C. It was stolen from another fish. D. It was easy to find.","excerpt":"\"Finally, with one last leap, the fish broke through the remaining bit of ice between it and the sembei, grasped its hard-won treat in its mouth, and swam away.\"","stem":"Why is the treat called \"hard-won\"?","choices":{"A":"It was expensive.","B":"The carp worked very hard to get it.","C":"It was stolen from another fish.","D":"It was easy to find."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Hard-won\" means earned through great effort. The carp spent all day jumping and breaking ice to get the sembei.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Finally, with one last leap, the fish broke through the remaining bit of ice between it and the sembei, grasped its hard-won treat in its mouth, and swam away.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. Which of these describes a \"conscientious\" person? A. Someone who is lazy and leaves work unfinished B. Someone who is careful, thorough, and hard-working C. Someone who likes to play games all day D. Someone who is always late for appointments","excerpt":"No,","stem":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. Which of these describes a \"conscientious\" person?","choices":{"A":"Someone who is lazy and leaves work unfinished","B":"Someone who is careful, thorough, and hard-working","C":"Someone who likes to play games all day","D":"Someone who is always late for appointments"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being conscientious means being diligent and doing your work carefully.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What is the main idea of this section of the play? A. Hayate should listen to his parents more. B. Hayate needs to focus on his feelings to become a better musician. C. Hayate should learn to read music more quickly. D. Hayate should quit the saxophone and play the drums.","excerpt":"\"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What is the main idea of this section of the play?","choices":{"A":"Hayate should listen to his parents more.","B":"Hayate needs to focus on his feelings to become a better musician.","C":"Hayate should learn to read music more quickly.","D":"Hayate should quit the saxophone and play the drums."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate realizes that his overthinking is hindering him and that expressing his heart is the key.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp How does this compare to Rosetsu\u0027s feelings at the very beginning of the story? A. He is much more confident now than he was at the start. B. He has lost all hope of becoming a painter. C. He is just as determined, but he is now learning through patience and hard work. D. He wants to quit painting entirely.","excerpt":"\"Each morning he eagerly awoke in hopes that he\u0027d be found worthy enough to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and every night he told himself, \u0027Soon, soon.\u0027\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp How does this compare to Rosetsu\u0027s feelings at the very beginning of the story?","choices":{"A":"He is much more confident now than he was at the start.","B":"He has lost all hope of becoming a painter.","C":"He is just as determined, but he is now learning through patience and hard work.","D":"He wants to quit painting entirely."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"He remains determined to succeed, but his journey has moved from simple excitement to the difficult reality of study.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Each morning he eagerly awoke in hopes that he\u0027d be found worthy enough to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and every night he told himself, \u0027Soon, soon.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Ben tell Hayate this story? A. To brag about his own musical talent. B. To show that even people who love music can get stressed. C. To tell Hayate that he should never play the piano. D. To convince Hayate to quit music.","excerpt":"\" ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano. . . . For some reason, when I started playing that [keyboard], it was fun.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Ben tell Hayate this story?","choices":{"A":"To brag about his own musical talent.","B":"To show that even people who love music can get stressed.","C":"To tell Hayate that he should never play the piano.","D":"To convince Hayate to quit music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben shares his experience to show Hayate that his feelings are normal and that changing his approach can help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano. . . . For some reason, when I started playing that [keyboard], it was fun.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why does hearing the other students make Rosetsu leave the school? A. He wants to go home to visit his parents. B. He is angry at the students and wants to fight them. C. Their negative words confirm his own feelings of failure and shame. D. He decides he wants to become a musician instead of a painter.","excerpt":"\"He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt. One day as when Rosetsu was grinding more ink for class, he heard two students speaking in the hall.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why does hearing the other students make Rosetsu leave the school?","choices":{"A":"He wants to go home to visit his parents.","B":"He is angry at the students and wants to fight them.","C":"Their negative words confirm his own feelings of failure and shame.","D":"He decides he wants to become a musician instead of a painter."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The students\u0027 harsh words confirm his worst fears about his lack of progress, causing him to feel so much shame that he runs away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He often felt discouraged and full of self-doubt. One day as when Rosetsu was grinding more ink for class, he heard two students speaking in the hall.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this context? A. loud noises made to scare away predators B. planned actions used to reach a goal C. special foods eaten to gain energy D. secret paths hidden under the ice","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei. He marveled at the carp\u0027s determination.\"","stem":"What does the word \"tactics\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"loud noises made to scare away predators","B":"planned actions used to reach a goal","C":"special foods eaten to gain energy","D":"secret paths hidden under the ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp uses different movements and \"tactics\" to try and reach the cracker, meaning it uses planned actions or strategies to achieve its goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei. He marveled at the carp\u0027s determination.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What lesson does Rosetsu learn from watching the carp? A. He should give up when things get too hard. B. He must be determined and refuse to give up. C. He needs to find a new school to study at. D. He should ask the carp for help with his painting.","excerpt":"\"\"If I am to succeed,\" Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"\"","stem":"What lesson does Rosetsu learn from watching the carp?","choices":{"A":"He should give up when things get too hard.","B":"He must be determined and refuse to give up.","C":"He needs to find a new school to study at.","D":"He should ask the carp for help with his painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu realizes he must be \"determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up,\" just like the carp trying to reach its food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"If I am to succeed,\" Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of Sensei Okyo\u0027s advice to Rosetsu? A. Rosetsu needs to work harder at making ink. B. Rosetsu\u0027s own self-doubt is stopping him from succeeding. C. Rosetsu should stop painting and go back home. D. Rosetsu must paint faster to finish his artwork.","excerpt":"\"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"\"","stem":"What is the main idea of Sensei Okyo\u0027s advice to Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu needs to work harder at making ink.","B":"Rosetsu\u0027s own self-doubt is stopping him from succeeding.","C":"Rosetsu should stop painting and go back home.","D":"Rosetsu must paint faster to finish his artwork."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sensei Okyo explains that Rosetsu is a hard worker, but his \"own doubts have held you back,\" meaning his lack of self-belief is the main problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q009","read_aloud":"How does Rosetsu apply the lesson he learned from the carp? A. He stops painting halfway through because he is scared. B. He works hard and finishes his paintings without giving up. C. He throws away his brush and uses a twig instead. D. He leaves the school to live in the snow with the carp.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last. After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\"","stem":"How does Rosetsu apply the lesson he learned from the carp?","choices":{"A":"He stops painting halfway through because he is scared.","B":"He works hard and finishes his paintings without giving up.","C":"He throws away his brush and uses a twig instead.","D":"He leaves the school to live in the snow with the carp."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu applies the carp\u0027s lesson by studying hard and completing many paintings, showing he is no longer giving up halfway through.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last. After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How does the carp\u0027s struggle in the ice mirror Rosetsu\u0027s struggle as a painter? A. Both the carp and Rosetsu are trying to escape from a cold winter storm. B. Both face a difficult barrier and must keep trying despite feeling exhausted. C. Both are trying to catch a sweet treat to eat for dinner. D. Both are being watched by a master teacher who is testing them.","excerpt":"\"Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize. Morning passed, noon came and went, and the sun began to sink, yet the bruised and exhausted carp still did not give up.\"","stem":"How does the carp\u0027s struggle in the ice mirror Rosetsu\u0027s struggle as a painter?","choices":{"A":"Both the carp and Rosetsu are trying to escape from a cold winter storm.","B":"Both face a difficult barrier and must keep trying despite feeling exhausted.","C":"Both are trying to catch a sweet treat to eat for dinner.","D":"Both are being watched by a master teacher who is testing them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp struggles against the hard ice and keeps jumping despite being exhausted, just as Rosetsu must push through his self-doubt and keep painting to achieve his dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize. Morning passed, noon came and went, and the sun began to sink, yet the bruised and exhausted carp still did not give up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What has caused Rosetsu\u0027s slow progress? A. Lack of talent B. His own doubts and fear of not being good enough C. His teacher not teaching him D. He lost his brush","excerpt":"\"Your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough!\"","stem":"What has caused Rosetsu\u0027s slow progress?","choices":{"A":"Lack of talent","B":"His own doubts and fear of not being good enough","C":"His teacher not teaching him","D":"He lost his brush"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sensei says his doubts held him back.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What does Hayate\u0027s sigh and words \"get it over with\" suggest about his feelings? A. He is excited to play. B. He is not looking forward to playing and feels pressured. C. He loves performing. D. He is angry at his parents.","excerpt":"\"HAYATE (sighing). I\u0027ll go. I might as well get it over with.\"","stem":"What does Hayate\u0027s sigh and words \"get it over with\" suggest about his feelings?","choices":{"A":"He is excited to play.","B":"He is not looking forward to playing and feels pressured.","C":"He loves performing.","D":"He is angry at his parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Get it over with\" shows reluctance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"HAYATE (sighing). I\u0027ll go. I might as well get it over with.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q013","read_aloud":"Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. Why does Rosetsu admire the carp? A. It is large and strong. B. It never gives up, even when exhausted and bruised. C. It can fly. D. It is colorful.","excerpt":"If I am to succeed,","stem":"Rosetsu said to himself, \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up. Why does Rosetsu admire the carp?","choices":{"A":"It is large and strong.","B":"It never gives up, even when exhausted and bruised.","C":"It can fly.","D":"It is colorful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp persisted until it reached its goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If I am to succeed,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q014","read_aloud":"Why did Rosetsu choose to paint a carp? A. He had never seen a carp before. B. The carp inspired him to persevere, and he wanted to honor it. C. His teacher told him to. D. Carp are easy to paint.","excerpt":"\"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp.\"","stem":"Why did Rosetsu choose to paint a carp?","choices":{"A":"He had never seen a carp before.","B":"The carp inspired him to persevere, and he wanted to honor it.","C":"His teacher told him to.","D":"Carp are easy to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp was his symbol of determination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q015","read_aloud":"the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. What does \"conscientious\" mean? A. lazy and careless B. diligent and thorough C. rude and mean D. quiet and shy","excerpt":"No,","stem":"the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. What does \"conscientious\" mean?","choices":{"A":"lazy and careless","B":"diligent and thorough","C":"rude and mean","D":"quiet and shy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Conscientious\" means careful, diligent, and thorough. Sensei Okyo says Rosetsu works hard, but his doubts stop him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How are Rosetsu and Hayate similar? A. They both quit when things got hard. B. They both found inspiration and worked harder. C. They both became famous painters. D. They both had mean teachers.","excerpt":"From The Carp: \"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\"","stem":"How are Rosetsu and Hayate similar?","choices":{"A":"They both quit when things got hard.","B":"They both found inspiration and worked harder.","C":"They both became famous painters.","D":"They both had mean teachers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu was inspired by the carp and worked harder. Hayate was inspired by the hermit thrush and played from his heart. Both found inspiration to keep going.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From The Carp: \"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What is the main theme, or message, of The Carp? A. Fish make good pets. B. Determination and perseverance lead to success. C. Art school is too hard. D. Strangers should not be trusted.","excerpt":"\"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\"","stem":"What is the main theme, or message, of The Carp?","choices":{"A":"Fish make good pets.","B":"Determination and perseverance lead to success.","C":"Art school is too hard.","D":"Strangers should not be trusted."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu learns from the carp that you must keep trying even when things are difficult. This determination helps him become a great painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What advice does Sensei Okyo give Rosetsu? A. To paint faster B. To believe in himself and finish his work C. To find a new teacher D. To stop painting forever","excerpt":"\"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"","stem":"What advice does Sensei Okyo give Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"To paint faster","B":"To believe in himself and finish his work","C":"To find a new teacher","D":"To stop painting forever"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sensei Okyo tells Rosetsu that fear of failure is holding him back. He must believe in himself and finish his paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Why did Rosetsu paint a carp? A. He liked the color of carp. B. The carp inspired him to never give up. C. His teacher told him to paint fish. D. Carp were easy to paint.","excerpt":"\"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\"","stem":"Why did Rosetsu paint a carp?","choices":{"A":"He liked the color of carp.","B":"The carp inspired him to never give up.","C":"His teacher told him to paint fish.","D":"Carp were easy to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu painted the carp to honor it. The carp taught him to keep trying, and he wanted to remember that lesson.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does it mean to be supportive? A. To argue with someone B. To encourage or help someone C. To ignore someone\u0027s success D. To make fun of someone\u0027s mistakes","excerpt":"\"Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does it mean to be supportive?","choices":{"A":"To argue with someone","B":"To encourage or help someone","C":"To ignore someone\u0027s success","D":"To make fun of someone\u0027s mistakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To be supportive is to show interest and encouragement toward someone else.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What does this show about Rosetsu\u0027s personality? A. He is easily discouraged when he fails. B. He is determined to overcome his challenges. C. He believes that things should be given to him for free. D. He does not care about becoming a great painter anymore.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What does this show about Rosetsu\u0027s personality?","choices":{"A":"He is easily discouraged when he fails.","B":"He is determined to overcome his challenges.","C":"He believes that things should be given to him for free.","D":"He does not care about becoming a great painter anymore."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu chooses to learn from his experience and commits to hard work, showing high levels of determination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What caused Hayate\u0027s playing to sound better? A. He bought a new, more expensive saxophone. B. He played while thinking only about his music teacher\u0027s rules. C. He started playing from his heart instead of overthinking. D. He practiced the same song for ten hours.","excerpt":"\"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What caused Hayate\u0027s playing to sound better?","choices":{"A":"He bought a new, more expensive saxophone.","B":"He played while thinking only about his music teacher\u0027s rules.","C":"He started playing from his heart instead of overthinking.","D":"He practiced the same song for ten hours."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"By stopping his overthinking and focusing on his feelings (inspired by the bir d), his playing improved.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why does Rosetsu choose to paint a carp? A. It is the easiest thing to paint. B. It is the only thing he knows how to paint. C. It represents the determination he learned during his journey. D. His sensei told him that he must paint a fish.","excerpt":"\"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why does Rosetsu choose to paint a carp?","choices":{"A":"It is the easiest thing to paint.","B":"It is the only thing he knows how to paint.","C":"It represents the determination he learned during his journey.","D":"His sensei told him that he must paint a fish."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The carp serves as a symbolic reminder of the persistence he needed to succeed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush How is this advice similar to what Rosetsu learns in \"The Carp\"? A. Both characters learn that they should quit when things get difficult. B. Both characters learn that natural talent is the only thing that matters. C. Both characters learn that focusing on their passion and persistence is more important than worrying about mistakes. D. Both characters learn that they need better teachers.","excerpt":"\" hayate. I\u0027m just messing around. That\u0027s the only time I sound okay. ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush How is this advice similar to what Rosetsu learns in \"The Carp\"?","choices":{"A":"Both characters learn that they should quit when things get difficult.","B":"Both characters learn that natural talent is the only thing that matters.","C":"Both characters learn that focusing on their passion and persistence is more important than worrying about mistakes.","D":"Both characters learn that they need better teachers."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Both stories center on the idea that internal belief and persistent, passionate effort (rather than fear of failure) are key to growth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" hayate. I\u0027m just messing around. That\u0027s the only time I sound okay. ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"supportive\" mean in this sentence? A. making fun of someone\u0027s mistakes B. encouraging and helping someone C. playing a loud musical instrument D. ignoring what someone is saying","excerpt":"\"wakana. Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose. mom. Wakana! dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"What does the word \"supportive\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"making fun of someone\u0027s mistakes","B":"encouraging and helping someone","C":"playing a loud musical instrument","D":"ignoring what someone is saying"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dad tells Wakana to be \"supportive,\" which means she should be encouraging and helpful to her brother instead of making fun of his playing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wakana. Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose. mom. Wakana! dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What instrument does Hayate play for the family concert? A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"What instrument does Hayate play for the family concert?","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What happens while Hayate is playing his song? A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"What happens while Hayate is playing his song?","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q009","read_aloud":"On what day does the Watanabe family hold their weekly concert? A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"On what day does the Watanabe family hold their weekly concert?","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q010","read_aloud":"Why does Hayate storm out of the living room? A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"Why does Hayate storm out of the living room?","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"supportive\" mean? A. Critical and mean B. Encouraging and helpful C. Ignoring someone D. Angry","excerpt":"\"Dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"What does \"supportive\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Critical and mean","B":"Encouraging and helpful","C":"Ignoring someone","D":"Angry"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Supportive means giving encouragement and help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What conflict is introduced here? A. Hayate is angry at his sister for her hurtful joke. B. Hayate has lost his saxophone. C. The family is moving. D. Hayate wants to play guitar.","excerpt":"\"WAKANA. Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose. … HAYATE storms out of the living room.\"","stem":"What conflict is introduced here?","choices":{"A":"Hayate is angry at his sister for her hurtful joke.","B":"Hayate has lost his saxophone.","C":"The family is moving.","D":"Hayate wants to play guitar."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wakana\u0027s comment hurts Hayate\u0027s feelings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"WAKANA. Yikes, your sax sounds like a sick moose. … HAYATE storms out of the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What does this dialogue reveal about Hayate\u0027s internal conflict? A. He thinks he is the best musician in the family. B. He feels frustrated and compares himself negatively to his family. C. He wants to quit music forever. D. He hates his family.","excerpt":"\"HAYATE. I don\u0027t see you, DAD, or WAKANA struggling. … I should do something else I\u0027m actually good at.\"","stem":"What does this dialogue reveal about Hayate\u0027s internal conflict?","choices":{"A":"He thinks he is the best musician in the family.","B":"He feels frustrated and compares himself negatively to his family.","C":"He wants to quit music forever.","D":"He hates his family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He feels he doesn\u0027t measure up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"HAYATE. I don\u0027t see you, DAD, or WAKANA struggling. … I should do something else I\u0027m actually good at.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q014","read_aloud":"If Hayate follows this advice, what might he do differently? A. Play only to please his family. B. Play for his own joy, not just to be perfect. C. Quit saxophone completely. D. Only play birdsongs.","excerpt":"\"WAKANA. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote? \u0027The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\u0027\"","stem":"If Hayate follows this advice, what might he do differently?","choices":{"A":"Play only to please his family.","B":"Play for his own joy, not just to be perfect.","C":"Quit saxophone completely.","D":"Only play birdsongs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Play for happiness, not just approval.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"WAKANA. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote? \u0027The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell you about the setting? A. The family is at a school. B. The family has a weekly music concert at home. C. The family is at a concert hall. D. The family is buying instruments.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room. An acoustic guitar leans against Dad\u0027s chair.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell you about the setting?","choices":{"A":"The family is at a school.","B":"The family has a weekly music concert at home.","C":"The family is at a concert hall.","D":"The family is buying instruments."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stage directions tell us it is Saturday and the family has a weekly concert in their living room. This is their home setting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room. An acoustic guitar leans against Dad\u0027s chair.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What do the stage directions show about Hayate? A. He is confident and relaxed. B. He is nervous and struggling. C. He is angry at his teacher. D. He is happy and laughing.","excerpt":"\"hayate. Just a jazz piece my music teacher taught me. (hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the piece.)\"","stem":"What do the stage directions show about Hayate?","choices":{"A":"He is confident and relaxed.","B":"He is nervous and struggling.","C":"He is angry at his teacher.","D":"He is happy and laughing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stage directions say \"harsh sounds,\" \"beads of sweat,\" and he stops early. These details show Hayate is nervous and having trouble.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. Just a jazz piece my music teacher taught me. (hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the piece.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Ben share his own story? A. To make fun of Hayate B. To show Hayate that he understands and to encourage him C. To brag about his piano skills D. To tell Hayate to quit","excerpt":"\"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\"","stem":"Why does Ben share his own story?","choices":{"A":"To make fun of Hayate","B":"To show Hayate that he understands and to encourage him","C":"To brag about his piano skills","D":"To tell Hayate to quit"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben tells his story about wanting to quit piano to show Hayate that he understands. He wants Hayate to know that struggle is normal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q018","read_aloud":"How has Wakana changed from Act 1? A. She is still making fun of Hayate. B. She is being more helpful and giving good advice. C. She wants Hayate to leave the family. D. She is angry at her parents.","excerpt":"\"wakana. No, it wasn\u0027t bad. You should only play music you love, though. hayate. I\u0027d ruin that too. Maybe I shouldn\u0027t play anything at all. wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit?\"","stem":"How has Wakana changed from Act 1?","choices":{"A":"She is still making fun of Hayate.","B":"She is being more helpful and giving good advice.","C":"She wants Hayate to leave the family.","D":"She is angry at her parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In Act 1, Wakana said Hayate sounded like \"a sick moose.\" Now she gives him advice about playing music he loves. She has become more supportive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wakana. No, it wasn\u0027t bad. You should only play music you love, though. hayate. I\u0027d ruin that too. Maybe I shouldn\u0027t play anything at all. wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Which situation best shows someone trying to \"quell\" something? A. A fire captain using water to stop a forest fire. B. A student starting a new argument in class. C. A painter choosing bright colors for a picture. D. A musician learning a new song on the radio.","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Which situation best shows someone trying to \"quell\" something?","choices":{"A":"A fire captain using water to stop a forest fire.","B":"A student starting a new argument in class.","C":"A painter choosing bright colors for a picture.","D":"A musician learning a new song on the radio."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Quelling is about stopping or suppressing something, like putting out a fire.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is Hayate really afraid to tell his parents he wants to quit? A. He is worried they will take away his computer. B. He fears they will think less of him if he fails. C. He knows they will make him play the guitar instead. D. He thinks they will tell his friends about his failure.","excerpt":"\" hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is Hayate really afraid to tell his parents he wants to quit?","choices":{"A":"He is worried they will take away his computer.","B":"He fears they will think less of him if he fails.","C":"He knows they will make him play the guitar instead.","D":"He thinks they will tell his friends about his failure."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He feels he is \"not good\" and thinks his family\u0027s expectations make him a failure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp How is this event like the conflict Rosetsu is experiencing in his life? A. Like the carp, Rosetsu is trapped in a place he cannot leave. B. Like the carp, Rosetsu must work slowly and consistently against hardship to reach his goal. C. Like the carp, Rosetsu is looking for food to eat. D. Like the carp, Rosetsu is fighting with his classmates.","excerpt":"\"A giant carp was jumping wildly in the middle of a half-frozen pond. . . . Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp How is this event like the conflict Rosetsu is experiencing in his life?","choices":{"A":"Like the carp, Rosetsu is trapped in a place he cannot leave.","B":"Like the carp, Rosetsu must work slowly and consistently against hardship to reach his goal.","C":"Like the carp, Rosetsu is looking for food to eat.","D":"Like the carp, Rosetsu is fighting with his classmates."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both the fish and Rosetsu face a difficult challenge that requires persistent effort to overcome.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A giant carp was jumping wildly in the middle of a half-frozen pond. . . . Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Do you think Hayate actually wanted to quit playing music, or was he just frustrated? A. He wanted to quit because he hated the instrument. B. He did not want to quit, but he felt defeated by his struggle. C. He wanted to quit so he could play video games. D. He wanted to quit to make his parents angry.","excerpt":"\" wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Do you think Hayate actually wanted to quit playing music, or was he just frustrated?","choices":{"A":"He wanted to quit because he hated the instrument.","B":"He did not want to quit, but he felt defeated by his struggle.","C":"He wanted to quit so he could play video games.","D":"He wanted to quit to make his parents angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He says, \"I love the sax,\" showing his frustration comes from his inability to meet his own standards, not from dislike of the music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp I must know why I have been kept behind these three years. . . . Was it a good choice for Rosetsu to speak honestly to his teacher? A. No, he should have kept his frustration to himself. B. Yes, because it allowed him to get the feedback and motivation he needed. C. No, he should have just stayed home and never returned. D. Yes, because the teacher would have eventually quit if he didn\u0027t.","excerpt":"The next day, he was granted permission to meet privately with Sensei Okyo.","stem":"Selection: The Carp I must know why I have been kept behind these three years. . . . Was it a good choice for Rosetsu to speak honestly to his teacher?","choices":{"A":"No, he should have kept his frustration to himself.","B":"Yes, because it allowed him to get the feedback and motivation he needed.","C":"No, he should have just stayed home and never returned.","D":"Yes, because the teacher would have eventually quit if he didn\u0027t."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Speaking up helped him understand that his \"doubts\" were the problem, which he could then fix.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The next day, he was granted permission to meet privately with Sensei Okyo."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"attitude\" mean in this context? A. the way a person thinks and feels about something B. the type of musical instrument a person plays C. the amount of time spent practicing a song D. the speed at which a person reads sheet music","excerpt":"\"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\"","stem":"What does the word \"attitude\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"the way a person thinks and feels about something","B":"the type of musical instrument a person plays","C":"the amount of time spent practicing a song","D":"the speed at which a person reads sheet music"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ben is talking about Hayate\u0027s negative \"attitude,\" which refers to the way he is thinking and feeling about his ability to play the saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What does Ben suggest Hayate should do to feel less anxious? A. quit playing music and shoot hoops instead B. practice on a different instrument to relax C. loosen up and spend more time playing what he wants D. ask his parents to buy him an electronic keyboard","excerpt":"\"ben. And for some reason, when I started playing that, it was fun. I didn\u0027t feel anxious when I played it-I just loosened up. And that helped me relax when I played our big grand piano, too.\"","stem":"What does Ben suggest Hayate should do to feel less anxious?","choices":{"A":"quit playing music and shoot hoops instead","B":"practice on a different instrument to relax","C":"loosen up and spend more time playing what he wants","D":"ask his parents to buy him an electronic keyboard"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ben tells Hayate that he needs to \"loosen up\" and spend more time playing what he wants to play instead of just trying to be perfect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. And for some reason, when I started playing that, it was fun. I didn\u0027t feel anxious when I played it-I just loosened up. And that helped me relax when I played our big grand piano, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q008","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: Hayate loves the saxophone; Effect: He wants to quit playing it. B. Cause: Hayate thinks he is not good; Effect: He is afraid to quit and disappoint his parents. C. Cause: Wakana tells him to quit; Effect: He immediately tells his parents. D. Cause: Hayate practices every day; Effect: He becomes a perfect player.","excerpt":"\"wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Hayate loves the saxophone; Effect: He wants to quit playing it.","B":"Cause: Hayate thinks he is not good; Effect: He is afraid to quit and disappoint his parents.","C":"Cause: Wakana tells him to quit; Effect: He immediately tells his parents.","D":"Cause: Hayate practices every day; Effect: He becomes a perfect player."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate feels he is not good at playing (cause), which makes him afraid to quit because he knows his parents would be disappointed (effect).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q009","read_aloud":"The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. How can Hayate apply Wakana\u0027s quote to his own life? A. He should only play music when he is happy and playing for himself. B. He should stop playing the saxophone and learn to sing like a bird. C. He should practice playing loud songs to please his parents. D. He should quit music entirely because birds do not play instruments.","excerpt":"wakana. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?","stem":"The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. How can Hayate apply Wakana\u0027s quote to his own life?","choices":{"A":"He should only play music when he is happy and playing for himself.","B":"He should stop playing the saxophone and learn to sing like a bird.","C":"He should practice playing loud songs to please his parents.","D":"He should quit music entirely because birds do not play instruments."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wakana\u0027s quote means the bird sings for its own happiness, so Hayate should apply this by playing music because he loves it, not just to please others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: wakana. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does Ben\u0027s advice differ from the pressure Hayate feels from himself? A. Ben wants Hayate to quit music, while Hayate wants to be perfect. B. Ben encourages playing for fun, while Hayate stresses over being perfect. C. Ben thinks Hayate should play the piano, while Hayate wants to play the sax. D. Ben believes Hayate is already the best, while Hayate thinks he is the worst.","excerpt":"\"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\"","stem":"How does Ben\u0027s advice differ from the pressure Hayate feels from himself?","choices":{"A":"Ben wants Hayate to quit music, while Hayate wants to be perfect.","B":"Ben encourages playing for fun, while Hayate stresses over being perfect.","C":"Ben thinks Hayate should play the piano, while Hayate wants to play the sax.","D":"Ben believes Hayate is already the best, while Hayate thinks he is the worst."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben tells Hayate to \"loosen up\" and play what he wants, which directly contrasts with Hayate\u0027s own stressful goal of trying to be \"perfect.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q011","read_aloud":"the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. What is an antonym of \"conscientious\"? A. Careful B. Careless C. Diligent D. Thorough","excerpt":"No,","stem":"the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. What is an antonym of \"conscientious\"?","choices":{"A":"Careful","B":"Careless","C":"Diligent","D":"Thorough"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Conscientious means careful; careless is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q012","read_aloud":"How does listening to the bird change Hayate\u0027s playing? A. He plays exactly like the bird. B. He relaxes and plays from his heart, which sounds better. C. He stops playing altogether. D. He plays louder.","excerpt":"\"The hermit thrush continues to sing. … He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays. The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh.\"","stem":"How does listening to the bird change Hayate\u0027s playing?","choices":{"A":"He plays exactly like the bird.","B":"He relaxes and plays from his heart, which sounds better.","C":"He stops playing altogether.","D":"He plays louder."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He lets go of tension and plays expressively.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hermit thrush continues to sing. … He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays. The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q013","read_aloud":"Why does Hayate name his song after the bird? A. He wants to be a bird. B. The bird inspired him to change his approach to music. C. The bird can talk. D. It was a school assignment.","excerpt":"\"HAYATE (blushing). Thanks. I call it \u0027Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Hayate name his song after the bird?","choices":{"A":"He wants to be a bird.","B":"The bird inspired him to change his approach to music.","C":"The bird can talk.","D":"It was a school assignment."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bird taught him to play with joy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"HAYATE (blushing). Thanks. I call it \u0027Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"conscientious\"? A. careless B. diligent C. lazy D. rude","excerpt":"\"You are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"conscientious\"?","choices":{"A":"careless","B":"diligent","C":"lazy","D":"rude"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Conscientious\" and \"diligent\" both mean careful and hardworking. Rosetsu works hard, but his self-doubt stops him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q015","read_aloud":"What do the words in parentheses tell the reader? A. What the characters are thinking B. Stage directions for how to act C. The title of the play D. What the audience should do","excerpt":"\"(hayate storms out of the living room. mom follows him and stops him in the hallway.)\"","stem":"What do the words in parentheses tell the reader?","choices":{"A":"What the characters are thinking","B":"Stage directions for how to act","C":"The title of the play","D":"What the audience should do"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In a drama, words in parentheses are stage directions. They tell the actors how to move and behave on stage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate storms out of the living room. mom follows him and stops him in the hallway.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q016","read_aloud":"How are a legend and a drama different? A. A legend uses narrative paragraphs; a drama uses dialogue and stage directions. B. They are exactly the same. C. A drama never has characters. D. A legend is always funny.","excerpt":"From The Carp: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"hayate. I\u0027ll go. I might as well get it over with.\"","stem":"How are a legend and a drama different?","choices":{"A":"A legend uses narrative paragraphs; a drama uses dialogue and stage directions.","B":"They are exactly the same.","C":"A drama never has characters.","D":"A legend is always funny."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A legend is told in paragraphs by a narrator. A drama is written as a script with character tags, dialogue, and stage directions for actors.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From The Carp: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"hayate. I\u0027ll go. I might as well get it over with.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Hayate talk to himself? A. He is practicing a speech. B. He is feeling frustrated and trying to figure out what to do. C. He is talking to the bird. D. He is singing a song.","excerpt":"\"hayate (talking to himself). Why can\u0027t I learn to play better? Last week I left the concert early. This week I won\u0027t go at all.\"","stem":"Why does Hayate talk to himself?","choices":{"A":"He is practicing a speech.","B":"He is feeling frustrated and trying to figure out what to do.","C":"He is talking to the bird.","D":"He is singing a song."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate is alone and talking to himself about his problems. He is frustrated and thinking about giving up on the concerts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate (talking to himself). Why can\u0027t I learn to play better? Last week I left the concert early. This week I won\u0027t go at all.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What does Hayate learn from the hermit thrush? A. Birds are better than saxophones. B. Music should come from the heart, not just from notes on paper. C. He should stop playing music. D. He needs a new teacher.","excerpt":"\"hayate (to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart.\"","stem":"What does Hayate learn from the hermit thrush?","choices":{"A":"Birds are better than saxophones.","B":"Music should come from the heart, not just from notes on paper.","C":"He should stop playing music.","D":"He needs a new teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bird sings naturally without studying. Hayate realizes he should feel the music and play from his heart instead of worrying about being perfect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate (to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Which is the best example of using \"tactics\" to achieve a goal? A. Wishing for something to happen. B. Developing a plan to study for a big test to get a high grade. C. Giving up when a task becomes too hard. D. Buying a new item because it looks nice.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Which is the best example of using \"tactics\" to achieve a goal?","choices":{"A":"Wishing for something to happen.","B":"Developing a plan to study for a big test to get a high grade.","C":"Giving up when a task becomes too hard.","D":"Buying a new item because it looks nice."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tactics are specific strategies used to reach an objective.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. What is the author trying to say through this quote? A. You should only do things that make other people happy. B. Birds are better at music than people. C. True success comes from doing what makes you happy, not from trying to impress people. D. People should only listen to birds when they want to learn music.","excerpt":"You should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. What is the author trying to say through this quote?","choices":{"A":"You should only do things that make other people happy.","B":"Birds are better at music than people.","C":"True success comes from doing what makes you happy, not from trying to impress people.","D":"People should only listen to birds when they want to learn music."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The quote emphasizes internal joy over external performance, which is exactly what Hayate needs to learn.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush How does the structure of Scene 4 change the tone of the play compared to Scene 1? A. It makes the play feel more confusing and sad. B. It shifts the tone from struggle and frustration to success and peace. C. It changes the setting to a completely different location. D. It makes the characters stop talking to each other.","excerpt":"\"Scene 4 hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush How does the structure of Scene 4 change the tone of the play compared to Scene 1?","choices":{"A":"It makes the play feel more confusing and sad.","B":"It shifts the tone from struggle and frustration to success and peace.","C":"It changes the setting to a completely different location.","D":"It makes the characters stop talking to each other."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earlier scenes show Hayate struggling and failing; this scene shows him playing with confidence and happiness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scene 4 hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why does Sensei Okyo say that Rosetsu\u0027s doubts are the main problem? A. Because Rosetsu is a bad painter. B. Because Rosetsu refuses to do his work. C. Because believing in oneself is necessary to complete a difficult task well. D. Because Rosetsu is too old to learn.","excerpt":"\"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back.\"\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why does Sensei Okyo say that Rosetsu\u0027s doubts are the main problem?","choices":{"A":"Because Rosetsu is a bad painter.","B":"Because Rosetsu refuses to do his work.","C":"Because believing in oneself is necessary to complete a difficult task well.","D":"Because Rosetsu is too old to learn."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Confidence is necessary for an artist to fully commit to their work; self-doubt makes the artist stop halfway through.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is this a major \"turning point\" for Hayate? A. It is the moment he decides to quit the saxophone. B. It is the moment he stops trying to be perfect and starts being musical. C. It is the moment his parents agree to let him join a rock band. D. It is the moment he realizes he needs a new teacher.","excerpt":"\" hayate. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is this a major \"turning point\" for Hayate?","choices":{"A":"It is the moment he decides to quit the saxophone.","B":"It is the moment he stops trying to be perfect and starts being musical.","C":"It is the moment his parents agree to let him join a rock band.","D":"It is the moment he realizes he needs a new teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Up until this point, he tried to force success; shifting to \"feeling the music\" allows him to finally succeed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" hayate. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"thrush\" refer to in this context? A. a type of musical instrument B. a small bird with a beautiful song C. a famous composer of classical music D. a sheet of music with notes on it","excerpt":"\"hayate(to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird. (He listens as the bird finishes its song and then starts again.)\"","stem":"What does the word \"thrush\" refer to in this context?","choices":{"A":"a type of musical instrument","B":"a small bird with a beautiful song","C":"a famous composer of classical music","D":"a sheet of music with notes on it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"hermit thrush\" is the bird Hayate is talking to in the backyard, and the text mentions it singing beautifully.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate(to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird. (He listens as the bird finishes its song and then starts again.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q007","read_aloud":"What does Hayate hear while he is standing in the backyard? A. his sister Wakana practicing the drums B. his friend Ben shooting a basketball C. a hermit thrush singing in a tree D. his dad playing the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"(Suddenly, hayate hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree. hayate watches and listens.)\"","stem":"What does Hayate hear while he is standing in the backyard?","choices":{"A":"his sister Wakana practicing the drums","B":"his friend Ben shooting a basketball","C":"a hermit thrush singing in a tree","D":"his dad playing the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate suddenly hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(Suddenly, hayate hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree. hayate watches and listens.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What does the hermit thrush symbolize for Hayate? A. the pressure to read sheet music perfectly B. the freedom to create music from the heart C. the need to practice scales every single day D. the fear of making a mistake in front of others","excerpt":"\"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"What does the hermit thrush symbolize for Hayate?","choices":{"A":"the pressure to read sheet music perfectly","B":"the freedom to create music from the heart","C":"the need to practice scales every single day","D":"the fear of making a mistake in front of others"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bird sings beautifully without reading notes, symbolizing for Hayate that he should play freely from his heart instead of overthinking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q009","read_aloud":"What does Hayate do after he realizes he should play from his heart? A. He throws his saxophone on the bed and goes to sleep. B. He plays a melody with his eyes closed, feeling the music. C. He runs outside to find the bird and catch it. D. He writes a letter to his friend Ben about the bird.","excerpt":"\"hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\"","stem":"What does Hayate do after he realizes he should play from his heart?","choices":{"A":"He throws his saxophone on the bed and goes to sleep.","B":"He plays a melody with his eyes closed, feeling the music.","C":"He runs outside to find the bird and catch it.","D":"He writes a letter to his friend Ben about the bird."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate applies his realization by picking up his saxophone and playing a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently to feel the music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q010","read_aloud":"How does the bird\u0027s song change the way Hayate plays his saxophone? A. It makes him play harsh and loud notes like a sick moose. B. It helps him play fuller, richer notes that sound beautiful. C. It causes him to forget how to read his sheet music. D. It makes him stop playing because he is too scared.","excerpt":"\"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\"","stem":"How does the bird\u0027s song change the way Hayate plays his saxophone?","choices":{"A":"It makes him play harsh and loud notes like a sick moose.","B":"It helps him play fuller, richer notes that sound beautiful.","C":"It causes him to forget how to read his sheet music.","D":"It makes him stop playing because he is too scared."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Inspired by the bird, Hayate\u0027s notes become \"fuller and rich\" instead of harsh, showing that playing from the heart improves his music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q011","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"tactics\"? A. Accidents B. Strategies C. Mistakes D. Songs","excerpt":"\"Rostetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"tactics\"?","choices":{"A":"Accidents","B":"Strategies","C":"Mistakes","D":"Songs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tactics are planned strategies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rostetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What common lesson do both characters learn? A. Give up if something is hard. B. Persevere and believe in yourself. C. Only talent matters, not effort. D. Other people\u0027s opinions are all that count.","excerpt":"Both Rosetsu and Hayate face self-doubt and discouragement.","stem":"What common lesson do both characters learn?","choices":{"A":"Give up if something is hard.","B":"Persevere and believe in yourself.","C":"Only talent matters, not effort.","D":"Other people\u0027s opinions are all that count."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both learn to persist and trust themselves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Both Rosetsu and Hayate face self-doubt and discouragement."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What does Hayate\u0027s wish reveal about his goal? A. He wants to become a bird. B. He wants to play music as beautifully and freely as the bird sings. C. He wants to stop playing music. D. He wants to catch the bird.","excerpt":"\"HAYATE (to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird.\"","stem":"What does Hayate\u0027s wish reveal about his goal?","choices":{"A":"He wants to become a bird.","B":"He wants to play music as beautifully and freely as the bird sings.","C":"He wants to stop playing music.","D":"He wants to catch the bird."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He admires the bird\u0027s natural, beautiful singing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"HAYATE (to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Using context clues, what does \"loosen up\" mean? A. tighten your muscles B. relax and stop worrying C. play faster D. hold your instrument tighter","excerpt":"\"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\"","stem":"Using context clues, what does \"loosen up\" mean?","choices":{"A":"tighten your muscles","B":"relax and stop worrying","C":"play faster","D":"hold your instrument tighter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben tells Hayate to stop trying to be perfect and have fun. \"Loosen up\" means to relax and not worry so much.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Why is this the climax of The Hermit Thrush? A. It is the most boring part. B. It is the turning point where Hayate finally plays well. C. It is the end of the story. D. It is when Hayate quits.","excerpt":"\"(hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays. The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do.)\"","stem":"Why is this the climax of The Hermit Thrush?","choices":{"A":"It is the most boring part.","B":"It is the turning point where Hayate finally plays well.","C":"It is the end of the story.","D":"It is when Hayate quits."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is the climax because everything changes here. Hayate stops worrying and plays from his heart. His music finally sounds good.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays. The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What does the carp symbolize, or represent, in the story? A. A tasty meal B. Determination and never giving up C. A pet for Rosetsu D. The color blue","excerpt":"\"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\"","stem":"What does the carp symbolize, or represent, in the story?","choices":{"A":"A tasty meal","B":"Determination and never giving up","C":"A pet for Rosetsu","D":"The color blue"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp represents determination. It kept trying all day to break the ice and get the sembei. Rosetsu wants to be just as determined.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What inspired Hayate to write his own music? A. His teacher gave him homework. B. The hermit thrush and playing from his heart. C. He wanted to win a contest. D. His sister told him to.","excerpt":"\"mom. I didn\u0027t know you were writing your own music! hayate. Yeah, I just got inspired, I guess.\"","stem":"What inspired Hayate to write his own music?","choices":{"A":"His teacher gave him homework.","B":"The hermit thrush and playing from his heart.","C":"He wanted to win a contest.","D":"His sister told him to."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Earlier, Hayate heard the hermit thrush and decided to play what was in his heart. This inspiration led him to write his own song.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"mom. I didn\u0027t know you were writing your own music! hayate. Yeah, I just got inspired, I guess.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Why does Hayate blush? A. He is embarrassed because he played badly. B. He is proud but shy about the praise. C. He is angry at his dad. D. He is cold.","excerpt":"\"dad (smiling). That was great, hayate! What was that song? hayate. It\u0027s the song I started writing a couple of months ago. mom. It\u0027s beautiful! It sounded almost like a birdsong. hayate (blushing). Thanks. I call it \u0027Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Hayate blush?","choices":{"A":"He is embarrassed because he played badly.","B":"He is proud but shy about the praise.","C":"He is angry at his dad.","D":"He is cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate\u0027s parents are praising him. He is happy and proud, but also a little shy. Blushing shows he feels good but is modest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"dad (smiling). That was great, hayate! What was that song? hayate. It\u0027s the song I started writing a couple of months ago. mom. It\u0027s beautiful! It sounded almost like a birdsong. hayate (blushing). Thanks. I call it \u0027Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Which person is showing that they \"persevere\"? A. Someone who stops running in a race when they get a cramp. B. Someone who practices a difficult piece of music every single day for a year. C. Someone who copies someone else\u0027s homework to finish faster. D. Someone who chooses not to take a test they are afraid of.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Which person is showing that they \"persevere\"?","choices":{"A":"Someone who stops running in a race when they get a cramp.","B":"Someone who practices a difficult piece of music every single day for a year.","C":"Someone who copies someone else\u0027s homework to finish faster.","D":"Someone who chooses not to take a test they are afraid of."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Perseverance requires sustained effort despite difficulty or lack of immediate success.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this suggest about the family\u0027s reaction to Hayate\u0027s change? A. They are worried that he has changed too much. B. They are proud and happy to see him finally enjoying himself. C. They are confused because they didn\u0027t know he could play at all. D. They are disappointed that he did not play the old song.","excerpt":"\" wakana. You sounded good, hayate-and you looked happy for a change! mom. I didn\u0027t know you were writing your own music!\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this suggest about the family\u0027s reaction to Hayate\u0027s change?","choices":{"A":"They are worried that he has changed too much.","B":"They are proud and happy to see him finally enjoying himself.","C":"They are confused because they didn\u0027t know he could play at all.","D":"They are disappointed that he did not play the old song."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Their praise (\"sounded good,\" \"looked happy\") shows they support his new, more authentic approach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" wakana. You sounded good, hayate-and you looked happy for a change! mom. I didn\u0027t know you were writing your own music!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why did the author include this specific event in the story? A. To add an animal character to make the story more fun for children. B. To show Rosetsu what determination really looks like in nature. C. To help Rosetsu learn how to catch fish for his dinner. D. To prove that Rosetsu was dreaming the whole time.","excerpt":"\"A giant carp was jumping wildly... Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice...\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why did the author include this specific event in the story?","choices":{"A":"To add an animal character to make the story more fun for children.","B":"To show Rosetsu what determination really looks like in nature.","C":"To help Rosetsu learn how to catch fish for his dinner.","D":"To prove that Rosetsu was dreaming the whole time."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp is a mirror for Rosetsu; by watching the carp succeed, Rosetsu gains a new perspective on his own struggle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A giant carp was jumping wildly... Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Do you agree with Ben\u0027s advice? Why or why not? A. No, because you should always do exactly what your teacher tells you to do. B. Yes, because music is an expression of self, and being too obsessed with perfection can ruin the joy of it. C. No, because playing perfectly is the only reason to learn an instrument. D. Yes, because playing what you want is always easier than practicing.","excerpt":"\" ben. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Do you agree with Ben\u0027s advice? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because you should always do exactly what your teacher tells you to do.","B":"Yes, because music is an expression of self, and being too obsessed with perfection can ruin the joy of it.","C":"No, because playing perfectly is the only reason to learn an instrument.","D":"Yes, because playing what you want is always easier than practicing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While practice is important, music requires emotion and passion; obsessing over perfection often makes playing stiff and mechanical.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" ben. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp How would the story have ended differently if the teacher had just given Rosetsu the answer instead of explaining this? A. Rosetsu would have become a great painter immediately. B. Rosetsu might not have learned how to overcome his own self-doubt. C. The story would have been much longer. D. Rosetsu would have been angry at his teacher.","excerpt":"\"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp How would the story have ended differently if the teacher had just given Rosetsu the answer instead of explaining this?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu would have become a great painter immediately.","B":"Rosetsu might not have learned how to overcome his own self-doubt.","C":"The story would have been much longer.","D":"Rosetsu would have been angry at his teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By explaining why Rosetsu was failing, the teacher allowed him to gain the internal strength he needed to succeed on his own.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"inspired\" mean in this sentence? A. forced to do something against your will B. filled with the urge to create or do something C. confused about what to play next D. tired of practicing the same old song","excerpt":"\"hayate. Yeah, I just got inspired, I guess. (hayate grins as he sits down. mom winks at him. dad pats him on the back.)\"","stem":"What does the word \"inspired\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"forced to do something against your will","B":"filled with the urge to create or do something","C":"confused about what to play next","D":"tired of practicing the same old song"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate says he got \"inspired,\" which means he was filled with a new, creative urge to write and play his own music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. Yeah, I just got inspired, I guess. (hayate grins as he sits down. mom winks at him. dad pats him on the back.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What happens two months after the first family concert? A. Hayate refuses to play the saxophone for his family. B. Hayate plays his own song and looks relaxed and happy. C. Hayate quits the family concerts to play basketball. D. Hayate plays a harsh song that sounds like a sick moose.","excerpt":"\"Scene 2. It\u0027s Saturday, two months later. In the living room, the Watanabe family watches and listens while hayate plays his saxophone. He looks relaxed and happy he plays.\"","stem":"What happens two months after the first family concert?","choices":{"A":"Hayate refuses to play the saxophone for his family.","B":"Hayate plays his own song and looks relaxed and happy.","C":"Hayate quits the family concerts to play basketball.","D":"Hayate plays a harsh song that sounds like a sick moose."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that two months later, Hayate plays his saxophone looking relaxed and happy, showing his growth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scene 2. It\u0027s Saturday, two months later. In the living room, the Watanabe family watches and listens while hayate plays his saxophone. He looks relaxed and happy he plays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. What is the main message of the play\u0027s ending? A. You should always play music exactly as it is written on the page. B. Finding joy and playing from the heart leads to beautiful results. C. Family concerts are too stressful and should be canceled. D. Birds make better musicians than humans do.","excerpt":"mom. It\u0027s beautiful! It sounded almost like a birdsong. hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it","stem":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. What is the main message of the play\u0027s ending?","choices":{"A":"You should always play music exactly as it is written on the page.","B":"Finding joy and playing from the heart leads to beautiful results.","C":"Family concerts are too stressful and should be canceled.","D":"Birds make better musicians than humans do."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate\u0027s beautiful, birdsong-like performance shows that when he stopped stressing and played from his heart, he created something beautiful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: mom. It\u0027s beautiful! It sounded almost like a birdsong. hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Was Hayate\u0027s decision to play his own unfinished song a good one? A. No, because his family was confused and did not like it. B. Yes, because it allowed him to express his true feelings and improve. C. No, because he should have practiced the old song more. D. Yes, because it proved that he does not need to practice at all.","excerpt":"\"hayate. I\u0027ll go.(He stands.) I\u0027m going to perform a song I\u0027m writing. It\u0027s not finished yet.(He begins to play. His performance is heartfelt and animated, and he smiles and sways as he plays.\"","stem":"Was Hayate\u0027s decision to play his own unfinished song a good one?","choices":{"A":"No, because his family was confused and did not like it.","B":"Yes, because it allowed him to express his true feelings and improve.","C":"No, because he should have practiced the old song more.","D":"Yes, because it proved that he does not need to practice at all."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Playing his own song allowed Hayate to be \"heartfelt and animated,\" showing it was a good choice that helped him express himself and enjoy playing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. I\u0027ll go.(He stands.) I\u0027m going to perform a song I\u0027m writing. It\u0027s not finished yet.(He begins to play. His performance is heartfelt and animated, and he smiles and sways as he plays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. If Hayate were to write a second song based on his friend Ben\u0027s advice, what might he name it? A. \"The Sick Moose\u0027s Lament\" B. \"Ode to an Electronic Keyboard\" C. \"The Perfect Sheet Music\" D. \"The Stressful Saturday Concert\"","excerpt":"hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it","stem":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. If Hayate were to write a second song based on his friend Ben\u0027s advice, what might he name it?","choices":{"A":"\"The Sick Moose\u0027s Lament\"","B":"\"Ode to an Electronic Keyboard\"","C":"\"The Perfect Sheet Music\"","D":"\"The Stressful Saturday Concert\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben helped Hayate relax by talking about his electronic keyboard, so a song honoring that advice might be named \"Ode to an Electronic Keyboard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What caused Rosetsu\u0027s change? A. Getting a new brush B. Watching the carp\u0027s determination and his teacher\u0027s advice about doubts C. Winning a contest D. Moving to a new city","excerpt":"Compare Rosetsu\u0027s feelings of self-doubt (paragraph 37) with his later success (paragraph 54).","stem":"What caused Rosetsu\u0027s change?","choices":{"A":"Getting a new brush","B":"Watching the carp\u0027s determination and his teacher\u0027s advice about doubts","C":"Winning a contest","D":"Moving to a new city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp and Sensei Okyo\u0027s words inspired him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Rosetsu\u0027s feelings of self-doubt (paragraph 37) with his later success (paragraph 54)."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author use a bird as a teacher? A. To show that nature can teach us important lessons about creativity and joy. B. Because birds play saxophone. C. To make the story scary. D. To add a character who talks.","excerpt":"The playwright includes the hermit thrush\u0027s song as a turning point.","stem":"Why does the author use a bird as a teacher?","choices":{"A":"To show that nature can teach us important lessons about creativity and joy.","B":"Because birds play saxophone.","C":"To make the story scary.","D":"To add a character who talks."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Nature inspires Hayate to play freely.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The playwright includes the hermit thrush\u0027s song as a turning point."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think Sensei Okyo\u0027s words are helpful to Rosetsu? Why? A. No, because they are mean. B. Yes, because they remind Rosetsu that others believe in him. C. No, because they are confusing. D. Yes, because they tell him to quit.","excerpt":"\"Had you no talent, I wouldn\u0027t have accepted you in the first place. Did not Sensei Yutei give you his brush?\"","stem":"Do you think Sensei Okyo\u0027s words are helpful to Rosetsu? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because they are mean.","B":"Yes, because they remind Rosetsu that others believe in him.","C":"No, because they are confusing.","D":"Yes, because they tell him to quit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The words remind Rosetsu of his potential.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Had you no talent, I wouldn\u0027t have accepted you in the first place. Did not Sensei Yutei give you his brush?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q014","read_aloud":"If the play had a scene where Hayate teaches another struggling student, what advice would he give? A. \"Give up if it\u0027s hard.\" B. \"Play for yourself and find joy in the music.\" C. \"Only practice songs you hate.\" D. \"Listen to your sister\u0027s jokes.\"","excerpt":"The whole drama.","stem":"If the play had a scene where Hayate teaches another struggling student, what advice would he give?","choices":{"A":"\"Give up if it\u0027s hard.\"","B":"\"Play for yourself and find joy in the music.\"","C":"\"Only practice songs you hate.\"","D":"\"Listen to your sister\u0027s jokes.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"That\u0027s what Hayate learned from the bird.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole drama."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"persevere\"? A. continue B. quit C. try D. work","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"persevere\"?","choices":{"A":"continue","B":"quit","C":"try","D":"work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Persevere\" means to keep going. The opposite is \"quit,\" which means to stop and give up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the word \"glorious\"? A. To show the day was sunny B. To show how special and wonderful this day was for Rosetsu C. To describe the color of the paint D. To make the story longer","excerpt":"\"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the word \"glorious\"?","choices":{"A":"To show the day was sunny","B":"To show how special and wonderful this day was for Rosetsu","C":"To describe the color of the paint","D":"To make the story longer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Glorious\" means magnificent and wonderful. The author uses this word to show that this day was very special because Rosetsu had worked so hard for it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush. His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q017","read_aloud":"How are the themes of these two texts similar? A. Both are about cooking. B. Both show that believing in yourself leads to success. C. Both are about animals as pets. D. Both show that quitting is the best choice.","excerpt":"From The Carp: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"How are the themes of these two texts similar?","choices":{"A":"Both are about cooking.","B":"Both show that believing in yourself leads to success.","C":"Both are about animals as pets.","D":"Both show that quitting is the best choice."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu believes in himself and keeps trying. Hayate believes in his own feelings and plays from his heart. Both texts show that self-belief is important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From The Carp: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q018","read_aloud":"the other student said. \"I think he\u0027s disappointed that Rosetsu will never be great. Were the other students right about Rosetsu? Use evidence. A. Yes, because Rosetsu had no talent. B. No, because Sensei Okyo believed in Rosetsu and knew he could be great. C. Yes, because Rosetsu quit and never came back. D. No, because Rosetsu was the teacher\u0027s favorite.","excerpt":"Sensei Okyo is very hard on Rosetsu-much harder than he is on the rest of us,","stem":"the other student said. \"I think he\u0027s disappointed that Rosetsu will never be great. Were the other students right about Rosetsu? Use evidence.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because Rosetsu had no talent.","B":"No, because Sensei Okyo believed in Rosetsu and knew he could be great.","C":"Yes, because Rosetsu quit and never came back.","D":"No, because Rosetsu was the teacher\u0027s favorite."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The students were wrong. Sensei Okyo was hard on Rosetsu because he saw his potential. He told Rosetsu he had talent and just needed to believe in himself.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sensei Okyo is very hard on Rosetsu-much harder than he is on the rest of us,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Is Hayate correct that music comes naturally to his family? A. Yes, they were born knowing how to play. B. No, practice probably helped them get better too. C. Yes, Hayate is the only one who needs lessons. D. No, they use magic to play well.","excerpt":"\"hayate. I don\u0027t see you, dad, or wakana struggling. You all play your instruments perfectly, and it seems to come to you naturally.\"","stem":"Is Hayate correct that music comes naturally to his family?","choices":{"A":"Yes, they were born knowing how to play.","B":"No, practice probably helped them get better too.","C":"Yes, Hayate is the only one who needs lessons.","D":"No, they use magic to play well."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate thinks his family is naturally perfect, but they probably practiced too. The story shows that everyone struggles sometimes, even if we do not see it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. I don\u0027t see you, dad, or wakana struggling. You all play your instruments perfectly, and it seems to come to you naturally.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. If you are \"conscientious\" about your chores, how do you do them? A. You do them quickly and skip the hard parts. B. You do them carefully, making sure you don\u0027t miss anything. C. You ask someone else to finish them for you. D. You only do them when someone is watching.","excerpt":"No,","stem":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. If you are \"conscientious\" about your chores, how do you do them?","choices":{"A":"You do them quickly and skip the hard parts.","B":"You do them carefully, making sure you don\u0027t miss anything.","C":"You ask someone else to finish them for you.","D":"You only do them when someone is watching."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Conscientious people take their responsibilities seriously and do their best.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana mention the quote about the bird? A. She likes showing off how smart she is. B. She realizes Hayate is suffering from trying too hard to please others and wants to guide him. C. She wants to play a game with Hayate. D. She is trying to distract Hayate so she can have the saxophone.","excerpt":"\" hayate. What? wakana. Just something I read once.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why does Wakana mention the quote about the bird?","choices":{"A":"She likes showing off how smart she is.","B":"She realizes Hayate is suffering from trying too hard to please others and wants to guide him.","C":"She wants to play a game with Hayate.","D":"She is trying to distract Hayate so she can have the saxophone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She sees her brother\u0027s distress and offers the quote to provide him with a new, healthier perspective on music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \" hayate. What? wakana. Just something I read once.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why does the author start the story with this feeling of joy? A. To make the ending feel sadder when he fails. B. To show how far he has to fall before he can truly learn what he needs. C. To tell us that the journey was easy for him. D. To warn the reader that he will be disappointed.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu had a long walk ahead of him, but his heart was filled with joy and excitement. \u0027This is the way my future lies!\u0027 he said to himself.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why does the author start the story with this feeling of joy?","choices":{"A":"To make the ending feel sadder when he fails.","B":"To show how far he has to fall before he can truly learn what he needs.","C":"To tell us that the journey was easy for him.","D":"To warn the reader that he will be disappointed."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Starting at a point of high optimism creates a stronger contrast with the later struggles, highlighting the growth he must go through to succeed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu had a long walk ahead of him, but his heart was filled with joy and excitement. \u0027This is the way my future lies!\u0027 he said to himself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does throwing the music aside show about Hayate\u0027s emotional state? A. He is bored with the song. B. He is completely overwhelmed by frustration and has lost control. C. He is making space to practice a different song. D. He is happy that he finished practicing.","excerpt":"\"Scene 2 It\u0027s Monday. hayate is practicing in his room, staring at his sheet music. His saxophone wails. He throws the music aside.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does throwing the music aside show about Hayate\u0027s emotional state?","choices":{"A":"He is bored with the song.","B":"He is completely overwhelmed by frustration and has lost control.","C":"He is making space to practice a different song.","D":"He is happy that he finished practicing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Throwing things in anger or despair is a classic sign of someone having reached their breaking point emotionally.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scene 2 It\u0027s Monday. hayate is practicing in his room, staring at his sheet music. His saxophone wails. He throws the music aside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Did not Sensei Yutei give you his brush?\" \"Yes!\" Rosetsu said. He smiled and bowed. \"Thank you, sensei. I shall do my best every day from now on.... Why is this moment important for Rosetsu\u0027s development as an artist? A. It gives him permission to stop working hard. B. It proves that he has finally accepted his talent and is ready to work for his goals. C. It makes him richer than his classmates. D. It makes him the teacher instead of the student.","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Selection: The Carp Did not Sensei Yutei give you his brush?\" \"Yes!\" Rosetsu said. He smiled and bowed. \"Thank you, sensei. I shall do my best every day from now on.... Why is this moment important for Rosetsu\u0027s development as an artist?","choices":{"A":"It gives him permission to stop working hard.","B":"It proves that he has finally accepted his talent and is ready to work for his goals.","C":"It makes him richer than his classmates.","D":"It makes him the teacher instead of the student."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By finally accepting the teacher\u0027s validation and moving past his doubt, he shifts his focus from \"fear of failure\" to \"joy of creation.\"","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"legend\" mean in this context? A. a true story about a modern scientist B. a traditional story based on a historical hero C. a play written to be performed on a stage D. a poem about a bird singing in a tree","excerpt":"\"A legend is a type of folktale based on a real cultural hero but with made-up parts. It includes some real people and events, exaggerated or made-up details, and stories that are linked to a historical time.\"","stem":"What does the word \"legend\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"a true story about a modern scientist","B":"a traditional story based on a historical hero","C":"a play written to be performed on a stage","D":"a poem about a bird singing in a tree"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a legend as a traditional story or folktale based on a real cultural hero from history, with some made-up parts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A legend is a type of folktale based on a real cultural hero but with made-up parts. It includes some real people and events, exaggerated or made-up details, and stories that are linked to a historical time.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q007","read_aloud":"features Rosetsu, a boy who wants to be a great painter. \"The Hermit Thrush\" features Hayate, a boy who struggles to play the saxophone. How are Rosetsu and Hayate similar? A. They both live in ancient Japan and study with a master. B. They both struggle with self-doubt and want to improve their art. C. They both have sisters who make fun of their artwork. D. They both quit their hobbies to play basketball.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"features Rosetsu, a boy who wants to be a great painter. \"The Hermit Thrush\" features Hayate, a boy who struggles to play the saxophone. How are Rosetsu and Hayate similar?","choices":{"A":"They both live in ancient Japan and study with a master.","B":"They both struggle with self-doubt and want to improve their art.","C":"They both have sisters who make fun of their artwork.","D":"They both quit their hobbies to play basketball."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both characters face internal struggles with their confidence and work hard to overcome their doubts to improve their artistic skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q008","read_aloud":"takes place in ancient Japan, with Rosetsu walking to Kyoto and studying at a traditional school. \"The Hermit Thrush\" takes place in a modern home in Los Angeles, California. How do the settings of the two stories differ? A. One is set in ancient Japan, while the other is set in modern California. B. One is set in a cold snowy forest, while the other is set in a hot desert. C. One is set in a busy city, while the other is set on a quiet farm. D. One is set in a school, while the other is set in a hospital.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"takes place in ancient Japan, with Rosetsu walking to Kyoto and studying at a traditional school. \"The Hermit Thrush\" takes place in a modern home in Los Angeles, California. How do the settings of the two stories differ?","choices":{"A":"One is set in ancient Japan, while the other is set in modern California.","B":"One is set in a cold snowy forest, while the other is set in a hot desert.","C":"One is set in a busy city, while the other is set on a quiet farm.","D":"One is set in a school, while the other is set in a hospital."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"The Carp\" is a legend set in ancient Japan, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a modern play set in a home in Los Angeles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q009","read_aloud":"shows Rosetsu learning from a determined carp in nature. \"The Hermit Thrush\" shows Hayate learning from a beautiful bird song in nature. How do both characters overcome their doubts? A. They both read books about famous artists and musicians. B. They both find inspiration in nature and realize they must believe in themselves. C. They both ask their parents for help with their homework. D. They both move to a new city to start over.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"shows Rosetsu learning from a determined carp in nature. \"The Hermit Thrush\" shows Hayate learning from a beautiful bird song in nature. How do both characters overcome their doubts?","choices":{"A":"They both read books about famous artists and musicians.","B":"They both find inspiration in nature and realize they must believe in themselves.","C":"They both ask their parents for help with their homework.","D":"They both move to a new city to start over."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu is inspired by a carp\u0027s determination, and Hayate is inspired by a bird\u0027s natural song, helping both realize they must play/paint from the heart and believe in themselves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q010","read_aloud":"is a legend about a boy who becomes a great painter. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play about a boy who learns to enjoy playing music. Which character\u0027s journey do you find more inspiring, and why? A. Rosetsu, because he ran away into the snow and gave up on his dream. B. Hayate, because he quit playing the saxophone to play the piano. C. Rosetsu, because he persevered through years of hard work and self-doubt to achieve his dream. D. Hayate, because he never practiced and just played whatever he wanted.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"is a legend about a boy who becomes a great painter. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play about a boy who learns to enjoy playing music. Which character\u0027s journey do you find more inspiring, and why?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu, because he ran away into the snow and gave up on his dream.","B":"Hayate, because he quit playing the saxophone to play the piano.","C":"Rosetsu, because he persevered through years of hard work and self-doubt to achieve his dream.","D":"Hayate, because he never practiced and just played whatever he wanted."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Rosetsu\u0027s journey is inspiring because he faced years of discouragement but used the carp\u0027s lesson to persevere and finally achieve his dream of becoming a great painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Is this element realistic or legendary? Why? A. Realistic, because it happens every day. B. Legendary, because it involves magic and a mysterious wise figure. C. Realistic, because brushes are real. D. Legendary, because it is boring.","excerpt":"The stranger (Sensei Yutei) appears suddenly and gives Rosetsu a magical brush.","stem":"Is this element realistic or legendary? Why?","choices":{"A":"Realistic, because it happens every day.","B":"Legendary, because it involves magic and a mysterious wise figure.","C":"Realistic, because brushes are real.","D":"Legendary, because it is boring."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Legends often have supernatural or mysterious elements.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The stranger (Sensei Yutei) appears suddenly and gives Rosetsu a magical brush."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q012","read_aloud":"How does this ending show a resolution? A. Hayate quits music. B. Hayate has found his own voice and confidence. C. Hayate moves away. D. The family stops having concerts.","excerpt":"The drama ends with Hayate playing his own song, \"Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\"","stem":"How does this ending show a resolution?","choices":{"A":"Hayate quits music.","B":"Hayate has found his own voice and confidence.","C":"Hayate moves away.","D":"The family stops having concerts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He is now confident and creative.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The drama ends with Hayate playing his own song, \"Ode to a Hermit Thrush.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think the carp is a good symbol for Rosetsu\u0027s goal? Why? A. No, because carp are not artists. B. Yes, because the carp\u0027s persistence models the determination Rosetsu needs. C. No, because carp are fish. D. Yes, because carp are easy to catch.","excerpt":"\"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp.\"","stem":"Do you think the carp is a good symbol for Rosetsu\u0027s goal? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because carp are not artists.","B":"Yes, because the carp\u0027s persistence models the determination Rosetsu needs.","C":"No, because carp are fish.","D":"Yes, because carp are easy to catch."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp never gives up, just as Rosetsu must not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"panic\"? A. calm B. fear and worry C. happiness D. sleepiness","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu looked around in a panic until his eyes landed on a nearby tree. He broke off a twig and picked off a few berries, mashing and mixing them to form a kind of ink.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"panic\"?","choices":{"A":"calm","B":"fear and worry","C":"happiness","D":"sleepiness"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Panic\" means sudden fear and worry. Rosetsu was nervous because the stranger challenged him to paint without a brush.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu looked around in a panic until his eyes landed on a nearby tree. He broke off a twig and picked off a few berries, mashing and mixing them to form a kind of ink.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the author start with \"Long ago\"? A. To show this is a made-up story from the past B. To tell us what time it is now C. To make the story scary D. To introduce a science lesson","excerpt":"\"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\"","stem":"Why does the author start with \"Long ago\"?","choices":{"A":"To show this is a made-up story from the past","B":"To tell us what time it is now","C":"To make the story scary","D":"To introduce a science lesson"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Legends often start with \"Long ago\" to show they are old stories passed down through time. This is a characteristic of the legend genre.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why does Hayate sound good when he is \"messing around\"? A. He is not worried about being perfect. B. He practices more when he messes around. C. The saxophone is broken. D. Ben is lying to him.","excerpt":"\"(hayate starts quietly playing a tune he made up.) ben. Whoa-that\u0027s good! hayate. I\u0027m just messing around. That\u0027s the only time I sound okay.\"","stem":"Why does Hayate sound good when he is \"messing around\"?","choices":{"A":"He is not worried about being perfect.","B":"He practices more when he messes around.","C":"The saxophone is broken.","D":"Ben is lying to him."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"When Hayate is just having fun, he relaxes. He is not stressed about being perfect, so his music sounds natural and good.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate starts quietly playing a tune he made up.) ben. Whoa-that\u0027s good! hayate. I\u0027m just messing around. That\u0027s the only time I sound okay.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q017","read_aloud":"Do you think this advice applies to things other than painting? Why? A. No, it only works for painters. B. Yes, believing in yourself helps in sports, music, school, and many things. C. No, it is bad advice for everyone. D. Yes, but only for adults.","excerpt":"\"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"","stem":"Do you think this advice applies to things other than painting? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, it only works for painters.","B":"Yes, believing in yourself helps in sports, music, school, and many things.","C":"No, it is bad advice for everyone.","D":"Yes, but only for adults."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This advice applies to many areas of life. Whether you play sports, do music, or take a test, believing in yourself helps you succeed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q018","read_aloud":"How might the story change if Hayate never heard the hermit thrush? A. He would have quit playing saxophone. B. He would have become famous immediately. C. His sister would have taught him. D. He would have bought a new instrument.","excerpt":"From The Hermit Thrush: \"The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\"","stem":"How might the story change if Hayate never heard the hermit thrush?","choices":{"A":"He would have quit playing saxophone.","B":"He would have become famous immediately.","C":"His sister would have taught him.","D":"He would have bought a new instrument."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The hermit thrush inspired Hayate to play from his heart. Without that moment, he might have kept struggling and eventually given up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From The Hermit Thrush: \"The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Which is a synonym for the word \"quell\" in this sentence? A. Start B. Calm C. Increase D. Excite","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Which is a synonym for the word \"quell\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Start","B":"Calm","C":"Increase","D":"Excite"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To quell doubts is to calm or silence them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this indicate about how Hayate has integrated his experience with nature into his music? A. He is stealing the bird\u0027s song. B. He has stopped practicing and is just playing random sounds. C. He has learned to draw inspiration from the natural world to create his own unique art. D. He is still not good enough to create his own melodies.","excerpt":"\"The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this indicate about how Hayate has integrated his experience with nature into his music?","choices":{"A":"He is stealing the bird\u0027s song.","B":"He has stopped practicing and is just playing random sounds.","C":"He has learned to draw inspiration from the natural world to create his own unique art.","D":"He is still not good enough to create his own melodies."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The echo shows that he has transitioned from trying to memorize someone else\u0027s notes to creating art that is inspired by his own observations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp What is the author\u0027s purpose in using this jump in time? A. To show that Rosetsu was not actually a good student. B. To illustrate that real skill takes a long time and does not happen overnight. C. To suggest that the sensei was not a good teacher. D. To show that Rosetsu was lazy during those three years.","excerpt":"\"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp What is the author\u0027s purpose in using this jump in time?","choices":{"A":"To show that Rosetsu was not actually a good student.","B":"To illustrate that real skill takes a long time and does not happen overnight.","C":"To suggest that the sensei was not a good teacher.","D":"To show that Rosetsu was lazy during those three years."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Skipping over time emphasizes that success is a gradual, difficult process rather than a quick fix.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Three years passed quickly. Rosetsu worked and studied, but he didn\u0027t make as much progress as he\u0027d like.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why do you think the author chose to have Hayate hit \"a few off notes\" instead of playing perfectly? A. To make the audience laugh at him. B. To show that even \"great\" or authentic artists are human and not always perfect. C. To show that he still isn\u0027t ready to play for an audience. D. To show that he has forgotten how to play.","excerpt":"\"He hits a few off notes, but mostly he plays well.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why do you think the author chose to have Hayate hit \"a few off notes\" instead of playing perfectly?","choices":{"A":"To make the audience laugh at him.","B":"To show that even \"great\" or authentic artists are human and not always perfect.","C":"To show that he still isn\u0027t ready to play for an audience.","D":"To show that he has forgotten how to play."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This choice makes Hayate\u0027s success feel more real and attainable; the goal is expression, not robotic perfection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He hits a few off notes, but mostly he plays well.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so. Imagine you are giving advice to someone who is struggling with something new, like a sport or instrument. Based on the lesson in this story, what would you say to them? A. \"If it\u0027s hard, just quit so you don\u0027t feel bad.\" B. \"You should only work hard if you\u0027re the best from the start.\" C. \"It is normal to feel doubt, but keep trying and believe that your effort will eventually lead to progress.\" D. \"You need to find a different activity because you\u0027re obviously not talented.\"","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Selection: The Carp You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so. Imagine you are giving advice to someone who is struggling with something new, like a sport or instrument. Based on the lesson in this story, what would you say to them?","choices":{"A":"\"If it\u0027s hard, just quit so you don\u0027t feel bad.\"","B":"\"You should only work hard if you\u0027re the best from the start.\"","C":"\"It is normal to feel doubt, but keep trying and believe that your effort will eventually lead to progress.\"","D":"\"You need to find a different activity because you\u0027re obviously not talented.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This answer reflects the central theme of both stories: persistent effort and self-belief are what lead to growth and success. To complete the assessment series as requested, here is the Comprehensive Test. This test covers both \"The Carp\" and \"The Hermit Thrush,\" focusing on themes, comprehension, and vocabulary across the entire scope of both selections.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"dialogue\" mean in this context? A. the instructions telling characters how to move B. the lines that the characters speak to each other C. the major divisions of a play into acts D. the costumes the actors wear on stage","excerpt":"\"A drama, or play, is written to be performed and to entertain. A drama tells the story through character tags, or the names of who is speaking, and dialogue, or the lines the characters speak.\"","stem":"What does the word \"dialogue\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"the instructions telling characters how to move","B":"the lines that the characters speak to each other","C":"the major divisions of a play into acts","D":"the costumes the actors wear on stage"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines dialogue as \"the lines the characters speak,\" which is how the story is told in a drama.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A drama, or play, is written to be performed and to entertain. A drama tells the story through character tags, or the names of who is speaking, and dialogue, or the lines the characters speak.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q007","read_aloud":"is written in paragraphs as a traditional story. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is written with character names like \"hayate.\" and \"mom.\" followed by their lines. How is \"The Carp\" structured differently from \"The Hermit Thrush\"? A. \"The Carp\" is a poem, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a news article. B. \"The Carp\" is a traditional story, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play script. C. \"The Carp\" is written in the first person, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a legend. D. \"The Carp\" is a comic book, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a diary.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"is written in paragraphs as a traditional story. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is written with character names like \"hayate.\" and \"mom.\" followed by their lines. How is \"The Carp\" structured differently from \"The Hermit Thrush\"?","choices":{"A":"\"The Carp\" is a poem, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a news article.","B":"\"The Carp\" is a traditional story, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play script.","C":"\"The Carp\" is written in the first person, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a legend.","D":"\"The Carp\" is a comic book, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a diary."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"The Carp\" is written as a traditional narrative story, while \"The Hermit Thrush\" is structured as a drama or play script with character tags and dialogue.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q008","read_aloud":"What text feature shows that \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play? A. the use of rhyming words at the end of each line B. the inclusion of stage directions and character tags C. the presence of chapters and a table of contents D. the use of illustrations and captions on every page","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"What text feature shows that \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a play?","choices":{"A":"the use of rhyming words at the end of each line","B":"the inclusion of stage directions and character tags","C":"the presence of chapters and a table of contents","D":"the use of illustrations and captions on every page"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt includes character tags (mom, da d) and descriptions of the setting and actions, which are stage directions typical of a play script.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q009","read_aloud":"uses descriptive paragraphs to show Rosetsu\u0027s feelings. \"The Hermit Thrush\" uses dialogue to show Hayate\u0027s frustration. Which format do you think is more effective for telling these stories? A. The legend format, because it allows the author to describe the beautiful paintings in detail. B. The play format, because it allows the audience to hear the characters\u0027 emotions directly through their words. C. Both formats are effective because they use different tools to help the reader connect with the characters\u0027 struggles. D. Neither format is effective because both stories are too boring to read.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"uses descriptive paragraphs to show Rosetsu\u0027s feelings. \"The Hermit Thrush\" uses dialogue to show Hayate\u0027s frustration. Which format do you think is more effective for telling these stories?","choices":{"A":"The legend format, because it allows the author to describe the beautiful paintings in detail.","B":"The play format, because it allows the audience to hear the characters\u0027 emotions directly through their words.","C":"Both formats are effective because they use different tools to help the reader connect with the characters\u0027 struggles.","D":"Neither format is effective because both stories are too boring to read."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Both formats are effective; the legend uses rich descriptions to show Rosetsu\u0027s journey, while the play uses dialogue to let the audience hear Hayate\u0027s feelings directly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q010","read_aloud":"is a legend. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a drama. If you were to adapt \"The Carp\" into a play, what two elements would you need to add? A. stage directions and character tags for dialogue B. rhyming stanzas and a rhyme scheme C. a narrator who reads the story from a book D. photographs of real painters and their brushes","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"is a legend. \"The Hermit Thrush\" is a drama. If you were to adapt \"The Carp\" into a play, what two elements would you need to add?","choices":{"A":"stage directions and character tags for dialogue","B":"rhyming stanzas and a rhyme scheme","C":"a narrator who reads the story from a book","D":"photographs of real painters and their brushes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To turn a traditional story into a play, you would need to add stage directions to show actions and character tags to show who is speaking the dialogue.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q011","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"persistent\"? A. Quitting B. Giving up C. Tenacious; continuing firmly D. Lazy","excerpt":"\"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"persistent\"?","choices":{"A":"Quitting","B":"Giving up","C":"Tenacious; continuing firmly","D":"Lazy"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Persistent means continuing despite difficulty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Which character\u0027s struggle do you relate to more? Why? A. Rosetsu, because of pressure to prove talent. B. Hayate, because of comparing himself to family. C. Both are relatable. D. Neither is relatable.","excerpt":"Both texts.","stem":"Which character\u0027s struggle do you relate to more? Why?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu, because of pressure to prove talent.","B":"Hayate, because of comparing himself to family.","C":"Both are relatable.","D":"Neither is relatable."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Both struggles are common and understandable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Both texts."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"supportive\"? A. helpful B. encouraging C. discouraging D. kind","excerpt":"\"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"supportive\"?","choices":{"A":"helpful","B":"encouraging","C":"discouraging","D":"kind"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Supportive\" means encouraging and helpful. The opposite is \"discouraging,\" which means to make someone feel bad about trying.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Why is this a good ending for a legend? A. It is sad and disappointing. B. It shows the hero achieving greatness, which legends often do. C. It leaves the reader confused. D. It introduces a new problem.","excerpt":"\"And so it was that Rosetsu became not only one of Sensei Okyo\u0027s best pupils, but one of Japan\u0027s greatest painters of all time.\"","stem":"Why is this a good ending for a legend?","choices":{"A":"It is sad and disappointing.","B":"It shows the hero achieving greatness, which legends often do.","C":"It leaves the reader confused.","D":"It introduces a new problem."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Legends often tell about heroes who become great. This ending shows Rosetsu achieving his dream, which fits the legend genre perfectly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"And so it was that Rosetsu became not only one of Sensei Okyo\u0027s best pupils, but one of Japan\u0027s greatest painters of all time.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the playwright return to Saturday for Act 3? A. To show that one week has passed B. To show the family at another weekly concert, so we can see Hayate\u0027s progress C. To make the play shorter D. To introduce new characters","excerpt":"\"ACT 3, Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday. mom, dad, wakana, and hayate sit in the living room.\"","stem":"Why does the playwright return to Saturday for Act 3?","choices":{"A":"To show that one week has passed","B":"To show the family at another weekly concert, so we can see Hayate\u0027s progress","C":"To make the play shorter","D":"To introduce new characters"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Act 1 was also on Saturday at the weekly concert. Returning to Saturday lets us compare Hayate\u0027s playing from before and after his growth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 3, Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday. mom, dad, wakana, and hayate sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Was Rosetsu right to follow his dream? Use evidence from the text. A. No, because he should have stayed home. B. Yes, because even though he struggled, he became a great painter. C. No, because he failed at art school. D. Yes, because it was easy and he never had problems.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu had a long walk ahead of him, but his heart was filled with joy and excitement. \u0027This is the way my future lies!\u0027\"","stem":"Was Rosetsu right to follow his dream? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because he should have stayed home.","B":"Yes, because even though he struggled, he became a great painter.","C":"No, because he failed at art school.","D":"Yes, because it was easy and he never had problems."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu faced many struggles and doubts, but he kept going. In the end, he became one of Japan\u0027s greatest painters. Following his dream was worth it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu had a long walk ahead of him, but his heart was filled with joy and excitement. \u0027This is the way my future lies!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q017","read_aloud":"If Rosetsu met Hayate, what advice might Rosetsu give him? A. \"Quit music and become a painter instead.\" B. \"Keep practicing and believe in yourself, even when it is hard.\" C. \"Never listen to your family.\" D. \"Only play music you have memorized.\"","excerpt":"From both texts.","stem":"If Rosetsu met Hayate, what advice might Rosetsu give him?","choices":{"A":"\"Quit music and become a painter instead.\"","B":"\"Keep practicing and believe in yourself, even when it is hard.\"","C":"\"Never listen to your family.\"","D":"\"Only play music you have memorized.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu learned to persevere and believe in himself. He would tell Hayate to keep trying and not give up, just like the carp taught him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From both texts."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. the way a person thinks and feels about something B. the type of musical instrument a person plays C. the amount of time spent practicing a song D. the speed at which a person reads sheet music","excerpt":"\"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"the way a person thinks and feels about something","B":"the type of musical instrument a person plays","C":"the amount of time spent practicing a song","D":"the speed at which a person reads sheet music"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ben is talking about Hayate\u0027s negative \"attitude,\" which refers to the way he is thinking and feeling about his ability to play the saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q001","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp If a person wants to \"quell\" their anxiety before a performance, what are they trying to do? A. Make their anxiety stronger so they perform better. B. Calm their feelings and stop the anxiety. C. Share their anxiety with the audience. D. Ignore the performance entirely.","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp If a person wants to \"quell\" their anxiety before a performance, what are they trying to do?","choices":{"A":"Make their anxiety stronger so they perform better.","B":"Calm their feelings and stop the anxiety.","C":"Share their anxiety with the audience.","D":"Ignore the performance entirely."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To \"quell\" means to put an end to or suppress something, such as feelings of doubt or anxiety.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q002","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. Why does the teacher call Rosetsu a \"conscientious\" worker? A. Because Rosetsu is fast and careless. B. Because Rosetsu is careful, hard-working, and thorough. C. Because Rosetsu works only when he feels like it. D. Because Rosetsu is easily distracted by others.","excerpt":"No,","stem":"Selection: The Carp the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. Why does the teacher call Rosetsu a \"conscientious\" worker?","choices":{"A":"Because Rosetsu is fast and careless.","B":"Because Rosetsu is careful, hard-working, and thorough.","C":"Because Rosetsu works only when he feels like it.","D":"Because Rosetsu is easily distracted by others."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A conscientious person is dedicated and takes their work seriously, which accurately describes Rosetsu\u0027s effort to learn painting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q003","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Which of these is an example of someone choosing to \"persevere\"? A. A student who studies for a math test every night despite finding it very difficult. B. A student who asks their teacher to let them skip the math test. C. A student who forgets to study and blames the teacher for their bad grade. D. A student who decides to do something else because the math is too hard.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Which of these is an example of someone choosing to \"persevere\"?","choices":{"A":"A student who studies for a math test every night despite finding it very difficult.","B":"A student who asks their teacher to let them skip the math test.","C":"A student who forgets to study and blames the teacher for their bad grade.","D":"A student who decides to do something else because the math is too hard."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To persevere is to keep trying and working toward a goal even when faced with difficulties.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ll ask Sensei Okyo how I can become worthy of Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush, and then I\u0027ll persevere until I gain my prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q004","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this change in Hayate\u0027s playing suggest about his growth as a musician? A. He is just copying a bird instead of learning music. B. He has finally found a way to let nature and his own feelings inspire his music. C. He has become so tired that he is starting to hear things. D. He is still unable to play his own music properly.","excerpt":"\"The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush What does this change in Hayate\u0027s playing suggest about his growth as a musician?","choices":{"A":"He is just copying a bird instead of learning music.","B":"He has finally found a way to let nature and his own feelings inspire his music.","C":"He has become so tired that he is starting to hear things.","D":"He is still unable to play his own music properly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By incorporating the song of the bird, Hayate shows he is moving away from mechanical perfection and toward genuine artistic expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q005","read_aloud":"Selection: Both How are the struggles of Rosetsu (\"The Carp\") and Hayate (\"The Hermit Thrush\") similar? A. Both characters are forced to change their careers by their parents. B. Both characters feel held back by their own internal doubts and the pressure to be perfect. C. Both characters hate what they are doing and want to move to a different country. D. Both characters have supportive teachers who never criticize them.","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Selection: Both How are the struggles of Rosetsu (\"The Carp\") and Hayate (\"The Hermit Thrush\") similar?","choices":{"A":"Both characters are forced to change their careers by their parents.","B":"Both characters feel held back by their own internal doubts and the pressure to be perfect.","C":"Both characters hate what they are doing and want to move to a different country.","D":"Both characters have supportive teachers who never criticize them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both stories center on characters who are talented but struggle because they are too focused on the pressure to succeed or meet external expectations rather than believing in themselves.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q006","read_aloud":"Selection: Both What is a major theme shared by both \"The Carp\" and \"The Hermit Thrush\"? A. If you don\u0027t succeed at first, you should try a different activity. B. Success is always easy if you have the right teacher. C. True mastery and happiness come from believing in yourself and persistently following your own passion. D. It is more important to please your parents than to enjoy your work.","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Selection: Both What is a major theme shared by both \"The Carp\" and \"The Hermit Thrush\"?","choices":{"A":"If you don\u0027t succeed at first, you should try a different activity.","B":"Success is always easy if you have the right teacher.","C":"True mastery and happiness come from believing in yourself and persistently following your own passion.","D":"It is more important to please your parents than to enjoy your work."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Both characters reach their breakthrough only when they stop worrying about perfection/others\u0027 opinions and start focusing on their internal passion and effort.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q007","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. According to the quote shared by Wakana, why does a bird sing? A. Because it wants other birds to like its song. B. Because it is happy. C. Because it is trying to be perfect. D. Because it is forced to by its parents.","excerpt":"You should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy. According to the quote shared by Wakana, why does a bird sing?","choices":{"A":"Because it wants other birds to like its song.","B":"Because it is happy.","C":"Because it is trying to be perfect.","D":"Because it is forced to by its parents."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explicitly states that the bird sings because it is happy, not to please others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q008","read_aloud":"Selection: The Carp Why does Rosetsu watch the carp? A. He is hungry and wants to catch it for lunch. B. He is bored and has nothing else to do. C. He observes its struggle and learns a lesson about persistence from it. D. He wants to see if the fish can break the ice quickly.","excerpt":"\"Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize.\"","stem":"Selection: The Carp Why does Rosetsu watch the carp?","choices":{"A":"He is hungry and wants to catch it for lunch.","B":"He is bored and has nothing else to do.","C":"He observes its struggle and learns a lesson about persistence from it.","D":"He wants to see if the fish can break the ice quickly."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Rosetsu watches the fish\u0027s repeated attempts and realizes that steady, persistent effort is how the fish (and he) can reach their goals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Each time the fish jumped, it broke a tiny bit of the ice and moved closer to its prize.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q009","read_aloud":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is it important that Hayate still hits \"a few off notes\"? A. To show that he is still a bad musician. B. To show that he has given up on trying. C. To show that being authentic and feeling the music is more important than being perfect. D. To show that he should go back to practicing the old way.","excerpt":"\"He hits a few off notes, but mostly he plays well.\"","stem":"Selection: The Hermit Thrush Why is it important that Hayate still hits \"a few off notes\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that he is still a bad musician.","B":"To show that he has given up on trying.","C":"To show that being authentic and feeling the music is more important than being perfect.","D":"To show that he should go back to practicing the old way."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author includes the \"off notes\" to prove that Hayate has stopped obsessing over perfection, which was what was originally keeping him from playing well.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He hits a few off notes, but mostly he plays well.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q010","read_aloud":"Selection: Both If you were the teacher for both Rosetsu and Hayate, what is one piece of advice you would give them to help them keep improving? A. \"Don\u0027t ever make a mistake, or you will fail.\" B. \"Focus on how your audience feels, not on how you feel.\" C. \"It is okay to struggle; keep practicing with heart, and learn from every mistake you make.\" D. \"If you are not the best after a few years, you should quit.\"","excerpt":"The Carp and The Hermit Thrush includes details that help readers answer questions with text evidence about How do the characters use art or music to understand themselves?","stem":"Selection: Both If you were the teacher for both Rosetsu and Hayate, what is one piece of advice you would give them to help them keep improving?","choices":{"A":"\"Don\u0027t ever make a mistake, or you will fail.\"","B":"\"Focus on how your audience feels, not on how you feel.\"","C":"\"It is okay to struggle; keep practicing with heart, and learn from every mistake you make.\"","D":"\"If you are not the best after a few years, you should quit.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This advice aligns with the lessons in both stories: that persistence, self-belief, and learning from mistakes are essential for growth. Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Carp\" and \"The Hermit Thrush\" Authors: Marie Yuen and Dana Crum Source: Student Interactive U3 Week 3, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"quell\" mean in this sentence? A. to make a feeling much stronger B. to put an end to a feeling or doubt C. to hide a secret from other people D. to share a feeling with a good friend","excerpt":"\"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"\"","stem":"What does \"quell\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to make a feeling much stronger","B":"to put an end to a feeling or doubt","C":"to hide a secret from other people","D":"to share a feeling with a good friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stranger wants Rosetsu to stop or \"quell\" his doubts by proving he is a painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"tactics\" mean in this context? A. planned actions used to reach a goal B. loud noises made to scare away predators C. special foods eaten to gain energy D. secret paths hidden under the ice","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"What does \"tactics\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"planned actions used to reach a goal","B":"loud noises made to scare away predators","C":"special foods eaten to gain energy","D":"secret paths hidden under the ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The carp uses different movements and \"tactics\" to try and reach the cracker, meaning it uses planned actions to achieve its goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"supportive\" mean in this sentence? A. making fun of someone\u0027s mistakes B. encouraging and helping someone C. playing a loud musical instrument D. ignoring what someone is saying","excerpt":"\"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"What does \"supportive\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"making fun of someone\u0027s mistakes","B":"encouraging and helping someone","C":"playing a loud musical instrument","D":"ignoring what someone is saying"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dad tells Wakana to be \"supportive,\" meaning she should encourage and help her brother instead of making fun of him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt from \"The Carp\"? A. Rosetsu gave up on painting and left the school. B. Rosetsu became a great painter by working hard and believing in himself. C. Rosetsu decided to paint only pictures of carp and birds. D. Rosetsu asked Sensei Okyo to give him his brush back.","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last. After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt from \"The Carp\"?","choices":{"A":"Rosetsu gave up on painting and left the school.","B":"Rosetsu became a great painter by working hard and believing in himself.","C":"Rosetsu decided to paint only pictures of carp and birds.","D":"Rosetsu asked Sensei Okyo to give him his brush back."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that Rosetsu worked hard, completed his paintings, and became equal to his teacher, proving he achieved his dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu studied and worked harder than ever, and he completed many paintings, each one more dazzling than the last. After another year passed, his skills and knowledge were almost equal to those of Sensei Okyo.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: Hayate sees the bird sing beautifully without reading notes; Effect: He realizes he should play from his heart. B. Cause: Hayate is angry at the bird; Effect: He throws his saxophone in the yard. C. Cause: The bird teaches Hayate how to read notes; Effect: Hayate plays a perfect song. D. Cause: Hayate wants to catch the bird; Effect: He stops playing music forever.","excerpt":"\"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart.\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Hayate sees the bird sing beautifully without reading notes; Effect: He realizes he should play from his heart.","B":"Cause: Hayate is angry at the bird; Effect: He throws his saxophone in the yard.","C":"Cause: The bird teaches Hayate how to read notes; Effect: Hayate plays a perfect song.","D":"Cause: Hayate wants to catch the bird; Effect: He stops playing music forever."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Seeing the bird sing beautifully without studying music (cause) makes Hayate realize he should play from his heart (effect).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q016","read_aloud":"shows Rosetsu learning from a determined carp in nature. \"The Hermit Thrush\" shows Hayate learning from a beautiful bird song in nature. What can you infer about the role of nature in both stories? A. Nature is a dangerous place that the characters must escape from. B. Nature provides inspiration and lessons that help the characters grow. C. Nature is boring and does not affect the characters at all. D. Nature is only used as a setting for the characters to play sports.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"shows Rosetsu learning from a determined carp in nature. \"The Hermit Thrush\" shows Hayate learning from a beautiful bird song in nature. What can you infer about the role of nature in both stories?","choices":{"A":"Nature is a dangerous place that the characters must escape from.","B":"Nature provides inspiration and lessons that help the characters grow.","C":"Nature is boring and does not affect the characters at all.","D":"Nature is only used as a setting for the characters to play sports."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both characters find inspiration in animals (a carp and a bir d), which teaches them valuable lessons about perseverance and playing from the heart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q017","read_aloud":"Who was the stranger that gave Rosetsu the painting brush? A. Sensei Yutei B. Sensei Okyo C. a wild carp D. a hermit thrush","excerpt":"\"\"Yes, I am Sensei Maruyama Okyo, and the stranger you met on your way here was Sensei Yutei.\"","stem":"Who was the stranger that gave Rosetsu the painting brush?","choices":{"A":"Sensei Yutei","B":"Sensei Okyo","C":"a wild carp","D":"a hermit thrush"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Sensei Okyo reveals that the stranger Rosetsu met was his own teacher, Sensei Yutei.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Yes, I am Sensei Maruyama Okyo, and the stranger you met on your way here was Sensei Yutei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q018","read_aloud":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. Why did Hayate name his song \"Ode to a Hermit Thrush\"? A. because his friend Ben taught him how to sing like a bird B. because the bird\u0027s song inspired him to play from his heart C. because his sister Wakana told him to name it after a bird D. because he wanted to make his parents disappointed","excerpt":"hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it","stem":"Ode to a Hermit Thrush. Why did Hayate name his song \"Ode to a Hermit Thrush\"?","choices":{"A":"because his friend Ben taught him how to sing like a bird","B":"because the bird\u0027s song inspired him to play from his heart","C":"because his sister Wakana told him to name it after a bird","D":"because he wanted to make his parents disappointed"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate heard the hermit thrush singing and realized he should play what was in his heart, so he named the song to honor the bird\u0027s inspiration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: hayate(blushing). Thanks. I call it"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q019","read_aloud":"How does Sensei Okyo\u0027s advice help Rosetsu finally succeed? A. It teaches Rosetsu that he needs to paint faster to finish his work. B. It helps Rosetsu realize that his lack of self-belief was his biggest obstacle. C. It shows Rosetsu that he should quit painting and become a teacher. D. It proves that Rosetsu needs a better brush to become a great painter.","excerpt":"\"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"\"","stem":"How does Sensei Okyo\u0027s advice help Rosetsu finally succeed?","choices":{"A":"It teaches Rosetsu that he needs to paint faster to finish his work.","B":"It helps Rosetsu realize that his lack of self-belief was his biggest obstacle.","C":"It shows Rosetsu that he should quit painting and become a teacher.","D":"It proves that Rosetsu needs a better brush to become a great painter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sensei Okyo explains that Rosetsu\u0027s \"own doubts have held you back,\" helping Rosetsu realize that he must believe in his own talents to succeed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"No,\" the sensei replied, \"you are a conscientious worker, but your own doubts have held you back. A great painter doesn\u0027t abandon his paintings halfway through for fear they won\u0027t be good enough! You must believe in your own talents if you want others to do so.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q020","read_aloud":"teaches the lesson of perseverance. \"The Hermit Thrush\" teaches the lesson of playing from the heart. If you were to write a short story combining the lessons from both texts, what would be the main message? A. You should give up when things get too hard and stressful. B. You must work hard and persevere, but also find joy and play from your heart. C. You should only practice music and never worry about painting. D. You should always listen to your friends and ignore your own feelings.","excerpt":"The Carp","stem":"teaches the lesson of perseverance. \"The Hermit Thrush\" teaches the lesson of playing from the heart. If you were to write a short story combining the lessons from both texts, what would be the main message?","choices":{"A":"You should give up when things get too hard and stressful.","B":"You must work hard and persevere, but also find joy and play from your heart.","C":"You should only practice music and never worry about painting.","D":"You should always listen to your friends and ignore your own feelings."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Combining the lessons from both texts means you should persevere through hard work (like Rosetsu) while also finding joy and expressing yourself from the heart (like Hayate). Section A - Text Information Titles: The Carp (legen d) and The Hermit Thrush (dram a) Authors: Marie Yuen (The Carp) and Dana Crum (The Hermit Thrush)","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Carp"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q021","read_aloud":"Being supportive means being ______. A. Mean and critical B. Encouraging and helpful C. Ignoring someone D. Silent","excerpt":"\"Dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"Being supportive means being ______.","choices":{"A":"Mean and critical","B":"Encouraging and helpful","C":"Ignoring someone","D":"Silent"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Supportive means giving help and encouragement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q022","read_aloud":"Why did Rosetsu paint a carp? A. It was easy. B. To honor the carp that taught him persistence. C. His teacher made him. D. He only knew how to paint fish.","excerpt":"\"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\"","stem":"Why did Rosetsu paint a carp?","choices":{"A":"It was easy.","B":"To honor the carp that taught him persistence.","C":"His teacher made him.","D":"He only knew how to paint fish."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The carp was his inspiration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His choice of subject matter? It was a carp, of course, in honor of the one that inspired him to persist no matter what.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q023","read_aloud":"Who said the quote about the bird? A. Dad B. Wakana C. Mom D. Ben","excerpt":"\"WAKANA. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote? \u0027The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\u0027\"","stem":"Who said the quote about the bird?","choices":{"A":"Dad","B":"Wakana","C":"Mom","D":"Ben"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wakana shares the quote.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"WAKANA. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote? \u0027The bird doesn\u0027t sing to please others. It sings because it is happy.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q024","read_aloud":"If you could give an award to both Rosetsu and Hayate, what would it be for? A. Most likely to quit B. Overcoming self-doubt through perseverance and finding their own voice C. Best at complaining D. Most talented without trying","excerpt":"Both texts.","stem":"If you could give an award to both Rosetsu and Hayate, what would it be for?","choices":{"A":"Most likely to quit","B":"Overcoming self-doubt through perseverance and finding their own voice","C":"Best at complaining","D":"Most talented without trying"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both earned success by overcoming internal struggles. Section A - Text information Title: The Carp \u0026 The Hermit Thrush Author: Marie Yuen (The Carp) and Dana Crum (The Hermit Thrush)","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Both texts."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q025","read_aloud":"What does \"tactics\" mean? A. planned actions to reach a goal B. mistakes and accidents C. songs and dances D. colors and shapes","excerpt":"\"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\"","stem":"What does \"tactics\" mean?","choices":{"A":"planned actions to reach a goal","B":"mistakes and accidents","C":"songs and dances","D":"colors and shapes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Tactics\" are planned ways to do something. The carp tried different strategies to get the cracker.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rosetsu watched the carp as it twisted and turned and tried all sorts of tactics to reach the sembei.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q026","read_aloud":"What does \"supportive\" mean? A. mean and rude B. encouraging and helpful C. quiet and shy D. angry and loud","excerpt":"\"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\"","stem":"What does \"supportive\" mean?","choices":{"A":"mean and rude","B":"encouraging and helpful","C":"quiet and shy","D":"angry and loud"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Supportive\" means to encourage someone. Dad wants Wakana to be kinder and more helpful to Hayate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"dad. Be more supportive of your brother.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q027","read_aloud":"What is Rosetsu\u0027s main goal? A. To become a famous musician B. To become the greatest painter in Japan C. To catch a giant carp D. To move to America","excerpt":"\"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\"","stem":"What is Rosetsu\u0027s main goal?","choices":{"A":"To become a famous musician","B":"To become the greatest painter in Japan","C":"To catch a giant carp","D":"To move to America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that Rosetsu dreams of becoming the greatest painter in all of Japan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Long ago in Japan, there lived a boy named Rosetsu who dreamed of becoming a painter. Not just any painter, but the greatest in all of Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q028","read_aloud":"What do the words in parentheses tell us? A. What Hayate is thinking B. Stage directions showing Hayate is nervous C. The title of the song D. What the audience is doing","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead.)\"","stem":"What do the words in parentheses tell us?","choices":{"A":"What Hayate is thinking","B":"Stage directions showing Hayate is nervous","C":"The title of the song","D":"What the audience is doing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The parentheses contain stage directions. They show Hayate\u0027s actions and that he is nervous because he is sweating and playing badly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q029","read_aloud":"How are Rosetsu and Hayate\u0027s problems similar? A. They both struggle with self-doubt and need inspiration. B. They both want to quit and never try again. C. They both hate their teachers. D. They both are naturally perfect at their skills.","excerpt":"From The Carp: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"How are Rosetsu and Hayate\u0027s problems similar?","choices":{"A":"They both struggle with self-doubt and need inspiration.","B":"They both want to quit and never try again.","C":"They both hate their teachers.","D":"They both are naturally perfect at their skills."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Rosetsu doubts himself until the carp inspires him. Hayate doubts himself until the hermit thrush inspires him. Both need inspiration to overcome self-doubt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From The Carp: \"If I am to succeed, I must be just like that carp: determined, persistent, and unwilling to give up.\" From The Hermit Thrush: \"I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q030","read_aloud":"Who gave Rosetsu the brush? A. His father B. A stranger who was really Sensei Yutei C. Sensei Okyo D. Another student","excerpt":"\"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\"","stem":"Who gave Rosetsu the brush?","choices":{"A":"His father","B":"A stranger who was really Sensei Yutei","C":"Sensei Okyo","D":"Another student"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An old stranger gave Rosetsu the brush. Later, the gatekeeper reveals the stranger was Sensei Yutei, his own teacher.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The brush once belonged to my own sensei, the great Ishida Yutei!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q031","read_aloud":"Why does hearing the bird help Hayate? A. The bird teaches him to read music. B. The bird shows him that natural feeling matters more than perfect technique. C. The bird tells him to quit. D. The bird gives him a new saxophone.","excerpt":"\"hayate. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much. (The hermit thrush continues to sing.)\"","stem":"Why does hearing the bird help Hayate?","choices":{"A":"The bird teaches him to read music.","B":"The bird shows him that natural feeling matters more than perfect technique.","C":"The bird tells him to quit.","D":"The bird gives him a new saxophone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bird sings naturally without studying. Hayate realizes he should feel the music instead of worrying about being perfect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much. (The hermit thrush continues to sing.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q032","read_aloud":"Why was this day \"glorious\" for Rosetsu? A. It was sunny outside. B. He had worked hard for years and finally earned the right to use the brush. C. He did not have to study anymore. D. His parents visited him.","excerpt":"\"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush.\"","stem":"Why was this day \"glorious\" for Rosetsu?","choices":{"A":"It was sunny outside.","B":"He had worked hard for years and finally earned the right to use the brush.","C":"He did not have to study anymore.","D":"His parents visited him."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rosetsu studied for years and overcame his doubts. Finally using the brush was a reward for all his hard work and perseverance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then came the glorious day he was allowed to paint with Sensei Yutei\u0027s brush.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q033","read_aloud":"What is the most important message readers can learn from both The Carp and The Hermit Thrush? A. Animals are better than people. B. When you face challenges, believe in yourself and keep trying. C. Quitting is always the best choice. D. Only talented people can succeed.","excerpt":"From both texts.","stem":"What is the most important message readers can learn from both The Carp and The Hermit Thrush?","choices":{"A":"Animals are better than people.","B":"When you face challenges, believe in yourself and keep trying.","C":"Quitting is always the best choice.","D":"Only talented people can succeed."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both texts show characters who struggle with self-doubt. Rosetsu learns from the carp to persevere. Hayate learns from the bird to play from his heart. Both teach us to believe in ourselves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From both texts."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q034","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q035","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q036","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. To make bigger B. To put an end to something C. To explain or describe D. To write down","excerpt":"\"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"To make bigger","B":"To put an end to something","C":"To explain or describe","D":"To write down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the man wants Rosetsu to stop or put an end to his doubts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you are meant to be a painter, prove it now, to quell the doubts inside you.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q037","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. the piano B. the drums C. the saxophone D. the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"the piano","B":"the drums","C":"the saxophone","D":"the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate arrives carrying his saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate is last to arrive, carrying his saxophone. He sits in the corner and stares down at his sneakers. dad(to hayate). You made it!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q038","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He plays perfectly and everyone cheers. B. He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early. C. He drops his saxophone on the floor. D. He starts singing along with the music.","excerpt":"\"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He plays perfectly and everyone cheers.","B":"He makes harsh sounds and stops playing early.","C":"He drops his saxophone on the floor.","D":"He starts singing along with the music."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes harsh sounds coming from the saxophone and sweat on his forehead, and he stops playing before finishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(hayate stands and raises his saxophone to his mouth. He takes a breath. Harsh sounds come from the saxophone. Beads of sweat appear on hayate\u0027s forehead. He stops playing before finishing the song.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Monday B. Wednesday C. Friday D. Saturday","excerpt":"\"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Monday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Friday","D":"Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The scene description clearly states that it is Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ACT 1 Scene 1. It\u0027s Saturday, the day of the family\u0027s weekly concert. mom, dad, and wakana sit in the living room.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He is angry that his family made him practice too much. B. He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing. C. He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben. D. He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home.","excerpt":"\"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He is angry that his family made him practice too much.","B":"He feels frustrated and believes he will never be good at playing.","C":"He wants to go outside to play basketball with his friend Ben.","D":"He is embarrassed that he forgot his sheet music at home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate tells his mom that he doesn\u0027t think he has \"what it takes\" and feels frustrated that his practice isn\u0027t making him better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate. She\u0027s right, though. I can\u0027t play well. I\u0027ve been taking lessons for a long time now, and I practice every day. But I don\u0027t think I have what it takes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. the way a person thinks and feels about something B. the type of musical instrument a person plays C. the amount of time spent practicing a song D. the speed at which a person reads sheet music","excerpt":"\"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"the way a person thinks and feels about something","B":"the type of musical instrument a person plays","C":"the amount of time spent practicing a song","D":"the speed at which a person reads sheet music"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ben is talking about Hayate\u0027s negative \"attitude,\" which refers to the way he is thinking and feeling about his ability to play the saxophone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. Not with that attitude you won\u0027t, young man! (hayate frowns at ben.) ben. Just kidding, dude. That\u0027s what my parents said all the time when I wanted to quit piano.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. quit playing music and shoot hoops instead B. practice on a different instrument to relax C. loosen up and spend more time playing what he wants D. ask his parents to buy him an electronic keyboard","excerpt":"\"ben. And for some reason, when I started playing that, it was fun. I didn\u0027t feel anxious when I played it-I just loosened up. And that helped me relax when I played our big grand piano, too.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"quit playing music and shoot hoops instead","B":"practice on a different instrument to relax","C":"loosen up and spend more time playing what he wants","D":"ask his parents to buy him an electronic keyboard"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ben tells Hayate that he needs to \"loosen up\" and spend more time playing what he wants to play instead of just trying to be perfect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. And for some reason, when I started playing that, it was fun. I didn\u0027t feel anxious when I played it-I just loosened up. And that helped me relax when I played our big grand piano, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Cause: Hayate loves the saxophone; Effect: He wants to quit playing it. B. Cause: Hayate thinks he is not good; Effect: He is afraid to quit and disappoint his parents. C. Cause: Wakana tells him to quit; Effect: He immediately tells his parents. D. Cause: Hayate practices every day; Effect: He becomes a perfect player.","excerpt":"\"wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Cause: Hayate loves the saxophone; Effect: He wants to quit playing it.","B":"Cause: Hayate thinks he is not good; Effect: He is afraid to quit and disappoint his parents.","C":"Cause: Wakana tells him to quit; Effect: He immediately tells his parents.","D":"Cause: Hayate practices every day; Effect: He becomes a perfect player."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate feels he is not good at playing (cause), which makes him afraid to quit because he knows his parents would be disappointed (effect).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wakana. If you don\u0027t like the saxophone, why don\u0027t you tell mom and dad you want to quit? hayate. I love the sax-I\u0027m just not good. Anyway, they\u0027d be so disappointed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. He should only play music when he is happy and playing for himself. B. He should stop playing the saxophone and learn to sing like a bird. C. He should practice playing loud songs to please his parents. D. He should quit music entirely because birds do not play instruments.","excerpt":"wakana. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"He should only play music when he is happy and playing for himself.","B":"He should stop playing the saxophone and learn to sing like a bird.","C":"He should practice playing loud songs to please his parents.","D":"He should quit music entirely because birds do not play instruments."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wakana\u0027s quote means the bird sings for its own happiness, so Hayate should apply this by playing music because he loves it, not just to please others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: wakana. Well, you should only keep playing if you like to. Do you know this quote?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. Ben wants Hayate to quit music, while Hayate wants to be perfect. B. Ben encourages playing for fun, while Hayate stresses over being perfect. C. Ben thinks Hayate should play the piano, while Hayate wants to play the sax. D. Ben believes Hayate is already the best, while Hayate thinks he is the worst.","excerpt":"\"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"Ben wants Hayate to quit music, while Hayate wants to be perfect.","B":"Ben encourages playing for fun, while Hayate stresses over being perfect.","C":"Ben thinks Hayate should play the piano, while Hayate wants to play the sax.","D":"Ben believes Hayate is already the best, while Hayate thinks he is the worst."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ben tells Hayate to \"loosen up\" and play what he wants, which directly contrasts with Hayate\u0027s own stressful goal of trying to be \"perfect.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ben. You know, maybe you need to loosen up, too. Spend more time playing what you want to play and less time trying to be perfect.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. a type of musical instrument B. a small bird with a beautiful song C. a famous composer of classical music D. a sheet of music with notes on it","excerpt":"\"hayate(to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird. (He listens as the bird finishes its song and then starts again.)\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"a type of musical instrument","B":"a small bird with a beautiful song","C":"a famous composer of classical music","D":"a sheet of music with notes on it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"hermit thrush\" is the bird Hayate is talking to in the backyard, and the text mentions it singing beautifully.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate(to the hermit thrush). If only I could play as well as you sing, little bird. (He listens as the bird finishes its song and then starts again.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. his sister Wakana practicing the drums B. his friend Ben shooting a basketball C. a hermit thrush singing in a tree D. his dad playing the acoustic guitar","excerpt":"\"(Suddenly, hayate hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree. hayate watches and listens.)\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"his sister Wakana practicing the drums","B":"his friend Ben shooting a basketball","C":"a hermit thrush singing in a tree","D":"his dad playing the acoustic guitar"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The stage directions state that Hayate suddenly hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"(Suddenly, hayate hears the beautiful sound of a hermit thrush singing in a nearby tree. hayate watches and listens.)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. the pressure to read sheet music perfectly B. the freedom to create music from the heart C. the need to practice scales every single day D. the fear of making a mistake in front of others","excerpt":"\"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"the pressure to read sheet music perfectly","B":"the freedom to create music from the heart","C":"the need to practice scales every single day","D":"the fear of making a mistake in front of others"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bird sings beautifully without reading notes, symbolizing for Hayate that he should play freely from his heart instead of overthinking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate(to the hermit thrush). You don\u0027t study music. You can\u0027t read notes. But you sing beautifully. (hayate looks thoughtful.) Maybe I should do what you do. I should play what\u0027s in my heart. I should feel the music and stop thinking so much.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. He throws his saxophone on the bed and goes to sleep. B. He plays a melody with his eyes closed, feeling the music. C. He runs outside to find the bird and catch it. D. He writes a letter to his friend Ben about the bird.","excerpt":"\"hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"He throws his saxophone on the bed and goes to sleep.","B":"He plays a melody with his eyes closed, feeling the music.","C":"He runs outside to find the bird and catch it.","D":"He writes a letter to his friend Ben about the bird."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hayate applies his realization by picking up his saxophone and playing a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently to feel the music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"hayate goes back to his house and returns to his room. He picks up his saxophone. He starts to play a melody with his eyes closed, swaying gently as he plays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w3-the-carp-and-the-hermit-thrush-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. It makes him play harsh and loud notes like a sick moose. B. It helps him play fuller, richer notes that sound beautiful. C. It causes him to forget how to read his sheet music. D. It makes him stop playing because he is too scared.","excerpt":"\"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"It makes him play harsh and loud notes like a sick moose.","B":"It helps him play fuller, richer notes that sound beautiful.","C":"It causes him to forget how to read his sheet music.","D":"It makes him stop playing because he is too scared."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Inspired by the bird, Hayate\u0027s notes become \"fuller and rich\" instead of harsh, showing that playing from the heart improves his music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The notes sound fuller and rich, not harsh as they usually do. The tune has some echoes of the hermit thrush\u0027s song.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":3,"week":4,"title":"Poetry Collection","author":"Davida Adedjouma and Malathi Michelle Iyengar","genre":"Poetry","essential_question":"How can poems preserve memories and honor creativity?","weekly_question":"How do the poets use images to connect family, art, and memory?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["vivid","sepia","spruce","retired","artist"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Poetry Collection. How do the poets use images to connect family, art, and memory?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"vivid\" mean in this sentence? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does the word \"vivid\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What happened to the father\u0027s art supplies? A. He used them every day. B. He sold them to make money. C. They sat on a shelf for a long time. D. He gave them away to his friends.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What happened to the father\u0027s art supplies?","choices":{"A":"He used them every day.","B":"He sold them to make money.","C":"They sat on a shelf for a long time.","D":"He gave them away to his friends."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states the supplies \"sat hardening on a shelf.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What is Aunty holding in the poem \"Sepia\"? A. A paintbrush B. A photo C. A violin D. A box of crayons","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What is Aunty holding in the poem \"Sepia\"?","choices":{"A":"A paintbrush","B":"A photo","C":"A violin","D":"A box of crayons"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem explicitly states, \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q004","read_aloud":"According to the poem \"Spruce,\" what instruments are mentioned? A. Piano and drums B. Clarinet and flute C. Violin, guitar, and bass D. Saxophone and trumpet","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"According to the poem \"Spruce,\" what instruments are mentioned?","choices":{"A":"Piano and drums","B":"Clarinet and flute","C":"Violin, guitar, and bass","D":"Saxophone and trumpet"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem clearly lists \"Violin, guitar and bass\" as the instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker in \"Artist to Artist\" write books? A. Because her father wanted to be an artist. B. Because she wanted to be a famous painter. C. Because her father forced her to write. D. Because she did not like to draw.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker in \"Artist to Artist\" write books?","choices":{"A":"Because her father wanted to be an artist.","B":"Because she wanted to be a famous painter.","C":"Because her father forced her to write.","D":"Because she did not like to draw."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first line of the poem says, \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"vivid\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. clear, bright, and lifelike B. dark, dull, and hard to see C. old, faded, and broken D. quiet, soft, and gentle","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does the word \"vivid\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"clear, bright, and lifelike","B":"dark, dull, and hard to see","C":"old, faded, and broken","D":"quiet, soft, and gentle"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker compares her words to a bright box of crayons, showing that \"vivid\" means clear and full of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The father loved riding the bus to work. B. The father worked hard at a tough job to support his family. C. The father sorted mail for only a few weeks. D. The father wanted to become a bus driver.","excerpt":"\"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The father loved riding the bus to work.","B":"The father worked hard at a tough job to support his family.","C":"The father sorted mail for only a few weeks.","D":"The father wanted to become a bus driver."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows the father working long hours to pay bills, which means he worked hard to take care of his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What is Aunty doing in this excerpt? A. She is crying about her old age. B. She is painting a picture of the speaker. C. She is showing the speaker a photo from her youth. D. She is asking the speaker to take her to the doctor.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What is Aunty doing in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"She is crying about her old age.","B":"She is painting a picture of the speaker.","C":"She is showing the speaker a photo from her youth.","D":"She is asking the speaker to take her to the doctor."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Aunty is laughing and saying \"Look!\" while holding up a photo from when she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Why is the speaker surprised by the photo? A. The speaker realizes she looks exactly like her Aunty did when she was young. B. The speaker sees that Aunty was wearing a strange outfit. C. The speaker notices that the photo is completely black and white. D. The speaker sees that Aunty was standing next to a famous artist.","excerpt":"\"The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"Why is the speaker surprised by the photo?","choices":{"A":"The speaker realizes she looks exactly like her Aunty did when she was young.","B":"The speaker sees that Aunty was wearing a strange outfit.","C":"The speaker notices that the photo is completely black and white.","D":"The speaker sees that Aunty was standing next to a famous artist."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker sees her own face in the photo and realizes she shares the same eyes as her Aunty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What did the speaker\u0027s father want to be? A. A doctor B. An artist C. A teacher D. A mail carrier","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"What did the speaker\u0027s father want to be?","choices":{"A":"A doctor","B":"An artist","C":"A teacher","D":"A mail carrier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says her father wanted to be an artist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q011","read_aloud":"Why did the speaker\u0027s father work at the post office instead of being an artist? A. He did not like art. B. He needed to earn money to pay bills. C. He lost his art supplies. D. He wanted to be a mail carrier.","excerpt":"\"But every night … he dressed in the blue uniform … \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office. Sorted mail … because we had bills to pay.\"","stem":"Why did the speaker\u0027s father work at the post office instead of being an artist?","choices":{"A":"He did not like art.","B":"He needed to earn money to pay bills.","C":"He lost his art supplies.","D":"He wanted to be a mail carrier."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He worked to pay the bills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But every night … he dressed in the blue uniform … \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office. Sorted mail … because we had bills to pay.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What happened to his art degrees? A. He framed them on the wall. B. They sat unused on a shelf. C. He threw them away. D. He gave them to his daughter.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\"","stem":"What happened to his art degrees?","choices":{"A":"He framed them on the wall.","B":"They sat unused on a shelf.","C":"He threw them away.","D":"He gave them to his daughter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The degrees sat hardening on a shelf.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker thank her father? A. He bought her books. B. He gave her the urge to create, even though he couldn\u0027t pursue his own art. C. He taught her to sort mail. D. He gave her money.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"Why does the speaker thank her father?","choices":{"A":"He bought her books.","B":"He gave her the urge to create, even though he couldn\u0027t pursue his own art.","C":"He taught her to sort mail.","D":"He gave her money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He inspired her creativity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What does the word \"vivid\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. dull and boring B. clear, bright, and lifelike C. dark and shadowy D. quiet and soft","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does the word \"vivid\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"dull and boring","B":"clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"dark and shadowy","D":"quiet and soft"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" means clear, bright, and full of life. The poet compares her words to bright crayon colors that stand out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What is this poem mainly about? A. A girl who hates to write B. A father\u0027s dream of being an artist and how it inspired his daughter C. A family that travels on buses D. A post office in a big city","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist when he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"What is this poem mainly about?","choices":{"A":"A girl who hates to write","B":"A father\u0027s dream of being an artist and how it inspired his daughter","C":"A family that travels on buses","D":"A post office in a big city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem tells about the speaker\u0027s father, who wanted to be an artist. His dream inspired the speaker to become a writer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist when he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q016","read_aloud":"Where did the father work? A. At a school B. At the downtown post office C. At a hospital D. At a grocery store","excerpt":"\"he dressed in the blue uniform \u0026 black shoes of many other fathers who also weren\u0027t doctors or lawyers, teachers or preachers, \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\"","stem":"Where did the father work?","choices":{"A":"At a school","B":"At the downtown post office","C":"At a hospital","D":"At a grocery store"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the father rode the bus to the downtown post office. He sorted mail there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"he dressed in the blue uniform \u0026 black shoes of many other fathers who also weren\u0027t doctors or lawyers, teachers or preachers, \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What did the father do at his job? A. He delivered packages to houses. B. He sorted mail by zip code. C. He drove the bus. D. He sold stamps.","excerpt":"\"Sorted mail by zip code-60620, 60621, 60622.\"","stem":"What did the father do at his job?","choices":{"A":"He delivered packages to houses.","B":"He sorted mail by zip code.","C":"He drove the bus.","D":"He sold stamps."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem clearly states that the father sorted mail by zip code at the post office.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sorted mail by zip code-60620, 60621, 60622.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What does \"feeling black and blue\" mean in this poem? A. He was physically hurt. B. He felt sad and tired from hard work. C. He liked the colors black and blue. D. He wore black and blue clothes.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What does \"feeling black and blue\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"He was physically hurt.","B":"He felt sad and tired from hard work.","C":"He liked the colors black and blue.","D":"He wore black and blue clothes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Black and blue\" describes feeling hurt or sad. The father worked hard for 30 years and felt worn out from the job.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What does \"burnished\" most likely mean here? A. Painted in bright colors B. Polished or made shiny C. Broken into pieces D. Covered in dirt","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"burnished\" most likely mean here?","choices":{"A":"Painted in bright colors","B":"Polished or made shiny","C":"Broken into pieces","D":"Covered in dirt"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Burnished\" refers to making a surface shiny, often by rubbing, which makes sense when talking about the wood of an instrument.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q020","read_aloud":"How long did the father ride the bus for work? A. 5 years B. 10 years C. 30 years D. A few months","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"How long did the father ride the bus for work?","choices":{"A":"5 years","B":"10 years","C":"30 years","D":"A few months"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem explicitly states, \"For 30 years my father rode the bus.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q021","read_aloud":"How does the poet describe Aunty\u0027s hand? A. It is steady and strong. B. It is very small. C. It trembles with age. D. It is covered in paint.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the poet describe Aunty\u0027s hand?","choices":{"A":"It is steady and strong.","B":"It is very small.","C":"It trembles with age.","D":"It is covered in paint."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly says her hand \"trembles with age.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q022","read_aloud":"How are the father and the speaker similar? A. They both work as bus drivers. B. They both enjoy creative expression. C. They both play the violin. D. They both live in the same house.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How are the father and the speaker similar?","choices":{"A":"They both work as bus drivers.","B":"They both enjoy creative expression.","C":"They both play the violin.","D":"They both live in the same house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both characters engage in artistic expression (writing and drawing), showing their shared creative nature.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q023","read_aloud":"Why does Aunty show a photo? A. To show she was once young. B. To teach the speaker how to take photos. C. To prove she was a famous artist. D. To complain about being old.","excerpt":"\"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"Why does Aunty show a photo?","choices":{"A":"To show she was once young.","B":"To teach the speaker how to take photos.","C":"To prove she was a famous artist.","D":"To complain about being old."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text suggests she is sharing a memory of her youth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q024","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments? A. They are old and broken. B. They are shiny and well-cared for. C. They were just built yesterday. D. They are very heavy to carry.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments?","choices":{"A":"They are old and broken.","B":"They are shiny and well-cared for.","C":"They were just built yesterday.","D":"They are very heavy to carry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Burnished\" means to polish a surface until it glows, suggesting the instruments are clean and cared for.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What type of wood were the instruments made from? A. Oak B. Pine C. Spruce D. Cherry","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What type of wood were the instruments made from?","choices":{"A":"Oak","B":"Pine","C":"Spruce","D":"Cherry"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly names the wood as \"spruce.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"burnished\" most likely mean here? A. Painted in bright colors B. Polished or made shiny C. Broken into pieces D. Covered in dirt","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"burnished\" most likely mean here?","choices":{"A":"Painted in bright colors","B":"Polished or made shiny","C":"Broken into pieces","D":"Covered in dirt"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Burnished\" refers to making a surface shiny, often by rubbing, which makes sense when talking about the wood of an instrument.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q002","read_aloud":"How long did the father ride the bus for work? A. 5 years B. 10 years C. 30 years D. A few months","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"How long did the father ride the bus for work?","choices":{"A":"5 years","B":"10 years","C":"30 years","D":"A few months"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem explicitly states, \"For 30 years my father rode the bus.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q003","read_aloud":"How does the poet describe Aunty\u0027s hand? A. It is steady and strong. B. It is very small. C. It trembles with age. D. It is covered in paint.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the poet describe Aunty\u0027s hand?","choices":{"A":"It is steady and strong.","B":"It is very small.","C":"It trembles with age.","D":"It is covered in paint."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly says her hand \"trembles with age.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q004","read_aloud":"How are the father and the speaker similar? A. They both work as bus drivers. B. They both enjoy creative expression. C. They both play the violin. D. They both live in the same house.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How are the father and the speaker similar?","choices":{"A":"They both work as bus drivers.","B":"They both enjoy creative expression.","C":"They both play the violin.","D":"They both live in the same house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both characters engage in artistic expression (writing and drawing), showing their shared creative nature.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Aunty show a photo? A. To show she was once young. B. To teach the speaker how to take photos. C. To prove she was a famous artist. D. To complain about being old.","excerpt":"\"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"Why does Aunty show a photo?","choices":{"A":"To show she was once young.","B":"To teach the speaker how to take photos.","C":"To prove she was a famous artist.","D":"To complain about being old."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text suggests she is sharing a memory of her youth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"retired\" mean in this sentence? A. no longer working B. starting a new school C. moving to a new city D. learning to paint","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\"","stem":"What does \"retired\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"no longer working","B":"starting a new school","C":"moving to a new city","D":"learning to paint"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker is asking her father what he wants to do now that he has finished his working years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What are the violin, guitar, and bass made of? A. maple wood B. oak wood C. spruce wood D. pine wood","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown. A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"What are the violin, guitar, and bass made of?","choices":{"A":"maple wood","B":"oak wood","C":"spruce wood","D":"pine wood"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem directly states that the instruments are \"built of spruce wood.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown. A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What is the correct order of events in the father\u0027s life based on the text? A. He retired, then he worked at the post office, then he went to art school. B. He went to art school, then he worked at the post office, then he retired. C. He worked at the post office, then he retired, then he went to art school. D. He retired, then he went to art school, then he worked at the post office.","excerpt":"\"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus... He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf\"","stem":"What is the correct order of events in the father\u0027s life based on the text?","choices":{"A":"He retired, then he worked at the post office, then he went to art school.","B":"He went to art school, then he worked at the post office, then he retired.","C":"He worked at the post office, then he retired, then he went to art school.","D":"He retired, then he went to art school, then he worked at the post office."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The father had degrees in art, then worked for 30 years at the post office, and is now retired.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus... He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q009","read_aloud":"Who is playing the violin in the poem \"Spruce\"? A. Papá B. Tío C. The speaker D. Abuelito","excerpt":"\"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papá\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\"","stem":"Who is playing the violin in the poem \"Spruce\"?","choices":{"A":"Papá","B":"Tío","C":"The speaker","D":"Abuelito"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papá\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why did the father stop drawing and painting? A. He did not have enough time because he was working hard to pay the bills. B. He lost his art supplies when he moved to a new house. C. He decided that he did not like art anymore. D. He gave his art supplies to his daughter to use for her books.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"Why did the father stop drawing and painting?","choices":{"A":"He did not have enough time because he was working hard to pay the bills.","B":"He lost his art supplies when he moved to a new house.","C":"He decided that he did not like art anymore.","D":"He gave his art supplies to his daughter to use for her books."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The father had to work constantly to pay the bills, which left him no time or energy to use his art supplies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"crinkled\" mean? A. Smooth and flat B. Wrinkled or creased like old paper C. Bright and shiny D. Wet and soggy","excerpt":"\"Brown. Sepia brown. Inky, crinkly sepia brown.\"","stem":"What does \"crinkled\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Smooth and flat","B":"Wrinkled or creased like old paper","C":"Bright and shiny","D":"Wet and soggy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Crinkled means wrinkled or creased.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Brown. Sepia brown. Inky, crinkly sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What is Aunty holding? A. A book B. A photo from when she was young C. A letter D. A paintbrush","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What is Aunty holding?","choices":{"A":"A book","B":"A photo from when she was young","C":"A letter","D":"A paintbrush"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She says, \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What imagery (sight) does the poet use here? A. The smell of the photo B. The sound of Aunty\u0027s voice C. The description of the girl\u0027s eyes as soft and shining D. The taste of sepia","excerpt":"\"The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What imagery (sight) does the poet use here?","choices":{"A":"The smell of the photo","B":"The sound of Aunty\u0027s voice","C":"The description of the girl\u0027s eyes as soft and shining","D":"The taste of sepia"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poet describes how the eyes look.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What does the speaker notice about the girl in the photo? A. The girl has a different face. B. The girl has the speaker\u0027s face. C. The girl is not related. D. The girl is smiling.","excerpt":"\"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"What does the speaker notice about the girl in the photo?","choices":{"A":"The girl has a different face.","B":"The girl has the speaker\u0027s face.","C":"The girl is not related.","D":"The girl is smiling."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says, \"I see a girl with my face!\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Why does Aunty hold the photo next to her cheek? A. To hide her face B. To compare the young face in the photo with her older face now C. To smell the photo D. To give it to the speaker","excerpt":"\"Look closer. Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\"","stem":"Why does Aunty hold the photo next to her cheek?","choices":{"A":"To hide her face","B":"To compare the young face in the photo with her older face now","C":"To smell the photo","D":"To give it to the speaker"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She is comparing her younger self to her older self.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Look closer. Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What did the father do first? A. He worked at the post office for 30 years. B. He drew people with crayons when he was young. C. He retired from his job. D. He taught art classes.","excerpt":"\"Drew people with meat on their bones in flesh-colored tones from my 64-colors box of crayons. But every night... he dressed in the blue uniform... For 30 years my father rode the bus...\"","stem":"What did the father do first?","choices":{"A":"He worked at the post office for 30 years.","B":"He drew people with crayons when he was young.","C":"He retired from his job.","D":"He taught art classes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says the father wanted to be an artist and drew people when he grew up. Then he worked at the post office for 30 years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Drew people with meat on their bones in flesh-colored tones from my 64-colors box of crayons. But every night... he dressed in the blue uniform... For 30 years my father rode the bus...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the father\u0027s art supplies? A. He used them every day. B. He did not use them for a long time. C. He sold them for money. D. He gave them to his daughter.","excerpt":"\"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the father\u0027s art supplies?","choices":{"A":"He used them every day.","B":"He did not use them for a long time.","C":"He sold them for money.","D":"He gave them to his daughter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The degrees and art supplies \"sat hardening on a shelf.\" This means they were not used for a long time. They just sat there collecting dust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Whose hand trembles in the poem \"Sepia\"? A. The mother\u0027s hand B. The speaker\u0027s hand C. Aunty\u0027s hand D. The grandmother\u0027s hand","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"Whose hand trembles in the poem \"Sepia\"?","choices":{"A":"The mother\u0027s hand","B":"The speaker\u0027s hand","C":"Aunty\u0027s hand","D":"The grandmother\u0027s hand"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem clearly says \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age.\" It is the aunt\u0027s hand that shakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Why is Aunty showing the photo? A. To show how much she has changed B. To prove she was young once C. To compare her young face to her old face D. To sell the photo","excerpt":"\"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"Why is Aunty showing the photo?","choices":{"A":"To show how much she has changed","B":"To prove she was young once","C":"To compare her young face to her old face","D":"To sell the photo"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Aunty shows the photo and the speaker sees a girl with her own face. The poem compares Aunty\u0027s young face to her old, crinkled face.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What does the word \"vivid\" mean in this sentence? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does the word \"vivid\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What happened to the father\u0027s art supplies? A. He used them every day. B. He sold them to make money. C. They sat on a shelf for a long time. D. He gave them away to his friends.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What happened to the father\u0027s art supplies?","choices":{"A":"He used them every day.","B":"He sold them to make money.","C":"They sat on a shelf for a long time.","D":"He gave them away to his friends."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states the supplies \"sat hardening on a shelf.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What is Aunty holding in the poem \"Sepia\"? A. A paintbrush B. A photo C. A violin D. A box of crayons","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What is Aunty holding in the poem \"Sepia\"?","choices":{"A":"A paintbrush","B":"A photo","C":"A violin","D":"A box of crayons"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem explicitly states, \"Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q023","read_aloud":"According to the poem \"Spruce,\" what instruments are mentioned? A. Piano and drums B. Clarinet and flute C. Violin, guitar, and bass D. Saxophone and trumpet","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"According to the poem \"Spruce,\" what instruments are mentioned?","choices":{"A":"Piano and drums","B":"Clarinet and flute","C":"Violin, guitar, and bass","D":"Saxophone and trumpet"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem clearly lists \"Violin, guitar and bass\" as the instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker in \"Artist to Artist\" write books? A. Because her father wanted to be an artist. B. Because she wanted to be a famous painter. C. Because her father forced her to write. D. Because she did not like to draw.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker in \"Artist to Artist\" write books?","choices":{"A":"Because her father wanted to be an artist.","B":"Because she wanted to be a famous painter.","C":"Because her father forced her to write.","D":"Because she did not like to draw."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first line of the poem says, \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q025","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments? A. They are old and broken. B. They are shiny and well-cared for. C. They were just built yesterday. D. They are very heavy to carry.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments?","choices":{"A":"They are old and broken.","B":"They are shiny and well-cared for.","C":"They were just built yesterday.","D":"They are very heavy to carry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Burnished\" means to polish a surface until it glows, suggesting the instruments are clean and cared for.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments? A. They are old and broken. B. They are shiny and well-cared for. C. They were just built yesterday. D. They are very heavy to carry.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"burnished\" imply about the instruments?","choices":{"A":"They are old and broken.","B":"They are shiny and well-cared for.","C":"They were just built yesterday.","D":"They are very heavy to carry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Burnished\" means to polish a surface until it glows, suggesting the instruments are clean and cared for.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The speaker writes books to fulfill a dream her father once had. B. The father forced his daughter to become a writer. C. Writing books is easier than being an artist. D. The father eventually became a famous painter.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The speaker writes books to fulfill a dream her father once had.","B":"The father forced his daughter to become a writer.","C":"Writing books is easier than being an artist.","D":"The father eventually became a famous painter."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker directly links her own career choice to her father\u0027s unfulfilled dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What type of wood were the instruments made from? A. Oak B. Pine C. Spruce D. Cherry","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What type of wood were the instruments made from?","choices":{"A":"Oak","B":"Pine","C":"Spruce","D":"Cherry"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly names the wood as \"spruce.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What does \"black and blue\" mean in this poem? A. The color of the bus. B. Feeling hurt, tired, or worn out. C. The color of his clothes. D. Being happy and excited for work.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What does \"black and blue\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"The color of the bus.","B":"Feeling hurt, tired, or worn out.","C":"The color of his clothes.","D":"Being happy and excited for work."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being \"black and blue\" is an idiom used here to describe his physical and emotional exhaustion from working for 30 years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What is the contrast the poet creates in this line? A. Her hand is old, but her spirit is happy. B. Her hand is big, but her voice is small. C. She is sad because she is old. D. She cannot speak, but she can draw.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What is the contrast the poet creates in this line?","choices":{"A":"Her hand is old, but her spirit is happy.","B":"Her hand is big, but her voice is small.","C":"She is sad because she is old.","D":"She cannot speak, but she can draw."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet contrasts the weakness of physical age (trembling han d) with the strength and joy of her personality (ringing laughter).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" mean in this context? A. moves quickly B. stays perfectly still C. shakes slightly D. feels very cold","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"moves quickly","B":"stays perfectly still","C":"shakes slightly","D":"feels very cold"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Aunty\u0027s hand \"trembles with age,\" which means it shakes a little bit because she is getting older.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How does the speaker feel when looking at the photo? A. angry and confused B. bored and tired C. scared and nervous D. connected and nostalgic","excerpt":"\"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown. Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"How does the speaker feel when looking at the photo?","choices":{"A":"angry and confused","B":"bored and tired","C":"scared and nervous","D":"connected and nostalgic"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The speaker uses words like \"nostalgic\" and sees her own face, showing she feels a deep connection to the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown. Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What is the speaker doing while Tío plays? A. singing a song B. dancing around C. writing a poem D. clapping a pattern","excerpt":"\"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce brown.\"","stem":"What is the speaker doing while Tío plays?","choices":{"A":"singing a song","B":"dancing around","C":"writing a poem","D":"clapping a pattern"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says the speaker\u0027s hands \"clap out a staccato pattern.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What does the speaker realize when looking at the photo? A. Aunty\u0027s eyes are the same color as the speaker\u0027s eyes. B. The speaker and Aunty share the same eye shape and color. C. Aunty\u0027s eyes in the photo look sad and tired. D. The speaker\u0027s eyes are completely different from Aunty\u0027s.","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What does the speaker realize when looking at the photo?","choices":{"A":"Aunty\u0027s eyes are the same color as the speaker\u0027s eyes.","B":"The speaker and Aunty share the same eye shape and color.","C":"Aunty\u0027s eyes in the photo look sad and tired.","D":"The speaker\u0027s eyes are completely different from Aunty\u0027s."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker sees her own face in the photo and realizes she has the same soft, shining, sepia brown eyes as Aunty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What instruments are mentioned? A. Drums and piano B. Violin and guitar C. Flute and trumpet D. Harp and cello","excerpt":"\"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\"","stem":"What instruments are mentioned?","choices":{"A":"Drums and piano","B":"Violin and guitar","C":"Flute and trumpet","D":"Harp and cello"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Violin (Abuelito) and guitar (Pap a).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does Tio play? A. Violin B. Guitar C. Contrabajo (bass) D. Drums","excerpt":"\"Tio winks at me from behind the contrabajo.\"","stem":"What does Tio play?","choices":{"A":"Violin","B":"Guitar","C":"Contrabajo (bass)","D":"Drums"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Tio is behind the contrabajo.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tio winks at me from behind the contrabajo.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What is \"spruce\" in this poem? A. A type of food B. A type of wood used to make instruments C. A person\u0027s name D. A color of paint","excerpt":"\"built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What is \"spruce\" in this poem?","choices":{"A":"A type of food","B":"A type of wood used to make instruments","C":"A person\u0027s name","D":"A color of paint"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Spruce is a type of wood, often used for musical instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" mean? A. shakes slightly B. dances quickly C. grows bigger D. turns colors","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" mean?","choices":{"A":"shakes slightly","B":"dances quickly","C":"grows bigger","D":"turns colors"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Trembles\" means to shake slightly. Aunty\u0027s hand shakes because she is old, but she is still happy and laughing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What sense does this imagery appeal to? A. hearing B. taste C. sight D. smell","excerpt":"\"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\"","stem":"What sense does this imagery appeal to?","choices":{"A":"hearing","B":"taste","C":"sight","D":"smell"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"These lines describe colors and feelings about colors. Imagery about colors appeals to the sense of sight.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"sepia\"? A. To make the poem longer B. To emphasize the color and create a rhythm C. Because she forgot other words D. To confuse the reader","excerpt":"\"Brown. Sepia. Inky, crinkly sepia.\"","stem":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"sepia\"?","choices":{"A":"To make the poem longer","B":"To emphasize the color and create a rhythm","C":"Because she forgot other words","D":"To confuse the reader"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repetition is a sound device in poetry. Repeating \"sepia\" emphasizes the brown color and creates a rhythm that sounds like a poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Brown. Sepia. Inky, crinkly sepia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What word describes Aunty\u0027s face now? A. smooth B. crinkled C. painted D. young","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled face.\"","stem":"What word describes Aunty\u0027s face now?","choices":{"A":"smooth","B":"crinkled","C":"painted","D":"young"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says Aunty\u0027s face is \"crinkled,\" which means wrinkled or creased from age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What does the speaker realize about the photo? A. The girl is a stranger. B. The girl in the photo is young Aunty, and they share the same eyes. C. The photo is fake. D. Aunty bought the photo at a store.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What does the speaker realize about the photo?","choices":{"A":"The girl is a stranger.","B":"The girl in the photo is young Aunty, and they share the same eyes.","C":"The photo is fake.","D":"Aunty bought the photo at a store."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker sees that the young girl in the photo has Aunty\u0027s eyes. She realizes the girl is young Aunty, and they share a family resemblance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q020","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show he liked the bus. B. To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy. C. To show he was very young. D. To prove he had a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show he liked the bus.","B":"To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy.","C":"To show he was very young.","D":"To prove he had a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A large number like 30 highlights the long sacrifice he made, making his story more impactful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Yes, because she loves writing more than anything. B. No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams. C. Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good. D. It does not matter what her father did.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because she loves writing more than anything.","B":"No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams.","C":"Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good.","D":"It does not matter what her father did."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem establishes the father\u0027s unfulfilled dream as the primary motivation for the daughter\u0027s career choice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q001","read_aloud":"If a story is \"vivid,\" what is it like? A. It is difficult to read. B. It feels very real and colorful. C. It is short and ends quickly. D. It is meant for small children.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"If a story is \"vivid,\" what is it like?","choices":{"A":"It is difficult to read.","B":"It feels very real and colorful.","C":"It is short and ends quickly.","D":"It is meant for small children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vivid imagery creates clear, bright pictures in the reader\u0027s mind, much like the colors in a large box of crayons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why did the father\u0027s art degrees \"sit hardening on a shelf\"? A. He forgot where he put them. B. He never got to use them because he was busy working on the bus. C. The shelf was too high to reach. D. He didn\u0027t want to be an artist anymore.","excerpt":"\"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\"","stem":"Why did the father\u0027s art degrees \"sit hardening on a shelf\"?","choices":{"A":"He forgot where he put them.","B":"He never got to use them because he was busy working on the bus.","C":"The shelf was too high to reach.","D":"He didn\u0027t want to be an artist anymore."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context implies he had to work a different job (the bus), so his art career was set aside.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q003","read_aloud":"How are the father\u0027s art and the speaker\u0027s writing similar? A. They both use paper and pens. B. They are both ways to be creative and share ideas. C. They both require riding a bus. D. They both use spruce wood.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How are the father\u0027s art and the speaker\u0027s writing similar?","choices":{"A":"They both use paper and pens.","B":"They are both ways to be creative and share ideas.","C":"They both require riding a bus.","D":"They both use spruce wood."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Though the tools are different, both activities are creative forms of expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q004","read_aloud":"If the father had been a famous artist, how might the poem be different? A. The speaker might have chosen a different job. B. The speaker would be sad. C. The father would be a bus driver. D. The speaker would stop writing books.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"If the father had been a famous artist, how might the poem be different?","choices":{"A":"The speaker might have chosen a different job.","B":"The speaker would be sad.","C":"The father would be a bus driver.","D":"The speaker would stop writing books."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker notes that her writing is a response to her father\u0027s unfulfilled dream; if he had succeeded, her path might have been different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the poet mention the bus? A. To show he liked to travel. B. To show he had a long, tiring commute for work. C. To prove he didn\u0027t own a car. D. To show he enjoyed looking out the window.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Why does the poet mention the bus?","choices":{"A":"To show he liked to travel.","B":"To show he had a long, tiring commute for work.","C":"To prove he didn\u0027t own a car.","D":"To show he enjoyed looking out the window."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bus represents the daily grind of his job that kept him from his dream of being an artist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"crinkled\" describe in this excerpt? A. Aunty\u0027s bright and smooth skin B. The edges of the old photograph C. Aunty\u0027s wrinkled skin from getting older D. The brown wood of the violin","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What does \"crinkled\" describe in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Aunty\u0027s bright and smooth skin","B":"The edges of the old photograph","C":"Aunty\u0027s wrinkled skin from getting older","D":"The brown wood of the violin"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Aunty is holding the photo next to her cheek, and \"crinkled\" describes the wrinkles on her face from age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the father\u0027s job at the post office? A. It was a highly respected job that made him very rich. B. It was a fun job that allowed him to paint during his shifts. C. It was a temporary job that he only worked for a few months. D. It was a tiring, blue-collar job that he took to support his family.","excerpt":"\"He dressed in the blue uniform\u0026 black shoes of many other fathers who also weren\u0027t doctors or lawyers, teachers or preachers,\u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the father\u0027s job at the post office?","choices":{"A":"It was a highly respected job that made him very rich.","B":"It was a fun job that allowed him to paint during his shifts.","C":"It was a temporary job that he only worked for a few months.","D":"It was a tiring, blue-collar job that he took to support his family."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The father worked late nights and weekends in a uniform, which shows it was a hard, working-class job he did to provide for his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He dressed in the blue uniform\u0026 black shoes of many other fathers who also weren\u0027t doctors or lawyers, teachers or preachers,\u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q008","read_aloud":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. How are the older relatives in both poems similar? A. They both play musical instruments for the family. B. They both look at old photographs and cry. C. They both moved away from the family a long time ago. D. They both show their love and history through their brown hands.","excerpt":"Sepia","stem":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. How are the older relatives in both poems similar?","choices":{"A":"They both play musical instruments for the family.","B":"They both look at old photographs and cry.","C":"They both moved away from the family a long time ago.","D":"They both show their love and history through their brown hands."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Both poems focus on the brown hands of the older relatives as they share their art, music, and memories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sepia"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q009","read_aloud":"How does the speaker apply her father\u0027s artistic dream to her own life? A. She paints pictures of her father at the post office. B. She uses bright, detailed words to write her books. C. She draws pictures with a 64-colors box of crayons. D. She works at the post office to pay her bills.","excerpt":"\"he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the speaker apply her father\u0027s artistic dream to her own life?","choices":{"A":"She paints pictures of her father at the post office.","B":"She uses bright, detailed words to write her books.","C":"She draws pictures with a 64-colors box of crayons.","D":"She works at the post office to pay her bills."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker writes books using words that are \"vivid\" like crayons, applying her father\u0027s visual art to her writing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How does the author use the color \"sepia brown\" to connect the past and the present? A. It shows that the photo is old, but Aunty\u0027s eyes are still the same. B. It shows that Aunty wants to buy a new brown dress. C. It shows that the speaker does not like old photographs. D. It shows that the photo was painted by an artist.","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"How does the author use the color \"sepia brown\" to connect the past and the present?","choices":{"A":"It shows that the photo is old, but Aunty\u0027s eyes are still the same.","B":"It shows that Aunty wants to buy a new brown dress.","C":"It shows that the speaker does not like old photographs.","D":"It shows that the photo was painted by an artist."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Sepia\" is a color associated with old photos, showing that while the photo is from the past, Aunty\u0027s eyes remain the same today.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"vivid\" mean? A. Dull and faded B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Dark and shadowy D. Quiet and soft","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64- colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does \"vivid\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Dull and faded","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Dark and shadowy","D":"Quiet and soft"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vivid means bright and clear, like colorful crayons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64- colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What does this line suggest about the speaker and Aunty? A. They are not related. B. They are related; the speaker sees family resemblance. C. They are strangers. D. The speaker is Aunty\u0027s mother.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What does this line suggest about the speaker and Aunty?","choices":{"A":"They are not related.","B":"They are related; the speaker sees family resemblance.","C":"They are strangers.","D":"The speaker is Aunty\u0027s mother."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sharing similar eyes shows family connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"hardening on a shelf\" suggest? A. He used them every day. B. They were unused and forgotten while he worked another job. C. They were brand new. D. He sold them.","excerpt":"\"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What does \"hardening on a shelf\" suggest?","choices":{"A":"He used them every day.","B":"They were unused and forgotten while he worked another job.","C":"They were brand new.","D":"He sold them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They sat unused for years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q014","read_aloud":"What does this contrast tell you about Aunty? A. She is unhappy. B. Her body is old, but her spirit is joyful. C. She cannot speak. D. She is angry.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What does this contrast tell you about Aunty?","choices":{"A":"She is unhappy.","B":"Her body is old, but her spirit is joyful.","C":"She cannot speak.","D":"She is angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Despite aging, she laughs and is joyful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"crinkled\" mean? A. smooth and flat B. wrinkled or creased C. wet and slippery D. cold and frozen","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled face.\"","stem":"What does \"crinkled\" mean?","choices":{"A":"smooth and flat","B":"wrinkled or creased","C":"wet and slippery","D":"cold and frozen"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Crinkled\" means wrinkled or creased, like a piece of paper that has been crushed. Aunty\u0027s face has wrinkles from age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How are these two poems similar? A. They both use colors to create strong images. B. They both are about cooking. C. They both use loud sounds. D. They both are set in the future.","excerpt":"From \"Artist to Artist\": \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\" From \"Sepia\": \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\"","stem":"How are these two poems similar?","choices":{"A":"They both use colors to create strong images.","B":"They both are about cooking.","C":"They both use loud sounds.","D":"They both are set in the future."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Both poems use colors to help readers see images. \"Artist to Artist\" uses crayon colors. \"Sepia\" uses shades of brown to describe memories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From \"Artist to Artist\": \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\" From \"Sepia\": \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker ask her father what he wants to be now? A. She thinks he should go back to work. B. Now that he is retired, he has time to be an artist again. C. She wants him to move away. D. She is making fun of him.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired ... ...what do you want to be?\"","stem":"Why does the speaker ask her father what he wants to be now?","choices":{"A":"She thinks he should go back to work.","B":"Now that he is retired, he has time to be an artist again.","C":"She wants him to move away.","D":"She is making fun of him."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The father worked for 30 years and could not be an artist. Now that he is retired, he has free time. The speaker hopes he can follow his dream again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired ... ...what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the poet use the word \"hardening\"? A. The degrees and paints became physically hard. B. To show that the father\u0027s dreams were unused and forgotten over time. C. The shelf was made of hard wood. D. The room was very cold.","excerpt":"\"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"Why does the poet use the word \"hardening\"?","choices":{"A":"The degrees and paints became physically hard.","B":"To show that the father\u0027s dreams were unused and forgotten over time.","C":"The shelf was made of hard wood.","D":"The room was very cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Hardening\" suggests that the father\u0027s art supplies and degrees sat unused for so long that they seemed to become stiff and forgotten. It shows his dreams were left behind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show he liked the bus. B. To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy. C. To show he was very young. D. To prove he had a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show he liked the bus.","B":"To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy.","C":"To show he was very young.","D":"To prove he had a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A large number like 30 highlights the long sacrifice he made, making his story more impactful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q001","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s use of \"vivid\" help the reader understand the writing? A. It tells us the book is very long. B. It shows the writing is colorful, clear, and full of detail. C. It explains that the author used crayons to write. D. It means the book is about art supplies.","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the author\u0027s use of \"vivid\" help the reader understand the writing?","choices":{"A":"It tells us the book is very long.","B":"It shows the writing is colorful, clear, and full of detail.","C":"It explains that the author used crayons to write.","D":"It means the book is about art supplies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The comparison to a large box of crayons highlights how the words create strong, clear images in the reader\u0027s mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What was the cause of the father\u0027s art supplies \"hardening on a shelf\"? A. He lost interest in art. B. He had to spend 30 years riding the bus for work instead of painting. C. He didn\u0027t know how to use his brushes properly. D. He wanted to save his art for when he was old.","excerpt":"\"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\"","stem":"What was the cause of the father\u0027s art supplies \"hardening on a shelf\"?","choices":{"A":"He lost interest in art.","B":"He had to spend 30 years riding the bus for work instead of painting.","C":"He didn\u0027t know how to use his brushes properly.","D":"He wanted to save his art for when he was old."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His demanding work schedule prevented him from practicing his art, causing his supplies to go unused.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Aunty\u0027s personality? A. She is angry about being old. B. She is fragile and unable to speak. C. She has a joyful and positive spirit despite her age. D. She is too tired to talk to anyone.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Aunty\u0027s personality?","choices":{"A":"She is angry about being old.","B":"She is fragile and unable to speak.","C":"She has a joyful and positive spirit despite her age.","D":"She is too tired to talk to anyone."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Even though her hand trembles, her voice \"rings with laughter,\" showing she remains happy and vibrant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q004","read_aloud":"If the father had chosen a different job, how might his life have been different? A. He might have had more time to use his art degrees. B. He would have forgotten how to draw. C. The speaker would not have learned to write. D. He would have traveled on a train instead.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"If the father had chosen a different job, how might his life have been different?","choices":{"A":"He might have had more time to use his art degrees.","B":"He would have forgotten how to draw.","C":"The speaker would not have learned to write.","D":"He would have traveled on a train instead."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem implies that his current job was the obstacle to his art; a different job might have allowed him to pursue his passion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why might the poet choose \"spruce wood\" to describe these instruments? A. To show that wood is the best material for houses. B. To describe the specific color and quality of the instruments. C. To explain that the instruments were made by a carpenter. D. To show that the instruments were very cheap to buy.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Why might the poet choose \"spruce wood\" to describe these instruments?","choices":{"A":"To show that wood is the best material for houses.","B":"To describe the specific color and quality of the instruments.","C":"To explain that the instruments were made by a carpenter.","D":"To show that the instruments were very cheap to buy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Spruce is a wood known for its use in musical instruments; mentioning it adds detail about the quality and color of the items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"melodic\" mean in this poem? A. loud and crashing B. dark and mysterious C. rough and bumpy D. pleasing and harmonious to hear","excerpt":"\"Brown. Spruce brown. Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"melodic\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"loud and crashing","B":"dark and mysterious","C":"rough and bumpy","D":"pleasing and harmonious to hear"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The word \"melodic\" describes the beautiful, musical sound of the instruments made of spruce wood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Brown. Spruce brown. Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What sound device is used in the phrase \"taka taka tak\"? A. rhyme B. metaphor C. simile D. onomatopoeia","excerpt":"\"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce brown.\"","stem":"What sound device is used in the phrase \"taka taka tak\"?","choices":{"A":"rhyme","B":"metaphor","C":"simile","D":"onomatopoeia"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Taka taka tak\" are words that imitate the actual sound of clapping, which is called onomatopoeia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What was the effect of the family having bills to pay? A. The father had to work long, tiring hours at the post office. B. The father had to sell his art supplies to buy food. C. The father had to ask his family for money. D. The father had to stop riding the bus to work.","excerpt":"\"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What was the effect of the family having bills to pay?","choices":{"A":"The father had to work long, tiring hours at the post office.","B":"The father had to sell his art supplies to buy food.","C":"The father had to ask his family for money.","D":"The father had to stop riding the bus to work."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Because the family had bills to pay, the father had to work all night and into the day at the post office.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q009","read_aloud":"If you were to draw a picture of this excerpt, what colors and feelings would you most likely include? A. dark gray colors and feelings of sadness B. bright red colors and feelings of anger C. cold blue colors and feelings of fear D. warm golden and brown colors and feelings of joy","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown. Ringing, singing brown.\"","stem":"If you were to draw a picture of this excerpt, what colors and feelings would you most likely include?","choices":{"A":"dark gray colors and feelings of sadness","B":"bright red colors and feelings of anger","C":"cold blue colors and feelings of fear","D":"warm golden and brown colors and feelings of joy"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Words like \"honey-colored\" and \"singing\" create a warm, happy, and musical feeling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown. Ringing, singing brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q010","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s use of the words \"every night,\" \"weekends,\" and \"holidays\" help the reader understand the father\u0027s life? A. It shows that he had a lot of free time to paint. B. It shows that he only worked when he wanted to. C. It shows that he loved traveling on the bus. D. It shows that he worked constantly and had very little time for himself.","excerpt":"\"But every night-\u0026 sometimes even weekends\u0026 holidays- he dressed in the blue uniform\u0026 black shoes... \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\"","stem":"How does the author\u0027s use of the words \"every night,\" \"weekends,\" and \"holidays\" help the reader understand the father\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"It shows that he had a lot of free time to paint.","B":"It shows that he only worked when he wanted to.","C":"It shows that he loved traveling on the bus.","D":"It shows that he worked constantly and had very little time for himself."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Listing all these times shows that the father was always working and rarely got a break.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But every night-\u0026 sometimes even weekends\u0026 holidays- he dressed in the blue uniform\u0026 black shoes... \u0026 rode the 10:00 p.m. bus to the downtown post office.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"melodic\"? A. Harsh B. Tuneful, sweet-sounding C. Silent D. Broken","excerpt":"\"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"melodic\"?","choices":{"A":"Harsh","B":"Tuneful, sweet-sounding","C":"Silent","D":"Broken"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Melodic means tuneful and pleasant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q012","read_aloud":"focuses on a father who gave up art; \"Sepia\" focuses on a family photo. What is one difference between the two poems? A. Both are about fathers. B. \"Artist to Artist\" is about sacrifice and legacy; \"Sepia\" is about aging and family resemblance. C. Both use the same sound devices. D. Neither poem mentions family.","excerpt":"Artist to Artist","stem":"focuses on a father who gave up art; \"Sepia\" focuses on a family photo. What is one difference between the two poems?","choices":{"A":"Both are about fathers.","B":"\"Artist to Artist\" is about sacrifice and legacy; \"Sepia\" is about aging and family resemblance.","C":"Both use the same sound devices.","D":"Neither poem mentions family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They have different central topics.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Artist to Artist"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What does this suggest about the family? A. They do not like music. B. Music is an important, shared family activity. C. Only one person plays music. D. They are all professional musicians.","excerpt":"\"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\"","stem":"What does this suggest about the family?","choices":{"A":"They do not like music.","B":"Music is an important, shared family activity.","C":"Only one person plays music.","D":"They are all professional musicians."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Multiple family members play together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q014","read_aloud":"If you were the speaker, what might you do to honor your father\u0027s sacrifice? A. Never write again. B. Continue creating art and thank him publicly. C. Throw away his art supplies. D. Ignore his example.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"If you were the speaker, what might you do to honor your father\u0027s sacrifice?","choices":{"A":"Never write again.","B":"Continue creating art and thank him publicly.","C":"Throw away his art supplies.","D":"Ignore his example."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Honoring his legacy by creating and thanking him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"melodic\" mean? A. ugly and harsh B. pleasing and harmonious to hear C. quiet and silent D. fast and loud","excerpt":"\"Rich, melodic spruce. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"melodic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"ugly and harsh","B":"pleasing and harmonious to hear","C":"quiet and silent","D":"fast and loud"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Melodic\" means sweet-sounding and pleasant to hear. The poem is about music, so \"melodic\" describes beautiful sounds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rich, melodic spruce. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What sound device does the poet use here? A. A simile B. Repetition of sounds and rhythm C. A metaphor D. A question","excerpt":"\"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\"","stem":"What sound device does the poet use here?","choices":{"A":"A simile","B":"Repetition of sounds and rhythm","C":"A metaphor","D":"A question"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses words with similar endings and a rhythmic pattern. \"Humming, strumming\" and \"ringing, singing\" create a musical feeling through repetition and rhyme.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What sound device is \"taka taka tak\"? A. A simile B. Onomatopoeia C. Alliteration D. A metaphor","excerpt":"\"taka taka tak, rapid spruce heartbeat.\"","stem":"What sound device is \"taka taka tak\"?","choices":{"A":"A simile","B":"Onomatopoeia","C":"Alliteration","D":"A metaphor"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Taka taka tak\" is onomatopoeia. These words sound like the actual sound of hands clapping or a drumbeat. They imitate a real sound.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"taka taka tak, rapid spruce heartbeat.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the poet call the melody \"honey-colored\"? A. The music is actually made of honey. B. To connect the sound of music to a sweet, warm color. C. The street is covered in honey. D. The musicians are eating honey.","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"Why does the poet call the melody \"honey-colored\"?","choices":{"A":"The music is actually made of honey.","B":"To connect the sound of music to a sweet, warm color.","C":"The street is covered in honey.","D":"The musicians are eating honey."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses imagery to connect sound and sight. \"Honey-colored\" makes the music seem sweet, warm, and golden, just like honey looks and tastes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q019","read_aloud":"What do these lines tell you about the family? A. They are fighting with each other. B. They are musicians who play together. C. They are cooking dinner. D. They are painting a house.","excerpt":"\"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s neck. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\"","stem":"What do these lines tell you about the family?","choices":{"A":"They are fighting with each other.","B":"They are musicians who play together.","C":"They are cooking dinner.","D":"They are painting a house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abuelito plays violin, Papa plays guitar, and Tio plays contrabajo. The whole family makes music together. This shows they share a musical tradition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s neck. Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q001","read_aloud":"Which of these items would most likely be described as \"burnished\"? A. A pile of wet leaves. B. An old, rusty bicycle chain. C. A freshly polished brass trumpet. D. A crumpled piece of notebook paper.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Which of these items would most likely be described as \"burnished\"?","choices":{"A":"A pile of wet leaves.","B":"An old, rusty bicycle chain.","C":"A freshly polished brass trumpet.","D":"A crumpled piece of notebook paper."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Burnished\" refers to a shiny, polished finish, which fits a brass trumpet best.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What is the order of events in the father\u0027s life? A. He was an artist, then a student, then a bus rider. B. He went to school, worked on the bus, and then retired. C. He retired, then went to school, then rode the bus. D. He never went to school and only drove the bus.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... what do you want to be?\"","stem":"What is the order of events in the father\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"He was an artist, then a student, then a bus rider.","B":"He went to school, worked on the bus, and then retired.","C":"He retired, then went to school, then rode the bus.","D":"He never went to school and only drove the bus."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem explains he earned degrees (school), worked for 30 years (bus), and is now retired.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker say \"thank you\" to her father? A. Because he gave her a box of crayons. B. Because he taught her how to ride the bus. C. Because his dream inspired her to pursue her own creative path. D. Because he painted a picture of her.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker say \"thank you\" to her father?","choices":{"A":"Because he gave her a box of crayons.","B":"Because he taught her how to ride the bus.","C":"Because his dream inspired her to pursue her own creative path.","D":"Because he painted a picture of her."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The speaker recognizes that his influence and his missed opportunities shaped her own dedication to writing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q004","read_aloud":"What does this short sentence tell us about the relationship between the speaker and her father? A. They were rivals who did not like each other. B. They were partners in the same profession. C. They share a connection through their creative talents. D. They lived in different parts of the world.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"What does this short sentence tell us about the relationship between the speaker and her father?","choices":{"A":"They were rivals who did not like each other.","B":"They were partners in the same profession.","C":"They share a connection through their creative talents.","D":"They lived in different parts of the world."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The parallel structure (\"I write, he drew\") links their actions and emphasizes their shared identity as creators.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q005","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s purpose in using the word \"but\" in this sentence? A. To show that the two parts of the sentence are opposites. B. To show that she is losing her hearing. C. To explain that she is actually very sad. D. To prove that her hand is stronger than her voice.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s purpose in using the word \"but\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To show that the two parts of the sentence are opposites.","B":"To show that she is losing her hearing.","C":"To explain that she is actually very sad.","D":"To prove that her hand is stronger than her voice."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The word \"but\" contrasts the physical weakness of the hand with the strength of the voice, highlighting her resilience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"vivid\" help describe the speaker\u0027s writing? A. It shows her writing is boring and plain. B. It shows her writing is bright, clear, and full of life. C. It shows her writing is confusing and hard to read. D. It shows her writing is short and simple.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the word \"vivid\" help describe the speaker\u0027s writing?","choices":{"A":"It shows her writing is boring and plain.","B":"It shows her writing is bright, clear, and full of life.","C":"It shows her writing is confusing and hard to read.","D":"It shows her writing is short and simple."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" means bright and clear, showing that the speaker\u0027s writing is full of life and detail, just like a box of crayons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What theme is developed in this excerpt? A. Art and creativity can be passed down through families. B. Working at the post office is the best job for artists. C. People should never retire from their jobs. D. Books are better than paintings.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\"","stem":"What theme is developed in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Art and creativity can be passed down through families.","B":"Working at the post office is the best job for artists.","C":"People should never retire from their jobs.","D":"Books are better than paintings."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The father drew, and now the daughter writes, showing that their creative spirits are passed down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Which sense does the imagery in this excerpt primarily appeal to? A. taste B. smell C. touch only D. sight and sound","excerpt":"\"Inky, crinkly sepia brown. Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"Which sense does the imagery in this excerpt primarily appeal to?","choices":{"A":"taste","B":"smell","C":"touch only","D":"sight and sound"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The poem describes the \"sepia brown\" color (sight) and Aunty\u0027s voice that \"rings with laughter\" (soun d).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Inky, crinkly sepia brown. Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q009","read_aloud":"How could you use the idea of \"sepia brown\" in your own life? A. To describe a bright, neon green bicycle. B. To describe a loud, crashing thunderstorm. C. To describe a sweet, delicious piece of candy. D. To describe an old, faded, and nostalgic memory or photograph.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"How could you use the idea of \"sepia brown\" in your own life?","choices":{"A":"To describe a bright, neon green bicycle.","B":"To describe a loud, crashing thunderstorm.","C":"To describe a sweet, delicious piece of candy.","D":"To describe an old, faded, and nostalgic memory or photograph."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Sepia\" is a brownish color often used for old photographs, so it represents old, nostalgic memories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s word choice create a sense of movement in this poem? A. Words like \"brown\" and \"spruce\" make the music feel slow and heavy. B. Words like \"maze\" and \"winks\" make the music feel confusing and scary. C. Words like \"guitar\" and \"contrabajo\" make the music feel silent and still. D. Words like \"travels,\" \"shifting,\" and \"clap\" make the music feel alive and active.","excerpt":"\"Papá\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords. Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern\"","stem":"How does the author\u0027s word choice create a sense of movement in this poem?","choices":{"A":"Words like \"brown\" and \"spruce\" make the music feel slow and heavy.","B":"Words like \"maze\" and \"winks\" make the music feel confusing and scary.","C":"Words like \"guitar\" and \"contrabajo\" make the music feel silent and still.","D":"Words like \"travels,\" \"shifting,\" and \"clap\" make the music feel alive and active."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Action words like \"travels\" and \"shifting\" make the music feel like it is moving and dancing around the street.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Papá\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords. Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" mean? A. Shakes slightly B. Sits still C. Jumps high D. Sleeps","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age.\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Shakes slightly","B":"Sits still","C":"Jumps high","D":"Sleeps"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Trembles means shakes, often from age or emotion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What theme is suggested here? A. Family members never look alike. B. Across generations, family traits (like faces) continue. C. Old photos are boring. D. Aging makes everyone look different.","excerpt":"\"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"What theme is suggested here?","choices":{"A":"Family members never look alike.","B":"Across generations, family traits (like faces) continue.","C":"Old photos are boring.","D":"Aging makes everyone look different."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Family resemblance connects generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What is the effect of placing \"he drew\" next to \"I write\"? A. It shows they are identical. B. It connects the father\u0027s unrealized dream to the daughter\u0027s realized creativity. C. It shows the father was a better artist. D. It shows they never spoke.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"What is the effect of placing \"he drew\" next to \"I write\"?","choices":{"A":"It shows they are identical.","B":"It connects the father\u0027s unrealized dream to the daughter\u0027s realized creativity.","C":"It shows the father was a better artist.","D":"It shows they never spoke."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She continues his dream through her own art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q014","read_aloud":"If you wanted to create a similar poem about your own family, what would you focus on? A. A shared activity that brings your family together B. A family argument C. A rainy day alone D. A grocery list","excerpt":"The whole poem describes a family music session.","stem":"If you wanted to create a similar poem about your own family, what would you focus on?","choices":{"A":"A shared activity that brings your family together","B":"A family argument","C":"A rainy day alone","D":"A grocery list"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Spruce\" focuses on a joyful shared family activity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole poem describes a family music session."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q015","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"melodic\"? A. harsh B. harmonious C. silent D. boring","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"melodic\"?","choices":{"A":"harsh","B":"harmonious","C":"silent","D":"boring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Melodic\" and \"harmonious\" both mean pleasant and musical. They describe sounds that are sweet and work well together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q016","read_aloud":"What mood, or feeling, do these lines create? A. sad and lonely B. joyful and harmonious C. scary and dark D. angry and loud","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\"","stem":"What mood, or feeling, do these lines create?","choices":{"A":"sad and lonely","B":"joyful and harmonious","C":"scary and dark","D":"angry and loud"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Words like \"honey-colored,\" \"humming,\" and \"singing\" create a warm, happy mood. The music sounds joyful and peaceful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Who is the speaker in \"Spruce\"? A. A person watching from outside B. A family member who is part of the music-making C. A music teacher D. A person who does not like music","excerpt":"\"Tio winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern.\"","stem":"Who is the speaker in \"Spruce\"?","choices":{"A":"A person watching from outside","B":"A family member who is part of the music-making","C":"A music teacher","D":"A person who does not like music"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says \"my hands clap out a staccato pattern.\" This shows the speaker is part of the family and joins in the music-making.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tio winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What does \"travels through a maze\" suggest about the music? A. The guitar is lost. B. The music moves in complex, winding patterns. C. The father is walking around. D. The chords are broken.","excerpt":"\"Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\"","stem":"What does \"travels through a maze\" suggest about the music?","choices":{"A":"The guitar is lost.","B":"The music moves in complex, winding patterns.","C":"The father is walking around.","D":"The chords are broken."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A maze has many twists and turns. \"Travels through a maze\" suggests the guitar music moves through many different chords in a complex, winding way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Papa\u0027s guitar travels through a maze of shifting chords.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q019","read_aloud":"How did the father inspire the speaker even though he stopped drawing? A. He taught her to draw every day. B. His dream and his gift of creativity lived on in her. C. He bought her expensive art supplies. D. He became a famous artist.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones.\"","stem":"How did the father inspire the speaker even though he stopped drawing?","choices":{"A":"He taught her to draw every day.","B":"His dream and his gift of creativity lived on in her.","C":"He bought her expensive art supplies.","D":"He became a famous artist."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The father could not be an artist, but he passed on his \"urge to create\" to his daughter. She writes books because of his inspiration. His dream lived on through her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q001","read_aloud":"If you are asked to write a \"vivid\" description of a forest, what should you do? A. Use very few words. B. Use words that describe the colors, sounds, and smells of the forest. C. Only mention the types of trees you see. D. Write about the history of the forest.","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"If you are asked to write a \"vivid\" description of a forest, what should you do?","choices":{"A":"Use very few words.","B":"Use words that describe the colors, sounds, and smells of the forest.","C":"Only mention the types of trees you see.","D":"Write about the history of the forest."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vivid writing uses sensory details to make the subject feel alive, just like a large box of colors creates a bright picture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What do you think the speaker learns from Aunty? A. That getting old is the end of life. B. That memories and joy can keep you young at heart. C. That you should never look at old photos. D. That it is important to stop laughing as you age.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"What do you think the speaker learns from Aunty?","choices":{"A":"That getting old is the end of life.","B":"That memories and joy can keep you young at heart.","C":"That you should never look at old photos.","D":"That it is important to stop laughing as you age."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By sharing her memory and laughing, Aunty shows the speaker that she still values her life and past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What would most likely happen if the father had never wanted to be an artist? A. The speaker might never have written her books. B. The father would have had to work on a bus for 60 years. C. The speaker would have become a bus driver. D. The father would have been a musician.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"What would most likely happen if the father had never wanted to be an artist?","choices":{"A":"The speaker might never have written her books.","B":"The father would have had to work on a bus for 60 years.","C":"The speaker would have become a bus driver.","D":"The father would have been a musician."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker explicitly states that her writing is a direct result of her father\u0027s unfulfilled dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does the author make these instruments seem special? A. By listing how much they cost at a store. B. By describing the material and how shiny they are. C. By saying they are the only ones in the world. D. By explaining how to build them from scratch.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the author make these instruments seem special?","choices":{"A":"By listing how much they cost at a store.","B":"By describing the material and how shiny they are.","C":"By saying they are the only ones in the world.","D":"By explaining how to build them from scratch."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By focusing on the \"spruce wood\" and the \"burnished\" finish, the poet gives the instruments a sense of beauty and craftsmanship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q005","read_aloud":"What is the author trying to show by saying the father felt \"black and blue\"? A. He liked the color blue very much. B. His job on the bus was physically and emotionally painful. C. The bus was painted a dark color. D. He often got into fights on the bus.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What is the author trying to show by saying the father felt \"black and blue\"?","choices":{"A":"He liked the color blue very much.","B":"His job on the bus was physically and emotionally painful.","C":"The bus was painted a dark color.","D":"He often got into fights on the bus."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The expression \"black and blue\" conveys the deep weariness and struggle of his long-term situation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q006","read_aloud":"How does the speaker\u0027s question \"what do you want to be?\" show her feelings toward her father? A. She is angry that he stopped working. B. She is worried that he has no money. C. She is curious and supportive of his next chapter in life. D. She is bored and wants him to get a new job.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\"","stem":"How does the speaker\u0027s question \"what do you want to be?\" show her feelings toward her father?","choices":{"A":"She is angry that he stopped working.","B":"She is worried that he has no money.","C":"She is curious and supportive of his next chapter in life.","D":"She is bored and wants him to get a new job."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The speaker is thanking her father and asking what he wants to do next, showing she supports him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q007","read_aloud":"includes \"Artist to Artist\", \"Sepia\", and \"Spruce\". What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing this collection of poems? A. To teach readers how to play musical instruments. B. To share personal reflections on family, memory, and art. C. To explain the history of the downtown post office. D. To persuade readers to buy a 64-colors box of crayons.","excerpt":"Poetry Collection","stem":"includes \"Artist to Artist\", \"Sepia\", and \"Spruce\". What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing this collection of poems?","choices":{"A":"To teach readers how to play musical instruments.","B":"To share personal reflections on family, memory, and art.","C":"To explain the history of the downtown post office.","D":"To persuade readers to buy a 64-colors box of crayons."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poems are about the speaker\u0027s father, aunt, and family music, showing the purpose is to reflect on family and memories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Poetry Collection"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q008","read_aloud":"uses free verse with no set rhyme scheme, while \"Spruce\" uses repetition and sound words. How does the structure of \"Spruce\" help convey its meaning? A. The strict rhyme scheme makes it feel like a rigid set of rules. B. The lack of punctuation makes the poem feel confusing and broken. C. The short lines make the poem feel quick and rushed. D. The repetition and sound words mimic the rhythm and feeling of making music.","excerpt":"Artist to Artist","stem":"uses free verse with no set rhyme scheme, while \"Spruce\" uses repetition and sound words. How does the structure of \"Spruce\" help convey its meaning?","choices":{"A":"The strict rhyme scheme makes it feel like a rigid set of rules.","B":"The lack of punctuation makes the poem feel confusing and broken.","C":"The short lines make the poem feel quick and rushed.","D":"The repetition and sound words mimic the rhythm and feeling of making music."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The repeating sounds and words in \"Spruce\" copy the beat and rhythm of the family playing instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Artist to Artist"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q009","read_aloud":"How does the contrast between the father\u0027s lost art and the speaker\u0027s writing develop the poem\u0027s meaning? A. It shows that the father\u0027s sacrifices were wasted because the speaker became a writer instead of a painter. B. It shows that the speaker is angry at her father for not teaching her how to paint. C. It shows that working at the post office is the only way to become a good writer. D. It shows that even though the father couldn\u0027t pursue his art, his creative spirit lived on through his daughter.","excerpt":"\"He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics. But along with his gapped teeth, his bow legs\u0026 his first name with an A at the end, he gave me the urge to create...\"","stem":"How does the contrast between the father\u0027s lost art and the speaker\u0027s writing develop the poem\u0027s meaning?","choices":{"A":"It shows that the father\u0027s sacrifices were wasted because the speaker became a writer instead of a painter.","B":"It shows that the speaker is angry at her father for not teaching her how to paint.","C":"It shows that working at the post office is the only way to become a good writer.","D":"It shows that even though the father couldn\u0027t pursue his art, his creative spirit lived on through his daughter."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The father couldn\u0027t paint, but he passed his creative \"urge\" to his daughter, who now creates art through her writing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics. But along with his gapped teeth, his bow legs\u0026 his first name with an A at the end, he gave me the urge to create...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q010","read_aloud":"\"A photo from when I was young.\" / \"Spruce\": \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown. How do both poems use the color brown to create a specific mood? A. In \"Sepia,\" brown creates a mood of old memories; in \"Spruce,\" it creates a mood of warm, rich music. B. In both poems, brown creates a mood of sadness and loss. C. In \"Sepia,\" brown creates a mood of anger; in \"Spruce,\" it creates a mood of fear. D. In both poems, brown is used to describe the outdoors and nature.","excerpt":"Sepia","stem":"\"A photo from when I was young.\" / \"Spruce\": \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown. How do both poems use the color brown to create a specific mood?","choices":{"A":"In \"Sepia,\" brown creates a mood of old memories; in \"Spruce,\" it creates a mood of warm, rich music.","B":"In both poems, brown creates a mood of sadness and loss.","C":"In \"Sepia,\" brown creates a mood of anger; in \"Spruce,\" it creates a mood of fear.","D":"In both poems, brown is used to describe the outdoors and nature."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Sepia brown\" is tied to old photos and memories, while \"spruce brown\" is tied to the warm sound of wooden instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sepia"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What is an antonym of \"vivid\"? A. Bright B. Dull C. Clear D. Lifelike","excerpt":"\"He gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64- colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What is an antonym of \"vivid\"?","choices":{"A":"Bright","B":"Dull","C":"Clear","D":"Lifelike"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vivid means bright and clear; dull is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones, in flesh-colored tones written in words as vivid as a 64- colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author include these details? A. To make the poem longer B. To show the father\u0027s hard work and the speaker\u0027s gratitude C. To complain about the post office D. To describe crayons","excerpt":"The speaker describes her father\u0027s sacrifice in detail.","stem":"Why does the author include these details?","choices":{"A":"To make the poem longer","B":"To show the father\u0027s hard work and the speaker\u0027s gratitude","C":"To complain about the post office","D":"To describe crayons"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The details emphasize sacrifice and thankfulness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The speaker describes her father\u0027s sacrifice in detail."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think this discovery is important to the speaker? Why? A. No, because faces don\u0027t matter. B. Yes, because it connects her to her family\u0027s past and shows resemblance. C. No, because it is just a photo. D. Yes, because she wants to be like Aunty.","excerpt":"\"I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"Do you think this discovery is important to the speaker? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because faces don\u0027t matter.","B":"Yes, because it connects her to her family\u0027s past and shows resemblance.","C":"No, because it is just a photo.","D":"Yes, because she wants to be like Aunty."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Seeing herself in the past connects her to family history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q014","read_aloud":"If you were to write a fourth poem about family for this collection, what might you title it? A. \"The Broken Toy\" B. \"Grandma\u0027s Hands\" C. \"Alone in My Room\" D. \"The Empty Street\"","excerpt":"All three poems are about family.","stem":"If you were to write a fourth poem about family for this collection, what might you title it?","choices":{"A":"\"The Broken Toy\"","B":"\"Grandma\u0027s Hands\"","C":"\"Alone in My Room\"","D":"\"The Empty Street\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It fits the theme of family and generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: All three poems are about family."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Using context clues, what does \"crinkly\" describe? A. smooth and flat B. wrinkled or creased C. wet and shiny D. loud and noisy","excerpt":"\"Inky, crinkly sepia.\"","stem":"Using context clues, what does \"crinkly\" describe?","choices":{"A":"smooth and flat","B":"wrinkled or creased","C":"wet and shiny","D":"loud and noisy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Crinkly\" means wrinkled or creased. In the poem, it describes the old sepia photo that has wrinkles and folds from age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Inky, crinkly sepia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What theme, or message, does \"Sepia\" express? A. Old photos are not valuable. B. Family connections last through time and generations. C. People should not take photos. D. Brown is the best color.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"What theme, or message, does \"Sepia\" express?","choices":{"A":"Old photos are not valuable.","B":"Family connections last through time and generations.","C":"People should not take photos.","D":"Brown is the best color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows that the young Aunty in the photo looks like the speaker. Their eyes are the same. This shows that family traits and connections pass from one generation to the next.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the poet compare the clapping to a \"heartbeat\"? A. The clapping is slow and quiet. B. The rhythm is fast and full of life, like a heart beating. C. The speaker is sick. D. The music is stopping.","excerpt":"\"my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce heartbeat.\"","stem":"Why does the poet compare the clapping to a \"heartbeat\"?","choices":{"A":"The clapping is slow and quiet.","B":"The rhythm is fast and full of life, like a heart beating.","C":"The speaker is sick.","D":"The music is stopping."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A heartbeat is a strong, steady rhythm that keeps you alive. Comparing the clapping to a heartbeat shows the music is energetic and full of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak, rapid spruce heartbeat.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What does the color imagery \"black and blue\" suggest? A. The father\u0027s uniform colors B. Feeling hurt, tired, and worn down from hard work C. The colors of the bus D. The crayons he used","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What does the color imagery \"black and blue\" suggest?","choices":{"A":"The father\u0027s uniform colors","B":"Feeling hurt, tired, and worn down from hard work","C":"The colors of the bus","D":"The crayons he used"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Black and blue\" usually means bruised and hurt. The poet uses this to show the father felt emotionally worn down from 30 years of hard work at a job he did not love.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q019","read_aloud":"What does \"meat on their bones\" suggest? A. The people were eating meat. B. The father drew realistic, full-bodied people with life and substance. C. The crayons were made of meat. D. The people were very thin.","excerpt":"\"Drew people with meat on their bones in flesh-colored tones from my 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does \"meat on their bones\" suggest?","choices":{"A":"The people were eating meat.","B":"The father drew realistic, full-bodied people with life and substance.","C":"The crayons were made of meat.","D":"The people were very thin."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Meat on their bones\" means the people looked real and full of life, not thin or flat. The father drew realistic, three-dimensional people with his crayons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Drew people with meat on their bones in flesh-colored tones from my 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q001","read_aloud":"Why would someone want to \"burnish\" a piece of wood? A. To make it look dull so it doesn\u0027t stand out. B. To protect the wood and make it look beautiful and shiny. C. To make the wood easier to burn for a fire. D. To change the wood into a different material.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Why would someone want to \"burnish\" a piece of wood?","choices":{"A":"To make it look dull so it doesn\u0027t stand out.","B":"To protect the wood and make it look beautiful and shiny.","C":"To make the wood easier to burn for a fire.","D":"To change the wood into a different material."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Burnishing is a method of finishing wood that improves its appearance and durability.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the relationship between the speaker\u0027s life and her father\u0027s past? A. They are completely unrelated. B. The speaker feels that her success is a way to honor her father\u0027s dream. C. The speaker is disappointed in her father\u0027s life. D. The father is jealous of his daughter\u0027s success.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the relationship between the speaker\u0027s life and her father\u0027s past?","choices":{"A":"They are completely unrelated.","B":"The speaker feels that her success is a way to honor her father\u0027s dream.","C":"The speaker is disappointed in her father\u0027s life.","D":"The father is jealous of his daughter\u0027s success."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By writing books because of his artistic dreams, she is turning his \"what if\" into a reality for their family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the poet focus on both the \"trembling hand\" and the \"laughing voice\"? A. To show that she is a confusing person. B. To show the two sides of being old-physical struggle vs. internal joy. C. To explain how she takes photos. D. To show that she is tired of talking.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"Why does the poet focus on both the \"trembling hand\" and the \"laughing voice\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that she is a confusing person.","B":"To show the two sides of being old-physical struggle vs. internal joy.","C":"To explain how she takes photos.","D":"To show that she is tired of talking."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This contrast captures the complexity of aging, acknowledging both the physical decline and the persistence of joy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think the poet\u0027s choice to compare words to a box of crayons is effective? A. No, because words and crayons are not the same thing. B. Yes, because it helps the reader visualize the variety and brightness of the author\u0027s language. C. No, because writers use pens, not crayons. D. Yes, because it means the book is for young children.","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Do you think the poet\u0027s choice to compare words to a box of crayons is effective?","choices":{"A":"No, because words and crayons are not the same thing.","B":"Yes, because it helps the reader visualize the variety and brightness of the author\u0027s language.","C":"No, because writers use pens, not crayons.","D":"Yes, because it means the book is for young children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This metaphor is effective because it uses a familiar object (a large box of crayons) to explain a complex idea (vivid language).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Do you think the father made a \"good\" choice by staying at his job for 30 years? A. No, he should have quit on the first day. B. Yes, he showed great commitment to supporting his family, even if it was hard. C. No, he was just being lazy and didn\u0027t want to draw. D. Yes, because he enjoyed riding the bus more than art.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Do you think the father made a \"good\" choice by staying at his job for 30 years?","choices":{"A":"No, he should have quit on the first day.","B":"Yes, he showed great commitment to supporting his family, even if it was hard.","C":"No, he was just being lazy and didn\u0027t want to draw.","D":"Yes, because he enjoyed riding the bus more than art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While the job was hard, the length of time he stayed shows a deep sense of responsibility toward his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does the contrast between Aunty\u0027s \"trembles\" hand and her \"laughter\" help characterize her? A. It shows she is angry about getting older. B. It shows she is cold and needs a warm blanket. C. It shows she is scared of the photograph. D. It shows she is physically frail but still full of joy and life.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\"","stem":"How does the contrast between Aunty\u0027s \"trembles\" hand and her \"laughter\" help characterize her?","choices":{"A":"It shows she is angry about getting older.","B":"It shows she is cold and needs a warm blanket.","C":"It shows she is scared of the photograph.","D":"It shows she is physically frail but still full of joy and life."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Even though her hand shakes from age, her laughter shows she is still happy and full of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What mood is created by the words \"honey-colored,\" \"drifts,\" and \"humming\"? A. a mood of danger and suspense B. a mood of sadness and grief C. a mood of confusion and chaos D. a mood of peace and warmth","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown. Ringing, singing brown.\"","stem":"What mood is created by the words \"honey-colored,\" \"drifts,\" and \"humming\"?","choices":{"A":"a mood of danger and suspense","B":"a mood of sadness and grief","C":"a mood of confusion and chaos","D":"a mood of peace and warmth"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"These soft, sweet words create a calm, happy, and warm feeling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown. Ringing, singing brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q008","read_aloud":"What is the tone of the speaker in this excerpt? A. bored and distant B. amazed and connected C. angry and resentful D. fearful and anxious","excerpt":"\"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face! Look closer. Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\"","stem":"What is the tone of the speaker in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"bored and distant","B":"amazed and connected","C":"angry and resentful","D":"fearful and anxious"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker is surprised to see her own face and feels a strong connection to her Aunty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face! Look closer. Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think the father\u0027s sacrifice was worth it? Use evidence from the text to support your answer. A. No, because he never got to paint again and forgot his art skills. B. No, because his daughter became a writer instead of a painter. C. Yes, because he got to ride the bus every night for 30 years. D. Yes, because he supported his family and passed his creative spirit on to his daughter.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones\"","stem":"Do you think the father\u0027s sacrifice was worth it? Use evidence from the text to support your answer.","choices":{"A":"No, because he never got to paint again and forgot his art skills.","B":"No, because his daughter became a writer instead of a painter.","C":"Yes, because he got to ride the bus every night for 30 years.","D":"Yes, because he supported his family and passed his creative spirit on to his daughter."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The father gave up his art to pay the bills, but he successfully passed his creative spirit to his daughter, who now writes books.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew\u0026 his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf... he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q010","read_aloud":"If you were to write a poem about a family heirloom, which object would you choose and how would you describe it using color and memory? A. A bright red sports car, describing how fast it goes and how loud it is. B. A worn, brown leather journal, describing the faded handwriting and the stories it holds from the past. C. A shiny silver smartphone, describing the apps it has and how it connects to the internet. D. A pair of brand-new white sneakers, describing how clean they are and where you will run in them.","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"If you were to write a poem about a family heirloom, which object would you choose and how would you describe it using color and memory?","choices":{"A":"A bright red sports car, describing how fast it goes and how loud it is.","B":"A worn, brown leather journal, describing the faded handwriting and the stories it holds from the past.","C":"A shiny silver smartphone, describing the apps it has and how it connects to the internet.","D":"A pair of brand-new white sneakers, describing how clean they are and where you will run in them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A worn leather journal fits the theme of family history, memory, and the color brown used in the poems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek. The eyes! I realize. The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means the opposite of \"melodic\"? A. Sweet B. Dissonant or harsh C. Tuneful D. Pleasant","excerpt":"\"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"Which word means the opposite of \"melodic\"?","choices":{"A":"Sweet","B":"Dissonant or harsh","C":"Tuneful","D":"Pleasant"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Melodic means sweet and pleasant; harsh is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think the father made a good choice to work at the post office? Why? A. No, because he should have followed his dream. B. Yes, because he needed to support his family, even though it was a sacrifice. C. No, because art is more important. D. Yes, because he hated art.","excerpt":"\"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\"","stem":"Do you think the father made a good choice to work at the post office? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because he should have followed his dream.","B":"Yes, because he needed to support his family, even though it was a sacrifice.","C":"No, because art is more important.","D":"Yes, because he hated art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He made a responsible but hard choice for his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the poet use these words? A. To show that the family is wealthy B. To immerse the reader in the musical atmosphere of the poem C. To teach music vocabulary D. To make the poem longer","excerpt":"The poet uses many musical words like \"melody,\" \"humming,\" \"strumming,\" \"chords,\" \"staccato.\"","stem":"Why does the poet use these words?","choices":{"A":"To show that the family is wealthy","B":"To immerse the reader in the musical atmosphere of the poem","C":"To teach music vocabulary","D":"To make the poem longer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The words create the sound and feeling of music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The poet uses many musical words like \"melody,\" \"humming,\" \"strumming,\" \"chords,\" \"staccato.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Why is \"sepia brown\" an important color choice in this poem? A. Sepia is the color of old photographs, matching the theme of memory and aging. B. Sepia is bright and modern. C. Sepia is the speaker\u0027s favorite color. D. Sepia is the color of the frame.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"Why is \"sepia brown\" an important color choice in this poem?","choices":{"A":"Sepia is the color of old photographs, matching the theme of memory and aging.","B":"Sepia is bright and modern.","C":"Sepia is the speaker\u0027s favorite color.","D":"Sepia is the color of the frame."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Sepia connects to old photos and the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q015","read_aloud":"If the father could answer, what might he say? A. \"I wish you hadn\u0027t written this.\" B. \"Keep creating; I\u0027m proud of you.\" C. \"Art is a waste of time.\" D. \"Stop writing and get a job.\"","excerpt":"The speaker writes, \"Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"If the father could answer, what might he say?","choices":{"A":"\"I wish you hadn\u0027t written this.\"","B":"\"Keep creating; I\u0027m proud of you.\"","C":"\"Art is a waste of time.\"","D":"\"Stop writing and get a job.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He inspired her, so he would likely be proud.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The speaker writes, \"Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"trembles\"? A. shakes B. steadies C. quivers D. wiggles","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"trembles\"?","choices":{"A":"shakes","B":"steadies","C":"quivers","D":"wiggles"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Trembles\" means to shake. The opposite is \"steadies,\" which means to hold still and not shake.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the poet use short sentences here? A. To make the poem longer B. To create a strong, emotional impact C. Because she ran out of ideas D. To confuse the reader","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"Why does the poet use short sentences here?","choices":{"A":"To make the poem longer","B":"To create a strong, emotional impact","C":"Because she ran out of ideas","D":"To confuse the reader"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Short sentences create emphasis and emotion. \"I write, he drew\" shows the connection between father and daughter. \"Daddy, thank you!\" is a direct, heartfelt expression of gratitude.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q018","read_aloud":"How do these two poems show family differently? A. One shows family through visual art; the other shows family through music. B. They both show the same thing. C. One is about animals; the other is about food. D. They are both about painting.","excerpt":"From \"Artist to Artist\": \"he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones.\" From \"Spruce\": \"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\"","stem":"How do these two poems show family differently?","choices":{"A":"One shows family through visual art; the other shows family through music.","B":"They both show the same thing.","C":"One is about animals; the other is about food.","D":"They are both about painting."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Artist to Artist\" shows family connection through drawing and writing. \"Spruce\" shows family connection through music. Both show art brings families together, but in different forms.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From \"Artist to Artist\": \"he gave me the urge to create characters with meat on their bones.\" From \"Spruce\": \"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Do you think the father made a good choice to work at the post office? Why or why not? A. No, because he should have ignored his family. B. Yes, because he sacrificed his dream to take care of his family. C. No, because he became rich and famous. D. Yes, because he hated art anyway.","excerpt":"\"But every night-\u0026 sometimes even weekends \u0026 holidays-he dressed in the blue uniform \u0026 black shoes... For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Do you think the father made a good choice to work at the post office? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because he should have ignored his family.","B":"Yes, because he sacrificed his dream to take care of his family.","C":"No, because he became rich and famous.","D":"Yes, because he hated art anyway."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The father gave up his art dream to work hard and pay bills for his family. This was a loving sacrifice. He put his family\u0027s needs before his own dreams.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But every night-\u0026 sometimes even weekends \u0026 holidays-he dressed in the blue uniform \u0026 black shoes... For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"brown\" with different descriptions? A. To make the poem boring B. To show different shades of memory and feeling C. Because she could not think of other words D. To describe a painting she bought","excerpt":"\"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\"","stem":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"brown\" with different descriptions?","choices":{"A":"To make the poem boring","B":"To show different shades of memory and feeling","C":"Because she could not think of other words","D":"To describe a painting she bought"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses \"brown\" with different words like \"wistful,\" \"muted,\" and \"nostalgic\" to show that memories have many layers. Each shade of brown represents a different feeling about the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q022","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q001","read_aloud":"If you are writing a poem, what would be the most \"vivid\" way to describe a rainy day? A. \"It was a wet day outside.\" B. \"Rain tapped against the window like tiny, silver drumsticks.\" C. \"The rain was falling down.\" D. \"I did not like the rain very much.\"","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"If you are writing a poem, what would be the most \"vivid\" way to describe a rainy day?","choices":{"A":"\"It was a wet day outside.\"","B":"\"Rain tapped against the window like tiny, silver drumsticks.\"","C":"\"The rain was falling down.\"","D":"\"I did not like the rain very much.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Option b uses imagery and comparison to create a clear, lively picture in the reader\u0027s mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What is the underlying message of this poem? A. You should always choose the job your parents want. B. Sometimes, dreams pass from one generation to the next. C. You should never take a job you don\u0027t like. D. Artists are usually better writers than others.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"What is the underlying message of this poem?","choices":{"A":"You should always choose the job your parents want.","B":"Sometimes, dreams pass from one generation to the next.","C":"You should never take a job you don\u0027t like.","D":"Artists are usually better writers than others."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem suggests that her father\u0027s artistic spirit lived on through her work, continuing his dream in a new form.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the phrase \"feeling black and blue\"? A. To describe the color of his bus pass. B. To create a powerful mental picture of how much he suffered. C. To suggest that he was a professional boxer. D. To show he was very cold.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the phrase \"feeling black and blue\"?","choices":{"A":"To describe the color of his bus pass.","B":"To create a powerful mental picture of how much he suffered.","C":"To suggest that he was a professional boxer.","D":"To show he was very cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By using an idiom that usually refers to injuries, the author shows the emotional weight of his daily life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q004","read_aloud":"How does the description of these instruments contribute to the \"mood\" of the poem? A. It makes the poem feel sad and dark. B. It makes the poem feel calm and appreciative of quality craftsmanship. C. It makes the poem feel fast and chaotic. D. It makes the poem feel angry and loud.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the description of these instruments contribute to the \"mood\" of the poem?","choices":{"A":"It makes the poem feel sad and dark.","B":"It makes the poem feel calm and appreciative of quality craftsmanship.","C":"It makes the poem feel fast and chaotic.","D":"It makes the poem feel angry and loud."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The focus on well-made, burnished instruments creates a sense of respect and quiet beauty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q005","read_aloud":"If you were to add one more line to this poem, what would best fit the mood? A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"If you were to add one more line to this poem, what would best fit the mood?","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"crinkled\" add to the imagery of the poem? A. It helps the reader hear the sound of the photograph tearing. B. It helps the reader taste the sweetness of Aunty\u0027s laughter. C. It helps the reader feel the cold wind outside. D. It helps the reader visualize the physical signs of Aunty\u0027s aging.","excerpt":"\"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\"","stem":"How does the word \"crinkled\" add to the imagery of the poem?","choices":{"A":"It helps the reader hear the sound of the photograph tearing.","B":"It helps the reader taste the sweetness of Aunty\u0027s laughter.","C":"It helps the reader feel the cold wind outside.","D":"It helps the reader visualize the physical signs of Aunty\u0027s aging."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Crinkled\" helps the reader picture the wrinkles on Aunty\u0027s face, showing her age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty holds the photo up next to her crinkled cheek.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q007","read_aloud":"What do the \"oils \u0026 acrylics\" on the shelf symbolize in the poem? A. the father\u0027s love for his family B. the father\u0027s abandoned dreams and unused talents C. the speaker\u0027s future career as a painter D. the post office\u0027s art supplies","excerpt":"\"his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What do the \"oils \u0026 acrylics\" on the shelf symbolize in the poem?","choices":{"A":"the father\u0027s love for his family","B":"the father\u0027s abandoned dreams and unused talents","C":"the speaker\u0027s future career as a painter","D":"the post office\u0027s art supplies"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paints sitting on the shelf represent the father\u0027s dreams of being an artist that he had to give up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q008","read_aloud":"\"I write, he drew.\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papá\u0027s guitar travels... How do both poems show the importance of family traditions? A. They show that families must work together to pay their bills. B. They show that older relatives prefer to live in the past. C. They show that children should always copy their parents\u0027 exact careers. D. They show that artistic expression and music are passed down through generations.","excerpt":"Artist to Artist","stem":"\"I write, he drew.\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. Papá\u0027s guitar travels... How do both poems show the importance of family traditions?","choices":{"A":"They show that families must work together to pay their bills.","B":"They show that older relatives prefer to live in the past.","C":"They show that children should always copy their parents\u0027 exact careers.","D":"They show that artistic expression and music are passed down through generations."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The father drew and the daughter writes; the grandfather and father play music, showing art and music are passed down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Artist to Artist"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Is the poet\u0027s repetition of the word \"brown\" and \"spruce\" effective in this poem? A. No, because it makes the poem sound repetitive and boring. B. No, because the reader cannot tell what instrument is being played. C. Yes, because it proves that all instruments must be made of spruce wood. D. Yes, because it connects the color of the wood to the rich, warm sound of the music.","excerpt":"\"Brown. Spruce brown. Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Is the poet\u0027s repetition of the word \"brown\" and \"spruce\" effective in this poem?","choices":{"A":"No, because it makes the poem sound repetitive and boring.","B":"No, because the reader cannot tell what instrument is being played.","C":"Yes, because it proves that all instruments must be made of spruce wood.","D":"Yes, because it connects the color of the wood to the rich, warm sound of the music."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Repeating \"spruce brown\" helps the reader connect the look of the wooden instruments to the warm sound they make.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Brown. Spruce brown. Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If you were to write a new stanza for \"Artist to Artist\" from the father\u0027s perspective, what would you write about? A. How much he hates sorting mail and riding the bus. B. How he plans to quit his job and move to a different city. C. How he wishes his daughter would help him sort the mail. D. How he watches the people and stories in the mail and imagines drawing them.","excerpt":"\"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"If you were to write a new stanza for \"Artist to Artist\" from the father\u0027s perspective, what would you write about?","choices":{"A":"How much he hates sorting mail and riding the bus.","B":"How he plans to quit his job and move to a different city.","C":"How he wishes his daughter would help him sort the mail.","D":"How he watches the people and stories in the mail and imagines drawing them."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Even though he couldn\u0027t paint, the father was still an artist at heart and would likely imagine drawing the things he saw.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" suggest about Aunty? A. She is strong. B. She is old and possibly frail, but still happy. C. She is angry. D. She is cold.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" suggest about Aunty?","choices":{"A":"She is strong.","B":"She is old and possibly frail, but still happy.","C":"She is angry.","D":"She is cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Trembling hands can come with age, but her joy remains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Is this poem effective without perfect rhyme? Why? A. No, all poems must rhyme. B. Yes, because sound devices like onomatopoeia and repetition create musicality. C. No, because it is confusing. D. Yes, because it is short.","excerpt":"The poem does not rhyme in a regular pattern but uses rhythm and sound repetition.","stem":"Is this poem effective without perfect rhyme? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, all poems must rhyme.","B":"Yes, because sound devices like onomatopoeia and repetition create musicality.","C":"No, because it is confusing.","D":"Yes, because it is short."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poets can use other sound devices to create musical effects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The poem does not rhyme in a regular pattern but uses rhythm and sound repetition."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Who is the speaker likely to be? A. Aunty\u0027s mother B. Aunty\u0027s niece or younger relative C. Aunty\u0027s teacher D. A stranger","excerpt":"The speaker is looking at an old photo of Aunty.","stem":"Who is the speaker likely to be?","choices":{"A":"Aunty\u0027s mother","B":"Aunty\u0027s niece or younger relative","C":"Aunty\u0027s teacher","D":"A stranger"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker calls her Aunty and sees her own face in the girl\u0027s face.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The speaker is looking at an old photo of Aunty."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think the father would feel honored by this poem? Why? A. No, because he never wanted to be in a poem. B. Yes, because the speaker honors his sacrifice and continues his artistic legacy. C. No, because he wanted to be a mail carrier. D. Yes, because the poem is short.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"Do you think the father would feel honored by this poem? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because he never wanted to be in a poem.","B":"Yes, because the speaker honors his sacrifice and continues his artistic legacy.","C":"No, because he wanted to be a mail carrier.","D":"Yes, because the poem is short."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem honors his dream and sacrifice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the poet use Spanish family names? A. To confuse the reader B. To honor the family\u0027s cultural heritage and make the poem authentic C. To teach Spanish vocabulary D. To rhyme with other words","excerpt":"The poem includes \"Abuelito,\" \"Papa,\" and \"Tio.\"","stem":"Why does the poet use Spanish family names?","choices":{"A":"To confuse the reader","B":"To honor the family\u0027s cultural heritage and make the poem authentic","C":"To teach Spanish vocabulary","D":"To rhyme with other words"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The names reflect the family\u0027s cultural background.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The poem includes \"Abuelito,\" \"Papa,\" and \"Tio.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Which phrase means almost the same as \"black and blue\" in this context? A. happy and joyful B. hurt and worn out C. colorful and bright D. fast and energetic","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Which phrase means almost the same as \"black and blue\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"happy and joyful","B":"hurt and worn out","C":"colorful and bright","D":"fast and energetic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this poem, \"black and blue\" means feeling hurt and worn out from hard work, not literal colors.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What do the oils and acrylics symbolize? A. Cleaning supplies B. The father\u0027s unused dreams and talents C. Food for the family D. Books for school","excerpt":"\"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"What do the oils and acrylics symbolize?","choices":{"A":"Cleaning supplies","B":"The father\u0027s unused dreams and talents","C":"Food for the family","D":"Books for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The oils and acrylics are art supplies. They symbolize the father\u0027s dream of being an artist, which he had to put away and leave unused.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q018","read_aloud":"How does the speaker feel when she sees the photo? A. Angry and confused B. Surprised and connected to her family C. Bored and tired D. Scared and worried","excerpt":"\"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"How does the speaker feel when she sees the photo?","choices":{"A":"Angry and confused","B":"Surprised and connected to her family","C":"Bored and tired","D":"Scared and worried"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker is surprised to see Aunty looked just like her when she was young. She feels a strong connection to her family history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Is that really you, Aunty? I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Why is it important that the speaker notices the eyes? A. Eyes are the only body part that matters. B. The eyes show a deep family connection that lasts through time. C. Aunty has special magical eyes. D. The photo was only of eyes.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"Why is it important that the speaker notices the eyes?","choices":{"A":"Eyes are the only body part that matters.","B":"The eyes show a deep family connection that lasts through time.","C":"Aunty has special magical eyes.","D":"The photo was only of eyes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Eyes are often called \"windows to the soul.\" Noticing the same eyes in young Aunty and old Aunty shows that some things about family never change, even as people age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q020","read_aloud":"If the father had never wanted to be an artist, how might the speaker\u0027s life be different? A. She would still be a writer because someone else inspired her. B. She might not have the \"urge to create\" and might not write books. C. She would be a famous painter instead. D. She would hate all art.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"If the father had never wanted to be an artist, how might the speaker\u0027s life be different?","choices":{"A":"She would still be a writer because someone else inspired her.","B":"She might not have the \"urge to create\" and might not write books.","C":"She would be a famous painter instead.","D":"She would hate all art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says her father gave her \"the urge to create.\" Without his inspiration, she might not have become a writer. His dream sparked her own creativity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q022","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q001","read_aloud":"If a person\u0027s work is \"burnished,\" what does it mean? A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"If a person\u0027s work is \"burnished,\" what does it mean?","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author use these four words to show a shift in family history? A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the author use these four words to show a shift in family history?","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why is \"30 years\" an important detail to include? A. To show he liked the bus. B. To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy. C. To show he was very young. D. To prove he had a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Why is \"30 years\" an important detail to include?","choices":{"A":"To show he liked the bus.","B":"To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy.","C":"To show he was very young.","D":"To prove he had a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A large number like 30 highlights the long sacrifice he made, making his story more impactful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think the speaker would have written books if her father had been a famous artist? A. Yes, because she loves writing more than anything. B. No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams. C. Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good. D. It does not matter what her father did.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"Do you think the speaker would have written books if her father had been a famous artist?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because she loves writing more than anything.","B":"No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams.","C":"Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good.","D":"It does not matter what her father did."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem establishes the father\u0027s unfulfilled dream as the primary motivation for the daughter\u0027s career choice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q005","read_aloud":"If you were going to write a poem about your own family, what \"action\" would you use to describe yourself and a family member? A. \"I run, they walk.\" B. \"I build, they design.\" C. \"I cook, they eat.\" D. \"I sleep, they work.\"","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"If you were going to write a poem about your own family, what \"action\" would you use to describe yourself and a family member?","choices":{"A":"\"I run, they walk.\"","B":"\"I build, they design.\"","C":"\"I cook, they eat.\"","D":"\"I sleep, they work.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is an open-ended comprehension question; option ( b) is the best answer because it mimics the creative parallel established in the original poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"melodic\" change the way the reader experiences the color brown in this poem? A. It makes the color brown seem loud and harsh. B. It connects the visual color to the beautiful, musical sound of the instruments. C. It makes the color brown seem dull and lifeless. D. It shows that the instruments are out of tune.","excerpt":"\"Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the word \"melodic\" change the way the reader experiences the color brown in this poem?","choices":{"A":"It makes the color brown seem loud and harsh.","B":"It connects the visual color to the beautiful, musical sound of the instruments.","C":"It makes the color brown seem dull and lifeless.","D":"It shows that the instruments are out of tune."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Melodic\" means musical, so it connects the brown color of the wood to the beautiful music the instruments play.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rich, melodic spruce brown. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q007","read_aloud":"What is the overall theme of this poetry collection? A. Art and music are only for people who have a lot of free time. B. Getting older is a sad and lonely experience. C. Working hard at a job is the only way to be happy. D. Family bonds, memories, and creative spirits connect generations.","excerpt":"The collection includes poems about a father\u0027s sacrifice, an aunt\u0027s old photo, and a family\u0027s music.","stem":"What is the overall theme of this poetry collection?","choices":{"A":"Art and music are only for people who have a lot of free time.","B":"Getting older is a sad and lonely experience.","C":"Working hard at a job is the only way to be happy.","D":"Family bonds, memories, and creative spirits connect generations."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"All three poems focus on family members sharing their art, music, and memories across different generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The collection includes poems about a father\u0027s sacrifice, an aunt\u0027s old photo, and a family\u0027s music."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q008","read_aloud":"How does the free verse structure of these poems help the authors achieve their purpose? A. It allows the poets to focus on raw emotions, memories, and natural rhythms without being restricted by rhyme. B. It makes the poems easier to memorize for a school performance. C. It forces the poets to use simple words that everyone can understand. D. It proves that the poets did not know how to write rhyming poetry.","excerpt":"The poems use free verse, sensory details, and figurative language instead of strict rhyme schemes.","stem":"How does the free verse structure of these poems help the authors achieve their purpose?","choices":{"A":"It allows the poets to focus on raw emotions, memories, and natural rhythms without being restricted by rhyme.","B":"It makes the poems easier to memorize for a school performance.","C":"It forces the poets to use simple words that everyone can understand.","D":"It proves that the poets did not know how to write rhyming poetry."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Free verse lets the poets focus on the feelings and memories they want to share without worrying about making every line rhyme.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The poems use free verse, sensory details, and figurative language instead of strict rhyme schemes."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q009","read_aloud":"\"he gave me the urge to create characters... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\" / \"Sepia\": \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown. Which poem do you think is more successful at capturing the feeling of love for a family member, and why? A. \"Artist to Artist,\" because it shows how a parent\u0027s sacrifice inspires a child\u0027s lifelong passion. B. \"Sepia,\" because it shows that looking at old photos is the only way to love your family. C. \"Artist to Artist,\" because it proves that writing books is better than painting pictures. D. \"Sepia,\" because it shows that family members must have the exact same eye color.","excerpt":"Artist to Artist","stem":"\"he gave me the urge to create characters... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\" / \"Sepia\": \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown. Which poem do you think is more successful at capturing the feeling of love for a family member, and why?","choices":{"A":"\"Artist to Artist,\" because it shows how a parent\u0027s sacrifice inspires a child\u0027s lifelong passion.","B":"\"Sepia,\" because it shows that looking at old photos is the only way to love your family.","C":"\"Artist to Artist,\" because it proves that writing books is better than painting pictures.","D":"\"Sepia,\" because it shows that family members must have the exact same eye color."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Artist to Artist\" beautifully shows how the father\u0027s hard work and love inspired his daughter\u0027s writing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Artist to Artist"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q010","read_aloud":"(Weekly Question) If you were to create a title for a new poem that combines the themes of \"Artist to Artist,\" \"Sepia\", and \"Spruce\", what would it be and why? A. \"The Post Office,\" because it focuses on the father\u0027s job and sorting mail. B. \"Roots and Rhythms,\" because it captures the ideas of family history, memories, and the music/art passed down through generations. C. \"Brown Wood and Crayons,\" because it only focuses on the physical objects mentioned in the poems. D. \"Getting Old,\" because it focuses only on the negative parts of aging and losing dreams.","excerpt":"What can our families teach us about ourselves?","stem":"(Weekly Question) If you were to create a title for a new poem that combines the themes of \"Artist to Artist,\" \"Sepia\", and \"Spruce\", what would it be and why?","choices":{"A":"\"The Post Office,\" because it focuses on the father\u0027s job and sorting mail.","B":"\"Roots and Rhythms,\" because it captures the ideas of family history, memories, and the music/art passed down through generations.","C":"\"Brown Wood and Crayons,\" because it only focuses on the physical objects mentioned in the poems.","D":"\"Getting Old,\" because it focuses only on the negative parts of aging and losing dreams."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Roots and Rhythms\" covers the family history (roots) and the music/art (rhythms) that connect the speakers to their relatives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What can our families teach us about ourselves?"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What is \"spruce\" in this context? A. A type of pine tree often used for musical instruments B. A person\u0027s name C. A dance move D. A color of paint","excerpt":"\"built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What is \"spruce\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"A type of pine tree often used for musical instruments","B":"A person\u0027s name","C":"A dance move","D":"A color of paint"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Spruce is a type of wood used for instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q012","read_aloud":"How does the speaker\u0027s point of view change after this realization? A. She feels disconnected from Aunty. B. She feels a strong family connection across time. C. She wants to leave. D. She doesn\u0027t care.","excerpt":"\"I see a girl with my face!\"","stem":"How does the speaker\u0027s point of view change after this realization?","choices":{"A":"She feels disconnected from Aunty.","B":"She feels a strong family connection across time.","C":"She wants to leave.","D":"She doesn\u0027t care."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Realizing she looks like young Aunty connects them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I see a girl with my face!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q013","read_aloud":"If you could answer for the father, what might he say? A. \"A mail carrier again.\" B. \"An artist, just like my daughter.\" C. \"I don\u0027t know.\" D. \"A doctor.\"","excerpt":"\"what do you want to be?\"","stem":"If you could answer for the father, what might he say?","choices":{"A":"\"A mail carrier again.\"","B":"\"An artist, just like my daughter.\"","C":"\"I don\u0027t know.\"","D":"\"A doctor.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He always wanted to be an artist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Which poem best shows how family teaches us about ourselves? A. \"Artist to Artist\" - shows how a parent\u0027s sacrifice inspires a child. B. \"Sepia\" - shows how seeing yourself in older relatives connects generations. C. \"Spruce\" - shows how shared family music creates belonging. D. All of the above.","excerpt":"All three poems.","stem":"Which poem best shows how family teaches us about ourselves?","choices":{"A":"\"Artist to Artist\" - shows how a parent\u0027s sacrifice inspires a child.","B":"\"Sepia\" - shows how seeing yourself in older relatives connects generations.","C":"\"Spruce\" - shows how shared family music creates belonging.","D":"All of the above."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Each poem teaches something important about family and self.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: All three poems."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"melodic\"? A. harmonious B. pleasant C. discordant D. sweet","excerpt":"\"Rich, melodic spruce.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"melodic\"?","choices":{"A":"harmonious","B":"pleasant","C":"discordant","D":"sweet"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Melodic\" means pleasant and musical. \"Discordant\" means harsh and not harmonious. It is the opposite of melodic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rich, melodic spruce.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Why is this a poem and not a story? A. It uses short lines, repetition, and imagery instead of full sentences and paragraphs. B. It is longer than a story. C. It has no characters. D. It is written in a different language.","excerpt":"\"Brown. Sepia. Inky, crinkly sepia.\"","stem":"Why is this a poem and not a story?","choices":{"A":"It uses short lines, repetition, and imagery instead of full sentences and paragraphs.","B":"It is longer than a story.","C":"It has no characters.","D":"It is written in a different language."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Poetry uses short lines, repetition, and imagery to create feelings and pictures. This poem does not use paragraphs or tell a story in the traditional way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Brown. Sepia. Inky, crinkly sepia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q017","read_aloud":"What mood does the poet create in these lines? A. Sad and lonely B. Warm, joyful, and full of family love C. Scary and dark D. Angry and frustrated","excerpt":"\"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing. Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s neck.\"","stem":"What mood does the poet create in these lines?","choices":{"A":"Sad and lonely","B":"Warm, joyful, and full of family love","C":"Scary and dark","D":"Angry and frustrated"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The words \"humming, strumming, ringing, singing\" create a musical, joyful mood. The family making music together feels warm and loving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing. Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s neck.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Is the ending of \"Artist to Artist\" hopeful or sad? Why? A. Sad, because the father wasted his life. B. Hopeful, because the father now has a chance to follow his dream again. C. Angry, because the speaker blames her father. D. Confusing, because we do not know what happens.","excerpt":"\"...what do you want to be? \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired ...\"","stem":"Is the ending of \"Artist to Artist\" hopeful or sad? Why?","choices":{"A":"Sad, because the father wasted his life.","B":"Hopeful, because the father now has a chance to follow his dream again.","C":"Angry, because the speaker blames her father.","D":"Confusing, because we do not know what happens."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ending is hopeful. The father worked hard for 30 years. Now that he is retired, he has time to be an artist again. The speaker\u0027s question suggests a new beginning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"...what do you want to be? \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q019","read_aloud":"What do all three poems teach us about how art and creativity connect families? A. Art divides families and makes them fight. B. Art helps families share traditions, memories, and love across generations. C. Art is only for professional artists. D. Families should not create art together.","excerpt":"From all three poems.","stem":"What do all three poems teach us about how art and creativity connect families?","choices":{"A":"Art divides families and makes them fight.","B":"Art helps families share traditions, memories, and love across generations.","C":"Art is only for professional artists.","D":"Families should not create art together."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In \"Artist to Artist,\" the father\u0027s art inspires the daughter. In \"Sepia,\" a photo connects generations. In \"Spruce,\" music brings the family together. All three show art strengthens family bonds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From all three poems."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by \"vivid\" in this comparison? A. Words that are difficult to understand. B. Words that are very bright, clear, and full of life. C. Words that are written in crayon colors. D. Words that are meant only for very young children.","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by \"vivid\" in this comparison?","choices":{"A":"Words that are difficult to understand.","B":"Words that are very bright, clear, and full of life.","C":"Words that are written in crayon colors.","D":"Words that are meant only for very young children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes something that creates a very clear, bright, and lifelike picture in the reader\u0027s mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"burnished\" describe about the instruments? A. That they have been polished until they are shiny. B. That they are made of very old wood. C. That they are broken and need to be repaired. D. That they are very large and heavy.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"burnished\" describe about the instruments?","choices":{"A":"That they have been polished until they are shiny.","B":"That they are made of very old wood.","C":"That they are broken and need to be repaired.","D":"That they are very large and heavy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To \"burnish\" means to polish or rub something until it becomes smooth and shiny.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the poet mention the type of wood? A. To tell the reader how to build an instrument. B. To show that the instruments are high quality and carefully made. C. To explain that instruments are made from trees. D. To prove the instruments are very cheap.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Why does the poet mention the type of wood?","choices":{"A":"To tell the reader how to build an instrument.","B":"To show that the instruments are high quality and carefully made.","C":"To explain that instruments are made from trees.","D":"To prove the instruments are very cheap."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Naming the specific wood used helps the reader understand the quality and care put into crafting the instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this poem? A. Writing books is better than painting. B. The speaker is fulfilling a dream that her father once had. C. Her father was a famous bus driver. D. Writing books is a very difficult job.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this poem?","choices":{"A":"Writing books is better than painting.","B":"The speaker is fulfilling a dream that her father once had.","C":"Her father was a famous bus driver.","D":"Writing books is a very difficult job."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows how the speaker\u0027s career is a way to continue her father\u0027s artistic passion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q005","read_aloud":"What does \"feeling black and blue\" tell the reader about the father? A. He was very tired and worn down by his work. B. He had to wear a uniform that was black and blue. C. He loved riding the bus for 30 years. D. He was trying to become a professional boxer.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What does \"feeling black and blue\" tell the reader about the father?","choices":{"A":"He was very tired and worn down by his work.","B":"He had to wear a uniform that was black and blue.","C":"He loved riding the bus for 30 years.","D":"He was trying to become a professional boxer."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This idiom is used to describe the deep physical and emotional exhaustion he felt from his job.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q006","read_aloud":"Why does the poet contrast her trembling hand with her laughing voice? A. To show she is sick and needs help. B. To highlight that she has a joyful spirit even though she is old. C. To show that she is a very loud person. D. To prove that she cannot draw anymore.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"Why does the poet contrast her trembling hand with her laughing voice?","choices":{"A":"To show she is sick and needs help.","B":"To highlight that she has a joyful spirit even though she is old.","C":"To show that she is a very loud person.","D":"To prove that she cannot draw anymore."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author contrasts her physical age with her vibrant personality to show her resilience and happiness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q007","read_aloud":"According to the poem, how long did the father work on the bus? A. 5 years B. 10 years C. 30 years D. His whole life","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus.\"","stem":"According to the poem, how long did the father work on the bus?","choices":{"A":"5 years","B":"10 years","C":"30 years","D":"His whole life"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem explicitly states, \"For 30 years my father rode the bus.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author use this specific structure? A. To show that writing and drawing are the same thing. B. To create a link between the speaker\u0027s and her father\u0027s creative spirits. C. To show that they did not work at the same time. D. To show that the father was a better artist than the writer.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"Why does the author use this specific structure?","choices":{"A":"To show that writing and drawing are the same thing.","B":"To create a link between the speaker\u0027s and her father\u0027s creative spirits.","C":"To show that they did not work at the same time.","D":"To show that the father was a better artist than the writer."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By placing these actions together, the poet highlights the shared creative nature between the two family members.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q009","read_aloud":"If you were the speaker, what is the best reason to value the photo your Aunty is showing you? A. It is worth a lot of money. B. It connects you to your family\u0027s history and the person your Aunty used to be. C. It is a perfect drawing of a landscape. D. You can use it for your own research project.","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\"","stem":"If you were the speaker, what is the best reason to value the photo your Aunty is showing you?","choices":{"A":"It is worth a lot of money.","B":"It connects you to your family\u0027s history and the person your Aunty used to be.","C":"It is a perfect drawing of a landscape.","D":"You can use it for your own research project."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The photo is a link to the past and a way to understand the Aunty\u0027s identity and personal history. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Poetry Collection\" (includes \"Artist to Artist\", \"Sepia\", and \"Spruce\") Authors: Davida Adedjouma and Malathi Michelle Iyengar Source: Student Interactive U3 Week 4, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter: Look! A photo from when I was young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"vivid\" mean in this context? A. clear, bright, and lifelike B. dark and dull C. old and faded D. quiet and soft","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does \"vivid\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"clear, bright, and lifelike","B":"dark and dull","C":"old and faded","D":"quiet and soft"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker compares her words to a bright box of crayons, meaning \"vivid\" means clear and full of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" mean in this context? A. shakes slightly B. moves quickly C. stays still D. feels cold","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"shakes slightly","B":"moves quickly","C":"stays still","D":"feels cold"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Aunty\u0027s hand \"trembles with age,\" which means it shakes a little bit because she is getting older.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"melodic\" mean in this context? A. loud and crashing B. rough and bumpy C. pleasing and harmonious to hear D. dark and mysterious","excerpt":"\"Rich, melodic spruce brown.\"","stem":"What does \"melodic\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"loud and crashing","B":"rough and bumpy","C":"pleasing and harmonious to hear","D":"dark and mysterious"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Melodic\" describes the beautiful, musical sound of the instruments made of spruce wood.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rich, melodic spruce brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The father worked a hard, tiring job to support his family. B. The father loved riding the bus to work every night. C. The father sorted mail for only a few weeks. D. The father wanted to become a bus driver.","excerpt":"\"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The father worked a hard, tiring job to support his family.","B":"The father loved riding the bus to work every night.","C":"The father sorted mail for only a few weeks.","D":"The father wanted to become a bus driver."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows the father working long hours to pay bills, which means he worked hard to take care of his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He sorted mail all night\u0026 into the day because we had bills to pay. For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q014","read_aloud":"What kind of imagery does the author use in this excerpt? A. imagery that appeals to the sense of taste B. imagery that appeals to the sense of smell C. imagery that appeals to the sense of touch D. imagery that appeals to the senses of sound and sight","excerpt":"\"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown.\"","stem":"What kind of imagery does the author use in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"imagery that appeals to the sense of taste","B":"imagery that appeals to the sense of smell","C":"imagery that appeals to the sense of touch","D":"imagery that appeals to the senses of sound and sight"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The poem describes the \"honey-colored\" sight and the \"humming, strumming\" sounds of the music.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey-colored melody drifts along our narrow street. Humming, strumming brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q015","read_aloud":"\"he gave me the urge to create\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. How are the two poems similar? A. Both poems are about people who work at the post office. B. Both poems show how family members express themselves through art and music. C. Both poems are about looking at old photographs. D. Both poems show that the speakers dislike their family members.","excerpt":"Artist to Artist","stem":"\"he gave me the urge to create\" / \"Spruce\": \"Abuelito\u0027s precise brown fingertips move along the violin\u0027s strings. How are the two poems similar?","choices":{"A":"Both poems are about people who work at the post office.","B":"Both poems show how family members express themselves through art and music.","C":"Both poems are about looking at old photographs.","D":"Both poems show that the speakers dislike their family members."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both poems focus on family members creating art and playing music together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Artist to Artist"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q016","read_aloud":"What instrument is Tío playing? A. the violin B. the guitar C. the piano D. the contrabajo","excerpt":"\"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak\"","stem":"What instrument is Tío playing?","choices":{"A":"the violin","B":"the guitar","C":"the piano","D":"the contrabajo"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says Tío winks from behind the \"contrabajo.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tío winks at me from behind the contrabajo as my hands clap out a staccato pattern: taka taka tak\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker mention the color \"sepia brown\"? A. To show that the girl needs to get her eyes checked by a doctor. B. To show that the photograph is printed on brown paper. C. To show that the girl is wearing brown eyeshadow. D. To show that the girl\u0027s eyes are a warm, old-fashioned, and nostalgic color.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker mention the color \"sepia brown\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that the girl needs to get her eyes checked by a doctor.","B":"To show that the photograph is printed on brown paper.","C":"To show that the girl is wearing brown eyeshadow.","D":"To show that the girl\u0027s eyes are a warm, old-fashioned, and nostalgic color."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"\"Sepia\" is a brownish color associated with old photos, showing the nostalgic, warm connection to the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q018","read_aloud":"How does the father\u0027s unused art supplies contrast with the gift he gave his daughter? A. He lost his physical art supplies, but he passed on his creative spirit and inspiration. B. He wanted his daughter to paint with his old oils and acrylics. C. He was angry that his art supplies were sitting on a shelf. D. He used his art supplies to build a new shelf for his daughter.","excerpt":"\"his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics. But along with his gapped teeth... he gave me the urge to create\"","stem":"How does the father\u0027s unused art supplies contrast with the gift he gave his daughter?","choices":{"A":"He lost his physical art supplies, but he passed on his creative spirit and inspiration.","B":"He wanted his daughter to paint with his old oils and acrylics.","C":"He was angry that his art supplies were sitting on a shelf.","D":"He used his art supplies to build a new shelf for his daughter."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The father couldn\u0027t use his paints, but he passed his creative \"urge\" to his daughter, who now creates art through her writing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"his degrees in art\u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics. But along with his gapped teeth... he gave me the urge to create\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q019","read_aloud":"Based on the entire collection, what is the most important lesson the speakers learn from their families? A. Families teach us that we should always choose a practical job over art. B. Families teach us that our memories, traditions, and creative spirits are gifts that connect us across generations. C. Families teach us that we should never look at old photographs because they are sad. D. Families teach us that musical instruments are more important than books.","excerpt":"\"What can our families teach us about ourselves?\"","stem":"Based on the entire collection, what is the most important lesson the speakers learn from their families?","choices":{"A":"Families teach us that we should always choose a practical job over art.","B":"Families teach us that our memories, traditions, and creative spirits are gifts that connect us across generations.","C":"Families teach us that we should never look at old photographs because they are sad.","D":"Families teach us that musical instruments are more important than books."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poems show that family members pass down their art, music, and memories, which connect the speakers to their past. Section A - Text Information Titles: Artist to Artist, Sepia, Spruce (Poetry Collection) Authors: Davida Adedjouma (\"Artist to Artist\"), Malathi Michelle Iyengar (\"Sepia\" and \"Spruce\")","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What can our families teach us about ourselves?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q020","read_aloud":"Retired means ______. A. Just started working B. No longer working after a career C. Working extra hours D. On vacation","excerpt":"\"now that you\u0027re retired … what do you want to be?\"","stem":"Retired means ______.","choices":{"A":"Just started working","B":"No longer working after a career","C":"Working extra hours","D":"On vacation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Retired means stopped working.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"now that you\u0027re retired … what do you want to be?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q021","read_aloud":"Melodic means ______. A. Harsh and loud B. Pleasant and sweet-sounding C. Silent D. Broken","excerpt":"\"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\"","stem":"Melodic means ______.","choices":{"A":"Harsh and loud","B":"Pleasant and sweet-sounding","C":"Silent","D":"Broken"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Melodic means pleasing to hear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A honey- colored melody drifts along our narrow street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of \"Artist to Artist\"? A. The speaker hates her father. B. The speaker honors her father\u0027s artistic dream and sacrifice. C. Mail carriers are better than artists. D. Crayons are the best art supply.","excerpt":"The whole poem.","stem":"What is the main idea of \"Artist to Artist\"?","choices":{"A":"The speaker hates her father.","B":"The speaker honors her father\u0027s artistic dream and sacrifice.","C":"Mail carriers are better than artists.","D":"Crayons are the best art supply."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem is a thank you to her father.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole poem."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q023","read_aloud":"What sound device is this? A. Simile B. Onomatopoeia C. Metaphor D. Rhyme","excerpt":"\"taka taka tak\"","stem":"What sound device is this?","choices":{"A":"Simile","B":"Onomatopoeia","C":"Metaphor","D":"Rhyme"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The words sound like the clapping rhythm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"taka taka tak\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q024","read_aloud":"Where did his degrees sit? A. On the wall B. On a shelf C. In a drawer D. In a trash can","excerpt":"\"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\"","stem":"Where did his degrees sit?","choices":{"A":"On the wall","B":"On a shelf","C":"In a drawer","D":"In a trash can"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"on a shelf.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q025","read_aloud":"What does this tell us about the speaker and Aunty? A. They are not related. B. They share family features and are related. C. The speaker is Aunty\u0027s mother. D. The speaker is Aunty\u0027s teacher.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes.\"","stem":"What does this tell us about the speaker and Aunty?","choices":{"A":"They are not related.","B":"They share family features and are related.","C":"The speaker is Aunty\u0027s mother.","D":"The speaker is Aunty\u0027s teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Same eyes show family connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you think music is an important part of this family\u0027s identity? Why? A. No, because only one person plays. B. Yes, because multiple family members play together, and the poem is full of musical words. C. No, because they play badly. D. Yes, because they are professional musicians.","excerpt":"The poem celebrates family music-making.","stem":"Do you think music is an important part of this family\u0027s identity? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because only one person plays.","B":"Yes, because multiple family members play together, and the poem is full of musical words.","C":"No, because they play badly.","D":"Yes, because they are professional musicians."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows music as a shared, joyful activity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The poem celebrates family music-making."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q027","read_aloud":"If you were to write a family poem for this collection, what would be your topic? A. A family recipe passed down B. A video game C. A broken toy D. A thunderstorm","excerpt":"All three poems.","stem":"If you were to write a family poem for this collection, what would be your topic?","choices":{"A":"A family recipe passed down","B":"A video game","C":"A broken toy","D":"A thunderstorm"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Recipes, like the topics in these poems, connect generations. Section A - Text information Title: Poetry Collection (\"Artist to Artist\", \"Sepia\", \"Spruce\") Author: Davida Adedjouma, Malathi Michelle Iyengar","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: All three poems."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does \"vivid\" mean? A. dull and gray B. clear, bright, and lifelike C. dark and shadowy D. quiet and soft","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"What does \"vivid\" mean?","choices":{"A":"dull and gray","B":"clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"dark and shadowy","D":"quiet and soft"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" means bright and full of life. The poet\u0027s words are as colorful and strong as bright crayons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q029","read_aloud":"What does \"trembles\" mean? A. dances quickly B. shakes slightly C. grows larger D. turns colors","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"What does \"trembles\" mean?","choices":{"A":"dances quickly","B":"shakes slightly","C":"grows larger","D":"turns colors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Trembles\" means to shake slightly. Aunty\u0027s hand shakes because she is old, but she is still happy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q030","read_aloud":"What does \"melodic\" mean? A. harsh and ugly B. pleasing and harmonious to hear C. silent and quiet D. fast and loud","excerpt":"\"Rich, melodic spruce. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"What does \"melodic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"harsh and ugly","B":"pleasing and harmonious to hear","C":"silent and quiet","D":"fast and loud"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Melodic\" means sweet-sounding and pleasant. It describes music that is beautiful to hear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rich, melodic spruce. Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q031","read_aloud":"What is \"Artist to Artist\" mainly about? A. A girl who hates school B. How a father\u0027s dream inspired his daughter to become a writer C. A family that travels a lot D. A post office in a big city","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist when he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too... he gave me the urge to create.\"","stem":"What is \"Artist to Artist\" mainly about?","choices":{"A":"A girl who hates school","B":"How a father\u0027s dream inspired his daughter to become a writer","C":"A family that travels a lot","D":"A post office in a big city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem tells how the father\u0027s unfulfilled dream of being an artist inspired the speaker to become a writer. His creativity passed to her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist when he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too... he gave me the urge to create.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q032","read_aloud":"What sense does this imagery appeal to? A. hearing B. taste C. sight and feeling D. smell","excerpt":"\"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\"","stem":"What sense does this imagery appeal to?","choices":{"A":"hearing","B":"taste","C":"sight and feeling","D":"smell"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"These lines describe colors and feelings. \"Muted brown\" appeals to sight. \"Wistful\" and \"nostalgic\" appeal to feelings and emotions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wistful, muted brown. Soft, nostalgic brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q033","read_aloud":"What sound device does the poet use? A. A simile with \"like\" or \"as\" B. Repetition and rhythm to create a musical feeling C. A question to the reader D. A long, boring list","excerpt":"\"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\"","stem":"What sound device does the poet use?","choices":{"A":"A simile with \"like\" or \"as\"","B":"Repetition and rhythm to create a musical feeling","C":"A question to the reader","D":"A long, boring list"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet repeats similar sounds and creates a rhythm. This makes the words sound like music, which fits the poem\u0027s topic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Humming, strumming. Ringing, singing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why did the father stop drawing? A. He did not like art anymore. B. He had to work at the post office to pay bills. C. He lost his crayons. D. His teacher told him to stop.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\"","stem":"Why did the father stop drawing?","choices":{"A":"He did not like art anymore.","B":"He had to work at the post office to pay bills.","C":"He lost his crayons.","D":"His teacher told him to stop."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says the father worked at the post office \"because we had bills to pay.\" He had to work instead of following his art dream.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue. He never drew \u0026 his degrees in art \u0026 education sat hardening on a shelf along with his oils \u0026 acrylics.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q035","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker notice the eyes in the photo? A. Eyes are the biggest body part. B. The eyes show a family connection that lasts through time. C. Aunty has unusual colored eyes. D. The photo only showed eyes.","excerpt":"\"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker notice the eyes in the photo?","choices":{"A":"Eyes are the biggest body part.","B":"The eyes show a family connection that lasts through time.","C":"Aunty has unusual colored eyes.","D":"The photo only showed eyes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker sees that she and young Aunty share the same eyes. This shows how family traits and connections pass through generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The girl has Aunty\u0027s eyes, soft and shining, sepia brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q036","read_aloud":"Why is this a strong ending for the poem? A. It is very long and detailed. B. It shows love and gratitude in a simple, powerful way. C. It introduces a new character. D. It makes the reader confused.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\"","stem":"Why is this a strong ending for the poem?","choices":{"A":"It is very long and detailed.","B":"It shows love and gratitude in a simple, powerful way.","C":"It introduces a new character.","D":"It makes the reader confused."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The short sentences create strong emotion. The speaker thanks her father for inspiring her, even though he could not follow his own dream. It is heartfelt and powerful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q037","read_aloud":"How do \"Artist to Artist,\" \"Sepia,\" and \"Spruce\" all show the importance of family? A. They all show families fighting. B. They show art, photos, and music connecting family members across time. C. They show families moving away from each other. D. They show that art is not important.","excerpt":"From all three poems.","stem":"How do \"Artist to Artist,\" \"Sepia,\" and \"Spruce\" all show the importance of family?","choices":{"A":"They all show families fighting.","B":"They show art, photos, and music connecting family members across time.","C":"They show families moving away from each other.","D":"They show that art is not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All three poems show how creative activities connect families. The father passes creativity to his daughter. The photo connects generations. Music brings the family together. Art keeps families close.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From all three poems."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q038","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. Dull and boring B. Clear, bright, and lifelike C. Small and hidden D. Old and dusty","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"Dull and boring","B":"Clear, bright, and lifelike","C":"Small and hidden","D":"Old and dusty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes colors or words that are very clear, bright, and easy to see in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew. Daddy, thank you! \u0026 now that you\u0027re retired... ... what do you want to be? ... written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. \"And then she fell asleep.\" B. \"She was very angry at the photo.\" C. \"She told a story that filled the room with life.\" D. \"She threw the photo away.\"","excerpt":"\"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"\"And then she fell asleep.\"","B":"\"She was very angry at the photo.\"","C":"\"She told a story that filled the room with life.\"","D":"\"She threw the photo away.\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This option matches the positive, vibrant tone created by her laughter and her connection to her past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aunty\u0027s brown hand trembles with age but her voice rings with laughter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It was done very quickly. B. It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent. C. It was done without any planning. D. It was done to hide mistakes.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It was done very quickly.","B":"It was done with great care and is now smooth and excellent.","C":"It was done without any planning.","D":"It was done to hide mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Applying the word \"burnished\" to someone\u0027s work suggests it has been polished to perfection through careful effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. By showing they are the same person. B. By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off. C. By showing they didn\u0027t know each other. D. By showing they had different hobbies.","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"By showing they are the same person.","B":"By showing that the daughter is taking over where the father left off.","C":"By showing they didn\u0027t know each other.","D":"By showing they had different hobbies."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By linking her writing to his drawing, the author shows a continuation of creative passion across two generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To show he liked the bus. B. To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy. C. To show he was very young. D. To prove he had a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To show he liked the bus.","B":"To emphasize that he spent a very long time in a situation that made him unhappy.","C":"To show he was very young.","D":"To prove he had a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A large number like 30 highlights the long sacrifice he made, making his story more impactful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For 30 years my father rode the bus feeling black and blue.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Yes, because she loves writing more than anything. B. No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams. C. Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good. D. It does not matter what her father did.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because she loves writing more than anything.","B":"No, her writing is a response to his missed dreams.","C":"Maybe, but it wouldn\u0027t have been as good.","D":"It does not matter what her father did."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem establishes the father\u0027s unfulfilled dream as the primary motivation for the daughter\u0027s career choice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. \"I run, they walk.\" B. \"I build, they design.\" C. \"I cook, they eat.\" D. \"I sleep, they work.\"","excerpt":"\"I write, he drew.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"\"I run, they walk.\"","B":"\"I build, they design.\"","C":"\"I cook, they eat.\"","D":"\"I sleep, they work.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is an open-ended comprehension question; option ( b) is the best answer because it mimics the creative parallel established in the original poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write, he drew.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Words that are difficult to understand. B. Words that are very bright, clear, and full of life. C. Words that are written in crayon colors. D. Words that are meant only for very young children.","excerpt":"\"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Words that are difficult to understand.","B":"Words that are very bright, clear, and full of life.","C":"Words that are written in crayon colors.","D":"Words that are meant only for very young children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Vivid\" describes something that creates a very clear, bright, and lifelike picture in the reader\u0027s mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"written in words as vivid as a 64-colors box of crayons.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. That they have been polished until they are shiny. B. That they are made of very old wood. C. That they are broken and need to be repaired. D. That they are very large and heavy.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"That they have been polished until they are shiny.","B":"That they are made of very old wood.","C":"That they are broken and need to be repaired.","D":"That they are very large and heavy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To \"burnish\" means to polish or rub something until it becomes smooth and shiny.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. To tell the reader how to build an instrument. B. To show that the instruments are high quality and carefully made. C. To explain that instruments are made from trees. D. To prove the instruments are very cheap.","excerpt":"\"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"To tell the reader how to build an instrument.","B":"To show that the instruments are high quality and carefully made.","C":"To explain that instruments are made from trees.","D":"To prove the instruments are very cheap."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Naming the specific wood used helps the reader understand the quality and care put into crafting the instruments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Violin, guitar and bass built of spruce wood, burnished brown.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w4-poetry-collection-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Writing books is better than painting. B. The speaker is fulfilling a dream that her father once had. C. Her father was a famous bus driver. D. Writing books is a very difficult job.","excerpt":"\"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Writing books is better than painting.","B":"The speaker is fulfilling a dream that her father once had.","C":"Her father was a famous bus driver.","D":"Writing books is a very difficult job."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows how the speaker\u0027s career is a way to continue her father\u0027s artistic passion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I write books, now, because my father wanted to be an artist he grew up \u0026 he was good at it, too.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":3,"week":5,"title":"Life \u0026 Art","author":"Blue Balliett","genre":"Mystery Fiction","essential_question":"How can art and architecture affect a community?","weekly_question":"Why does the Robie House matter to the characters?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["radically","architect","structural","domestic","museum"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Life \u0026 Art. Why does the Robie House matter to the characters?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"radically\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What does the word \"radically\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard? A. The Robie House B. Life \u0026 Art C. A message for students D. A map of Chicago","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote LIFE \u0026 ART.\"","stem":"What did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard?","choices":{"A":"The Robie House","B":"Life \u0026 Art","C":"A message for students","D":"A map of Chicago"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that Ms. Hussey wrote \"LIFE \u0026 ART\" on the blackboard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote LIFE \u0026 ART.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q003","read_aloud":"Who answered Ms. Hussey\u0027s question about the house? A. Tommy B. Petra C. Calder D. Denise","excerpt":"\"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027 Ms. Hussey nodded.\"","stem":"Who answered Ms. Hussey\u0027s question about the house?","choices":{"A":"Tommy","B":"Petra","C":"Calder","D":"Denise"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says, \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up,\" followed by him naming \"The Robie House.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027 Ms. Hussey nodded.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What is going to happen to the Robie House? A. It will be repainted. B. It will be cut into sections. C. It will be sold to a new family. D. It will be used as a school.","excerpt":"\"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\"","stem":"What is going to happen to the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It will be repainted.","B":"It will be cut into sections.","C":"It will be sold to a new family.","D":"It will be used as a school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states the home \"will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the university want to get rid of the house? A. They want to build a new playground. B. It needs too many repairs. C. Nobody likes the house anymore. D. They need the money for books.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\"","stem":"Why does the university want to get rid of the house?","choices":{"A":"They want to build a new playground.","B":"It needs too many repairs.","C":"Nobody likes the house anymore.","D":"They need the money for books."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The university says the house needs an \"impossibly large number of structural repairs,\" which is why they are dismantling it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q007","read_aloud":"life\" and \"art\" began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \"life art\" became \"a trifle\" or \"a filter. What detail shows that Calder is good at solving puzzles? A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"life\" and \"art\" began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \"life art\" became \"a trifle\" or \"a filter. What detail shows that Calder is good at solving puzzles?","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q008","read_aloud":"My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it. According to this excerpt, how do people in the neighborhood feel about the house? A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it. According to this excerpt, how do people in the neighborhood feel about the house?","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q009","read_aloud":"trifle\" meant something not too valuable or important, as his Grandma Ranjana had sometimes used that word, and a filter could mean-well, something you looked through or poured stuff through. Why does Calder think about the meanings of \"trifle\" and \"filter\"? A. He wants to buy a new filter for his house. B. He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words. C. He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert. D. He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson.","excerpt":"He knew the word","stem":"trifle\" meant something not too valuable or important, as his Grandma Ranjana had sometimes used that word, and a filter could mean-well, something you looked through or poured stuff through. Why does Calder think about the meanings of \"trifle\" and \"filter\"?","choices":{"A":"He wants to buy a new filter for his house.","B":"He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words.","C":"He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert.","D":"He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder believes there might be a message in the words, so he thinks about their different meanings to figure it out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He knew the word"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"radically\" mean in this sentence? A. In a small, unimportant way B. In an extreme or far-reaching way C. Slowly and carefully D. Without any change","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What does \"radically\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"In a small, unimportant way","B":"In an extreme or far-reaching way","C":"Slowly and carefully","D":"Without any change"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Radically means in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q011","read_aloud":"Whose hand shot up first? A. Tommy\u0027s B. Petra\u0027s C. Calder\u0027s D. Denise\u0027s","excerpt":"\"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027\"","stem":"Whose hand shot up first?","choices":{"A":"Tommy\u0027s","B":"Petra\u0027s","C":"Calder\u0027s","D":"Denise\u0027s"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says Calder\u0027s hand shot up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q012","read_aloud":"Why does Calder want to tell Petra? A. She is the teacher. B. She always understands his new ideas. C. She doesn\u0027t like him. D. She has a new book.","excerpt":"\"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\"","stem":"Why does Calder want to tell Petra?","choices":{"A":"She is the teacher.","B":"She always understands his new ideas.","C":"She doesn\u0027t like him.","D":"She has a new book."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Petra always understands him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is Ms. Hussey doing at the beginning of the story? A. Teaching a lesson about chalk B. Teaching a lesson about how life and art connect C. Cleaning the blackboard D. Drawing a picture of a house","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art.\"","stem":"What is Ms. Hussey doing at the beginning of the story?","choices":{"A":"Teaching a lesson about chalk","B":"Teaching a lesson about how life and art connect","C":"Cleaning the blackboard","D":"Drawing a picture of a house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey writes \"life \u0026 art\" on the board. She wants the class to think about how life and art mix together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What does Calder guess Ms. Hussey is talking about? A. A museum in New York B. The Robie House C. A school building D. A park in Chicago","excerpt":"\"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027\"","stem":"What does Calder guess Ms. Hussey is talking about?","choices":{"A":"A museum in New York","B":"The Robie House","C":"A school building","D":"A park in Chicago"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder raises his hand and guesses \"The Robie House?\" He knows what his teacher is thinking about.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What do Calder\u0027s parents say about the Robie House? A. Everyone loves it B. People either love it or hate it C. No one knows about it D. It is too small","excerpt":"\"My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","stem":"What do Calder\u0027s parents say about the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"Everyone loves it","B":"People either love it or hate it","C":"No one knows about it","D":"It is too small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder says people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\" This means some people like it and some do not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Calder? A. He is bored in class B. He thinks creatively and makes connections C. He cannot spell D. He is drawing a picture","excerpt":"\"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Calder?","choices":{"A":"He is bored in class","B":"He thinks creatively and makes connections","C":"He cannot spell","D":"He is drawing a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder rearranges letters in his mind. He turns \"life art\" into \"a trifle\" and \"a filter.\" This shows he thinks in creative ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What does the word \"embodies\" mean in this sentence? A. To destroy or tear down B. To show or represent something clearly C. To hide something from others D. To paint in bright colors","excerpt":"\"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice. Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"What does the word \"embodies\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To destroy or tear down","B":"To show or represent something clearly","C":"To hide something from others","D":"To paint in bright colors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests the house stands for or clearly shows Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s special spirit and vision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice. Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What happened to the house in 1941? A. It was turned into a museum. B. It was bought by three families. C. The seminary announced it would be demolished. D. It was officially named a national treasure.","excerpt":"\"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary. ... Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\"","stem":"What happened to the house in 1941?","choices":{"A":"It was turned into a museum.","B":"It was bought by three families.","C":"The seminary announced it would be demolished.","D":"It was officially named a national treasure."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that in 1941, the seminary announced the house was going to be demolished because they wanted the land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary. ... Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Why was the newspaper trembling in Ms. Hussey\u0027s hands? A. She was very cold in the classroom. B. She was upset or nervous about the news. C. She was trying to show the class how to read. D. The classroom was very windy.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey held the now-crumpled article in front of her with both hands, and Tommy noticed that the newspaper trembled.\"","stem":"Why was the newspaper trembling in Ms. Hussey\u0027s hands?","choices":{"A":"She was very cold in the classroom.","B":"She was upset or nervous about the news.","C":"She was trying to show the class how to read.","D":"The classroom was very windy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that the newspaper trembled suggests Ms. Hussey was experiencing a strong emotional reaction, like being upset or nervous, about the news of the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey held the now-crumpled article in front of her with both hands, and Tommy noticed that the newspaper trembled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q020","read_aloud":"How did Frank Lloyd Wright save the house in 1941? A. He bought the house back himself. B. He formed a committee to protect it. C. He moved the house to Japan. D. He turned it into a school for architects.","excerpt":"\"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... He put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\"","stem":"How did Frank Lloyd Wright save the house in 1941?","choices":{"A":"He bought the house back himself.","B":"He formed a committee to protect it.","C":"He moved the house to Japan.","D":"He turned it into a school for architects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he \"put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians\" to rescue the building.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... He put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What is Calder doing in this paragraph? A. He is trying to build a new house. B. He is rearranging letters to find hidden meanings. C. He is drawing a picture for his teacher. D. He is arguing with his friend Tommy.","excerpt":"\"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \u0027life art\u0027 became \u0027a trifle\u0027 or \u0027a filter.\u0027\"","stem":"What is Calder doing in this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"He is trying to build a new house.","B":"He is rearranging letters to find hidden meanings.","C":"He is drawing a picture for his teacher.","D":"He is arguing with his friend Tommy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder is manipulating the letters of the words \"life\" and \"art\" in his mind to discover new words, which is a way of looking for hidden messages.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \u0027life art\u0027 became \u0027a trifle\u0027 or \u0027a filter.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q022","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean? A. Impossible to be split into pieces B. Painted in many different colors C. Very easy to break apart D. Made of old, dusty materials","excerpt":"\"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Impossible to be split into pieces","B":"Painted in many different colors","C":"Very easy to break apart","D":"Made of old, dusty materials"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about \"carving up\" the house, which means it should stay as one whole piece that cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house? A. They want to give it to other museums. B. They need the land for something else. C. They cannot afford the needed structural repairs. D. They do not like the architect anymore.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\"","stem":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house?","choices":{"A":"They want to give it to other museums.","B":"They need the land for something else.","C":"They cannot afford the needed structural repairs.","D":"They do not like the architect anymore."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"While they might want the land, the text explicitly quotes the university saying they cannot afford the \"millions of dollars of renovation\" because the building is a \"hazard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What caused the Robie House to be saved in 1957? A. The university decided it was too beautiful to destroy. B. Frank Lloyd Wright persuaded a developer to buy it. C. A museum offered to pay for the repairs. D. The neighborhood held a protest.","excerpt":"\"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. ... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\"","stem":"What caused the Robie House to be saved in 1957?","choices":{"A":"The university decided it was too beautiful to destroy.","B":"Frank Lloyd Wright persuaded a developer to buy it.","C":"A museum offered to pay for the repairs.","D":"The neighborhood held a protest."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Frank Lloyd Wright returned and talked William Zeckendorf into buying the house, which saved it from the seminary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. ... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l01-q025","read_aloud":"According to Ms. Hussey, what made the Robie House \"revolutionary\" when it was built? A. It was built by a famous man. B. It was the most expensive house in Chicago. C. Its design features were very new and different for the time. D. It was made entirely of glass.","excerpt":"\"Things that were normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside; a hidden front entrance; deep, overhanging eaves; an attached three-car garage.\"","stem":"According to Ms. Hussey, what made the Robie House \"revolutionary\" when it was built?","choices":{"A":"It was built by a famous man.","B":"It was the most expensive house in Chicago.","C":"Its design features were very new and different for the time.","D":"It was made entirely of glass."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ms. Hussey lists several design features that were not normal at the time, which made the house \"revolutionary.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that were normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside; a hidden front entrance; deep, overhanging eaves; an attached three-car garage.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"embodies\" mean in this sentence? A. To destroy or tear down B. To show or represent something clearly C. To hide something from others D. To paint in bright colors","excerpt":"\"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice. Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"What does the word \"embodies\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To destroy or tear down","B":"To show or represent something clearly","C":"To hide something from others","D":"To paint in bright colors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests the house stands for or clearly shows Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s special spirit and vision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice. Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What happened to the house in 1941? A. It was turned into a museum. B. It was bought by three families. C. The seminary announced it would be demolished. D. It was officially named a national treasure.","excerpt":"\"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary. ... Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\"","stem":"What happened to the house in 1941?","choices":{"A":"It was turned into a museum.","B":"It was bought by three families.","C":"The seminary announced it would be demolished.","D":"It was officially named a national treasure."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that in 1941, the seminary announced the house was going to be demolished because they wanted the land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary. ... Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q003","read_aloud":"Why was the newspaper trembling in Ms. Hussey\u0027s hands? A. She was very cold in the classroom. B. She was upset or nervous about the news. C. She was trying to show the class how to read. D. The classroom was very windy.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey held the now-crumpled article in front of her with both hands, and Tommy noticed that the newspaper trembled.\"","stem":"Why was the newspaper trembling in Ms. Hussey\u0027s hands?","choices":{"A":"She was very cold in the classroom.","B":"She was upset or nervous about the news.","C":"She was trying to show the class how to read.","D":"The classroom was very windy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that the newspaper trembled suggests Ms. Hussey was experiencing a strong emotional reaction, like being upset or nervous, about the news of the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey held the now-crumpled article in front of her with both hands, and Tommy noticed that the newspaper trembled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q004","read_aloud":"How did Frank Lloyd Wright save the house in 1941? A. He bought the house back himself. B. He formed a committee to protect it. C. He moved the house to Japan. D. He turned it into a school for architects.","excerpt":"\"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... He put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\"","stem":"How did Frank Lloyd Wright save the house in 1941?","choices":{"A":"He bought the house back himself.","B":"He formed a committee to protect it.","C":"He moved the house to Japan.","D":"He turned it into a school for architects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he \"put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians\" to rescue the building.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... He put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What is Calder doing in this paragraph? A. He is trying to build a new house. B. He is rearranging letters to find hidden meanings. C. He is drawing a picture for his teacher. D. He is arguing with his friend Tommy.","excerpt":"\"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \u0027life art\u0027 became \u0027a trifle\u0027 or \u0027a filter.\u0027\"","stem":"What is Calder doing in this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"He is trying to build a new house.","B":"He is rearranging letters to find hidden meanings.","C":"He is drawing a picture for his teacher.","D":"He is arguing with his friend Tommy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder is manipulating the letters of the words \"life\" and \"art\" in his mind to discover new words, which is a way of looking for hidden messages.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words \u0027life\u0027 and \u0027art\u0027 began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \u0027life art\u0027 became \u0027a trifle\u0027 or \u0027a filter.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"embodies\"? A. destroys B. represents C. forgets D. hides","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"embodies\"?","choices":{"A":"destroys","B":"represents","C":"forgets","D":"hides"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house shows or \"represents\" Wright\u0027s spirit and vision, which is what \"embodies\" means.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q007","read_aloud":"How does Denise react when Ms. Hussey asks her a question? A. She answers the question quickly. B. She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails. C. She stands up and leaves the room. D. She apologizes for being rude.","excerpt":"\"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\"","stem":"How does Denise react when Ms. Hussey asks her a question?","choices":{"A":"She answers the question quickly.","B":"She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails.","C":"She stands up and leaves the room.","D":"She apologizes for being rude."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Denise \"raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails,\" showing she is ignoring the question.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: The house is famous; Effect: It will be cut into sections. B. Cause: The university owns the house; Effect: They announced it will be cut up and donated. C. Cause: Museums want new art; Effect: They built the Robie House. D. Cause: The house is tragic; Effect: People will move to Hyde Park.","excerpt":"\"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: The house is famous; Effect: It will be cut into sections.","B":"Cause: The university owns the house; Effect: They announced it will be cut up and donated.","C":"Cause: Museums want new art; Effect: They built the Robie House.","D":"Cause: The house is tragic; Effect: People will move to Hyde Park."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the University of Chicago owns the house, they have the power to announce that it will be cut up and donated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q009","read_aloud":"Why is the university cutting up the Robie House? A. It needs too many structural repairs. B. It is too small for the students. C. It is located in the wrong city. D. It is not a famous building.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\"","stem":"Why is the university cutting up the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It needs too many structural repairs.","B":"It is too small for the students.","C":"It is located in the wrong city.","D":"It is not a famous building."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that the reason is an \"impossibly large number of structural repairs.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q010","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt suggest about the seminary\u0027s care for the house? A. They protected it from any damage. B. They did not take good care of it. C. They wanted to turn it into a museum. D. They planned to expand the building.","excerpt":"\"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt suggest about the seminary\u0027s care for the house?","choices":{"A":"They protected it from any damage.","B":"They did not take good care of it.","C":"They wanted to turn it into a museum.","D":"They planned to expand the building."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the seminary \"allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair,\" meaning they did not take good care of it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Why did the seminary want to tear down the Robie House in 1957? A. It was too expensive to heat. B. It was dangerous and in poor condition. C. They wanted to build a parking lot. D. Frank Lloyd Wright asked them to.","excerpt":"\"The building limped on, looking worse and worse, until 1957, when the seminary announced that it was dangerous and would need to be torn down.\"","stem":"Why did the seminary want to tear down the Robie House in 1957?","choices":{"A":"It was too expensive to heat.","B":"It was dangerous and in poor condition.","C":"They wanted to build a parking lot.","D":"Frank Lloyd Wright asked them to."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The building was dangerous and looked worse and worse.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The building limped on, looking worse and worse, until 1957, when the seminary announced that it was dangerous and would need to be torn down.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q012","read_aloud":"How old was Frank Lloyd Wright when he returned to save the Robie House again? A. 70 B. 80 C. 90 D. 100","excerpt":"\"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. He had recently completed plans for the Guggenheim Museum in New York City.\"","stem":"How old was Frank Lloyd Wright when he returned to save the Robie House again?","choices":{"A":"70","B":"80","C":"90","D":"100"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he was ninety years old.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. He had recently completed plans for the Guggenheim Museum in New York City.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What did Wright persuade Zeckendorf to do? A. Tear down the house B. Buy the house from the seminary C. Build a new house D. Ignore the house","excerpt":"\"He persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\"","stem":"What did Wright persuade Zeckendorf to do?","choices":{"A":"Tear down the house","B":"Buy the house from the seminary","C":"Build a new house","D":"Ignore the house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He persuaded Zeckendorf to buy it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What does \"embodies\" mean in this sentence? A. hides or covers up B. symbolizes or represents in a clear way C. destroys completely D. builds quickly","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"What does \"embodies\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"hides or covers up","B":"symbolizes or represents in a clear way","C":"destroys completely","D":"builds quickly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Embodies\" means to represent or show something clearly. The house shows Wright\u0027s spirit and vision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What did Ms. Hussey do first? A. She read a newspaper article B. She picked up chalk and wrote on the board C. She asked the class a question D. She sat on a radiator","excerpt":"\"She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"What did Ms. Hussey do first?","choices":{"A":"She read a newspaper article","B":"She picked up chalk and wrote on the board","C":"She asked the class a question","D":"She sat on a radiator"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story begins with Ms. Hussey picking up chalk and writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard. This happens first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Denise? A. She is excited to share B. She is disrespectful and does not care C. She knows a lot about the house D. She is raising her hand","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey frowned. \u0027Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\u0027 Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Denise?","choices":{"A":"She is excited to share","B":"She is disrespectful and does not care","C":"She knows a lot about the house","D":"She is raising her hand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Denise says \"Duh\" rudely. Then she studies her fingernails instead of answering. This shows she is disrespectful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey frowned. \u0027Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\u0027 Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Who owns the Robie House? A. The city of Chicago B. The University of Chicago C. Frank Lloyd Wright D. A private family","excerpt":"\"The University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\"","stem":"Who owns the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"The city of Chicago","B":"The University of Chicago","C":"Frank Lloyd Wright","D":"A private family"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The article says the University of Chicago owns the Robie House. They announced plans to cut it into pieces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the university want to take down the house? A. They need more parking space B. The house needs too many expensive repairs C. They want to build a shopping mall D. The house is too new","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\"","stem":"Why does the university want to take down the house?","choices":{"A":"They need more parking space","B":"The house needs too many expensive repairs","C":"They want to build a shopping mall","D":"The house is too new"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The university says there are too many structural repairs needed. They cannot afford to fix the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q019","read_aloud":"What does the word \"radically\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What does the word \"radically\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard? A. The Robie House B. Life \u0026 Art C. A message for students D. A map of Chicago","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote LIFE \u0026 ART.\"","stem":"What did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard?","choices":{"A":"The Robie House","B":"Life \u0026 Art","C":"A message for students","D":"A map of Chicago"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that Ms. Hussey wrote \"LIFE \u0026 ART\" on the blackboard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote LIFE \u0026 ART.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Who answered Ms. Hussey\u0027s question about the house? A. Tommy B. Petra C. Calder D. Denise","excerpt":"\"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027 Ms. Hussey nodded.\"","stem":"Who answered Ms. Hussey\u0027s question about the house?","choices":{"A":"Tommy","B":"Petra","C":"Calder","D":"Denise"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says, \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up,\" followed by him naming \"The Robie House.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder\u0027s hand shot up. \u0027The Robie House?\u0027 Ms. Hussey nodded.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What is going to happen to the Robie House? A. It will be repainted. B. It will be cut into sections. C. It will be sold to a new family. D. It will be used as a school.","excerpt":"\"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\"","stem":"What is going to happen to the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It will be repainted.","B":"It will be cut into sections.","C":"It will be sold to a new family.","D":"It will be used as a school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states the home \"will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Why does the university want to get rid of the house? A. They want to build a new playground. B. It needs too many repairs. C. Nobody likes the house anymore. D. They need the money for books.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\"","stem":"Why does the university want to get rid of the house?","choices":{"A":"They want to build a new playground.","B":"It needs too many repairs.","C":"Nobody likes the house anymore.","D":"They need the money for books."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The university says the house needs an \"impossibly large number of structural repairs,\" which is why they are dismantling it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean? A. Impossible to be split into pieces B. Painted in many different colors C. Very easy to break apart D. Made of old, dusty materials","excerpt":"\"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Impossible to be split into pieces","B":"Painted in many different colors","C":"Very easy to break apart","D":"Made of old, dusty materials"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about \"carving up\" the house, which means it should stay as one whole piece that cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house? A. They want to give it to other museums. B. They need the land for something else. C. They cannot afford the needed structural repairs. D. They do not like the architect anymore.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\"","stem":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house?","choices":{"A":"They want to give it to other museums.","B":"They need the land for something else.","C":"They cannot afford the needed structural repairs.","D":"They do not like the architect anymore."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"While they might want the land, the text explicitly quotes the university saying they cannot afford the \"millions of dollars of renovation\" because the building is a \"hazard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean? A. Impossible to be split into pieces B. Painted in many different colors C. Very easy to break apart D. Made of old, dusty materials","excerpt":"\"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the context, what does \"indivisible\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Impossible to be split into pieces","B":"Painted in many different colors","C":"Very easy to break apart","D":"Made of old, dusty materials"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about \"carving up\" the house, which means it should stay as one whole piece that cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I felt sick when I read this. A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house? A. They want to give it to other museums. B. They need the land for something else. C. They cannot afford the needed structural repairs. D. They do not like the architect anymore.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\"","stem":"What is the main reason the university gives for wanting to get rid of the house?","choices":{"A":"They want to give it to other museums.","B":"They need the land for something else.","C":"They cannot afford the needed structural repairs.","D":"They do not like the architect anymore."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"While they might want the land, the text explicitly quotes the university saying they cannot afford the \"millions of dollars of renovation\" because the building is a \"hazard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason [to dismantle the house].\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What caused the Robie House to be saved in 1957? A. The university decided it was too beautiful to destroy. B. Frank Lloyd Wright persuaded a developer to buy it. C. A museum offered to pay for the repairs. D. The neighborhood held a protest.","excerpt":"\"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. ... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\"","stem":"What caused the Robie House to be saved in 1957?","choices":{"A":"The university decided it was too beautiful to destroy.","B":"Frank Lloyd Wright persuaded a developer to buy it.","C":"A museum offered to pay for the repairs.","D":"The neighborhood held a protest."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Frank Lloyd Wright returned and talked William Zeckendorf into buying the house, which saved it from the seminary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. ... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q004","read_aloud":"According to Ms. Hussey, what made the Robie House \"revolutionary\" when it was built? A. It was built by a famous man. B. It was the most expensive house in Chicago. C. Its design features were very new and different for the time. D. It was made entirely of glass.","excerpt":"\"Things that were normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside; a hidden front entrance; deep, overhanging eaves; an attached three-car garage.\"","stem":"According to Ms. Hussey, what made the Robie House \"revolutionary\" when it was built?","choices":{"A":"It was built by a famous man.","B":"It was the most expensive house in Chicago.","C":"Its design features were very new and different for the time.","D":"It was made entirely of glass."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ms. Hussey lists several design features that were not normal at the time, which made the house \"revolutionary.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that were normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside; a hidden front entrance; deep, overhanging eaves; an attached three-car garage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What can you understand about Ms. Hussey from this description? A. She always says exactly what she is thinking immediately. B. She hides things from her students because she does not trust them. C. She thinks carefully before deciding what to tell her students. D. She is too confused to teach her lesson.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey paused, twisting the end of her hair around one finger. The class waited, knowing this meant she was thinking about whether to share something.\"","stem":"What can you understand about Ms. Hussey from this description?","choices":{"A":"She always says exactly what she is thinking immediately.","B":"She hides things from her students because she does not trust them.","C":"She thinks carefully before deciding what to tell her students.","D":"She is too confused to teach her lesson."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The class knows her physical actions mean she is deciding whether or not to share information, showing she is thoughtful about her interactions with them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey paused, twisting the end of her hair around one finger. The class waited, knowing this meant she was thinking about whether to share something.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"indivisible\" mean in this context? A. able to be separated into parts B. unable to be split into pieces C. very old and fragile D. bright and full of windows","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"What does \"indivisible\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"able to be separated into parts","B":"unable to be split into pieces","C":"very old and fragile","D":"bright and full of windows"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about carving up the house, so \"indivisible\" means it cannot be split into pieces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What did the seminary want to do with the land in 1941? A. Turn it into a public park. B. Build new student housing. C. Sell it to a museum. D. Plant a large garden.","excerpt":"\"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\"","stem":"What did the seminary want to do with the land in 1941?","choices":{"A":"Turn it into a public park.","B":"Build new student housing.","C":"Sell it to a museum.","D":"Plant a large garden."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states the seminary wanted the land \"for new student housing.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q008","read_aloud":"a source of worldwide architectural inspiration. How did Frank Lloyd Wright stop the demolition the first time? A. He bought the house with his own money. B. He gathered famous experts to declare it an inspiration. C. He threatened to sue the seminary. D. He hid the blueprints for the house.","excerpt":"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be","stem":"a source of worldwide architectural inspiration. How did Frank Lloyd Wright stop the demolition the first time?","choices":{"A":"He bought the house with his own money.","B":"He gathered famous experts to declare it an inspiration.","C":"He threatened to sue the seminary.","D":"He hid the blueprints for the house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wright put together a committee of famous architects and historians to declare the house an inspiration, which shamed the seminary into keeping it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q009","read_aloud":"Who was shamed into keeping the Robie House? A. the University of Chicago B. the seminary C. the museums D. the students","excerpt":"\"The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\"","stem":"Who was shamed into keeping the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"the University of Chicago","B":"the seminary","C":"the museums","D":"the students"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that \"The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Why did the seminary announce the house was dangerous in 1957? A. Because it had been poorly maintained and looked worse over time. B. Because a storm had destroyed the roof. C. Because students were playing inside it. D. Because Frank Lloyd Wright wanted to rebuild it.","excerpt":"\"The building limped on, looking worse and worse, until 1957, when the seminary announced that it was dangerous and would need to be torn down.\"","stem":"Why did the seminary announce the house was dangerous in 1957?","choices":{"A":"Because it had been poorly maintained and looked worse over time.","B":"Because a storm had destroyed the roof.","C":"Because students were playing inside it.","D":"Because Frank Lloyd Wright wanted to rebuild it."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the building \"limped on, looking worse and worse,\" which led to the announcement that it was dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The building limped on, looking worse and worse, until 1957, when the seminary announced that it was dangerous and would need to be torn down.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"indivisible\" mean? A. Able to be split into many pieces B. Unable to be split into pieces C. Very colorful D. Very old","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"What does \"indivisible\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Able to be split into many pieces","B":"Unable to be split into pieces","C":"Very colorful","D":"Very old"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Indivisible means cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q012","read_aloud":"How does Ms. Hussey feel about the news? A. Happy B. Sick and upset C. Excited D. Confused","excerpt":"\"I felt sick when I read this.\"","stem":"How does Ms. Hussey feel about the news?","choices":{"A":"Happy","B":"Sick and upset","C":"Excited","D":"Confused"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She says she felt sick.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I felt sick when I read this.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Ms. Hussey\u0027s feelings? A. She hates all museums. B. She loves museums but hates the idea of cutting up the house for them. C. She has never been to a museum. D. She wants to keep the house in one piece for herself.","excerpt":"\"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Ms. Hussey\u0027s feelings?","choices":{"A":"She hates all museums.","B":"She loves museums but hates the idea of cutting up the house for them.","C":"She has never been to a museum.","D":"She wants to keep the house in one piece for herself."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She loves museums but not this plan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q014","read_aloud":"Where does Tommy live? A. Across town B. Right next to the Robie House C. In a different city D. In the Robie House","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House?\"","stem":"Where does Tommy live?","choices":{"A":"Across town","B":"Right next to the Robie House","C":"In a different city","D":"In the Robie House"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His apartment is right next to one side of the Robie House.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Why were these features revolutionary? A. They were very expensive. B. They were new and different from what came before. C. They were illegal. D. They were ugly.","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside.\"","stem":"Why were these features revolutionary?","choices":{"A":"They were very expensive.","B":"They were new and different from what came before.","C":"They were illegal.","D":"They were ugly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Revolutionary means new and different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q016","read_aloud":"Why did the seminary agree to keep the house? A. They wanted more money B. Wright shamed them into keeping it C. The students asked nicely D. The house was already fixed","excerpt":"\"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\"","stem":"Why did the seminary agree to keep the house?","choices":{"A":"They wanted more money","B":"Wright shamed them into keeping it","C":"The students asked nicely","D":"The house was already fixed"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wright formed a committee and declared the house important. The seminary was \"shamed into keeping it.\" They felt embarrassed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Tommy? A. He is shy and watches others B. He is angry at the class C. He is sleeping in class D. He is drawing a picture","excerpt":"\"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Tommy?","choices":{"A":"He is shy and watches others","B":"He is angry at the class","C":"He is sleeping in class","D":"He is drawing a picture"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tommy turns around and looks at the other students. He is quiet and watches how people react before he acts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q018","read_aloud":"How old was Wright when he saved the house the second time? A. 50 years old B. 70 years old C. 90 years old D. 100 years old","excerpt":"\"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park.\"","stem":"How old was Wright when he saved the house the second time?","choices":{"A":"50 years old","B":"70 years old","C":"90 years old","D":"100 years old"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states Wright was \"ninety years old\" when he returned to save the house again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q019","read_aloud":"Why is it confusing that Ms. Hussey said \"museums\" like a dirty word? A. She usually loves museums B. She hates all buildings C. She never uses bad words D. She wants to destroy the house","excerpt":"\"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"Why is it confusing that Ms. Hussey said \"museums\" like a dirty word?","choices":{"A":"She usually loves museums","B":"She hates all buildings","C":"She never uses bad words","D":"She wants to destroy the house"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The class knows Ms. Hussey loves museums. But she thinks putting pieces of the house in museums is wrong. This seems strange.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"revolutionary\" mean in this sentence? A. Something that is very old and dusty B. Very different and advanced compared to what came before C. Something that happens every single year D. A design that is meant to be hidden from view","excerpt":"\"\u0027It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other...\u0027\"","stem":"What does \"revolutionary\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Something that is very old and dusty","B":"Very different and advanced compared to what came before","C":"Something that happens every single year","D":"A design that is meant to be hidden from view"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is explaining that these features changed how houses were built because they were new and advanced for that time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other...\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why does the narrator think it is confusing that Ms. Hussey said \"museums\" like a \"dirty word\"? A. Because she usually hates visiting museums. B. Because the students know she actually enjoys museums. C. Because museums are clean places to visit. D. Because she is a teacher and should love museums.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"Why does the narrator think it is confusing that Ms. Hussey said \"museums\" like a \"dirty word\"?","choices":{"A":"Because she usually hates visiting museums.","B":"Because the students know she actually enjoys museums.","C":"Because museums are clean places to visit.","D":"Because she is a teacher and should love museums."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that it is confusing because \"The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q003","read_aloud":"she confided, \"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children. And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe. Why does Ms. Hussey find it ironic that Wright focused on play space? A. Because he hated children. B. Because he had just left his own children behind. C. Because he did not have enough money to build a playground. D. Because he was too old to care about children.","excerpt":"Actually,","stem":"she confided, \"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children. And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe. Why does Ms. Hussey find it ironic that Wright focused on play space?","choices":{"A":"Because he hated children.","B":"Because he had just left his own children behind.","C":"Because he did not have enough money to build a playground.","D":"Because he was too old to care about children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is pointing out the conflict between him designing a great place for other children while having just walked away from his own.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Actually,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey say that in the \"real world,\" the house cannot just sit empty? A. Because it would cost too much to heat the house. B. Because the university could be held responsible if it becomes dangerous to passersby. C. Because the neighbors want a new park built on the land. D. Because empty houses always attract ghosts.","excerpt":"\"Petra Andalee was frowning. \u0027Can\u0027t the house just sit there empty until the money comes in?\u0027 Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot. \u0027In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey say that in the \"real world,\" the house cannot just sit empty?","choices":{"A":"Because it would cost too much to heat the house.","B":"Because the university could be held responsible if it becomes dangerous to passersby.","C":"Because the neighbors want a new park built on the land.","D":"Because empty houses always attract ghosts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She explains that if the house falls on someone walking by, the owner is responsible, so they cannot afford to leave it empty and unmaintained.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Petra Andalee was frowning. \u0027Can\u0027t the house just sit there empty until the money comes in?\u0027 Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot. \u0027In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q005","read_aloud":"How does this information about Tommy change how we see his reaction to the story? A. It shows why he is probably not interested in the Robie House. B. It shows why he might feel a deep personal connection to themes of disappointment and broken promises. C. It explains why he is the best artist in the class. D. It shows that he is happy his stepfather made promises.","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America... And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\"","stem":"How does this information about Tommy change how we see his reaction to the story?","choices":{"A":"It shows why he is probably not interested in the Robie House.","B":"It shows why he might feel a deep personal connection to themes of disappointment and broken promises.","C":"It explains why he is the best artist in the class.","D":"It shows that he is happy his stepfather made promises."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This personal background reveals why Tommy may be sensitive to the idea of \"broken\" things and broken promises, similar to the university\u0027s broken promises regarding the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America... And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q006","read_aloud":"How is the word \"revolutionary\" used in this sentence? A. to describe a violent political uprising B. to describe something new and groundbreaking C. to describe something old and outdated D. to describe something small and simple","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\"","stem":"How is the word \"revolutionary\" used in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to describe a violent political uprising","B":"to describe something new and groundbreaking","C":"to describe something old and outdated","D":"to describe something small and simple"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes new design ideas like flowing rooms, so \"revolutionary\" means new and groundbreaking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What detail shows that Frank Lloyd Wright was highly respected at age ninety? A. He walked with a cane. B. He was considered a national treasure. C. He lived in Hyde Park. D. He had just retired from his job.","excerpt":"\"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. He had recently completed plans for the Guggenheim Museum in New York City, and he was, by then, a national treasure himself.\"","stem":"What detail shows that Frank Lloyd Wright was highly respected at age ninety?","choices":{"A":"He walked with a cane.","B":"He was considered a national treasure.","C":"He lived in Hyde Park.","D":"He had just retired from his job."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that by that time, he was \"a national treasure himself,\" showing his high level of respect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park. He had recently completed plans for the Guggenheim Museum in New York City, and he was, by then, a national treasure himself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q008","read_aloud":"one of the cornerstones of American architecture\" and commenting that only the kitchen needed improvement, he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary. What was the result of Wright\u0027s persuasion? A. William Zeckendorf bought the house. B. The seminary tore the house down. C. The kitchen was completely rebuilt. D. Wright moved into the house.","excerpt":"Describing the Robie House as","stem":"one of the cornerstones of American architecture\" and commenting that only the kitchen needed improvement, he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary. What was the result of Wright\u0027s persuasion?","choices":{"A":"William Zeckendorf bought the house.","B":"The seminary tore the house down.","C":"The kitchen was completely rebuilt.","D":"Wright moved into the house."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states that Wright \"persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Describing the Robie House as"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If you were an architect, how might you feel about the house being remodeled for office use? A. Happy, because offices are more modern. B. Upset, because it changes the original artistic design. C. Indifferent, because all buildings are the same. D. Confused, because offices do not need windows.","excerpt":"\"In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago, which remodeled much of the interior for office use.\"","stem":"If you were an architect, how might you feel about the house being remodeled for office use?","choices":{"A":"Happy, because offices are more modern.","B":"Upset, because it changes the original artistic design.","C":"Indifferent, because all buildings are the same.","D":"Confused, because offices do not need windows."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An architect would likely be upset because remodeling a historic art piece for offices changes its original, revolutionary design.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago, which remodeled much of the interior for office use.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q010","read_aloud":"It is only after extensive attempts to raise funds, both nationally and internationally, that we have made this painful decision. How does John Stone\u0027s statement try to shape the public\u0027s view of the university\u0027s decision? A. It makes the university look greedy and careless. B. It makes the university look responsible and forced by circumstances. C. It makes the university look like it does not care about history. D. It makes the university look like it has too much money.","excerpt":"John Stone, president of the university, said today,","stem":"It is only after extensive attempts to raise funds, both nationally and internationally, that we have made this painful decision. How does John Stone\u0027s statement try to shape the public\u0027s view of the university\u0027s decision?","choices":{"A":"It makes the university look greedy and careless.","B":"It makes the university look responsible and forced by circumstances.","C":"It makes the university look like it does not care about history.","D":"It makes the university look like it has too much money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By mentioning \"extensive attempts to raise funds\" and calling it a \"painful decision,\" Stone tries to show the university had no other choice and acted responsibly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: John Stone, president of the university, said today,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What conflict between life and art is shown here? A. Art is always more important than money. B. Real-world concerns (safety, money) threaten the preservation of art. C. The house is not art. D. No one cares about art.","excerpt":"\"The university probably can\u0027t afford to own a piece of property that they aren\u0027t able to use, and if part of the house fell on someone walking by, the owner would be held responsible.\"","stem":"What conflict between life and art is shown here?","choices":{"A":"Art is always more important than money.","B":"Real-world concerns (safety, money) threaten the preservation of art.","C":"The house is not art.","D":"No one cares about art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Practical issues make saving the art difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university probably can\u0027t afford to own a piece of property that they aren\u0027t able to use, and if part of the house fell on someone walking by, the owner would be held responsible.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q012","read_aloud":"Calder suggested. What does Calder want to do? A. Ignore the problem B. Visit the house and think of ways to save it C. Tear down the house himself D. Write a letter","excerpt":"Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,","stem":"Calder suggested. What does Calder want to do?","choices":{"A":"Ignore the problem","B":"Visit the house and think of ways to save it","C":"Tear down the house himself","D":"Write a letter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He wants to visit and come up with ideas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What does Ms. Hussey suggest about Wright\u0027s possible feelings? A. He was angry at his own children. B. He may have been using the design to ask for forgiveness. C. He hated children. D. He only cared about money.","excerpt":"\"At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children. And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe.\"","stem":"What does Ms. Hussey suggest about Wright\u0027s possible feelings?","choices":{"A":"He was angry at his own children.","B":"He may have been using the design to ask for forgiveness.","C":"He hated children.","D":"He only cared about money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She wonders if it was a way to ask for forgiveness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children. And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q014","read_aloud":"How does Tommy\u0027s personal life connect to the theme of the story? A. He is not interested. B. He understands loss, broken promises, and the need for forgiveness or preservation. C. He wants to be an architect. D. He hates the Robie House.","excerpt":"\"Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America… And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\"","stem":"How does Tommy\u0027s personal life connect to the theme of the story?","choices":{"A":"He is not interested.","B":"He understands loss, broken promises, and the need for forgiveness or preservation.","C":"He wants to be an architect.","D":"He hates the Robie House."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tommy\u0027s experiences mirror themes of loss and broken promises.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America… And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"revolutionary\" mean? A. boring and old B. very different from what came before C. small and hidden D. broken and damaged","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other.\"","stem":"What does \"revolutionary\" mean?","choices":{"A":"boring and old","B":"very different from what came before","C":"small and hidden","D":"broken and damaged"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Revolutionary\" means very new and different. Wright\u0027s ideas were new back then, but now they seem normal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How are Wright\u0027s ideas different from today\u0027s architecture? A. They are exactly the same B. His ideas were new then, but common now C. His ideas were bad D. No one uses his ideas today","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\"","stem":"How are Wright\u0027s ideas different from today\u0027s architecture?","choices":{"A":"They are exactly the same","B":"His ideas were new then, but common now","C":"His ideas were bad","D":"No one uses his ideas today"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wright\u0027s ideas like flowing rooms were \"revolutionary then.\" Now they are \"normal to us.\" His new ideas became common.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What happened to the house after families lived in it? A. It became a museum right away B. A seminary bought it and used it for cafeteria and dorms C. It was torn down immediately D. Wright moved back into it","excerpt":"\"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary.\"","stem":"What happened to the house after families lived in it?","choices":{"A":"It became a museum right away","B":"A seminary bought it and used it for cafeteria and dorms","C":"It was torn down immediately","D":"Wright moved back into it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The seminary bought the house in 1926. They used it for cafeteria and dormitory space. They did not take care of it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why did the house fall into disrepair? A. The seminary did not take care of it B. Wright designed it badly C. The families broke it D. It was too new","excerpt":"\"The seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\"","stem":"Why did the house fall into disrepair?","choices":{"A":"The seminary did not take care of it","B":"Wright designed it badly","C":"The families broke it","D":"It was too new"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the seminary \"allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\" They did not fix or care for the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Why does Calder want to tell Petra? A. She is his teacher B. She understands his creative thinking C. She lives near the house D. She wrote the newspaper article","excerpt":"\"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\"","stem":"Why does Calder want to tell Petra?","choices":{"A":"She is his teacher","B":"She understands his creative thinking","C":"She lives near the house","D":"She wrote the newspaper article"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Petra \"always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\" She gets how his mind works.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"ironic\" mean in this situation? A. The house is made of iron and cold materials. B. It is very sad because the house is falling down. C. The result is the opposite of what was intended. D. The house is becoming a museum for people to visit.","excerpt":"\"\u0027I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\u0027\"","stem":"What does \"ironic\" mean in this situation?","choices":{"A":"The house is made of iron and cold materials.","B":"It is very sad because the house is falling down.","C":"The result is the opposite of what was intended.","D":"The house is becoming a museum for people to visit."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"It is ironic because the house was meant to be a family home for children, but no family has lived there in a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What is Ms. Hussey trying to encourage her students to do? A. To stop worrying about the house and focus on their schoolwork. B. To think deeply about the definition of \"home\" and \"art.\" C. To write a letter to the University of Chicago. D. To go inside the Robie House to play.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\"","stem":"What is Ms. Hussey trying to encourage her students to do?","choices":{"A":"To stop worrying about the house and focus on their schoolwork.","B":"To think deeply about the definition of \"home\" and \"art.\"","C":"To write a letter to the University of Chicago.","D":"To go inside the Robie House to play."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She is asking them to challenge their understanding of what makes a house a home and what makes something art, moving beyond simple facts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author describe Ms. Hussey as if she had \"touched something hot\"? A. To show she was very cold in the room. B. To show that she was startled or shocked by Petra\u0027s suggestion. C. To show that the classroom radiator was turned up too high. D. To show she was trying to cook something.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot.\"","stem":"Why does the author describe Ms. Hussey as if she had \"touched something hot\"?","choices":{"A":"To show she was very cold in the room.","B":"To show that she was startled or shocked by Petra\u0027s suggestion.","C":"To show that the classroom radiator was turned up too high.","D":"To show she was trying to cook something."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This description is a metaphor to show that Petra\u0027s question hit a sensitive or difficult point that caught Ms. Hussey off guard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q004","read_aloud":"What does Ms. Hussey think might have motivated Frank Lloyd Wright? A. He wanted to become the richest architect in the world. B. He was trying to make up for his past mistakes by creating something good for others. C. He wanted the university to pay him for more buildings. D. He wanted to build the most expensive house in Chicago.","excerpt":"\"Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\"","stem":"What does Ms. Hussey think might have motivated Frank Lloyd Wright?","choices":{"A":"He wanted to become the richest architect in the world.","B":"He was trying to make up for his past mistakes by creating something good for others.","C":"He wanted the university to pay him for more buildings.","D":"He wanted to build the most expensive house in Chicago."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey suggests that by designing a great space for other children, he was seeking forgiveness for leaving his own children.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why is Tommy hesitant to tell the class about where he lives? A. He is afraid he will get in trouble for being too close to the house. B. He is not sure if the other students will think he is lucky or if they will react negatively. C. He thinks the other students will make fun of his apartment. D. He is waiting for Ms. Hussey to call on someone else.","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\"","stem":"Why is Tommy hesitant to tell the class about where he lives?","choices":{"A":"He is afraid he will get in trouble for being too close to the house.","B":"He is not sure if the other students will think he is lucky or if they will react negatively.","C":"He thinks the other students will make fun of his apartment.","D":"He is waiting for Ms. Hussey to call on someone else."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He is questioning how his classmates will perceive his living situation, which shows he is worried about fitting in or being judged by them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"ironic\" mean in this context? A. exactly as expected B. contrary to what you would expect C. very funny and amusing D. sad and disappointing","excerpt":"\"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\"","stem":"What does \"ironic\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"exactly as expected","B":"contrary to what you would expect","C":"very funny and amusing","D":"sad and disappointing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is unexpected (ironi c) that a house built for children has had no families living in it for decades.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Wright built many houses over seventy years. B. The Robie House was uniquely important to Wright. C. Wright liked to fight with seminary leaders. D. The house was saved by a committee of architects.","excerpt":"\"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Wright built many houses over seventy years.","B":"The Robie House was uniquely important to Wright.","C":"Wright liked to fight with seminary leaders.","D":"The house was saved by a committee of architects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that it was the \"only structure\" he fought to save, and that he did it twice, shows it was uniquely important to him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Robie House was the only structure Frank Lloyd Wright ever built, during a career that spanned almost seventy years, that he fought to save, and he saved it not once but twice.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q008","read_aloud":"Why does Tommy only raise his hand \"just barely\"? A. He is unsure if he should share his personal connection to the house. B. He does not know the answer to the teacher\u0027s question. C. He is tired and wants to go home. D. He is trying to get the teacher\u0027s attention quickly.","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\"","stem":"Why does Tommy only raise his hand \"just barely\"?","choices":{"A":"He is unsure if he should share his personal connection to the house.","B":"He does not know the answer to the teacher\u0027s question.","C":"He is tired and wants to go home.","D":"He is trying to get the teacher\u0027s attention quickly."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tommy is debating whether to tell the class he lives next door and wonders how they will react, showing his hesitation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q009","read_aloud":"Why didn\u0027t Ms. Hussey call on Tommy? A. She thought his answer was wrong. B. She was looking out the window. C. She was pacing and did not see his hand. D. She wanted Denise to answer instead.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey was pacing again and didn\u0027t see Tommy\u0027s hand.\"","stem":"Why didn\u0027t Ms. Hussey call on Tommy?","choices":{"A":"She thought his answer was wrong.","B":"She was looking out the window.","C":"She was pacing and did not see his hand.","D":"She wanted Denise to answer instead."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that Ms. Hussey \"was pacing again and didn\u0027t see Tommy\u0027s hand.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey was pacing again and didn\u0027t see Tommy\u0027s hand.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q010","read_aloud":"a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work. How does the university try to make cutting up the house sound positive? A. By claiming it will give more people around the world access to the art. B. By saying the house was too ugly to keep together. C. By promising to build a new house for the students. D. By stating that museums pay a lot of money for it.","excerpt":"In a letter to the press, the university defends its decision as","stem":"a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work. How does the university try to make cutting up the house sound positive?","choices":{"A":"By claiming it will give more people around the world access to the art.","B":"By saying the house was too ugly to keep together.","C":"By promising to build a new house for the students.","D":"By stating that museums pay a lot of money for it."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The university frames the destruction as a \"bold move\" that will allow \"many millions of people\" to see the work in museums.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In a letter to the press, the university defends its decision as"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q011","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of \"revolutionary\"? A. New B. Groundbreaking C. Traditional or ordinary D. Different","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of \"revolutionary\"?","choices":{"A":"New","B":"Groundbreaking","C":"Traditional or ordinary","D":"Different"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Revolutionary means new and different; traditional is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What does this contradiction reveal about Ms. Hussey\u0027s values? A. She hates all museums. B. She values the house as a whole, indivisible piece, not cut up in museums. C. She doesn\u0027t care about the house. D. She wants the house for herself.","excerpt":"\"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"What does this contradiction reveal about Ms. Hussey\u0027s values?","choices":{"A":"She hates all museums.","B":"She values the house as a whole, indivisible piece, not cut up in museums.","C":"She doesn\u0027t care about the house.","D":"She wants the house for herself."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She wants the house preserved whole, not broken apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q013","read_aloud":"Why does Tommy look down? A. He is sleepy. B. He is thinking about his own painful family experiences. C. He lost his pencil. D. He is drawing.","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up.\"","stem":"Why does Tommy look down?","choices":{"A":"He is sleepy.","B":"He is thinking about his own painful family experiences.","C":"He lost his pencil.","D":"He is drawing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text connects his silence to personal pain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q014","read_aloud":"What deeper question is Ms. Hussey asking? A. What color to paint the walls B. What defines a home and can a building be both home and art C. How to cook dinner D. Where to go on vacation","excerpt":"\"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art…\"","stem":"What deeper question is Ms. Hussey asking?","choices":{"A":"What color to paint the walls","B":"What defines a home and can a building be both home and art","C":"How to cook dinner","D":"Where to go on vacation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She is asking about the meaning of home and art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art…\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q015","read_aloud":"If you lived in Hyde Park, why might you want to save the Robie House? A. It is new. B. It is part of your community\u0027s memory and history. C. It is ugly. D. No one cares about it.","excerpt":"\"What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\"","stem":"If you lived in Hyde Park, why might you want to save the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It is new.","B":"It is part of your community\u0027s memory and history.","C":"It is ugly.","D":"No one cares about it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It has been there for generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"ironic\" mean? A. exactly what you expect B. contrary to expectation C. very funny D. extremely sad","excerpt":"\"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"","stem":"What does \"ironic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"exactly what you expect","B":"contrary to expectation","C":"very funny","D":"extremely sad"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Ironic\" means the opposite of what you expect. The house was built for children, but no family has lived there since 1926.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What theme is Ms. Hussey exploring? A. Houses should always be torn down B. The connection between art, home, and life C. Museums are bad places D. Children should not live in art","excerpt":"\"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\"","stem":"What theme is Ms. Hussey exploring?","choices":{"A":"Houses should always be torn down","B":"The connection between art, home, and life","C":"Museums are bad places","D":"Children should not live in art"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey asks if a home can also be art. She is exploring how art, home, and life connect to each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q018","read_aloud":"What does this show about Tommy? A. He is confident and loud B. He is unsure and hesitant C. He is angry at the teacher D. He knows nothing about the house","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\"","stem":"What does this show about Tommy?","choices":{"A":"He is confident and loud","B":"He is unsure and hesitant","C":"He is angry at the teacher","D":"He knows nothing about the house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tommy raises his hand \"just barely\" and wonders if he should speak. He is unsure what others will think. This shows he is hesitant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Why does the university think cutting up the house is good? A. More people around the world can see Wright\u0027s work B. They want to destroy his work C. They need the land for a parking lot D. The house is too ugly to keep","excerpt":"\"In a letter to the press, the university defends its decision as \u0027a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the university think cutting up the house is good?","choices":{"A":"More people around the world can see Wright\u0027s work","B":"They want to destroy his work","C":"They need the land for a parking lot","D":"The house is too ugly to keep"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The university says putting pieces in museums will let millions of people see Wright\u0027s work. They think this is a \"bold move.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a letter to the press, the university defends its decision as \u0027a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Why do people in Hyde Park feel sad? A. They will miss the house as part of their community B. They wanted to buy the house C. They never liked the house D. They are moving away","excerpt":"\"As one Hyde Parker said, \u0027This breaks my heart. Hyde Park weeps.\u0027\"","stem":"Why do people in Hyde Park feel sad?","choices":{"A":"They will miss the house as part of their community","B":"They wanted to buy the house","C":"They never liked the house","D":"They are moving away"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The person says \"Hyde Park weeps.\" The house has been part of the neighborhood for a century. People feel like they are losing something important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As one Hyde Parker said, \u0027This breaks my heart. Hyde Park weeps.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q001","read_aloud":"If the seminary\u0027s decision was radically changed by Wright, what happened? A. They changed their minds a little bit. B. They made a huge, extreme change in their plan to demolish it. C. They decided to sell the land to someone else. D. They decided to paint the house a different color.","excerpt":"\"Wright... declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027 The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\"","stem":"If the seminary\u0027s decision was radically changed by Wright, what happened?","choices":{"A":"They changed their minds a little bit.","B":"They made a huge, extreme change in their plan to demolish it.","C":"They decided to sell the land to someone else.","D":"They decided to paint the house a different color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To change \"radically\" means to make a total or extreme change in direction, which fits their shift from planning to demolish the house to deciding to keep it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright... declared the Robie House to be \u0027a source of worldwide architectural inspiration.\u0027 The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What does this tell us about the Robie House? A. It is a very boring and plain building. B. It is very popular and loved by everyone in the neighborhood. C. It has a very bold, unique design that causes strong reactions. D. Nobody in the neighborhood knows what the house looks like.","excerpt":"\"Calder went on, \u0027My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this tell us about the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It is a very boring and plain building.","B":"It is very popular and loved by everyone in the neighborhood.","C":"It has a very bold, unique design that causes strong reactions.","D":"Nobody in the neighborhood knows what the house looks like."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The fact that people have such opposite reactions (\"love it\" vs. \"can\u0027t stand it\") shows it is a unique building that causes strong opinions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder went on, \u0027My parents said that people in the neighborhood either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What contrast is Ms. Hussey making? A. Between the design of the house and the design of the school. B. Between the past (when the house was built) and the present (what is normal today). C. Between Frank Lloyd Wright and other architects. D. Between the Robie House and the museums where it will be sent.","excerpt":"\"\u0027It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then...\u0027\"","stem":"What contrast is Ms. Hussey making?","choices":{"A":"Between the design of the house and the design of the school.","B":"Between the past (when the house was built) and the present (what is normal today).","C":"Between Frank Lloyd Wright and other architects.","D":"Between the Robie House and the museums where it will be sent."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She is contrasting how \"normal\" these design features seem to the students today versus how \"revolutionary\" they were when Wright first designed them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it. Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then...\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How does this information contribute to the conflict in the story? A. It shows that the house is perfectly maintained and ready for visitors. B. It creates a barrier that prevents the students from seeing and saving the house themselves. C. It explains why the university needs to make so many repairs. D. It explains that the university hates visitors.","excerpt":"\"\u0027I wish we could [visit], but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year...\u0027\"","stem":"How does this information contribute to the conflict in the story?","choices":{"A":"It shows that the house is perfectly maintained and ready for visitors.","B":"It creates a barrier that prevents the students from seeing and saving the house themselves.","C":"It explains why the university needs to make so many repairs.","D":"It explains that the university hates visitors."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By making the house inaccessible, the university makes it much harder for the students to help or even understand the true state of the building.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I wish we could [visit], but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year...\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey suggest they \"think\" even if they cannot do an investigation? A. Because she wants them to do homework on the weekend. B. Because she believes the power of ideas is a valuable first step in taking action. C. Because she is too tired to lead an investigation. D. Because she wants to make sure they do not forget the story.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey looked around, then sighed also. \u0027Okay-maybe it\u0027s too much to start an investigation so late in the year. But it\u0027s never too late to think.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey suggest they \"think\" even if they cannot do an investigation?","choices":{"A":"Because she wants them to do homework on the weekend.","B":"Because she believes the power of ideas is a valuable first step in taking action.","C":"Because she is too tired to lead an investigation.","D":"Because she wants to make sure they do not forget the story."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even when she admits they cannot do a full investigation, she encourages the students not to give up on the ideas and the importance of the situation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey looked around, then sighed also. \u0027Okay-maybe it\u0027s too much to start an investigation so late in the year. But it\u0027s never too late to think.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"radically\" in this sentence? A. slightly B. completely C. rarely D. slowly","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"radically\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"slightly","B":"completely","C":"rarely","D":"slowly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Completely\" is a synonym for \"radically,\" as both mean a total or extreme change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What does the puzzle metaphor help the reader understand? A. The house was confusing to live in. B. Every part of the house was designed to fit together perfectly. C. The furniture was made of cardboard. D. The house was missing many pieces.","excerpt":"\"\"Plus, the detail on the interior was extraordinary: Furniture, lamps, ceiling panels, rugs, and window designs all fit together like pieces of a puzzle.\"","stem":"What does the puzzle metaphor help the reader understand?","choices":{"A":"The house was confusing to live in.","B":"Every part of the house was designed to fit together perfectly.","C":"The furniture was made of cardboard.","D":"The house was missing many pieces."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing the design to \"pieces of a puzzle\" shows that every element was intentionally made to fit together perfectly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Plus, the detail on the interior was extraordinary: Furniture, lamps, ceiling panels, rugs, and window designs all fit together like pieces of a puzzle.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q008","read_aloud":"What detail shows the durability of the Robie House\u0027s design? A. It has 174 windows. B. It was built for Frederick C. Robie. C. Almost all of the glass windows are still intact. D. It has thousands of pieces of colored glass.","excerpt":"There were once 174 art-glass windows in that house, which meant thousands of pieces of colored glass. Amazingly, almost all of the windows are still intact.","stem":"What detail shows the durability of the Robie House\u0027s design?","choices":{"A":"It has 174 windows.","B":"It was built for Frederick C. Robie.","C":"Almost all of the glass windows are still intact.","D":"It has thousands of pieces of colored glass."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The fact that \"almost all of the windows are still intact\" after many years shows the durability of the design.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: There were once 174 art-glass windows in that house, which meant thousands of pieces of colored glass. Amazingly, almost all of the windows are still intact."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q009","read_aloud":"If you were designing a window, why might you avoid the term \"stained glass\"? A. Because it is too expensive to make. B. Because it sounds like the glass is dirty or damaged. C. Because it does not let any light through. D. Because it is only used in churches.","excerpt":"\"\"What\u0027s art glass?\" someone asked. \"It\u0027s what most people call \u0027stained glass,\u0027 but Wright didn\u0027t like that label. He described his windows as \u0027leaded glass,\u0027 \u0027light screens,\u0027 or \u0027art glass.\u0027\"","stem":"If you were designing a window, why might you avoid the term \"stained glass\"?","choices":{"A":"Because it is too expensive to make.","B":"Because it sounds like the glass is dirty or damaged.","C":"Because it does not let any light through.","D":"Because it is only used in churches."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Stained\" can imply something is dirty or flawed, so an artist might prefer terms like \"art glass\" or \"light screens\" to sound more beautiful and intentional.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"What\u0027s art glass?\" someone asked. \"It\u0027s what most people call \u0027stained glass,\u0027 but Wright didn\u0027t like that label. He described his windows as \u0027leaded glass,\u0027 \u0027light screens,\u0027 or \u0027art glass.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does this quote describe Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s creative process? A. He copied the ideas of other famous architects. B. He used simple, easy-to-understand shapes. C. His designs were complex and required visual experience to grasp. D. He preferred to write about his ideas rather than build them.","excerpt":"Wright thought in a geometry that you have to see to understand, and even then it\u0027s hard to figure out what you are seeing.","stem":"How does this quote describe Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s creative process?","choices":{"A":"He copied the ideas of other famous architects.","B":"He used simple, easy-to-understand shapes.","C":"His designs were complex and required visual experience to grasp.","D":"He preferred to write about his ideas rather than build them."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The quote says his geometry is something \"you have to see to understand\" and is \"hard to figure out,\" meaning his designs were complex and visual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wright thought in a geometry that you have to see to understand, and even then it\u0027s hard to figure out what you are seeing."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q011","read_aloud":"If something embodies an idea, it ______. A. Destroys it B. Represents or shows it clearly C. Ignores it D. Forgets it","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision.\"","stem":"If something embodies an idea, it ______.","choices":{"A":"Destroys it","B":"Represents or shows it clearly","C":"Ignores it","D":"Forgets it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Embodies means represents in a clear way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What theme about perseverance does this suggest? A. Giving up is easy. B. Important things are worth fighting for over and over. C. Art does not matter. D. Only one person can save a building.","excerpt":"The house has survived multiple threats. Wright saved it twice. Now the university wants to cut it up.","stem":"What theme about perseverance does this suggest?","choices":{"A":"Giving up is easy.","B":"Important things are worth fighting for over and over.","C":"Art does not matter.","D":"Only one person can save a building."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house\u0027s history shows repeated efforts to save it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The house has survived multiple threats. Wright saved it twice. Now the university wants to cut it up."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q013","read_aloud":"How does the narrator help readers understand Calder? A. By telling us what he thinks and feels B. By showing only what Calder does, not thinks C. By ignoring Calder D. By telling us what Ms. Hussey thinks","excerpt":"\"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\"","stem":"How does the narrator help readers understand Calder?","choices":{"A":"By telling us what he thinks and feels","B":"By showing only what Calder does, not thinks","C":"By ignoring Calder","D":"By telling us what Ms. Hussey thinks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The narrator shares Calder\u0027s thoughts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Calder couldn\u0027t wait to tell Petra. She always understood when he discovered new ideas by rearranging the old ones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q014","read_aloud":"What does the Lucky Stone symbolize about Ms. Hussey? A. She is a rock collector. B. The stone shows her emotions; she holds it when worried. C. She uses it to throw at students. D. It is a paperweight.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side. She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\"","stem":"What does the Lucky Stone symbolize about Ms. Hussey?","choices":{"A":"She is a rock collector.","B":"The stone shows her emotions; she holds it when worried.","C":"She uses it to throw at students.","D":"It is a paperweight."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stone is a symbol of her worry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side. She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q015","read_aloud":"What does the silhouette image suggest about Ms. Hussey at this moment? A. She is happy. B. She is thoughtful and perhaps a little dark or burdened. C. She is playing a game. D. She is angry.","excerpt":"\"She held it now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\"","stem":"What does the silhouette image suggest about Ms. Hussey at this moment?","choices":{"A":"She is happy.","B":"She is thoughtful and perhaps a little dark or burdened.","C":"She is playing a game.","D":"She is angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Silhouettes can suggest mystery or deep thought.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She held it now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"revolutionary\"? A. old-fashioned B. groundbreaking C. boring D. tiny","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"revolutionary\"?","choices":{"A":"old-fashioned","B":"groundbreaking","C":"boring","D":"tiny"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Revolutionary\" and \"groundbreaking\" both mean very new and different. They describe ideas that change how people think.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Tommy not look up? A. He is drawing a picture B. He feels uncomfortable thinking about his family C. He is sleeping D. He is angry at Ms. Hussey","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry.\"","stem":"Why does Tommy not look up?","choices":{"A":"He is drawing a picture","B":"He feels uncomfortable thinking about his family","C":"He is sleeping","D":"He is angry at Ms. Hussey"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey talks about fathers saying sorry. Tommy thinks about his dads who never apologized. He feels sad and uncomfortable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q018","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey hold her Lucky Stone? A. She is showing it to the class for a lesson B. She is worried and upset about the Robie House C. She wants to play a game D. She lost her chalk","excerpt":"\"She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey hold her Lucky Stone?","choices":{"A":"She is showing it to the class for a lesson","B":"She is worried and upset about the Robie House","C":"She wants to play a game","D":"She lost her chalk"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The children know the Lucky Stone means she is \"worried or upset.\" She is upset about the house being torn apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Wright\u0027s designs? A. They are simple and easy to copy B. They are complex and hard to understand C. They use no math at all D. They are all painted white","excerpt":"\"Wright thought in a geometry that you have to see to understand, and even then it\u0027s hard to figure out what you are seeing.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Wright\u0027s designs?","choices":{"A":"They are simple and easy to copy","B":"They are complex and hard to understand","C":"They use no math at all","D":"They are all painted white"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey says Wright\u0027s geometry is hard to understand even when you see it. His designs are complex and unusual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wright thought in a geometry that you have to see to understand, and even then it\u0027s hard to figure out what you are seeing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey find this interesting? A. Wright was thinking about children\u0027s happiness even though he left his own family B. Wright did not like children C. Wright had no children D. Wright only built schools","excerpt":"\"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children.\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey find this interesting?","choices":{"A":"Wright was thinking about children\u0027s happiness even though he left his own family","B":"Wright did not like children","C":"Wright had no children","D":"Wright only built schools"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Wright left his wife and six children. But he designed play space for other children. Ms. Hussey wonders if this was his way of making up for leaving his family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Which of the following best fits the meaning of \"embodies\" in this context? A. A copy of a original design B. A physical representation of an idea C. A list of instructions for building D. A secret held by the architect","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"Which of the following best fits the meaning of \"embodies\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"A copy of a original design","B":"A physical representation of an idea","C":"A list of instructions for building","D":"A secret held by the architect"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house serves as a physical, real-life form that represents his personal vision and spirit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Tommy feels about promises? A. He feels excited and hopeful when someone makes a promise. B. He feels skeptical and likely expects them to be broken. C. He thinks promises are just for babies. D. He thinks people are always honest.","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Tommy feels about promises?","choices":{"A":"He feels excited and hopeful when someone makes a promise.","B":"He feels skeptical and likely expects them to be broken.","C":"He thinks promises are just for babies.","D":"He thinks people are always honest."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because he has experienced his stepfather breaking every promise, it is reasonable to infer he no longer trusts promises.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What was the cause of the seminary\u0027s plan to demolish the Robie House? A. They were angry at Frank Lloyd Wright. B. They wanted to use the land for student housing. C. They thought the house was not beautiful. D. They needed to raise money for other museums.","excerpt":"\"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\"","stem":"What was the cause of the seminary\u0027s plan to demolish the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"They were angry at Frank Lloyd Wright.","B":"They wanted to use the land for student housing.","C":"They thought the house was not beautiful.","D":"They needed to raise money for other museums."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly says they announced the demolition because they were \"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does Ms. Hussey connect the concepts of \"Art\" and \"Life\"? A. She suggests that houses are meant to be empty art pieces. B. She suggests that a home needs to be lived in to be \"alive\" and meaningful. C. She argues that art is more important than having a home. D. She argues that students should only study art.","excerpt":"\"\u0027So: Art \u0026 Life.\u0027 ... \u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\"","stem":"How does Ms. Hussey connect the concepts of \"Art\" and \"Life\"?","choices":{"A":"She suggests that houses are meant to be empty art pieces.","B":"She suggests that a home needs to be lived in to be \"alive\" and meaningful.","C":"She argues that art is more important than having a home.","D":"She argues that students should only study art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By questioning if a home can \"exist\" if it is empty, she suggests that the \"life\" part of a home comes from the people who live there, connecting the physical building (art) to human experience (life).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027So: Art \u0026 Life.\u0027 ... \u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q005","read_aloud":"What is the author showing by noting Ms. Hussey\u0027s tone? A. That she is a confused teacher who changes her mind often. B. That she values the original purpose of art and fears that museums might strip it of its true meaning. C. That she is trying to trick her students. D. That she is mad at the class for liking museums.","excerpt":"\"The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums. ... She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing.\"","stem":"What is the author showing by noting Ms. Hussey\u0027s tone?","choices":{"A":"That she is a confused teacher who changes her mind often.","B":"That she values the original purpose of art and fears that museums might strip it of its true meaning.","C":"That she is trying to trick her students.","D":"That she is mad at the class for liking museums."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even though she likes museums, she sees the dismantling of the Robie House into museum pieces as wrong, suggesting she believes art belongs in its original, meaningful context rather than as disconnected \"chunks.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums. ... She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"embodies\" mean in this sentence? A. physically attacks B. completely forgets C. represents or expresses D. secretly hides","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"What does \"embodies\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"physically attacks","B":"completely forgets","C":"represents or expresses","D":"secretly hides"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The house expresses or \"represents\" Wright\u0027s spirit and vision, which is the meaning of \"embodies.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Can\u0027t the house just sit there empty until the money comes in?\" Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot. How does Ms. Hussey react to Petra\u0027s suggestion? A. She agrees with it immediately. B. She acts shocked or pained by the idea. C. She laughs and thinks it is funny. D. She ignores Petra and walks away.","excerpt":"Petra Andalee was frowning.","stem":"Can\u0027t the house just sit there empty until the money comes in?\" Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot. How does Ms. Hussey react to Petra\u0027s suggestion?","choices":{"A":"She agrees with it immediately.","B":"She acts shocked or pained by the idea.","C":"She laughs and thinks it is funny.","D":"She ignores Petra and walks away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey draws a \"quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot,\" which shows she is shocked or pained by the suggestion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Petra Andalee was frowning."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What two reasons does Ms. Hussey give for why the house cannot just sit empty? A. It is too beautiful and it is too old. B. The university cannot afford it, and it is a safety hazard. C. The students want to play in it, and it is too small. D. It is a museum, and it is too far away.","excerpt":"\"\"In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no. The university probably can\u0027t afford to own a piece of property that they aren\u0027t able to use, and if part of the house fell on someone walking by, the owner would be held responsible.\"\"","stem":"What two reasons does Ms. Hussey give for why the house cannot just sit empty?","choices":{"A":"It is too beautiful and it is too old.","B":"The university cannot afford it, and it is a safety hazard.","C":"The students want to play in it, and it is too small.","D":"It is a museum, and it is too far away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey mentions the university \"can\u0027t afford to own\" it and that the owner would be \"held responsible\" if it fell on someone, citing financial and safety reasons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no. The university probably can\u0027t afford to own a piece of property that they aren\u0027t able to use, and if part of the house fell on someone walking by, the owner would be held responsible.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q009","read_aloud":"If you were in Calder\u0027s group, what is one idea you might suggest to save the house? A. Start a fundraising campaign to pay for the repairs. B. Help the university cut the house into pieces faster. C. Move the house to a different country. D. Turn the house into a parking lot.","excerpt":"\"\"Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\" Calder suggested.\"","stem":"If you were in Calder\u0027s group, what is one idea you might suggest to save the house?","choices":{"A":"Start a fundraising campaign to pay for the repairs.","B":"Help the university cut the house into pieces faster.","C":"Move the house to a different country.","D":"Turn the house into a parking lot."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since the university\u0027s main problem is money for repairs, a fundraising campaign is a logical and helpful idea to suggest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\" Calder suggested.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q010","read_aloud":"How does the detail about the house being \"built for children\" deepen the sadness of the situation? A. It shows that children do not like architecture. B. It highlights the contrast between the house\u0027s joyful purpose and its current empty state. C. It proves that the house is too small for adults. D. It suggests that children are responsible for the damage.","excerpt":"\"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\"","stem":"How does the detail about the house being \"built for children\" deepen the sadness of the situation?","choices":{"A":"It shows that children do not like architecture.","B":"It highlights the contrast between the house\u0027s joyful purpose and its current empty state.","C":"It proves that the house is too small for adults.","D":"It suggests that children are responsible for the damage."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the house was designed to be a happy, playful space for children makes the fact that it has been empty and threatened with destruction much sadder.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q011","read_aloud":"If something is \"indivisible,\" you ______. A. Can split it into many parts B. Cannot split it into parts C. Can paint it easily D. Can move it","excerpt":"\"The idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"If something is \"indivisible,\" you ______.","choices":{"A":"Can split it into many parts","B":"Cannot split it into parts","C":"Can paint it easily","D":"Can move it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Indivisible means cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What common idea connects Tommy\u0027s life and the house\u0027s story? A. Both are about math. B. Both involve loss, broken promises, and the need to preserve what is valuable. C. Both are about sports. D. Both are about cooking.","excerpt":"Tommy\u0027s father died; his stepfather broke promises. The Robie House has been threatened multiple times.","stem":"What common idea connects Tommy\u0027s life and the house\u0027s story?","choices":{"A":"Both are about math.","B":"Both involve loss, broken promises, and the need to preserve what is valuable.","C":"Both are about sports.","D":"Both are about cooking."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The theme of loss and broken promises connects them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tommy\u0027s father died; his stepfather broke promises. The Robie House has been threatened multiple times."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this history? A. To show the house was always in good condition. B. To show that the house has been worth saving many times and is important. C. To make the story longer. D. To prove that the university is right.","excerpt":"The author includes the history of the Robie House (saved in 1941 and 1957).","stem":"Why does the author include this history?","choices":{"A":"To show the house was always in good condition.","B":"To show that the house has been worth saving many times and is important.","C":"To make the story longer.","D":"To prove that the university is right."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The history shows the house\u0027s importance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author includes the history of the Robie House (saved in 1941 and 1957)."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q014","read_aloud":"If you were a student in Ms. Hussey\u0027s class, what is one question you would ask about the house? A. \"What is for lunch?\" B. \"How can we, as a community, raise money to save it whole?\" C. \"What is your favorite color?\" D. \"Can we go home early?\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you were a student in Ms. Hussey\u0027s class, what is one question you would ask about the house?","choices":{"A":"\"What is for lunch?\"","B":"\"How can we, as a community, raise money to save it whole?\"","C":"\"What is your favorite color?\"","D":"\"Can we go home early?\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"That question addresses the central conflict.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Using context clues, what does \"indivisible\" mean? A. easy to break apart B. cannot be separated C. very small D. made of many colors","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\"","stem":"Using context clues, what does \"indivisible\" mean?","choices":{"A":"easy to break apart","B":"cannot be separated","C":"very small","D":"made of many colors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey says the house is \"one indivisible piece.\" She hates the idea of \"carving up the structure.\" This means it cannot be split.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What might the Lucky Stone symbolize? A. A paperweight B. Hope and comfort when things are hard C. A science experiment D. A gift from Wright","excerpt":"\"She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side. She called it her Lucky Stone.\"","stem":"What might the Lucky Stone symbolize?","choices":{"A":"A paperweight","B":"Hope and comfort when things are hard","C":"A science experiment","D":"A gift from Wright"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey picks up the Lucky Stone when she is \"worried or upset.\" It gives her comfort. It symbolizes hope during hard times.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side. She called it her Lucky Stone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the author include Calder\u0027s thoughts? A. To show Calder is confused B. To show how Calder thinks creatively by connecting ideas C. To make the story longer D. To teach vocabulary","excerpt":"\"He knew the word \u0027trifle\u0027 meant something not too valuable or important, as his Grandma Ranjana had sometimes used that word, and a filter could mean-well, something you looked through or poured stuff through.\"","stem":"Why does the author include Calder\u0027s thoughts?","choices":{"A":"To show Calder is confused","B":"To show how Calder thinks creatively by connecting ideas","C":"To make the story longer","D":"To teach vocabulary"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author shows Calder\u0027s thoughts to help readers understand his character. Calder sees connections between words and ideas. This is how his mind works.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He knew the word \u0027trifle\u0027 meant something not too valuable or important, as his Grandma Ranjana had sometimes used that word, and a filter could mean-well, something you looked through or poured stuff through.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q018","read_aloud":"How did Wright save the house the second time? A. He bought it himself B. He convinced a developer to buy it C. He tore it down and rebuilt it D. He asked the government for money","excerpt":"\"Describing the Robie House as \u0027one of the cornerstones of American architecture\u0027 and commenting that only the kitchen needed improvement, he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\"","stem":"How did Wright save the house the second time?","choices":{"A":"He bought it himself","B":"He convinced a developer to buy it","C":"He tore it down and rebuilt it","D":"He asked the government for money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wright persuaded a developer named Zeckendorf to buy the house. He called it a \"cornerstone of American architecture\" to convince him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Describing the Robie House as \u0027one of the cornerstones of American architecture\u0027 and commenting that only the kitchen needed improvement, he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare the house to a puzzle? A. The house is a game B. All the parts fit together perfectly in Wright\u0027s design C. The house is confusing and broken D. Wright liked to play games","excerpt":"\"The detail on the interior was extraordinary: Furniture, lamps, ceiling panels, rugs, and window designs all fit together like pieces of a puzzle.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare the house to a puzzle?","choices":{"A":"The house is a game","B":"All the parts fit together perfectly in Wright\u0027s design","C":"The house is confusing and broken","D":"Wright liked to play games"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A puzzle has pieces that fit together perfectly. The author uses this comparison to show how every part of Wright\u0027s design works together as one whole.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The detail on the interior was extraordinary: Furniture, lamps, ceiling panels, rugs, and window designs all fit together like pieces of a puzzle.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q001","read_aloud":"Which of the following situations is also \"ironic\"? A. A fire station burning down. B. A chef cooking a delicious meal. C. A sunny day at the beach. D. A student reading a book.","excerpt":"\"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"","stem":"Which of the following situations is also \"ironic\"?","choices":{"A":"A fire station burning down.","B":"A chef cooking a delicious meal.","C":"A sunny day at the beach.","D":"A student reading a book."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"It is ironic when something meant to do one thing (like protect against fire) experiences that very thing (fire), just as it is ironic that a house built for children has not been used by a family in a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Ms. Hussey\u0027s view of Frank Lloyd Wright as a person? A. She thinks he was a perfect human being. B. She thinks he was a complicated person with both talent and personal flaws. C. She thinks he was only interested in money. D. She thinks he did not care about his own children.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\u0027\"","stem":"What can you infer about Ms. Hussey\u0027s view of Frank Lloyd Wright as a person?","choices":{"A":"She thinks he was a perfect human being.","B":"She thinks he was a complicated person with both talent and personal flaws.","C":"She thinks he was only interested in money.","D":"She thinks he did not care about his own children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By acknowledging his amazing talent (\"thinking creatively\") and his personal failure (\"left his wife and six children\"), she shows she sees him as a complex, flawed, but talented individual.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the \"Lucky Stone\" as a symbol? A. To show that Ms. Hussey is very rich. B. To give the students a way to understand Ms. Hussey\u0027s feelings without her having to speak. C. To explain how stones are formed. D. To show that the classroom is a magical place.","excerpt":"\"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone... she called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the \"Lucky Stone\" as a symbol?","choices":{"A":"To show that Ms. Hussey is very rich.","B":"To give the students a way to understand Ms. Hussey\u0027s feelings without her having to speak.","C":"To explain how stones are formed.","D":"To show that the classroom is a magical place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stone serves as a visual signal of her emotional state, allowing the reader and the characters to know she is \"worried or upset\" without it being directly stated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone... she called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think the university\u0027s defense is a fair way to describe destroying the house? A. Yes, because more people will get to see pieces of the house in other museums. B. No, because it ignores that the house\u0027s true value lies in it being a complete, \"indivisible\" piece of art. C. Yes, because the university always knows what is best for art. D. No, because the university should have just charged money for tours.","excerpt":"\"The university defends its decision as \u0027a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think the university\u0027s defense is a fair way to describe destroying the house?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because more people will get to see pieces of the house in other museums.","B":"No, because it ignores that the house\u0027s true value lies in it being a complete, \"indivisible\" piece of art.","C":"Yes, because the university always knows what is best for art.","D":"No, because the university should have just charged money for tours."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While the university argues it is a \"bold move\" for accessibility, many would argue (like Ms. Hussey) that a building\u0027s significance is in its entirety, and destroying that is not \"access.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university defends its decision as \u0027a bold move to provide many millions of people, around the world, with access to Wright\u0027s extraordinary work.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q005","read_aloud":"If you were one of the characters, what could be another way to express your concern for the Robie House? A. Write a song about why the house is important. B. Forbid the university from touching the house. C. Ignore the news and focus on your own home. D. Buy the house yourself.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\u0027 Calder suggested.\"","stem":"If you were one of the characters, what could be another way to express your concern for the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"Write a song about why the house is important.","B":"Forbid the university from touching the house.","C":"Ignore the news and focus on your own home.","D":"Buy the house yourself."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Creating art (like a song) to support art is a creative way to express concern, fitting the themes of the story.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\u0027 Calder suggested.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for \"indivisible\"? A. unbreakable B. separable C. complete D. solid","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for \"indivisible\"?","choices":{"A":"unbreakable","B":"separable","C":"complete","D":"solid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Indivisible\" means unable to be divided, so \"separable\" is its opposite, or antonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What connection does Ms. Hussey make about Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s life? A. He built the house to hide from his family. B. He may have focused on play space to cope with leaving his own children. C. He did not know how to design houses for families. D. He wanted to adopt six new children.","excerpt":"\"\"Actually,\" she confided, \"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children.\"","stem":"What connection does Ms. Hussey make about Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"He built the house to hide from his family.","B":"He may have focused on play space to cope with leaving his own children.","C":"He did not know how to design houses for families.","D":"He wanted to adopt six new children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey wonders if his focus on play space was \"his way of asking the universe for forgiveness\" after leaving his wife and six children.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Actually,\" she confided, \"I\u0027ve always wondered about Mr. Wright\u0027s focus on play space. At the time he was working on the Robie House, he had just left his wife and six children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q008","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt reveal about Tommy\u0027s home life? A. He has a perfect and happy family. B. He has experienced significant loss and family tension. C. He lives with his grandparents in South America. D. He does not care about his family at all.","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America-he\u0027d been arrested at a political demonstration and was never seen again.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt reveal about Tommy\u0027s home life?","choices":{"A":"He has a perfect and happy family.","B":"He has experienced significant loss and family tension.","C":"He lives with his grandparents in South America.","D":"He does not care about his family at all."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions his real dad died and his stepdad broke promises, revealing significant loss and tension in his life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America-he\u0027d been arrested at a political demonstration and was never seen again.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think Ms. Hussey\u0027s theory about Wright\u0027s motives is a reasonable interpretation? Use clues from the text. A. No, because architects only care about money, not feelings. B. Yes, because people often channel their personal regrets into their creative work. C. No, because Wright did not have any children of his own. D. Yes, because the text says Wright apologized to his family.","excerpt":"And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe. Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness....","stem":"Do you think Ms. Hussey\u0027s theory about Wright\u0027s motives is a reasonable interpretation? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because architects only care about money, not feelings.","B":"Yes, because people often channel their personal regrets into their creative work.","C":"No, because Wright did not have any children of his own.","D":"Yes, because the text says Wright apologized to his family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is a reasonable interpretation because the text notes he had just left his own children, making it plausible that he channeled his regret into designing safe spaces for other children.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: And yet here he was, thinking creatively about what would make someone else\u0027s kids happy and safe. Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness...."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Is Tommy\u0027s choice to stay quiet about living next to the Robie House a good decision for him? Use clues from the paragraph. A. No, because he should always share his personal life with the class. B. Yes, because he is dealing with complicated family feelings and may not want to be the center of attention. C. No, because his classmates will be angry if he does not speak. D. Yes, because he does not actually live next to the house.","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry.\"","stem":"Is Tommy\u0027s choice to stay quiet about living next to the Robie House a good decision for him? Use clues from the paragraph.","choices":{"A":"No, because he should always share his personal life with the class.","B":"Yes, because he is dealing with complicated family feelings and may not want to be the center of attention.","C":"No, because his classmates will be angry if he does not speak.","D":"Yes, because he does not actually live next to the house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Given the text about his complicated family situation and broken promises, it is a good decision for him to protect his privacy and not draw attention to himself.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"revolutionary\"? A. Old B. Groundbreaking C. Boring D. Ordinary","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"revolutionary\"?","choices":{"A":"Old","B":"Groundbreaking","C":"Boring","D":"Ordinary"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Revolutionary means new and groundbreaking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think the university\u0027s decision is reasonable? Why or why not? A. Yes, because safety and money matter. B. No, because art always comes first. C. Yes, because they don\u0027t like Wright. D. No, because they should sell it instead.","excerpt":"The university says it cannot afford to fix the house.","stem":"Do you think the university\u0027s decision is reasonable? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because safety and money matter.","B":"No, because art always comes first.","C":"Yes, because they don\u0027t like Wright.","D":"No, because they should sell it instead."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows practical reasons for the decision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The university says it cannot afford to fix the house."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q013","read_aloud":"What perspective does Ms. Hussey hold about the house? A. It is worthless. B. It is valuable and should not be destroyed. C. It should be cut up. D. It is dangerous.","excerpt":"Ms. Hussey says, \"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\"","stem":"What perspective does Ms. Hussey hold about the house?","choices":{"A":"It is worthless.","B":"It is valuable and should not be destroyed.","C":"It should be cut up.","D":"It is dangerous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She calls its destruction a crime.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Ms. Hussey says, \"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Why might the students be quiet? A. They are sleeping. B. They are thinking deeply about difficult questions. C. They are angry. D. They are eating.","excerpt":"The class is quiet after Ms. Hussey asks deep questions about home and art.","stem":"Why might the students be quiet?","choices":{"A":"They are sleeping.","B":"They are thinking deeply about difficult questions.","C":"They are angry.","D":"They are eating."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The questions are big and make you think.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The class is quiet after Ms. Hussey asks deep questions about home and art."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"ironic\"? A. surprising B. expected C. funny D. strange","excerpt":"\"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"ironic\"?","choices":{"A":"surprising","B":"expected","C":"funny","D":"strange"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Ironic\" means contrary to what you expect. The opposite is \"expected,\" which means exactly what you think will happen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q016","read_aloud":"What is a major theme of this story? A. Art and life are connected, and we must protect important art B. All old houses should be torn down C. Museums are bad places D. Children should not live in nice houses","excerpt":"\"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\"","stem":"What is a major theme of this story?","choices":{"A":"Art and life are connected, and we must protect important art","B":"All old houses should be torn down","C":"Museums are bad places","D":"Children should not live in nice houses"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The story explores how the Robie House is both a home and a work of art. Ms. Hussey and the students want to protect it. This shows art and life are deeply connected.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q017","read_aloud":"How is Tommy\u0027s family history different from Wright\u0027s? A. Tommy\u0027s fathers never apologized; Wright may have wanted forgiveness for leaving his family B. They both had perfect families C. Tommy never knew his father; Wright never had children D. They are exactly the same","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America... And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\"","stem":"How is Tommy\u0027s family history different from Wright\u0027s?","choices":{"A":"Tommy\u0027s fathers never apologized; Wright may have wanted forgiveness for leaving his family","B":"They both had perfect families","C":"Tommy never knew his father; Wright never had children","D":"They are exactly the same"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tommy\u0027s dads never said sorry. Wright left his wife and six children. Ms. Hussey wonders if Wright designed play space as \"a way of asking the universe for forgiveness.\" Both deal with family pain but in different ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America... And Tommy\u0027s stepfather had started out with a bunch of promises and then broken every one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think the university is right to cut up the house? Why or why not? A. Yes, because they tried everything and cannot afford it B. No, because the house is too important to destroy, even if it costs money C. Yes, because Wright would want it in museums D. No, because the house is ugly","excerpt":"\"It is only after extensive attempts to raise funds, both nationally and internationally, that we have made this painful decision.\"","stem":"Do you think the university is right to cut up the house? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because they tried everything and cannot afford it","B":"No, because the house is too important to destroy, even if it costs money","C":"Yes, because Wright would want it in museums","D":"No, because the house is ugly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While the university says they tried to raise funds, many believe the house \"embodies\" Wright\u0027s spirit and cannot be split. It is a historic treasure that should be saved whole.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is only after extensive attempts to raise funds, both nationally and internationally, that we have made this painful decision.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey say this? A. She thinks Petra\u0027s idea is impossible in reality B. She agrees with Petra completely C. She wants to tear down the house D. She does not like Petra","excerpt":"\"In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no.\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey say this?","choices":{"A":"She thinks Petra\u0027s idea is impossible in reality","B":"She agrees with Petra completely","C":"She wants to tear down the house","D":"She does not like Petra"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Petra asks if the house can sit empty until money comes. Ms. Hussey wishes this could happen, but the university cannot afford it. In the \"real world,\" some things are not possible even if we want them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an ideal world, yes. In the real world, no.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q001","read_aloud":"If an architect today built a house exactly like the Robie House, would it still be called \"revolutionary\"? A. Yes, because it is still the best house ever built. B. No, because those design features are now considered \"normal\" and standard. C. Yes, because nobody knows how to build houses anymore. D. No, because the house is too old to be considered modern.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\u0027\"","stem":"If an architect today built a house exactly like the Robie House, would it still be called \"revolutionary\"?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it is still the best house ever built.","B":"No, because those design features are now considered \"normal\" and standard.","C":"Yes, because nobody knows how to build houses anymore.","D":"No, because the house is too old to be considered modern."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The term \"revolutionary\" applies to new and different ideas; because these ideas are now \"normal,\" they are no longer revolutionary in the modern day.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What does the author\u0027s use of the word \"shamed\" tell the reader? A. That the seminary was easily persuaded to do the right thing. B. That public or expert pressure was necessary to make them change their plans. C. That Frank Lloyd Wright paid them a lot of money. D. That the seminary was very happy to keep the house.","excerpt":"\"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\"","stem":"What does the author\u0027s use of the word \"shamed\" tell the reader?","choices":{"A":"That the seminary was easily persuaded to do the right thing.","B":"That public or expert pressure was necessary to make them change their plans.","C":"That Frank Lloyd Wright paid them a lot of money.","D":"That the seminary was very happy to keep the house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Shamed\" implies that it took negative attention or social pressure from world-famous experts to force the seminary to keep the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. ... The seminary was shamed into keeping it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Is this a good way to describe Ms. Hussey\u0027s reaction? A. No, it does not explain why she was hot. B. Yes, it effectively captures the sudden, uncomfortable nature of the student\u0027s question. C. No, it is too confusing for a story. D. Yes, it means she was physically burning up.","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot.\"","stem":"Is this a good way to describe Ms. Hussey\u0027s reaction?","choices":{"A":"No, it does not explain why she was hot.","B":"Yes, it effectively captures the sudden, uncomfortable nature of the student\u0027s question.","C":"No, it is too confusing for a story.","D":"Yes, it means she was physically burning up."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is an effective metaphor for being caught off guard by a question that hits on something personal or difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey drew a quick breath as if she\u0027d touched something hot.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q004","read_aloud":"What is the best synonym for \"revolutionary\" in this context? A. traditional B. groundbreaking C. boring D. dangerous","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\"","stem":"What is the best synonym for \"revolutionary\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"traditional","B":"groundbreaking","C":"boring","D":"dangerous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Groundbreaking\" is a synonym for \"revolutionary,\" as both describe something new and innovative.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q005","read_aloud":"How does the student\u0027s response challenge Ms. Hussey\u0027s perspective? A. It agrees that the house is a crime scene. B. It questions whether the building can truly be considered a \"home.\" C. It suggests that the house should be destroyed immediately. D. It proves that the student has never seen the house.","excerpt":"\"\"Anyway,\" Ms. Hussey said, her voice businesslike again, \"it seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\" \"It doesn\u0027t look like a home to me,\" one of the kids piped up.\"","stem":"How does the student\u0027s response challenge Ms. Hussey\u0027s perspective?","choices":{"A":"It agrees that the house is a crime scene.","B":"It questions whether the building can truly be considered a \"home.\"","C":"It suggests that the house should be destroyed immediately.","D":"It proves that the student has never seen the house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The student challenges Ms. Hussey\u0027s emotional view by pointing out that, to them, the building does not even look like a \"home.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Anyway,\" Ms. Hussey said, her voice businesslike again, \"it seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\" \"It doesn\u0027t look like a home to me,\" one of the kids piped up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q006","read_aloud":"What new question does Ms. Hussey introduce to the class? A. How much does the house cost to build? B. Can a home exist if it is empty, and can a home also be art? C. Who is going to buy the house next? D. Why did Frederick C. Robie move away?","excerpt":"\"\"Really?\" Ms. Hussey said, looking pleased. \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art...\"\"","stem":"What new question does Ms. Hussey introduce to the class?","choices":{"A":"How much does the house cost to build?","B":"Can a home exist if it is empty, and can a home also be art?","C":"Who is going to buy the house next?","D":"Why did Frederick C. Robie move away?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey explicitly asks the class to figure out if a home can exist if it\u0027s empty and if a home can also be a piece of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Really?\" Ms. Hussey said, looking pleased. \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art...\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q007","read_aloud":"Okay-maybe it\u0027s too much to start an investigation so late in the year. But it\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? If you were a student in this class, what specific action would you propose in response to Ms. Hussey\u0027s question? A. I would propose writing a joint letter to the university explaining why the house should be preserved whole. B. I would propose that we all move into the house to live there. C. I would propose that we stop thinking about it and do our homework. D. I would propose that we help the university cut the house into pieces.","excerpt":"The class was quiet. Someone sighed. Ms. Hussey looked around, then sighed also.","stem":"Okay-maybe it\u0027s too much to start an investigation so late in the year. But it\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? If you were a student in this class, what specific action would you propose in response to Ms. Hussey\u0027s question?","choices":{"A":"I would propose writing a joint letter to the university explaining why the house should be preserved whole.","B":"I would propose that we all move into the house to live there.","C":"I would propose that we stop thinking about it and do our homework.","D":"I would propose that we help the university cut the house into pieces."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Writing a joint letter is a realistic, constructive action that students could take to express their desire to preserve the house as a whole piece of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The class was quiet. Someone sighed. Ms. Hussey looked around, then sighed also."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Imagine you are creating a poster to save the Robie House. What slogan would you write based on this excerpt? A. \"Tear It Down: Make Way for the Future!\" B. \"Preserve Our History: Keep the Robie House Whole!\" C. \"Empty Houses Are Dangerous: Demolish It Now!\" D. \"Art Is Expensive: Sell the Pieces!\"","excerpt":"Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember. It\u0027s just too horrible to think of it being pulled apart.","stem":"Imagine you are creating a poster to save the Robie House. What slogan would you write based on this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"\"Tear It Down: Make Way for the Future!\"","B":"\"Preserve Our History: Keep the Robie House Whole!\"","C":"\"Empty Houses Are Dangerous: Demolish It Now!\"","D":"\"Art Is Expensive: Sell the Pieces!\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt emphasizes the house\u0027s long history in the community and the horror of it being \"pulled apart,\" making \"Preserve Our History: Keep the Robie House Whole!\" a fitting slogan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember. It\u0027s just too horrible to think of it being pulled apart."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q009","read_aloud":"What is an antonym of \"indivisible\"? A. Whole B. Divisible or breakable C. Solid D. United","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\"","stem":"What is an antonym of \"indivisible\"?","choices":{"A":"Whole","B":"Divisible or breakable","C":"Solid","D":"United"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Indivisible means cannot be divided; divisible is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q010","read_aloud":"What theme connects all these elements? A. Destruction is always bad. B. Things of value (art, family, promises) are fragile but worth fighting for. C. Only rich people matter. D. Art is never important.","excerpt":"The house has survived multiple threats. Tommy has experienced loss. Wright designed play space while his own family was broken.","stem":"What theme connects all these elements?","choices":{"A":"Destruction is always bad.","B":"Things of value (art, family, promises) are fragile but worth fighting for.","C":"Only rich people matter.","D":"Art is never important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Value and fragility connect them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The house has survived multiple threats. Tommy has experienced loss. Wright designed play space while his own family was broken."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Why might the author choose this point of view? A. To show only one character\u0027s thoughts B. To show the thoughts and feelings of multiple characters (Calder, Ms. Hussey, Tommy) C. To confuse the reader D. To never show any thoughts","excerpt":"The author uses third-person omniscient point of view.","stem":"Why might the author choose this point of view?","choices":{"A":"To show only one character\u0027s thoughts","B":"To show the thoughts and feelings of multiple characters (Calder, Ms. Hussey, Tommy)","C":"To confuse the reader","D":"To never show any thoughts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Omniscient means knowing all characters\u0027 thoughts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author uses third-person omniscient point of view."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Do you agree that destroying a historic house is a crime? Why? A. No, because houses are just buildings. B. Yes, because historic buildings hold community memory and artistic value. C. No, because new buildings are better. D. Yes, because it is against the law.","excerpt":"Ms. Hussey says, \"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home.\"","stem":"Do you agree that destroying a historic house is a crime? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because houses are just buildings.","B":"Yes, because historic buildings hold community memory and artistic value.","C":"No, because new buildings are better.","D":"Yes, because it is against the law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text argues for the building\u0027s value.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Ms. Hussey says, \"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"indivisible\"? A. breakable B. unbreakable C. whole D. separate","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"indivisible\"?","choices":{"A":"breakable","B":"unbreakable","C":"whole","D":"separate"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Indivisible\" means cannot be divided. \"Whole\" means complete and not split. They are similar in meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author include reactions from around the world? A. To show only local people care B. To show the Robie House is important to many people globally C. To make the story longer D. To introduce new characters","excerpt":"\"The news has shocked architecture buffs around the world and has left Hyde Park reeling.\"","stem":"Why does the author include reactions from around the world?","choices":{"A":"To show only local people care","B":"To show the Robie House is important to many people globally","C":"To make the story longer","D":"To introduce new characters"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author shows that people around the world are shocked. This proves the Robie House is not just a local building. It is globally important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The news has shocked architecture buffs around the world and has left Hyde Park reeling.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q015","read_aloud":"How does the author show Tommy\u0027s personality? A. Through loud actions and big speeches B. Through quiet observations and hesitant actions C. Through angry outbursts D. Through dancing and singing","excerpt":"\"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him... Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely.\"","stem":"How does the author show Tommy\u0027s personality?","choices":{"A":"Through loud actions and big speeches","B":"Through quiet observations and hesitant actions","C":"Through angry outbursts","D":"Through dancing and singing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tommy watches others, raises his hand \"just barely,\" and wonders what others think. These quiet, careful actions show he is observant and shy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him... Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Do you think Wright needed forgiveness for leaving his family? A. Yes, because leaving six children is a serious choice that may have hurt them B. No, because artists should never care about family C. Yes, because he was a bad architect D. No, because families do not matter","excerpt":"\"Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness....\"","stem":"Do you think Wright needed forgiveness for leaving his family?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because leaving six children is a serious choice that may have hurt them","B":"No, because artists should never care about family","C":"Yes, because he was a bad architect","D":"No, because families do not matter"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Leaving a wife and six children is a serious decision. Ms. Hussey wonders if Wright felt guilty. Designing play space for other children might have been his way of making peace.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness....\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What might the students do to try to save the house? A. Give up and do nothing B. Write letters, raise money, or protest to show the community cares C. Tear it down themselves D. Move to another city","excerpt":"\"What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\"","stem":"What might the students do to try to save the house?","choices":{"A":"Give up and do nothing","B":"Write letters, raise money, or protest to show the community cares","C":"Tear it down themselves","D":"Move to another city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The students care about the house. In real life, people save historic buildings by writing letters, raising money, or protesting. The students might take action to show the house matters.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He wants to buy a new filter for his house. B. He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words. C. He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert. D. He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson.","excerpt":"He knew the word","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He wants to buy a new filter for his house.","B":"He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words.","C":"He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert.","D":"He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder believes there might be a message in the words, so he thinks about their different meanings to figure it out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He knew the word"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. destroys B. represents C. forgets D. hides","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"destroys","B":"represents","C":"forgets","D":"hides"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house shows or \"represents\" Wright\u0027s spirit and vision, which is what \"embodies\" means.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey believe the Robie House should be an \"indivisible piece\"? A. Because splitting it up makes it worth more money. B. Because the house\u0027s design is a single, complete work of art where everything relates to everything else. C. Because museums will not accept more than one piece. D. Because she wants the house to stay empty.","excerpt":"\"\u0027A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey believe the Robie House should be an \"indivisible piece\"?","choices":{"A":"Because splitting it up makes it worth more money.","B":"Because the house\u0027s design is a single, complete work of art where everything relates to everything else.","C":"Because museums will not accept more than one piece.","D":"Because she wants the house to stay empty."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The context shows that the design, the windows, and the living spaces work together; Ms. Hussey believes cutting it up destroys the \"extraordinary\" design.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q002","read_aloud":"Why might it be important that Tommy lives next to the Robie House? A. It means he is the richest kid in the class. B. It gives him a personal connection to the setting of the mystery they are investigating. C. It means he will be the one to save the house. D. It means he does not have to pay for a school bus.","excerpt":"\"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\"","stem":"Why might it be important that Tommy lives next to the Robie House?","choices":{"A":"It means he is the richest kid in the class.","B":"It gives him a personal connection to the setting of the mystery they are investigating.","C":"It means he will be the one to save the house.","D":"It means he does not have to pay for a school bus."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In a mystery, being personally connected to the \"case\" usually gives the character an advantage, and living right next to the house allows him to see or experience things others cannot.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely. Should he tell the class that his new apartment was right next to one side of the Robie House? Would other kids think that was lucky?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author have Ms. Hussey speculate on Wright\u0027s motivations? A. To show that she is a gossip. B. To show that our understanding of art is influenced by the lives of the artists who made it. C. To distract the students from the main lesson. D. To prove that Wright was a bad father.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author have Ms. Hussey speculate on Wright\u0027s motivations?","choices":{"A":"To show that she is a gossip.","B":"To show that our understanding of art is influenced by the lives of the artists who made it.","C":"To distract the students from the main lesson.","D":"To prove that Wright was a bad father."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It highlights the thematic question of the unit: how \"Life \u0026 Art\" are connected, and how understanding an artist\u0027s personal life changes how we perceive their work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Maybe it was his way of asking the universe for forgiveness. . . .\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q004","read_aloud":"If you were tasked with defending the Robie House, what would be your strongest argument? A. The house is very large and should be used for something else. B. The house is an \"indivisible\" work of art that captures a specific moment in history and human experience. C. The house should be destroyed because it is too old. D. The house should be given to a museum because they will take better care of it.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\"","stem":"If you were tasked with defending the Robie House, what would be your strongest argument?","choices":{"A":"The house is very large and should be used for something else.","B":"The house is an \"indivisible\" work of art that captures a specific moment in history and human experience.","C":"The house should be destroyed because it is too old.","D":"The house should be given to a museum because they will take better care of it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This argument directly addresses the themes of the story: the value of art, the importance of historic preservation, and the unique connection between life (the home) and art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art . . .\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q005","read_aloud":"How does the word \"ironic\" function in this sentence? A. It highlights the unexpected contrast between the house\u0027s purpose and its reality. B. It shows that the house is very funny to look at. C. It means that the house is exactly as everyone expected. D. It describes the color of the paint on the house.","excerpt":"\"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\"","stem":"How does the word \"ironic\" function in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"It highlights the unexpected contrast between the house\u0027s purpose and its reality.","B":"It shows that the house is very funny to look at.","C":"It means that the house is exactly as everyone expected.","D":"It describes the color of the paint on the house."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Ironic\" is used to point out the unexpected and sad contrast between a house built for children and the fact that no family has lived in it for decades.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q006","read_aloud":"What role does the \"Lucky Stone\" play in this scene? A. It is a toy for the students to play with. B. It is a symbol of Ms. Hussey\u0027s worry and emotional connection to the topic. C. It is a piece of the Robie House that she stole. D. It is a tool she uses to measure the classroom.","excerpt":"\"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side.\"","stem":"What role does the \"Lucky Stone\" play in this scene?","choices":{"A":"It is a toy for the students to play with.","B":"It is a symbol of Ms. Hussey\u0027s worry and emotional connection to the topic.","C":"It is a piece of the Robie House that she stole.","D":"It is a tool she uses to measure the classroom."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text notes that when she picks it up, \"the children knew that she was worried or upset,\" making it a symbol of her emotional state.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. She had picked up a round, gray stone that lived on her desk, a rock with two bands of white that crossed neatly on either side.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q007","read_aloud":"How does the description of Ms. Hussey as a \"silhouette in the sunshine\" affect the mood of the ending? A. It makes the scene feel chaotic and loud. B. It creates a quiet, thoughtful, and slightly sad mood. C. It makes the scene feel scary and dangerous. D. It makes the scene feel like a funny comedy.","excerpt":"\"She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset. She held it now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\"","stem":"How does the description of Ms. Hussey as a \"silhouette in the sunshine\" affect the mood of the ending?","choices":{"A":"It makes the scene feel chaotic and loud.","B":"It creates a quiet, thoughtful, and slightly sad mood.","C":"It makes the scene feel scary and dangerous.","D":"It makes the scene feel like a funny comedy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A silhouette in the sunshine creates a quiet, visual image that matches the thoughtful and slightly sad mood of the class sighing and worrying.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She called it her Lucky Stone, and when she picked it up, the children knew that she was worried or upset. She held it now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Based on the entire selection, is the University of Chicago\u0027s decision to dismantle the Robie House justified? Use evidence from the text. A. Yes, because the university needs the money more than the world needs art. B. No, because the house is a historic, indivisible work of art that its own creator fought to save. C. Yes, because Frank Lloyd Wright wanted it to be cut into pieces. D. No, because the students in the class promised to pay for the repairs.","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"Based on the entire selection, is the University of Chicago\u0027s decision to dismantle the Robie House justified? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the university needs the money more than the world needs art.","B":"No, because the house is a historic, indivisible work of art that its own creator fought to save.","C":"Yes, because Frank Lloyd Wright wanted it to be cut into pieces.","D":"No, because the students in the class promised to pay for the repairs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text emphasizes that the house is an \"indivisible piece\" and that Wright fought to save it twice, suggesting that dismantling it destroys its true value as a work of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q009","read_aloud":"If the Robie House could speak to the University of Chicago, what message do you think it would give based on the themes of this story? A. \"I am just a building, so please cut me up and sell my parts.\" B. \"I am a piece of living history and art; please find a way to keep me whole and standing.\" C. \"I am too dangerous, so you should tear me down immediately.\" D. \"I do not care what happens to me, as long as I get a new roof.\"","excerpt":"\"But it\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\"","stem":"If the Robie House could speak to the University of Chicago, what message do you think it would give based on the themes of this story?","choices":{"A":"\"I am just a building, so please cut me up and sell my parts.\"","B":"\"I am a piece of living history and art; please find a way to keep me whole and standing.\"","C":"\"I am too dangerous, so you should tear me down immediately.\"","D":"\"I do not care what happens to me, as long as I get a new roof.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story\u0027s themes focus on the house being an \"indivisible piece\" of art and a historic part of the community, so it would logically plead to be kept whole.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But it\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q010","read_aloud":"Revolutionary means ______. A. Old and boring B. Extremely new and different C. Very small D. Very tall","excerpt":"\"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\"","stem":"Revolutionary means ______.","choices":{"A":"Old and boring","B":"Extremely new and different","C":"Very small","D":"Very tall"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Revolutionary means new and different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What is one big theme of \"Life \u0026 Art\"? A. Money is all that matters. B. Art and memory are worth fighting for, even when practical life makes it hard. C. Old buildings should always be torn down. D. Only famous people matter.","excerpt":"Review the history of the Robie House and the characters\u0027 personal struggles.","stem":"What is one big theme of \"Life \u0026 Art\"?","choices":{"A":"Money is all that matters.","B":"Art and memory are worth fighting for, even when practical life makes it hard.","C":"Old buildings should always be torn down.","D":"Only famous people matter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story balances art\u0027s value with real-world problems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Review the history of the Robie House and the characters\u0027 personal struggles."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"embodies\"? A. represents B. hides C. shows D. reveals","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of \"embodies\"?","choices":{"A":"represents","B":"hides","C":"shows","D":"reveals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Embodies\" means to show or represent clearly. The opposite is \"hides,\" which means to cover up or keep secret.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Why is this realistic fiction? A. It has dragons and magic B. The characters have real feelings and deal with real problems C. It takes place on another planet D. The characters are cartoon animals","excerpt":"\"Tommy thought Ms. Hussey was hard to figure out, too. Did she understand? And was she angry or excited?\"","stem":"Why is this realistic fiction?","choices":{"A":"It has dragons and magic","B":"The characters have real feelings and deal with real problems","C":"It takes place on another planet","D":"The characters are cartoon animals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Realistic fiction shows believable characters with real feelings. Tommy, Calder, and Petra think and feel like real kids. They deal with a real problem about a historic house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy thought Ms. Hussey was hard to figure out, too. Did she understand? And was she angry or excited?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q014","read_aloud":"What tone does this create? A. Happy and joyful B. Sad and mournful C. Angry and violent D. Silly and funny","excerpt":"\"\u0027This breaks my heart. Hyde Park weeps.\u0027\"","stem":"What tone does this create?","choices":{"A":"Happy and joyful","B":"Sad and mournful","C":"Angry and violent","D":"Silly and funny"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Breaks my heart\" and \"weeps\" create a sad, mournful tone. The person feels like the neighborhood is losing something precious.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027This breaks my heart. Hyde Park weeps.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Is Ms. Hussey right that cutting up the house destroys its meaning? A. No, because pieces in museums are better than nothing B. Yes, because the house was designed as one whole piece, like a puzzle C. No, because Wright wanted it in pieces D. Yes, because museums are bad","excerpt":"\"The idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"Is Ms. Hussey right that cutting up the house destroys its meaning?","choices":{"A":"No, because pieces in museums are better than nothing","B":"Yes, because the house was designed as one whole piece, like a puzzle","C":"No, because Wright wanted it in pieces","D":"Yes, because museums are bad"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey says the house is \"one indivisible piece.\" Wright designed every part to fit together. Cutting it up destroys how the house works as a whole, like taking apart a puzzle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q016","read_aloud":"If the Robie House could speak, what might it say? A. \"Tear me down quickly!\" B. \"I was built to bring people together in beauty. Please keep me whole.\" C. \"I do not matter at all.\" D. \"Cut me into pieces for museums.\"","excerpt":"From the whole story.","stem":"If the Robie House could speak, what might it say?","choices":{"A":"\"Tear me down quickly!\"","B":"\"I was built to bring people together in beauty. Please keep me whole.\"","C":"\"I do not matter at all.\"","D":"\"Cut me into pieces for museums.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house was built as a home with flowing spaces and beautiful art glass. It represents Wright\u0027s vision of life and art together. It would want to stay whole and continue inspiring people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: From the whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He wants to buy a new filter for his house. B. He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words. C. He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert. D. He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson.","excerpt":"He knew the word","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He wants to buy a new filter for his house.","B":"He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words.","C":"He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert.","D":"He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder believes there might be a message in the words, so he thinks about their different meanings to figure it out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He knew the word"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. destroys B. represents C. forgets D. hides","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"destroys","B":"represents","C":"forgets","D":"hides"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house shows or \"represents\" Wright\u0027s spirit and vision, which is what \"embodies\" means.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. She answers the question quickly. B. She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails. C. She stands up and leaves the room. D. She apologizes for being rude.","excerpt":"\"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"She answers the question quickly.","B":"She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails.","C":"She stands up and leaves the room.","D":"She apologizes for being rude."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Denise \"raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails,\" showing she is ignoring the question.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q001","read_aloud":"If the house embodies Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s spirit, what is the house doing? A. It is hiding his spirit from the public. B. It is acting as a physical form of his ideas. C. It is becoming a person and talking to people. D. It is trying to be someone else.","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"If the house embodies Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s spirit, what is the house doing?","choices":{"A":"It is hiding his spirit from the public.","B":"It is acting as a physical form of his ideas.","C":"It is becoming a person and talking to people.","D":"It is trying to be someone else."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Embodies\" means it represents or expresses an idea in a physical form; the house shows his spirit in its design.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q002","read_aloud":"Why were these design features revolutionary? A. Because they had never been used in homes before. B. Because they were common in every home built in 1910. C. Because they made the house very expensive. D. Because they made the house dangerous to live in.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\u0027\"","stem":"Why were these design features revolutionary?","choices":{"A":"Because they had never been used in homes before.","B":"Because they were common in every home built in 1910.","C":"Because they made the house very expensive.","D":"Because they made the house dangerous to live in."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Revolutionary\" means very new and different, which is why Ms. Hussey says they were not \"normal\" at the time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Things that are normal to us now were revolutionary then, like rooms that flowed into each other; living space that moved easily between inside and outside...\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q003","read_aloud":"What makes the house being empty ironic? A. It is ironic because it is the biggest house in Chicago. B. It is ironic because it was intended for families, but no family has lived there for a long time. C. It is ironic because the university owns it now. D. It is ironic because the house is falling down.","excerpt":"\"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"","stem":"What makes the house being empty ironic?","choices":{"A":"It is ironic because it is the biggest house in Chicago.","B":"It is ironic because it was intended for families, but no family has lived there for a long time.","C":"It is ironic because the university owns it now.","D":"It is ironic because the house is falling down."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is ironic when the actual situation (empty house) is the opposite of the original purpose (built for families/children).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main conflict the characters face? A. Their teacher, Ms. Hussey, is going to move away. B. They need to build a new house for their teacher. C. They want to save a historic Frank Lloyd Wright house from being destroyed. D. They need to finish a research project before school ends.","excerpt":"\"When strange things start happening at a local home designed by architect Frank Lloyd Wright, sixth-grade sleuths Calder, Tommy, and Petra are eager to take the case-and to save the building in the process.\"","stem":"What is the main conflict the characters face?","choices":{"A":"Their teacher, Ms. Hussey, is going to move away.","B":"They need to build a new house for their teacher.","C":"They want to save a historic Frank Lloyd Wright house from being destroyed.","D":"They need to finish a research project before school ends."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The story is about the characters learning about the plan to dismantle the Robie House and their efforts to \"take the case\" and \"save the building.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When strange things start happening at a local home designed by architect Frank Lloyd Wright, sixth-grade sleuths Calder, Tommy, and Petra are eager to take the case-and to save the building in the process.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey include the students\u0027 grandparents in her statement? A. To show the house is very old and has a long history in their community. B. To show that their grandparents also hated the house. C. To suggest that they should ask their grandparents for money. D. To make the students feel bad about their age.","excerpt":"\"\u0027It\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey include the students\u0027 grandparents in her statement?","choices":{"A":"To show the house is very old and has a long history in their community.","B":"To show that their grandparents also hated the house.","C":"To suggest that they should ask their grandparents for money.","D":"To make the students feel bad about their age."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"By mentioning generations (students, parents, grandparents), she is emphasizing that the house has been a meaningful part of the community for a very long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027It\u0027s never too late to think. What could we do? Art-home or not, the Robie House has been a part of Hyde Park for as long as you, your parents, or maybe even your grandparents remember.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q006","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why does Ms. Hussey think the Robie House is a treasure? A. Because it is the most expensive building in Chicago. B. Because of its unique, ground-breaking design and its history as a masterpiece of architecture. C. Because she wants the students to build one just like it. D. Because she knows Frank Lloyd Wright personally.","excerpt":"\"\u0027I know all of you have passed it many times-it\u0027s only three blocks away. It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the text, why does Ms. Hussey think the Robie House is a treasure?","choices":{"A":"Because it is the most expensive building in Chicago.","B":"Because of its unique, ground-breaking design and its history as a masterpiece of architecture.","C":"Because she wants the students to build one just like it.","D":"Because she knows Frank Lloyd Wright personally."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She highlights the house\u0027s architectural importance and innovative design to explain why it is a treasure that shouldn\u0027t be lost.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I know all of you have passed it many times-it\u0027s only three blocks away. It\u0027s long and low, but remember that it\u0027s been almost a century since Wright designed it.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q007","read_aloud":"How does the students\u0027 desire to visit the house show that they are thinking differently about \"Art\" and \"Life\"? A. They want to treat it like a museum piece to look at from afar. B. They want to experience the house to understand why it is important to the life of their community. C. They want to play inside it because they are bored. D. They want to take pieces of it home.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\u0027 Calder suggested.\"","stem":"How does the students\u0027 desire to visit the house show that they are thinking differently about \"Art\" and \"Life\"?","choices":{"A":"They want to treat it like a museum piece to look at from afar.","B":"They want to experience the house to understand why it is important to the life of their community.","C":"They want to play inside it because they are bored.","D":"They want to take pieces of it home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By wanting to go there, they are showing interest in the actual experience of the house, which connects the \"art\" of the building to the \"life\" of the people visiting it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Maybe we can visit the place and come up with ideas,\u0027 Calder suggested.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the teacher react this way? A. Because she is being sarcastic to make the class laugh. B. Because she fears the house will lose its \"life\" if it becomes a museum exhibit. C. Because she thinks museums are full of dirty things. D. Because she wants to quit being a teacher.","excerpt":"\"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"Why does the teacher react this way?","choices":{"A":"Because she is being sarcastic to make the class laugh.","B":"Because she fears the house will lose its \"life\" if it becomes a museum exhibit.","C":"Because she thinks museums are full of dirty things.","D":"Because she wants to quit being a teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her reaction shows that she believes art should be experienced in its original place, not in a museum, where it becomes just a collection of \"chunks\" and \"pieces.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word, which was a little confusing. The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q009","read_aloud":"What does Ms. Hussey mean by this question? A. That houses that are empty should always be torn down. B. That a home is defined by more than just walls; it needs the people who live in it. C. That the Robie House is definitely not a home. D. That the students should buy the house and live in it.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty.\u0027\"","stem":"What does Ms. Hussey mean by this question?","choices":{"A":"That houses that are empty should always be torn down.","B":"That a home is defined by more than just walls; it needs the people who live in it.","C":"That the Robie House is definitely not a home.","D":"That the students should buy the house and live in it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She is challenging her students to think about what makes a space feel alive, suggesting that the \"life\" in \"Life \u0026 Art\" comes from human connection and habitation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q010","read_aloud":"Why is this moment important to the story\u0027s overall message? A. It shows that the teacher is very tired and needs a nap. B. It shows that the teacher cares deeply and is personally worried about the fate of the Robie House. C. It shows that the stone is more important than the house. D. It shows that the classroom is not a serious place for learning.","excerpt":"\"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. ... She held it [the stone] now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\"","stem":"Why is this moment important to the story\u0027s overall message?","choices":{"A":"It shows that the teacher is very tired and needs a nap.","B":"It shows that the teacher cares deeply and is personally worried about the fate of the Robie House.","C":"It shows that the stone is more important than the house.","D":"It shows that the classroom is not a serious place for learning."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This moment highlights the emotional stakes of the situation; by showing how worried the teacher is, it demonstrates that this is not just a lesson, but a situation that deeply affects people\u0027s hearts and spirits. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Life \u0026 Art\" (from The Wright 3) Author: Blue Balliett Source: Student Interactive U3 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Their teacher sat on the edge of a radiator. ... She held it [the stone] now in both hands, her body a silhouette in the sunshine coming from the window behind her.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"radically\" mean in this context? A. slightly and slowly B. completely and extremely C. quietly and secretly D. rarely and occasionally","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"What does \"radically\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"slightly and slowly","B":"completely and extremely","C":"quietly and secretly","D":"rarely and occasionally"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the house changed architecture in a major way. \"Radically\" means completely or extremely.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"indivisible\" mean in this sentence? A. able to be separated into parts B. unable to be split into pieces C. very old and fragile D. bright and full of windows","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"What does \"indivisible\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"able to be separated into parts","B":"unable to be split into pieces","C":"very old and fragile","D":"bright and full of windows"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about carving up the house, so \"indivisible\" means it cannot be split into pieces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q013","read_aloud":"What is the best synonym for \"ironic\" in this context? A. expected B. unexpected C. joyful D. boring","excerpt":"\"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\"","stem":"What is the best synonym for \"ironic\" in this context?","choices":{"A":"expected","B":"unexpected","C":"joyful","D":"boring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Ironic\" highlights the unexpected contrast between the house\u0027s purpose and its current empty reality.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"I wish we could, but they haven\u0027t allowed visitors inside for more than a year, and no family has lived there since 1926. This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The University of Chicago is building a new museum. B. The Robie House will be cut up and sent to different museums. C. Frank Lloyd Wright designed four great museums. D. Hyde Park is a tragic place to live.","excerpt":"\"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The University of Chicago is building a new museum.","B":"The Robie House will be cut up and sent to different museums.","C":"Frank Lloyd Wright designed four great museums.","D":"Hyde Park is a tragic place to live."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt\u0027s main point is the announcement that the Robie House will be cut into sections and donated to museums.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: The seminary used the building poorly; Effect: It fell into serious disrepair. B. Cause: The building was a cafeteria; Effect: It became a famous museum. C. Cause: The seminary was located steps away; Effect: It bought the house. D. Cause: The structure was repaired; Effect: It became a dormitory.","excerpt":"\"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: The seminary used the building poorly; Effect: It fell into serious disrepair.","B":"Cause: The building was a cafeteria; Effect: It became a famous museum.","C":"Cause: The seminary was located steps away; Effect: It bought the house.","D":"Cause: The structure was repaired; Effect: It became a dormitory."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Because the seminary used the building for its own needs without proper care, the effect was that it fell into serious disrepair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q016","read_aloud":"What is the correct sequence of events? A. Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf bought it, Zeckendorf gave it to the University of Chicago. B. Zeckendorf bought it, Wright rescued it, the seminary tore it down. C. The University of Chicago bought it, Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf used it for offices. D. The seminary tore it down, Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf bought it.","excerpt":"\"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary. Zeckendorf used it for office space and made plans to give it to the National Trust for Historic Preservation. In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago...\"","stem":"What is the correct sequence of events?","choices":{"A":"Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf bought it, Zeckendorf gave it to the University of Chicago.","B":"Zeckendorf bought it, Wright rescued it, the seminary tore it down.","C":"The University of Chicago bought it, Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf used it for offices.","D":"The seminary tore it down, Wright rescued it, Zeckendorf bought it."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states Wright rescued it, then Zeckendorf bought it, and later Zeckendorf deeded it to the University of Chicago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue... he persuaded William Zeckendorf, a developer, to buy the house from the seminary. Zeckendorf used it for office space and made plans to give it to the National Trust for Historic Preservation. In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q017","read_aloud":"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. What two words did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard? A. art and history B. life and art C. home and family D. light and air","excerpt":"Let\u0027s try it.","stem":"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. What two words did Ms. Hussey write on the blackboard?","choices":{"A":"art and history","B":"life and art","C":"home and family","D":"light and air"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explicitly states that Ms. Hussey \"wrote life \u0026 art.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Let\u0027s try it."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q018","read_aloud":"life\" and \"art\" began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \"life art\" became \"a trifle\" or \"a filter. Why does Calder rearrange the letters in his mind? A. He is trying to find a hidden message or new meaning in the words. B. He is trying to spell his own name. C. He is bored and wants to draw a picture. D. He is trying to correct the teacher\u0027s spelling.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"life\" and \"art\" began to shift rapidly in his mind. If those seven letters were put in another order, \"life art\" became \"a trifle\" or \"a filter. Why does Calder rearrange the letters in his mind?","choices":{"A":"He is trying to find a hidden message or new meaning in the words.","B":"He is trying to spell his own name.","C":"He is bored and wants to draw a picture.","D":"He is trying to correct the teacher\u0027s spelling."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Calder believes there might be a message, so he shifts the letters to see if they form new words with different meanings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q019","read_aloud":"How does Tommy\u0027s personal life connect to his feelings about the Robie House discussion? A. It makes him want to speak up loudly to get attention. B. It makes him withdrawn and hesitant to share his personal connection to the house. C. It makes him angry at Frank Lloyd Wright. D. It makes him want to move to South America.","excerpt":"\"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America...\"","stem":"How does Tommy\u0027s personal life connect to his feelings about the Robie House discussion?","choices":{"A":"It makes him want to speak up loudly to get attention.","B":"It makes him withdrawn and hesitant to share his personal connection to the house.","C":"It makes him angry at Frank Lloyd Wright.","D":"It makes him want to move to South America."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tommy\u0027s complicated family situation and feelings of being let down make him withdraw and hesitate to share that he lives next to the house.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy picked at a sticker on his desk, careful not to look up. Neither one of his dads had said sorry. When Tommy was a baby, his real dad had died in South America...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q020","read_aloud":"To embody something means to ______. A. Destroy it B. Represent or show it clearly C. Hide it D. Forget it","excerpt":"\"The house embodies his unique spirit and vision.\"","stem":"To embody something means to ______.","choices":{"A":"Destroy it","B":"Represent or show it clearly","C":"Hide it","D":"Forget it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Embodies means to represent clearly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house embodies his unique spirit and vision.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q021","read_aloud":"Indivisible means ______. A. Able to be split B. Unable to be split C. Very colorful D. Very old","excerpt":"\"The house is one indivisible piece.\"","stem":"Indivisible means ______.","choices":{"A":"Able to be split","B":"Unable to be split","C":"Very colorful","D":"Very old"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Indivisible means cannot be divided.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house is one indivisible piece.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of \"Life \u0026 Art\"? A. Math is more important than art. B. A beloved historic house is threatened, and the community struggles with art\u0027s value versus real-world problems. C. All old houses should be destroyed. D. The Robie House is ugly.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"What is the main idea of \"Life \u0026 Art\"?","choices":{"A":"Math is more important than art.","B":"A beloved historic house is threatened, and the community struggles with art\u0027s value versus real-world problems.","C":"All old houses should be destroyed.","D":"The Robie House is ugly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story centers on this conflict.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q023","read_aloud":"Why does the university want to cut up the house? A. They hate Frank Lloyd Wright. B. They cannot afford to fix it. C. They want more parking. D. They are moving.","excerpt":"\"The university cannot afford to keep it.\"","stem":"Why does the university want to cut up the house?","choices":{"A":"They hate Frank Lloyd Wright.","B":"They cannot afford to fix it.","C":"They want more parking.","D":"They are moving."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they cannot afford to keep it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cannot afford to keep it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q024","read_aloud":"What does this phrase suggest? A. People are happy. B. People are very sad about losing the house. C. It is raining. D. No one cares.","excerpt":"\"Hyde Park weeps.\"","stem":"What does this phrase suggest?","choices":{"A":"People are happy.","B":"People are very sad about losing the house.","C":"It is raining.","D":"No one cares."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Weeps\" means cries with sadness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hyde Park weeps.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q025","read_aloud":"What conflict does this show? A. Everyone agrees. B. Emotional value vs. practical money problems. C. The house is not important. D. Only one person has an opinion.","excerpt":"Compare Ms. Hussey\u0027s reaction (\"I felt sick\") with the university\u0027s reason (\"cannot afford to keep it\").","stem":"What conflict does this show?","choices":{"A":"Everyone agrees.","B":"Emotional value vs. practical money problems.","C":"The house is not important.","D":"Only one person has an opinion."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Heart vs. wallet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Ms. Hussey\u0027s reaction (\"I felt sick\") with the university\u0027s reason (\"cannot afford to keep it\")."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Ms. Hussey? Why? A. No, because buildings don\u0027t matter. B. Yes, because the house is unique and historically important. C. No, because the university knows best. D. Yes, because it is old.","excerpt":"\"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\"","stem":"Do you agree with Ms. Hussey? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because buildings don\u0027t matter.","B":"Yes, because the house is unique and historically important.","C":"No, because the university knows best.","D":"Yes, because it is old."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text supports the house\u0027s unique value.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It seems like a crime to destroy such a home, don\u0027t you think?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q027","read_aloud":"If you could give one piece of advice to the university, what would it be? A. \"Tear it down immediately.\" B. \"Find another way-fundraise, partner with the community-to keep the house whole.\" C. \"Cut it up as fast as possible.\" D. \"Ignore the problem.\"","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you could give one piece of advice to the university, what would it be?","choices":{"A":"\"Tear it down immediately.\"","B":"\"Find another way-fundraise, partner with the community-to keep the house whole.\"","C":"\"Cut it up as fast as possible.\"","D":"\"Ignore the problem.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This matches the story\u0027s call to action. Section A - Text information Title: Life \u0026 Art (from The Wright 3) Author: Blue Balliett","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does \"embodies\" mean? A. hides completely B. symbolizes or represents clearly C. destroys slowly D. builds quickly","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"What does \"embodies\" mean?","choices":{"A":"hides completely","B":"symbolizes or represents clearly","C":"destroys slowly","D":"builds quickly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Embodies\" means to represent or show something clearly. The house shows Wright\u0027s spirit and vision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q029","read_aloud":"What does \"ironic\" mean? A. exactly what you expect B. contrary to expectation C. very funny D. extremely boring","excerpt":"\"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\"","stem":"What does \"ironic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"exactly what you expect","B":"contrary to expectation","C":"very funny","D":"extremely boring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Ironic\" means the opposite of what you expect. The house was built for children, but no children have lived there for almost a century.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This is deeply ironic, of course, since the house was built for children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q030","read_aloud":"What is the main topic of Ms. Hussey\u0027s lesson? A. How to draw houses B. The connection between life and art C. How to read newspapers D. The history of chalk","excerpt":"\"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. \u0027I\u0027m thinking about what happens when life and art don\u0027t mix well.\u0027\"","stem":"What is the main topic of Ms. Hussey\u0027s lesson?","choices":{"A":"How to draw houses","B":"The connection between life and art","C":"How to read newspapers","D":"The history of chalk"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey writes \"life \u0026 art\" and asks what happens when they do not mix well. She wants students to think about how life and art connect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. \u0027I\u0027m thinking about what happens when life and art don\u0027t mix well.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q031","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Tommy? A. He is confident and loud B. He is quiet, observant, and unsure about sharing C. He is angry at the teacher D. He knows nothing about the topic","excerpt":"\"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him. Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Tommy?","choices":{"A":"He is confident and loud","B":"He is quiet, observant, and unsure about sharing","C":"He is angry at the teacher","D":"He knows nothing about the topic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tommy watches others and barely raises his hand. He wonders if he should share. This shows he is quiet, careful, and hesitant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tommy swiveled in his seat and studied the faces around him. Tommy\u0027s hand was raised, but just barely.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q032","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. Wright saved the house at age 90 B. The seminary bought the house C. Wright saved the house the first time D. The university announced they would cut up the house","excerpt":"\"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary... It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue... The building limped on... Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"Wright saved the house at age 90","B":"The seminary bought the house","C":"Wright saved the house the first time","D":"The university announced they would cut up the house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"First, three families owned the house. Then the seminary bought it in 1926. Then Wright saved it. Then he saved it again at age 90.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The house was owned by three families before 1926, when it was bought by the Chicago Theological Seminary... It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue... The building limped on... Wright was then ninety years old, and brandishing his cane, returned to Hyde Park.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q033","read_aloud":"Who owns the Robie House now? A. Frank Lloyd Wright B. The Chicago Theological Seminary C. The University of Chicago D. A private family","excerpt":"\"In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago, which remodeled much of the interior for office use.\"","stem":"Who owns the Robie House now?","choices":{"A":"Frank Lloyd Wright","B":"The Chicago Theological Seminary","C":"The University of Chicago","D":"A private family"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Zeckendorf gave the house to the University of Chicago in 1963. The university still owns it and wants to cut it into pieces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1963, however, he changed his mind and deeded it to the University of Chicago, which remodeled much of the interior for office use.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why does Ms. Hussey hate the idea of museums in this case? A. She hates all museums now B. She thinks putting chunks of the house in museums destroys its wholeness C. She wants to keep the house for herself D. She thinks museums are too small","excerpt":"\"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word... The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\"","stem":"Why does Ms. Hussey hate the idea of museums in this case?","choices":{"A":"She hates all museums now","B":"She thinks putting chunks of the house in museums destroys its wholeness","C":"She wants to keep the house for herself","D":"She thinks museums are too small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey loves museums, but she thinks the house is \"one indivisible piece.\" Cutting it up for museums destroys what makes it special as a whole work of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said \u0027museums\u0027 as if it were a dirty word... The class knew Ms. Hussey loved to go to museums.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q035","read_aloud":"What is Ms. Hussey asking the class to think about? A. Whether art can be a home, and whether a home can be art B. How to build a new house C. Why museums are bad D. How to draw buildings","excerpt":"\"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\"","stem":"What is Ms. Hussey asking the class to think about?","choices":{"A":"Whether art can be a home, and whether a home can be art","B":"How to build a new house","C":"Why museums are bad","D":"How to draw buildings"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ms. Hussey asks deep questions about the nature of home and art. She wants students to think about whether a building can be both a home and a work of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Perhaps we have to figure out if the building is still a home, and whether a home can exist if it\u0027s empty. Or, beyond that, whether a home can also be a piece of art ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q036","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q037","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q038","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. In a small, quiet way B. In an extreme or major way C. By accident or mistake D. Using very expensive tools","excerpt":"\"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"In a small, quiet way","B":"In an extreme or major way","C":"By accident or mistake","D":"Using very expensive tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Radically\" describes a significant change, meaning the house changed architecture in a very big or extreme way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many consider Wright to be the greatest architect of the twentieth century, and his Prairie Style jewel, the home built for Frederick C. Robie, to be a house that radically changed the domestic architecture of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson. B. Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion. C. The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced. D. The students are not paying attention to the lesson.","excerpt":"\"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Ms. Hussey is teaching a math lesson.","B":"Ms. Hussey is writing words on the board to start a discussion.","C":"The chalk is broken and needs to be replaced.","D":"The students are not paying attention to the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Ms. Hussey writing \"life \u0026 art\" on the blackboard to begin talking about the topic with her class.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Let\u0027s try it.\" Ms. Hussey picked up a jagged chunk and turned toward the blackboard. She wrote life \u0026 art. The chalk made an ugly double line with each vertical stroke.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. He writes words with ugly chalk lines. B. He can rearrange letters to form new words. C. He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood. D. He plays with his pentominoes on his desk.","excerpt":"As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"He writes words with ugly chalk lines.","B":"He can rearrange letters to form new words.","C":"He listens to his parents talk about the neighborhood.","D":"He plays with his pentominoes on his desk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder quickly figures out that the letters in \"life art\" can be rearranged to spell \"a trifle\" or \"a filter,\" showing his puzzle-solving skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As Calder\u0027s fingers moved, the words"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They all love it very much. B. They either love it or dislike it. C. They do not know about it at all. D. They want to buy it for themselves.","excerpt":"Calder went on,","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They all love it very much.","B":"They either love it or dislike it.","C":"They do not know about it at all.","D":"They want to buy it for themselves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder explicitly states that people in the neighborhood \"either love it or can\u0027t stand it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Calder went on,"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. He wants to buy a new filter for his house. B. He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words. C. He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert. D. He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson.","excerpt":"He knew the word","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"He wants to buy a new filter for his house.","B":"He is trying to understand a hidden message in the words.","C":"He is hungry and wants to eat a trifle dessert.","D":"He is trying to distract his teacher from the lesson."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calder believes there might be a message in the words, so he thinks about their different meanings to figure it out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He knew the word"},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. destroys B. represents C. forgets D. hides","excerpt":"\"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"destroys","B":"represents","C":"forgets","D":"hides"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The house shows or \"represents\" Wright\u0027s spirit and vision, which is what \"embodies\" means.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many believe that the house embodies his unique spirit and vision in a timeless form.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. She answers the question quickly. B. She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails. C. She stands up and leaves the room. D. She apologizes for being rude.","excerpt":"\"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"She answers the question quickly.","B":"She ignores the teacher and looks at her nails.","C":"She stands up and leaves the room.","D":"She apologizes for being rude."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Denise \"raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails,\" showing she is ignoring the question.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Duh.\" Ms. Hussey frowned. \"Who said that? Denise? Tell us what you know about the house.\" Denise Dodge raised one eyebrow and studied her fingernails.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Cause: The house is famous; Effect: It will be cut into sections. B. Cause: The university owns the house; Effect: They announced it will be cut up and donated. C. Cause: Museums want new art; Effect: They built the Robie House. D. Cause: The house is tragic; Effect: People will move to Hyde Park.","excerpt":"\"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Cause: The house is famous; Effect: It will be cut into sections.","B":"Cause: The university owns the house; Effect: They announced it will be cut up and donated.","C":"Cause: Museums want new art; Effect: They built the Robie House.","D":"Cause: The house is tragic; Effect: People will move to Hyde Park."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the University of Chicago owns the house, they have the power to announce that it will be cut up and donated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a tragic piece of news for Hyde Park, the University of Chicago, owners of Frank Lloyd Wright\u0027s famous Robie House, announced today that the 1910 home will be cut into sections and donated to four great museums around the world...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. It needs too many structural repairs. B. It is too small for the students. C. It is located in the wrong city. D. It is not a famous building.","excerpt":"\"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"It needs too many structural repairs.","B":"It is too small for the students.","C":"It is located in the wrong city.","D":"It is not a famous building."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that the reason is an \"impossibly large number of structural repairs.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The university cited an impossibly large number of structural repairs as the reason.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. They protected it from any damage. B. They did not take good care of it. C. They wanted to turn it into a museum. D. They planned to expand the building.","excerpt":"\"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"They protected it from any damage.","B":"They did not take good care of it.","C":"They wanted to turn it into a museum.","D":"They planned to expand the building."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the seminary \"allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair,\" meaning they did not take good care of it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Affiliated with the University of Chicago and located just steps from the Robie House, the seminary used Wright\u0027s building for cafeteria and dormitory space, but allowed the structure to fall into serious disrepair.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. able to be separated into parts B. unable to be split into pieces C. very old and fragile D. bright and full of windows","excerpt":"\"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"able to be separated into parts","B":"unable to be split into pieces","C":"very old and fragile","D":"bright and full of windows"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ms. Hussey is upset about carving up the house, so \"indivisible\" means it cannot be split into pieces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A house like that needs light and air, and is one indivisible piece-the idea of carving up the structure and preserving chunks of it in museums!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. Turn it into a public park. B. Build new student housing. C. Sell it to a museum. D. Plant a large garden.","excerpt":"\"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"Turn it into a public park.","B":"Build new student housing.","C":"Sell it to a museum.","D":"Plant a large garden."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states the seminary wanted the land \"for new student housing.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wanting the land beneath it for new student housing, the seminary announced in 1941 that the house was going to be demolished.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u3-w5-life-and-art-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. He bought the house with his own money. B. He gathered famous experts to declare it an inspiration. C. He threatened to sue the seminary. D. He hid the blueprints for the house.","excerpt":"It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"He bought the house with his own money.","B":"He gathered famous experts to declare it an inspiration.","C":"He threatened to sue the seminary.","D":"He hid the blueprints for the house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wright put together a committee of famous architects and historians to declare the house an inspiration, which shamed the seminary into keeping it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was Frank Lloyd Wright himself who came to the rescue. In an unprecedented move within the architectural community, he put together a committee of world-famous architects and art historians and declared the Robie House to be"}]}}]};const target=window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA||{selections:[]};const existingIds=new Set((target.selections||[]).map((selection)=>selection.selection_id));grade5Unit3Selections.selections.forEach((selection)=>{if(!existingIds.has(selection.selection_id)){target.selections.push(selection);}});window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA=target;})();